g10.d: Ἀβιούδ Abioúd, ab-ee-ood'; of Hebrew origin (H31); Abihud, an Israelite:—Abiud.

g100.d:
ἁδρότης hadrótēs, had-rot'-ace; from ἁδρός hadrós (stout); plumpness, i.e. (figuratively)
 liberality:—abundance.

g1000.d: βολή bolḗ, bol-ay'; from G906; a throw (as a measure of distance):—cast.
g1000.r: From βάλλω (G906)|English: cast, put, thrust, cast out, lay, lie, misc

g1001.d: βολίζω bolízō, bol-id'-zo; from G1002; to heave the lead:—sound.

g1003.d: †Βοόζ Boóz, bo-oz'; of Hebrew origin (H1162); Booz, (i.e. Boaz), an Israelite:—Booz.

g1004.d: βόρβορος bórboros, bor'-bor-os; of uncertain derivation; mud:—mire.

g1005.d: βοῤῥᾶς borrhâs, bor-hras'; of uncertain derivation; the north (properly, wind):—north.

g1006.d:
βόσκω bóskō, bos'-ko; a prolonged form of a primary verb (compare G977, G1016); to pasture; by
 extension to, fodder; reflexively, to graze:—feed, keep.
g1006.r: A prol. form of a primary verb, cf βιβρώσκω (G977) & βοῦς (G1016)|English: eat

g1008.d: βοτάνη botánē, bot-an'-ay; from G1006; herbage (as if for grazing):—herb.

g1009.d:
βότρυς bótrys, bot'-rooce; of uncertain derivation; a bunch (of grapes):—(vine) cluster (of the
 vine).

g101.d: ἀδυνατέω adynatéō, ad-oo-nat-eh'-o; from G102; to be unable, i.e. (passively) impossible:—be impossible.
g101.r: From ἀδύνατος (G102)|English: impossible, impotent, could not do, weak, not possible

g1010.d:
βουλευτής bouleutḗs, bool-yoo-tace'; from G1011; an adviser, i.e. (specially) a councillor or member of the
 Jewish Sanhedrin:—counsellor.
g1010.r: From βουλεύω (G1011)|English: consult, be minded, purpose, determine, take counsel

g1011.d:
†βουλεύω bouleúō, bool-yoo'-o; from G1012; to advise, i.e. (reflexively) deliberate, or (by
 implication) resolve:—consult, take counsel, determine, be minded,
 purpose.

g1012.d:
βουλή boulḗ, boo-lay'; from G1014; volition, i.e. (objectively) advice, or (by implication)
 purpose:—+ advise, counsel, will.
g1012.r: From βούλομαι (G1014)|English: will, would, be minded, intend, be disposed, be willing, list, of his own will

g1013.d: βούλημα boúlēma, boo'-lay-mah; from G1014; a resolve:—purpose, will.
g1013.r: From βούλομαι (G1014)|English: will, would, be minded, intend, be disposed, be willing, list, of his own will

g1014.d:
βούλομαι boúlomai, boo'-lom-ahee; middle voice of a primary verb; to "will," i.e. (reflexively) be
 willing:—be disposed, minded, intend, list, (be, of own) will (-ing). 
 Compare G2309.
g1014.r: Middle voice of a primary verb|

g1015.d: βουνός bounós, boo-nos'; probably of foreign origin; a hillock:—hill.

g1016.d:
βοῦς boûs, booce; probably from the base of G1006; an ox (as grazing), i.e. an animal of
 that species ("beef"):—ox.
g1016.r: Probably from the base of βόσκω (G1006)|English: feed, keep

g1017.d:
βραβεῖον brabeîon, brab-i'-on; from βραβεύς brabeús (an umpire of uncertain derivation); an award (of
 arbitration), i.e. (specially) a prize in the public games:—prize.
g1017.r: From brabeus (an umpire of uncertain derivation)|

g1018.d:
βραβεύω brabeúō, brab-yoo'-o; from the same as G1017; to arbitrate, i.e. (genitive case) to govern
 (figuratively, prevail):—rule.
g1018.r: From the same as βραβεῖον (G1017)|English: prize

g1019.d: βραδύνω bradýnō, brad-oo'-no; from G1021; to delay:—be slack, tarry.

g102.d:
ἀδύνατος adýnatos, ad-oo'-nat-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G1415; unable, i.e. weak (literally
 or figuratively); passively, impossible:—could not do, impossible,
 impotent, not possible, weak.
g102.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and δυνατός (G1415)|English: Alpha

g1020.d: βραδυπλοέω bradyploéō, brad-oo-plo-eh'-o; from G1021 and a prolonged form of G4126; to sail slowly:—sail slowly.
g1020.r: From βραδύς (G1021) and a prolonged form of πλέω (G4126)|English: slow

g1021.d: βραδύς bradýs, brad-ooce'; of uncertain affinity; slow; figuratively, dull:—slow.

g1022.d: βραδύτης bradýtēs, brad-oo'-tace; from G1021; tardiness:—slackness.

g1023.d:
βραχίων brachíōn, brakh-ee'-own; properly, comparative of G1024, but apparently in the sense of
 βράσσω brássō (to wield); the arm, i.e. (figuratively)
 strength:—arm.
g1023.r: Properly, comparative of βραχύς (G1024), but apparently in the sense of brasso (to wield)|English: a little, a little space, a little while, few words

g1024.d:
βραχύς brachýs, brakh-ooce'; of uncertain affinity; short (of time, place, quantity, or
 number):—few words, little (space, while).

g1025.d:
βρέφος bréphos, bref'-os; of uncertain affinity; an infant (properly, unborn) literally or
 figuratively:—babe, (young) child, infant.

g1026.d:
βρέχω bréchō, brekh'-o; a primary verb; to moisten (especially by a shower):—(send) rain,
 wash.

g1027.d: βροντή brontḗ, bron-tay'; akin to βρέμω brémō (to roar); thunder:—thunder(-ing).

g1028.d: βροχή brochḗ, brokh-ay'; from G1026; rain:—rain.
g1028.r: From βρέχω (G1026)|English: rain, wash, rain send rain

g1029.d: βρόχος bróchos, brokh'-os; of uncertain derivation; a noose:—snare.

g103.d: ᾄδω áidō, ad'-o; a primary verb; to sing:—sing.

g1030.d: βρυγμός brygmós, broog-mos'; from G1031; a grating (of the teeth):—gnashing.

g1031.d: βρύχω brýchō, broo'-kho; a primary verb; to grate the teeth (in pain or rage):—gnash.

g1032.d:
βρύω brýō, broo'-o; a primary verb; to swell out, i.e. (by implication) to gush:—send
 forth.

g1033.d:
βρῶμα brōma, bro'-mah; from the base of G977; food (literally or figuratively), especially
 (ceremonially) articles allowed or forbidden by the Jewish law:—meat,
 victuals.
g1033.r: From the base of βιβρώσκω (G977)|English: eat

g1034.d: βρώσιμος brṓsimos, bro'-sim-os; from G1035; eatable:—meat.
g1034.r: From βρῶσις (G1035)|English: meat, rust, morsel of meat, eating, food

g1035.r: From the base of βιβρώσκω (G977)|English: eat

g1036.d: βυθίζω bythízō, boo-thid'-zo; from G1037; to sink; by implication, to drown:—begin to sink, drown.

g1037.d: βυθός bythós, boo-thos'; a variation of G899; depth, i.e. (by implication) the sea:—deep.
g1037.r: A variation of βάθος (G899)|English: depth, deep, deep, deepness, deep thing

g1038.d: βυρσεύς byrseús, boorce-yooce'; from βύρσα býrsa (a hide); a tanner:—tanner.

g1039.d: βύσσινος býssinos, boos'-see-nos; from G1040; made of linen (neuter a linen cloth):—fine linen.

g104.d:
ἀεί aeí, ah-eye'; from an obsolete primary noun (apparently meaning continued duration); 
 "ever," by qualification regularly; by implication, earnestly:—always, ever.
g104.r: From an obsolete primary noun (apparently meaning continued duration)|

g1040.d: βύσσος býssos, boos'-sos; of Hebrew origin (H948); white linen:—fine linen.
g1040.r: Of Hebrew origin בּוּץ (H948)|English: fine linen, white linen

g1041.d:
βωμός bōmós, bo'-mos; from the base of G939; properly, a stand, i.e. (specially) an
 altar:—altar.
g1041.r: From the base of βάσις (G939)|English: foot (sole of)

g1042.d:
†γαββαθά gabbathá, gab-bath-ah'; of Chaldee origin (compare H1355); the knoll; gabbatha, a vernacular
 term for the Roman tribunal in Jerusalem:—Gabbatha.
g1042.r: Of Aramaic origin cf גַּב (H1355)|English: back

g1043.d: Γαβριήλ Gabriḗl, gab-ree-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H1403); Gabriel, an archangel:—Gabriel.

g1044.d: γάγγραινα gángraina, gang'-grahee-nah; from γραίνω graínō (to gnaw); an ulcer ("gangrene"):—canker.

g1045.d: Γάδ Gád, gad; of Hebrew origin (H1410); Gad, a tribe of Israelites:—Gad.

g1046.d:
†Γαδαρηνός Gadarēnós, gad-ar-ay-nos'; from Γαδαρά Gadará (a town east of the Jordan); a Gadarene or inhabitant of
 Gadara:—Gadarene.
g1046.r: From Gadara (a town east of the Jordan)|

g1047.d: γάζα gáza, gad'-zah; of foreign origin; a treasure:—treasure.

g1048.d:
Γάζα Gáza, gad'-zah; of Hebrew origin (H5804); Gazah (i.e. Azzah), a place in
 Palestine:—Gaza.
g1048.r: Of Hebrew origin עַזָּה (H5804)|English: Gaza, Azzah

g1049.d:
γαζοφυλάκιον gazophylákion, gad-zof-oo-lak'-ee-on; from G1047 and G5438; a treasure-house, i.e. a court in the temple for
 the collection-boxes:—treasury.

g105.d: ἀετός aetós, ah-et-os'; from the same as; an eagle (from its wind-like flight):—eagle.
g105.r: From the same as ἀήρ (G109)|English: air

g1050.d: Γάϊος Gáïos, gah'-ee-os; of Latin origin; Gaius (i.e. Caius), a Christian:—Gaius.

g1051.d: γάλα gála, gal'-ah; of uncertain affinity; milk (figuratively):—milk.

g1052.d: Γαλάτης Galátēs, gal-at'-ace; from G1053; a Galatian or inhabitant of Galatia:—Galatian.

g1053.d: Γαλατία Galatía, gal-at-ee'-ah; of foreign origin; Galatia, a region of Asia:—Galatia.

g1054.d: Γαλατικός Galatikós, gal-at-ee-kos'; from G1053; Galatic or relating to Galatia:—of Galatia.

g1055.d: γαλήνη galḗnē, gal-ay'-nay; of uncertain derivation; tranquillity:—calm.

g1056.d:
Γαλιλαία Galilaía, gal-il-ah'-yah; of Hebrew origin (H1551); Galilæa (i.e. the heathen circle), a region
 of Palestine:—Galilee.

g1057.d: Γαλιλαῖος Galilaîos, gal-ee-lah'-yos; from G1056; Galilean or belonging to Galilea:—Galilean, of Galilee.

g1058.d: Γαλλίων Gallíōn, gal-lee'-own; of Latin origin; Gallion (i.e. Gallio), a Roman officer:—Gallio.

g1059.d:
Γαμαλιήλ Gamaliḗl, gam-al-ee-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H1583); Gamaliel (i.e. Gamliel), an
 Israelite:—Gamaliel.

g106.d:
ἄζυμος ázymos, ad'-zoo-mos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G2219; unleavened, i.e.
 (figuratively) uncorrupted; (in the neutral plural) specially (by
 implication) the Passover week:—unleavened (bread).
g106.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and ζύμη (G2219)|English: Alpha

g1060.d: γαμέω gaméō, gam-eh'-o; from G1062; to wed (of either sex):—marry (a wife).

g1061.d: †γαμίσκω gamískō, gam-is'-ko; from G1062; to espouse (a daughter to a husband):—give in marriage.

g1062.d: γάμος gámos, gam'-os; of uncertain affinity; nuptials:—marriage, wedding.

g1063.d:
γάρ gár, gar; a primary particle; properly, assigning a reason (used in argument,
 explanation or intensification; often with other particles):—and, as,
 because (that), but, even, for, indeed, no doubt, seeing, then,
 therefore, verily, what, why, yet.

g1064.d:
γαστήρ gastḗr, gas-tare'; of uncertain derivation; the stomach; by analogy, the matrix;
 figuratively, a gourmand:—belly, + with child, womb.

g1065.d:
γέ gé, gheh; a primary particle of emphasis or qualification (often used with other
 particles prefixed):—and besides, doubtless, at least, yet.
g1065.r: A primary particle of emphasis or qualification (often used with other particles prefixed)|

g1066.d:
Γεδεών Gedeṓn, ghed-eh-own'; of Hebrew origin (H1439); Gedeon (i.e. Gid(e)on), an Israelite:—Gedeon
 (in the King James Version).

g1067.r: Of Hebrew origin גַּיְא (H1516) and הִנֹּם (H2011)|English: valley

g1069.d:
γείτων geítōn, ghi'-tone; from G1093; a neighbour (as adjoining one's ground); by implication, a
 friend:—neighbour.
g1069.r: From γῆ (G1093)|English: earth, land, ground, country, world, earthly

g107.d: Ἀζώρ Azṓr, ad-zore'; of Hebrew origin (compare H5809); Azor, an Israelite:—Azorigin
g107.r: Of Hebrew origin, cf עַזּוּר (H5809)|English: Azur, Azzur

g1070.d:
γελάω geláō, ghel-ah'-o; of uncertain affinity; to laugh (as a sign of joy or
 satisfaction):—laugh.

g1071.d: γέλως gélōs, ghel'-os; from G1070; laughter (as a mark of gratification):—laughter.

g1072.d: γεμίζω gemízō, ghem-id'-zo; transitive from G1073; to fill entirely:—fill (be) full.
g1072.r: Transitive from γέμω (G1073)|English: full, be full

g1073.d: γέμω gémō, ghem'-o; a primary verb; to swell out, i.e. be full:—be full.

g1074.d:
γενεά geneá, ghen-eh-ah'; from (a presumed derivative of) G1085; a generation; by implication, an
 age (the period or the persons):—age, generation, nation, time.
g1074.r: From (a presumed derivative of) γένος (G1085)|English: kind, kindred, offspring, nation, stock, born, diversity, misc.

g1075.d:
γενεαλογέω genealogéō, ghen-eh-al-og-eh'-o; from G1074 and G3056; to reckon by generations, i.e. trace in
 genealogy:—count by descent.
g1075.r: From γενεά (G1074) and λόγος (G3056)|English: generation, time, age, nation

g1076.d:
γενεαλογία genealogía, ghen-eh-al-og-ee'-ah; from the same as G1075; tracing by generations, i.e.
 "genealogy":—genealogy.
g1076.r: From the same as γενεαλογέω (G1075)|English: count (one's) descent

g1077.d: γενέσια genésia, ghen-es'-ee-ah; neuter plural of a derivative of G1078; birthday ceremonies:—birthday.
g1077.r: From a derivative of γένεσις (G1078)|English: generation, natural, nature

g1078.d:
γένεσις génesis, ghen'-es-is; from the same as G1074; nativity; figuratively, nature:—generation,
 nature(-ral).
g1078.r: From the same as γενεά (G1074)|English: generation, time, age, nation

g1079.d: γενετή genetḗ, ghen-et-ay; feminine of a presumed derivative of the base of G1074; birth:—birth.
g1079.r: From a presumed derivative of the base of γενεά (G1074)|English: generation, time, age, nation

g108.d:
Ἄζωτος Ázōtos, ad'-zo-tos; of Hebrew origin (H795); Azotus (i.e. Ashdod), a place in
 Palestine:—Azotus.

g1080.d:
γεννάω gennáō, ghen-nah'-o; from a variation of G1085; to procreate (properly, of the father, but
 by extension of the mother); figuratively, to regenerate:—bear,
 beget, be born, bring forth, conceive, be delivered of, gender, make,
 spring.
g1080.r: From a variation of γένος (G1085)|English: kind, kindred, offspring, nation, stock, born, diversity, misc.

g1081.d:
†γέννημα génnēma, ghen'-nay-mah; from G1080; offspring; by analogy, produce (literally or
 figuratively):—fruit, generation.
g1081.r: From γεννάω (G1080)|English: begat, be born, bear, gender, bring forth, be delivered, misc

g1082.d:
Γεννησαρέτ Gennēsarét, ghen-nay-sar-et'; of Hebrew origin (compare H3672); Gennesaret (i.e. Kinnereth), a lake
 and plain in Palestine:—Gennesaret.
g1082.r: Of Hebrew origin, cf כִּנְּרוֹת (H3672)|English: Chinnereth, Chinneroth, Cinneroth

g1084.d: γεννητός gennētós, ghen-nay-tos'; from G1080; born:—they that are born.
g1084.r: From γεννάω (G1080)|English: begat, be born, bear, gender, bring forth, be delivered, misc

g1085.d:
γένος génos, ghen'-os; from G1096; "kin" (abstract or concrete, literal or figurative,
 individual or collective):—born, country(-man), diversity,
 generation, kind(-red), nation, offspring, stock.
g1085.r: From γίνομαι (G1096)|English: be, come to pass, be made, be done, come, become, God forbid, arise, have, be fulfilled, be married to, be preferred, not tr, misc, vr done

g1086.d:
Γεργεσηνός Gergesēnós, gher-ghes-ay-nos'; of Hebrew origin (H1622); a Gergesene (i.e. Girgashite) or one of the
 aborigines of Palestine:—Gergesene.
g1086.r: Of Hebrew origin גִּרְגָּשִׁי (H1622)|English: Girgashite, Girgasite

g1087.d:
γερουσία gerousía, gher-oo-see'-ah; from G1088; the eldership, i.e. (collectively) the Jewish
 Sanhedrin:—senate.

g1088.d: γέρων gérōn, gher'-own; of uncertain affinity (compare G1094); aged:—old.
g1088.r: Of uncertain affinity, cf γῆρας (G1094)|English: old age

g1089.d:
γεύομαι geúomai, ghyoo'-om-ahee; a primary verb; to taste; by implication, to eat; figuratively, to
 experience (good or ill):—eat, taste.

g109.d:
ἀήρ aḗr, ah-ayr'; from ἄημι áēmi (to breathe unconsciously, i.e. respire; by analogy, to
 blow); "air" (as naturally circumambient):—air. Compare G5594.
g109.r: From aemi (to breathe unconsciously, i.e. respire; by analogy, to blow)|

g1090.d: γεωργέω geōrgéō, gheh-or-gheh'-o; from G1092; to till (the soil):—dress.

g1091.d:
γεώργιον geṓrgion, gheh-ore'-ghee-on; neuter of a (presumed) derivative of G1092; cultivable, i.e. a
 farm:—husbandry.
g1091.r: From a (presumed) derivative of γεωργός (G1092)|English: husbandman

g1092.d:
γεωργός geōrgós, gheh-ore-gos'; from G1093 and the base of G2041; a land-worker, i.e.
 farmer:—husbandman.
g1092.r: From γῆ (G1093) and the base of ἔργον (G2041)|English: earth, land, ground, country, world, earthly

g1093.d:
γῆ gē, ghay; contracted from a primary word; soil; by extension a region, or the
 solid part or the whole of the terrene globe (including the occupants
 in each application):—country, earth(-ly), ground, land, world.

g1094.d: γῆρας gēras, ghay'-ras; akin to G1088; senility:—old age.

g1095.d: γηράσκω gēráskō, ghay-ras'-ko; from G1094; to be senescent:—be (wax) old.

g1096.d:
γίνομαι gínomai, ghin'-om-ahee; a prolongation and middle voice form of a primary verb; to cause to be
 ("gen"-erate), i.e. (reflexively) to become (come into being), used
 with great latitude (literal, figurative, intensive, etc.):—arise, be
 assembled, be(-come, -fall, -have self), be brought (to pass), (be)
 come (to pass), continue, be divided, draw, be ended, fall, be
 finished, follow, be found, be fulfilled, + God forbid, grow, happen,
 have, be kept, be made, be married, be ordained to be, partake, pass,
 be performed, be published, require, seem, be showed, × soon as it
 was, sound, be taken, be turned, use, wax, will, would, be wrought.
g1096.r: A prolongation and middle voice form of a primary verb|

g1097.d:
γινώσκω ginṓskō, ghin-oce'-ko; a prolonged form of a primary verb; to "know" (absolutely) in a great
 variety of applications and with many implications (as follow, with
 others not thus clearly expressed):—allow, be aware (of), feel,
 (have) know(-ledge), perceived, be resolved, can speak, be sure,
 understand.
g1097.r: A prolonged form of a primary verb|

g1098.d:
γλεῦκος gleûkos, glyoo'-kos; akin to G1099; sweet wine, i.e. (properly) must (fresh juice), but used
 of the more saccharine (and therefore highly inebriating) fermented
 wine:—new wine.

g1099.d:
γλυκύς glykýs, gloo-koos'; of uncertain affinity; sweet (i.e. not bitter nor salt):—sweet,
 fresh.

g11.d:
Ἀβραάμ Abraám, ab-rah-am'; of Hebrew origin (H85); Abraham, the Hebrew patriarch:—Abraham. (In
 Acts 7:16 the text should probably read Jacob.)

g110.d:
ἀθανασία athanasía, ath-an-as-ee'-ah; from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and G2288; 
 deathlessness:—immortality.
g110.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and θάνατος (G2288)|English: Alpha

g1100.d:
γλῶσσα glōssa, gloce-sah'; of uncertain affinity; the tongue; by implication, a language
 (specially, one naturally unacquired):—tongue.

g1101.d:
γλωσσόκομον glōssókomon, gloce-sok'-om-on; from G1100 and the base of G2889; properly, a case (to keep mouthpieces
 of wind-instruments in) i.e. (by extension) a casket or (specially)
 purse:—bag.
g1101.r: From γλῶσσα (G1100) and the base of κόσμος (G2889)|English: tongue

g1102.d:
γναφεύς gnapheús, gnaf-yuce'; by variation for a derivative from κνάπτω knáptō (to tease cloth); a
 cloth-dresser:—fuller.
g1102.r: By variation for a derivative from knapto (to tease cloth)|

g1103.d:
γνήσιος gnḗsios, gnay'-see-os; from the same as G1077; legitimate (of birth), i.e. genuine:—own,
 sincerity, true.
g1103.r: From the same as γενέσια (G1077)|English: birthday

g1104.d: γνησίως gnēsíōs, gnay-see'-ose; adverb from G1103; genuinely, i.e. really:—naturally.

g1105.d: γνόφος gnóphos, gnof'-os; akin to G3509; gloom (as of a storm):—blackness.

g1106.d:
γνώμη gnṓmē, gno'-may; from G1097; cognition, i.e. (subjectively) opinion, or (objectively)
 resolve (counsel, consent, etc.):—advice, + agree, judgment, mind,
 purpose, will.
g1106.r: From γινώσκω (G1097)|English: know, perceive, understand, misc

g1107.d:
γνωρίζω gnōrízō, gno-rid'-zo; from a derivative of G1097; to make known; subjectively, to
 know:—certify, declare, make known, give to understand, do to wit,
 wot.
g1107.r: From a derivative of γινώσκω (G1097)|English: know, perceive, understand, misc

g1108.d:
γνῶσις gnōsis, gno'-sis; from G1097; knowing (the act), i.e. (by implication)
 knowledge:—knowledge, science.
g1108.r: From γινώσκω (G1097)|English: know, perceive, understand, misc

g1109.d: γνώστης gnṓstēs, gnoce'-tace; from G1097; a knower:—expert.
g1109.r: From γινώσκω (G1097)|English: know, perceive, understand, misc

g111.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of themis (statute, from the base of τίθημι (G5087))|English: Alpha

g1110.d: γνωστός gnōstós, gnoce-tos'; from G1097; well-known:—acquaintance, (which may be) known, notable.
g1110.r: From γινώσκω (G1097)|English: know, perceive, understand, misc

g1111.d: γογγύζω gongýzō, gong-good'-zo; of uncertain derivation; to grumble:—murmur.

g1112.d: γογγυσμός gongysmós, gong-goos-mos'; from G1111; a grumbling:—grudging, murmuring.

g1113.d: γογγυστής gongystḗs, gong-goos-tace'; from G1111; a grumbler:—murmurer.

g1114.d:
γόης góēs, go'-ace; from γοάω goáō (to wail); properly, a wizard (as muttering spells), i.e.
 (by implication) an imposter:—seducer.

g1115.d:
Γολγοθᾶ Golgothâ, gol-goth-ah'; of Chaldee origin (compare H1538); the skull; Golgotha, a knoll near
 Jerusalem:—Golgotha.
g1115.r: Of Aramaic origin [cf גֻּלְגֹּלֶת (H1538)]|English: poll, scull, every man, head

g1116.d:
Γόμοῤῥα Gómorrha, gom'-or-hrhah; of Hebrew origin (H6017); Gomorrha (i.e. Amorah), a place near the Dead
 Sea:—Gomorrha.

g1117.d:
γόμος gómos, gom'-os; from G1073; a load (as filling), i.e. (specially) a cargo, or (by
 extension) wares:—burden, merchandise.

g1118.d: γονεύς goneús, gon-yooce'; from the base of G1096; a parent:—parent.
g1118.r: From the base of γίνομαι (G1096)|English: be, come to pass, be made, be done, come, become, God forbid, arise, have, be fulfilled, be married to, be preferred, not tr, misc, vr done

g1119.d: γόνυ góny, gon-oo'; of uncertain affinity; the "knee":—knee(X -l).

g112.d: ἄθεος átheos, ath'-eh-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G2316; godless:—without God.
g112.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and θεός (G2316)|English: Alpha

g1120.d:
γονυπετέω gonypetéō, gon-oo-pet-eh'-o; from a compound of G1119 and the alternate of G4098; to fall on the
 knee:—bow the knee, kneel down.
g1120.r: From a compound of γόνυ (G1119) and the alternate of πίπτω (G4098)|English: knee, kneel

g1121.d:
γράμμα grámma, gram'-mah; from G1125; a writing, i.e. a letter, note, epistle, book, etc.; plural
 learning:—bill, learning, letter, scripture, writing, written.

g1122.d:
γραμματεύς grammateús, gram-mat-yooce'; from G1121. a writer, i.e. (professionally) scribe or
 secretary:—scribe, town-clerk.
g1122.r: From γράμμα (G1121)|English: letter, bill, writing, learning, scripture, written

g1123.d: γραπτός graptós, grap-tos'; from G1125; inscribed (figuratively):—written.

g1124.d:
γραφή graphḗ, graf-ay'; from G1125; a document, i.e. holy Writ (or its contents or a statement in
 it):—scripture.

g1125.d:
†γράφω gráphō, graf'-o; a primary verb; to "grave", especially to write; figuratively, to
 describe:—describe, write(-ing, -ten).

g1126.d:
γραώδης graṓdēs, grah-o'-dace; from γραύς graús (an old woman) and G1491; crone-like, i.e. silly:—old
 wives'.
g1126.r: From graus (an old woman) and εἶδος (G1491)|English: shape, fashion, sight, appearance

g1127.d:
γρηγορεύω grēgoreúō, gray-gor-yoo'-o; from G1453; to keep awake, i.e. watch (literally or figuratively):—be
 vigilant, wake, (be) watch(-ful).
g1127.r: From ἐγείρω (G1453)|English: rise, raise, arise, raise up, rise up, rise again, raise again, misc

g1128.d:
γυμνάζω gymnázō, goom-nad'-zo; from G1131; to practise naked (in the games), i.e. train
 (figuratively):—exercise.

g1129.d: γυμνασία gymnasía, goom-nas-ee'-ah; from G1128; training, i.e. (figuratively) asceticism:—exercise.

g113.d:
ἄθεσμος áthesmos, ath'-es-mos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G5087 (in the sense
 of enacting); lawless, i.e. (by implication) criminal:—wicked.
g113.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of τίθημι (G5087) (in the sense of enacting)|English: Alpha

g1130.d:
γυμνητεύω gymnēteúō, goom-nayt-yoo'-o; from a derivative of G1131; to strip, i.e. (reflexively) go poorly
 clad:—be naked.
g1130.r: From a derivative of γυμνός (G1131)|English: naked, bare

g1131.d:
γυμνός gymnós, goom-nos'; of uncertain affinity; nude (absolute or relative, literal or
 figurative):—naked.

g1132.d: γυμνότης gymnótēs, goom-not'-ace; from G1131; nudity (absolute or comparative):—nakedness.

g1133.d: γυναικάριον gynaikárion, goo-nahee-kar'-ee-on; a diminutive from G1135; a little (i.e. foolish) woman:—silly woman.
g1133.r: A diminutive from γυνή (G1135)|English: women, wife

g1134.d: γυναικεῖος gynaikeîos, goo-nahee-ki'-os; from G1135; feminine:—wife.

g1135.d:
γυνή gynḗ, goo-nay'; probably from the base of G1096; a woman; specially, a wife:—wife,
 woman.
g1135.r: Probably from the base of γίνομαι (G1096)|English: be, come to pass, be made, be done, come, become, God forbid, arise, have, be fulfilled, be married to, be preferred, not tr, misc, vr done

g1136.d:
Γώγ Gṓg, gogue; of Hebrew origin (H1463); Gog, a symbolic name for some future
 Antichrist:—Gog.

g1137.d: γωνία gōnía, go-nee'-ah; probably akin to G1119; an angle:—corner, quarter.
g1137.r: Probably akin to γόνυ (G1119)|English: knee, kneel

g1138.d:
†Δαβίδ Dabíd, dab-eed'; of Hebrew origin (H1732); Dabid (i.e. David), the Israelite
 king:—David.

g1139.d:
δαιμονίζομαι daimonízomai, dahee-mon-id'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G1142; to be exercised by a dæmon:—have a (be vexed
 with, be possessed with) devil(-s).
g1139.r: Middle voice from δαίμων (G1142)|English: devils, devil

g114.d:
ἀθετέω athetéō, ath-et-eh'-o; from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of
 G5087; to set aside, i.e. (by implication) to disesteem, neutralize or
 violate:—cast off, despise, disannul, frustrate, bring to nought,
 reject.
g114.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of τίθημι (G5087)|English: Alpha

g1140.d:
δαιμόνιον daimónion, dahee-mon'-ee-on; neuter of a derivative of G1142; a dæmonic being; by extension a
 deity:—devil, god.
g1140.r: Neuter of a derivative of δαίμων (G1142)|English: devils, devil

g1141.d: δαιμονιώδης daimoniṓdēs, dahee-mon-ee-o'-dace; from G1140 and G1142; dæmon-like:—devilish.
g1141.r: From δαιμόνιον (G1140) and δαίμων (G1142)|English: devil, god

g1142.d:
δαίμων daímōn, dah'-ee-mown; from δαίω daíō (to distribute fortunes); a dæmon or supernatural spirit (of
 a bad nature):—devil.

g1143.d:
δάκνω dáknō, dak'-no; a prolonged form of a primary root; to bite, i.e. (figuratively)
 thwart:—bite.
g1143.r: A prolonged form of a primary root|

g1144.d: δάκρυ dákry, dak'-roo; of uncertain affinity; a tear:—tear.

g1145.d: δακρύω dakrýō, dak-roo'-o; from G1144; to shed tears:—weep. Compare G2799.

g1146.d: δακτύλιος daktýlios, dak-too'-lee-os; from G1147; a finger-ring:—ring.

g1147.d: δάκτυλος dáktylos, dak'-too-los; probably from G1176; a finger:—finger.

g1148.d:
Δαλμανουθά Dalmanouthá, dal-man-oo-thah'; probably of Chaldee origin; Dalmanutha, a place in
 Palestine:—Dalmanutha.

g1149.d:
Δαλματία Dalmatía, dal-mat-ee'-ah; probably of foreign derivation; Dalmatia, a region of
 Europe:—Dalmatia.

g115.d:
ἀθέτησις athétēsis, ath-et'-ay-sis; from G114; cancellation (literally or figuratively):—disannulling, put
 away.
g115.r: From ἀθετέω (G114)|English: despise, reject, bring to nothing, frustrate, disannul, cast off

g1150.d:
δαμάζω damázō, dam-ad'-zo; a variation of an obsolete primary of the same meaning; to
 tame:—tame.
g1150.r: A variation of an obsolete primary of the same meaning|

g1151.d: δάμαλις dámalis, dam'-al-is; probably from the base of G1150; a heifer (as tame):—heifer.
g1151.r: Probably from the base of δαμάζω (G1150)|English: tame

g1152.d:
Δάμαρις Dámaris, dam'-ar-is; probably from the base of G1150; perhaps gentle; Damaris, an Athenian
 woman:—Damaris.
g1152.r: Probably from the base of δαμάζω (G1150)|English: tame

g1153.d: Δαμασκηνός Damaskēnós, dam-as-kay-nos'; from G1154; a Damascene or inhabitant of Damascus:—Damascene.

g1154.d: Δαμασκός Damaskós, dam-as-kos'; of Hebrew origin (H1834); Damascus, a city of Syria:—Damascus.
g1154.r: Of Hebrew origin דַּמֶּשֶׂק (H1834)|English: Damascus, Syriadamascus

g1155.d: †δανείζω daneízō, dan-ide'-zo; from G1156; to loan on interest; reflexively, to borrow:—borrow, lend.

g1156.d: δάνειον dáneion, dan'-i-on; from δάνος dános (a gift); probably akin to the base of G1325; a loan:—debt.

g1157.d: †δανειστής daneistḗs, dan-ice-tace'; from G1155; a lender:—creditor.

g1158.d: Δανιήλ Daniḗl, dan-ee-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H1840); Daniel, an Israelite:—Daniel.

g1159.d:
δαπανάω dapanáō, dap-an-ah'-o; from G1160; to expend, i.e. (in a good sense) to incur cost, or (in a
 bad one) to waste:—be at charges, consume, spend.

g116.d:
Ἀθῆναι Athēnai, ath-ay-nahee; plural of Ἀθήνη Athḗnē (the goddess of wisdom, who was reputed to have
 founded the city); Athenæ, the capitol of Greece:—Athens.
g116.r: Plural of Athene (the goddess of wisdom, who was reputed to have founded the city)|

g1160.d: δαπάνη dapánē, dap-an'-ay; from δάπτω dáptō (to devour); expense (as consuming):—cost.

g1161.d:
δέ dé, deh; a primary particle (adversative or continuative); but, and,
 etc.:—also, and, but, moreover, now (often unexpressed in English).

g1162.d: δέησις déēsis, deh'-ay-sis; from G1189; a petition:—prayer, request, supplication.
g1162.r: From δέομαι (G1189)|English: pray, beseech, make request

g1163.d:
†δεῖ deî, die; 3rd person singular active present of G1210; also deon deh-on'; neuter
 active participle of the same; both used impersonally; it is (was,
 etc.) necessary (as binding):—behoved, be meet, must (needs), (be)
 need(-ful), ought, should.
g1163.r: Third person singular active present of δέω (G1210)|English: bind, tie, knit, be in bonds, wind

g1164.d: δεῖγμα deîgma, digh'-mah; from the base of G1166; a specimen (as shown):—example.
g1164.r: From the base of δεικνύω (G1166)|English: show

g1165.d: δειγματίζω deigmatízō, digh-mat-id'-zo; from G1164; to exhibit:—make a shew.

g1166.d:
†δεικνύω deiknýō, dike-noo'-o; a prolonged form of an obsolete primary of the same meaning; to show
 (literally or figuratively):—shew.
g1166.r: A prolonged form of an obsolete primary of the same meaning|

g1167.d: δειλία deilía, di-lee'-ah; from G1169; timidity:—fear.

g1168.d: δειλιάω deiliáō, di-lee-ah'-o; from G1167; to be timid:—be afraid.

g1169.d: δειλός deilós, di-los'; from δεός deós (dread); timid, i.e. (by implication) faithless:—fearful.

g117.d: Ἀθηναῖος Athēnaîos, ath-ay-nah'-yos; from G116; an Athenæan or inhabitant of Athenæ:—Athenian.

g1170.d:
δεῖνα deîna, di'-nah; probably from the same as G1171 (through the idea of forgetting the
 name as fearful, i.e. strange); so and so (when the person is not
 specified):—such a man.
g1170.r: Probably from the same as δεινῶς (G1171) (through the idea of forgetting the name as fearful, i.e. strange)|English: grievously, vehemently

g1171.d:
δεινῶς deinōs, di-noce'; adverb from a derivative of the same as G1169; terribly, i.e.
 excessively:—grievously, vehemently.
g1171.r: From a derivative of the same as δειλός (G1169)|English: fearful

g1172.d:
δειπνέω deipnéō, dipe-neh'-o; from G1173; to dine, i.e. take the principle (or evening) meal:—sup (X
 -er).

g1173.d:
δεῖπνον deîpnon, dipe'-non; from the same as G1160; dinner, i.e. the chief meal (usually in the
 evening):—feast, supper.
g1173.r: From the same as δαπάνη (G1160)|English: cost

g1174.d:
†δεισιδαιμονέστερος deisidaimonésteros, dice-ee-dahee-mon-es'-ter-os; the compound of a derivative of the base of G1169 and G1142; more
 religious than others:—too superstitious.
g1174.r: The compound of a derivative of the base of δειλός (G1169) and δαίμων (G1142)|English: fearful

g1175.d: δεισιδαιμονία deisidaimonía, dice-ee-dahee-mon-ee'-ah; from the same as G1174; religion:—superstition.
g1175.r: From the same as δεισιδαίμων (G1174)|English: too superstitious

g1176.d: δέκα déka, dek'-ah; a primary number; ten:—(eight-)een, ten.

g1177.d: δεκαδύο dekadýo, dek-ad-oo'-o; from G1176 and G1417; two and ten, i.e. twelve:—twelve.
g1177.r: From δέκα (G1176) and δύο (G1417)|English: ten, eighteen

g1178.d: δεκαπέντε dekapénte, dek-ap-en'-teh; from G1176 and G4002; ten and five, i.e. fifteen:—fifteen.
g1178.r: From δέκα (G1176) and πέντε (G4002)|English: ten, eighteen

g1179.d:
Δεκάπολις Dekápolis, dek-ap'-ol-is; from G1176 and G4172; the ten-city region; the Decapolis, a district in
 Syria:—Decapolis.
g1179.r: From δέκα (G1176) and πόλις (G4172)|English: ten, eighteen

g118.d:
ἀθλέω athléō, ath-leh'-o; from ἄθλος áthlos (a contest in the public lists); to contend in the
 competitive games:—strive.
g118.r: From athlos (a contest in the public lists)|

g1180.d: δεκατέσσαρες dekatéssares, dek-at-es'-sar-es; from G1176 and G5064; ten and four, i.e. fourteen:—fourteen.
g1180.r: From δέκα (G1176) and τέσσαρες (G5064)|English: ten, eighteen

g1182.d: δέκατος dékatos, dek'-at-os; ordinal from G1176; tenth:—tenth.

g1183.d:
δεκατόω dekatóō, dek-at-o'-o; from G1181; to tithe, i.e. to give or take a tenth:—pay (receive)
 tithes.
g1183.r: From δεκάτη (G1181)|English: tithe, tenth part, tenth

g1184.d: δεκτός dektós, dek-tos'; from G1209; approved; (figuratively) propitious:—accepted(-table).
g1184.r: From δέχομαι (G1209)|English: receive, take, accept, take up

g1185.d:
δελεάζω deleázō, del-eh-ad'-zo; from the base of G1388; to entrap, i.e. (figuratively) delude:—allure,
 beguile, entice.
g1185.r: From the base of δόλος (G1388)|English: guile, subtilty, deceit, craft

g1186.d: δένδρον déndron, den'-dron; probably from δρύς drýs (an oak); a tree:—tree.

g1187.d:
δεξιολάβος dexiolábos, dex-ee-ol-ab'-os; from G1188 and G2983; a guardsman (as if taking the right) or
 light-armed soldier:—spearman.
g1187.r: From δεξιός (G1188) and λαμβάνω (G2983)|English: right hand, right, right side

g1188.d:
δεξιός dexiós, dex-ee-os'; from G1209; the right side or (feminine) hand (as that which usually
 takes):—right (hand, side).
g1188.r: From δέχομαι (G1209)|English: receive, take, accept, take up

g1189.d:
δέομαι déomai, deh'-om-ahee; middle voice of G1210; to beg (as binding oneself), i.e.
 petition:—beseech, pray (to), make request. Compare G4441.
g1189.r: Middle voice of δέω (G1210)|English: bind, tie, knit, be in bonds, wind

g119.d: ἄθλησις áthlēsis, ath'-lay-sis; from G118; a struggle (figuratively):—fight.

g1190.d: Δερβαῖος Derbaîos, der-bah'-ee-os; from G1191; a Derbæan or inhabitant of Derbe:—of Derbe.

g1191.d: Δέρβη Dérbē, der-bay'; of foreign origin; Derbe, a place in Asia Minor:—Derbe.

g1192.d: δέρμα dérma, der'-mah; from G1194; a hide:—skin.

g1193.d: δερμάτινος dermátinos, der-mat'-ee-nos; from G1192; made of hide:—leathern, of a skin.

g1194.d:
δέρω dérō, der'-o; a primary verb; properly, to flay, i.e. (by implication) to scourge,
 or (by analogy) to thrash:—beat, smite.

g1195.d:
δεσμεύω desmeúō, des-myoo'-o; from a (presumed) derivative of G1196; to be a binder (captor), i.e. to
 enchain (a prisoner), to tie on (a load):—bind.
g1195.r: From a (presumed) derivative of δεσμέω (G1196)|English: bind

g1197.d: δέσμη désmē, des-may'; from G1196; a bundle:—bundle.

g1198.d: δέσμιος désmios, des'-mee-os; from G1199; a captive (as bound):—in bonds, prisoner.
g1198.r: From δεσμός (G1199)|English: bond, band, string, chain

g1199.d:
δεσμόν desmón, des-mon'; neuter and masculine respectively from G1210; a band, i.e. ligament (of
 the body) or shackle (of a prisoner); figuratively, an impediment or
 disability:—band, bond, chain, string.
g1199.r: Neuter and masculine respectively from δέω (G1210)|English: bind, tie, knit, be in bonds, wind

g12.d:
ἄβυσσος ábyssos, ab'-us-sos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a variation of G1037; depthless,
 i.e. (specially) (infernal) "abyss":—deep, (bottomless) pit.
g12.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a variation of βυθός (G1037)|English: Alpha

g120.d:
ἀθυμέω athyméō, ath-oo-meh'-o; from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and G2372; to be
 spiritless, i.e. disheartened:—be dismayed.
g120.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and θυμός (G2372)|English: Alpha

g1200.d:
δεσμοφύλαξ desmophýlax, des-mof-oo'-lax; from G1199 and G5441; a jailer (as guarding the prisoners):—jailor,
 keeper of the prison.
g1200.r: From δεσμός (G1199) and φύλαξ (G5441)|English: bond, band, string, chain

g1201.d:
δεσμωτήριον desmōtḗrion, des-mo-tay'-ree-on; from a derivative of G1199 (equivalent to G1196); a place of bondage,
 i.e. a dungeon:—prison.
g1201.r: From a derivative of δεσμός (G1199) (equivalent to δεσμέω (G1196))|English: bond, band, string, chain

g1202.d: δεσμώτης desmṓtēs, des-mo'-tace; from the same as G1201; (passively) a captive:—prisoner.
g1202.r: From the same as δεσμωτήριον (G1201)|English: prison

g1203.d:
δεσπότης despótēs, des-pot'-ace; perhaps from G1210 and πόσις pósis (a husband); an absolute ruler
 ("despot"):—Lord, master.
g1203.r: Perhaps from δέω (G1210) and posis (a husband)|English: bind, tie, knit, be in bonds, wind

g1204.d:
δεῦρο deûro, dyoo'-ro; of uncertain affinity; here; used also imperative hither!; and of
 time, hitherto:—come (hither), hither(-to).

g1205.d:
δεῦτε deûte, dyoo'-teh; from G1204 and an imperative form of εἶμι eîmi (to go); come hither!:—come,
 × follow.
g1205.r: From δεῦρο (G1204) and an imperative form of eimi (to go)|English: come, come hither, hitherto

g1206.d: δευτεραῖος deuteraîos, dyoo-ter-ah'-yos; from G1208; secondary, i.e. (specially) on the second day:—next day.
g1206.r: From δεύτερος (G1208)|English: second, the second time, the second time, again, again, secondarily, afterward

g1208.d:
δεύτερος deúteros, dyoo'-ter-os; as the comparative of G1417; (ordinal) second (in time, place, or rank;
 also adverb):—afterward, again, second(-arily, time).
g1208.r: As the compare of δύο (G1417)|English: two, twain, both, two and two

g1209.d:
δέχομαι déchomai, dekh'-om-ahee; middle voice of a primary verb; to receive (in various applications,
 literally or figuratively):—accept, receive, take. Compare G2983.
g1209.r: Middle voice of a primary verb|

g121.d:
†ἄθωος áthōos, ath'-o-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and probably a derivative of G5087
 (meaning a penalty); not guilty:—innocent.
g121.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and probably a derivative of τίθημι (G5087) (meaning a penalty)|English: Alpha

g1210.d:
δέω déō, deh'-o; a primary verb; to bind (in various applications, literally or
 figuratively):—bind, be in bonds, knit, tie, wind. See also G1163,
 G1189.

g1211.d:
δή dḗ, day; probably akin to G1161; a particle of emphasis or explicitness; now,
 then, etc.:—also, and, doubtless, now, therefore.
g1211.r: Probably akin to δέ (G1161)|English: but, and, now, then, also, yet, yea, so, moreover, nevertheless, for, even, misc, not tr

g1212.d: δῆλος dēlos, day'-los; of uncertain derivation; clear:—+ bewray, certain, evident, manifest.

g1213.d: δηλόω dēlóō, day-lo'-o; from G1212; to make plain (by words):—declare, shew, signify.
g1213.r: From δῆλος (G1212)|English: bewray, manifest, evident, certain

g1214.d: Δημᾶς Dēmâs, day-mas'; probably for G1216; Demas, a Christian:—Demas.

g1215.d:
δημηγορέω dēmēgoréō, day-may-gor-eh'-o; from a compound of G1218 and G58; to be a people-gatherer, i.e. to
 address a public assembly:—make an oration.
g1215.r: From a compound of δῆμος (G1218) and ἀγορά (G58)|English: people

g1216.d:
Δημήτριος Dēmḗtrios, day-may'-tree-os; from Δημήτηρ Dēmḗtēr (Ceres); Demetrius, the name of an Ephesian and of a
 Christian:—Demetrius.

g1217.d:
δημιουργός dēmiourgós, day-me-oor-gos'; from G1218 and G2041; a worker for the people, i.e. mechanic (spoken of
 the Creator):—maker.

g1218.d: δῆμος dēmos, day'-mos; from G1210; the public (as bound together socially):—people.
g1218.r: From δέω (G1210)|English: bind, tie, knit, be in bonds, wind

g1219.d:
δημόσιος dēmósios, day-mos'ee-os; from G1218; public; (feminine singular dative case as adverb) in
 public:—common, openly, publickly.

g122.d: αἴγειος aígeios, ah'-ee-ghi-os; from αἴξ aíx (a goat); belonging to a goat:—goat.

g1220.d: δηνάριον dēnárion, day-nar'-ee-on; of Latin origin; a denarius (or ten asses):—pence, penny(-worth).

g1222.d:
δήπου dḗpou, day'-poo; from G1211 and G4225; a particle of asseveration; indeed
 doubtless:—verily.
g1222.r: From δή (G1211) and πού (G4225)|English: also, now, and, therefore, doubtless, not tr

g1223.d:
διά diá, dee-ah'; a primary preposition denoting the channel of an act; through (in very
 wide applications, local, causal, or occasional):—after, always,
 among, at, to avoid, because of (that), briefly, by, for (cause) …
 fore, from, in, by occasion of, of, by reason of, for sake, that,
 thereby, therefore, × though, through(-out), to, wherefore, with
 (-in).
g1223.r: A primary preposition denoting the channel of an act|

g1224.d: διαβαίνω diabaínō, dee-ab-ah'-ee-no; from G1223 and the base of G939; to cross:—come over, pass (through).
g1224.r: From διά (G1223) and the base of βάσις (G939)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1225.d: διαβάλλω diabállō, dee-ab-al'-lo; from G1223 and G906; (figuratively) to traduce:—accuse.
g1225.r: From διά (G1223) and βάλλω (G906)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1226.d:
διαβεβαιόομαι diabebaióomai, dee-ab-eb-ahee-o'-om-ahee; middle voice of a compound of G1223 and G950; to confirm thoroughly (by
 words), i.e. asseverate:—affirm constantly.
g1226.r: Middle voice of a compound of διά (G1223) and βεβαιόω (G950)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1227.d:
διαβλέπω diablépō, dee-ab-lep'-o; from G1223 and G991; to look through, i.e. recover full vision:—see
 clearly.
g1227.r: From διά (G1223) and βλέπω (G991)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1228.d:
διάβολος diábolos, dee-ab'-ol-os; from G1225; a traducer; specially, Satan (compare H7854):—false
 accuser, devil, slanderer.

g1229.d:
διαγγέλλω diangéllō, de-ang-gel'-lo; from G1223 and the base of G32; to herald thoroughly:—declare, preach,
 signify.
g1229.r: From διά (G1223) and the base of ἄγγελος (G32)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g123.d:
αἰγιαλός aigialós, ahee-ghee-al-os'; from ἀΐσσω aḯssō (to rush) and G251 (in the sense of the sea; a beach (on
 which the waves dash):—shore.
g123.r: From aisso (to rush) and ἅλς (G251) (in the sense of the sea)|English: salt

g1230.d: διαγίνομαι diagínomai, dee-ag-in'-om-ahee; from G1223 and G1096; to elapse meanwhile:—X after, be past, be spent.
g1230.r: From διά (G1223) and γίνομαι (G1096)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1231.d:
διαγινώσκω diaginṓskō, dee-ag-in-o'-sko; from G1223 and G1097; to know thoroughly, i.e. ascertain
 exactly:—(would) enquire, know the uttermost.
g1231.r: From διά (G1223) and γινώσκω (G1097)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1233.d: διάγνωσις diágnōsis, dee-ag'-no-sis; from G1231; (magisterial) examination ("diagnosis"):—hearing.
g1233.r: From διαγινώσκω (G1231)|English: enquire, know the uttermost

g1234.d: διαγογγύζω diagongýzō, dee-ag-ong-good'-zo; from G1223 and G1111; to complain throughout a crowd:—murmur.
g1234.r: From διά (G1223) and γογγύζω (G1111)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1235.d: διαγρηγορέω diagrēgoréō, dee-ag-ray-gor-eh'-o; from G1223 and G1127; to waken thoroughly:—be awake.
g1235.r: From διά (G1223) and γρηγορέω (G1127)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1236.d: διάγω diágō, dee-ag'-o; from G1223 and G71; to pass time or life:—lead life, living.
g1236.r: From διά (G1223) and ἄγω (G71)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1237.d:
διαδέχομαι diadéchomai, dee-ad-ekh'-om-ahee; from G1223 and G1209; to receive in turn, i.e. (figuratively) succeed
 to:—come after.
g1237.r: From διά (G1223) and δέχομαι (G1209)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1238.d:
διάδημα diádēma, dee-ad'-ay-mah; from a compound of G1223 and G1210; a "diadem" (as bound about the
 head):—crown. Compare G4735.
g1238.r: From a compound of διά (G1223) and δέω (G1210)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1239.d:
διαδίδωμι diadídōmi, dee-ad-id'-o-mee; from G1223 and G1325; to give throughout a crowd, i.e. deal out; also to
 deliver over (as to a successor):—(make) distribute(-ion), divide,
 give.
g1239.r: From διά (G1223) and δίδωμι (G1325)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g124.d: Αἰγύπτιος Aigýptios, ahee-goop'-tee-os; from G125; an Ægyptian or inhabitant of Ægyptus:—Egyptian.

g1240.d: διάδοχος diádochos, dee-ad'-okh-os; from G1237; a successor in office:—room.

g1241.d: διαζώννυμι diazṓnnymi, dee-az-own'-noo-mee; from G1223 and G2224; to gird tightly:—gird.
g1241.r: From διά (G1223) and ζώννυμι (G2224)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1242.d:
διαθήκη diathḗkē, dee-ath-ay'-kay; from G1303; properly, a disposition, i.e. (specially) a contract
 (especially a devisory will):—covenant, testament.

g1243.d:
διαίρεσις diaíresis, dee-ah'-ee-res-is; from G1244; a distinction or (concretely) variety:—difference,
 diversity.

g1244.d: διαιρέω diairéō, dee-ahee-reh'-o; from G1223 and G138; to separate, i.e. distribute:—divide.
g1244.r: From διά (G1223) and αἱρέω (G138)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1245.d:
†διακαθαρίζω diakatharízō, dee-ak-ath-ar-id'-zo; from G1223 and G2511; to cleanse perfectly, i.e. (specially)
 winnow:—thoroughly purge.
g1245.r: From διά (G1223) and καθαρίζω (G2511)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1246.d:
διακατελέγχομαι diakatelénchomai, dee-ak-at-el-eng'-khom-ahee; middle voice from G1223 and a compound of G2596 and G1651; to prove
 downright, i.e. confute:—convince.
g1246.r: Middle voice from διά (G1223) and a compound of κατά (G2596) and ἐλέγχω (G1651)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1247.d:
διακονέω diakonéō, dee-ak-on-eh'-o; from G1249; to be an attendant, i.e. wait upon (menially or as a host,
 friend, or (figuratively) teacher); technically, to act as a Christian
 deacon:—(ad-)minister (unto), serve, use the office of a deacon.

g1248.d:
διακονία diakonía, dee-ak-on-ee'-ah; from G1249; attendance (as a servant, etc.); figuratively
 (eleemosynary) aid, (official) service (especially of the Christian
 teacher, or technically of the diaconate):—(ad-)minister(-ing,
 -tration, -try), office, relief, service(-ing).

g1249.d:
διάκονος diákonos, dee-ak'-on-os; probably from an obsolete διάκω diákō (to run on errands; compare G1377); an
 attendant, i.e. (genitive case) a waiter (at table or in other menial
 duties); specially, a Christian teacher and pastor (technically, a
 deacon or deaconess):—deacon, minister, servant.
g1249.r: Probably from an obsolete diako (to run on errands, cf διώκω (G1377))|English: persecute, follow after, follow, suffer persecution, misc

g125.d: Αἴγυπτος Aígyptos, ah'-ee-goop-tos; of uncertain derivation; Ægyptus, the land of the Nile:—Egypt.

g1250.d: διακόσιοι diakósioi, dee-ak-os'-ee-oy; from G1364 and G1540; two hundred:—two hundred.
g1250.r: From δίς (G1364) and ἑκατόν (G1540)|English: twice, again

g1251.d:
†διακούομαι diakoúomai, dee-ak-oo'-om-ahee; middle voice from G1223 and G191; to hear throughout, i.e. patiently
 listen (to a prisoner's plea):—hear.
g1251.r: Middle voice from διά (G1223) and ἀκούω (G191)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1252.d:
διακρίνω diakrínō, dee-ak-ree'-no; from G1223 and G2919; to separate thoroughly, i.e. (literally and
 reflexively) to withdraw from, or (by implication) oppose;
 figuratively, to discriminate (by implication, decide), or
 (reflexively) hesitate:—contend, make (to) differ(-ence), discern,
 doubt, judge, be partial, stagger, waver.
g1252.r: From διά (G1223) and κρίνω (G2919)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1253.d: διάκρισις diákrisis, dee-ak'-ree-sis; from G1252; judicial estimation:—discern(-ing), disputation.
g1253.r: From διακρίνω (G1252)|English: doubt, judge, discern, contend, waver, misc

g1254.d:
διακωλύω diakōlýō, dee-ak-o-loo'-o; from G1223 and G2967; to hinder altogether, i.e. utterly
 prohibit:—forbid.
g1254.r: From διά (G1223) and κωλύω (G2967)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1255.d:
διαλαλέω dialaléō, dee-al-al-eh'-o; from G1223 and G2980; to talk throughout a company, i.e. converse or
 (genitive case) publish:—commune, noise abroad.
g1255.r: From διά (G1223) and λαλέω (G2980)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1256.d:
διαλέγομαι dialégomai, dee-al-eg'-om-ahee; middle voice from G1223 and G3004; to say thoroughly, i.e. discuss (in
 argument or exhortation):—dispute, preach (unto), reason (with),
 speak.
g1256.r: Middle voice from διά (G1223) and λέγω (G3004)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1257.d: διαλείπω dialeípō, dee-al-i'-po; from G1223 and G3007; to leave off in the middle, i.e. intermit:—cease.
g1257.r: From διά (G1223) and λείπω (G3007)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1258.d: διάλεκτος diálektos, dee-al'-ek-tos; from G1256; a (mode of) discourse, i.e. "dialect":—language, tongue.
g1258.r: From διαλέγομαι (G1256)|English: dispute, reason with, reason, preach unto, preach, speak

g1259.d:
διαλλάσσω diallássō, dee-al-las'-so; from G1223 and G236; to change thoroughly, i.e. (mentally) to
 conciliate:—reconcile.
g1259.r: From διά (G1223) and ἀλλάσσω (G236)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g126.d:
ἀΐδιος aḯdios, ah-id'-ee-os; from G104; everduring (forward and backward, or forward
 only):—eternal, everlasting.

g1260.d:
διαλογίζομαι dialogízomai, dee-al-og-id'-zom-ahee; from G1223 and G3049; to reckon thoroughly, i.e. (genitive case) to
 deliberate (by reflection or discussion):—cast in mind, consider,
 dispute, muse, reason, think.
g1260.r: From διά (G1223) and λογίζομαι (G3049)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1261.d:
διαλογισμός dialogismós, dee-al-og-is-mos'; from G1260; discussion, i.e. (internal) consideration (by implication,
 purpose), or (external) debate:—dispute, doubtful(-ing), imagination,
 reasoning, thought.
g1261.r: From διαλογίζομαι (G1260)|English: reason, dispute, cast in the mind, muse, think, consider

g1262.d: διαλύω dialýō, dee-al-oo'-o; from G1223 and G3089; to dissolve utterly:—scatter.
g1262.r: From διά (G1223) and λύω (G3089)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1263.d:
διαμαρτύρομαι diamartýromai, dee-am-ar-too'-rom-ahee; from G1223 and G3140; to attest or protest earnestly, or (by
 implication) hortatively:—charge, testify (unto), witness.
g1263.r: From διά (G1223) and μαρτυρέω (G3140)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1264.d: διαμάχομαι diamáchomai, dee-am-akh'-om-ahee; from G1223 and G3164; to fight fiercely (in altercation):—strive.
g1264.r: From διά (G1223) and μάχομαι (G3164)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1265.d:
διαμένω diaménō, dee-am-en'-o; from G1223 and G3306; to stay constantly (in being or
 relation):—continue, remain.
g1265.r: From διά (G1223) and μένω (G3306)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1266.d:
διαμερίζω diamerízō, dee-am-er-id'-zo; from G1223 and G3307; to partition thoroughly (literally in
 distribution, figuratively in dissension):—cloven, divide, part.
g1266.r: From διά (G1223) and μερίζω (G3307)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1267.d: διαμερισμός diamerismós, dee-am-er-is-mos'; from G1266; disunion (of opinion and conduct):—division.

g1268.d:
διανέμω dianémō, dee-an-em'-o; from G1223 and the base of G3551; to distribute, i.e. (of information)
 to disseminate:—spread.
g1268.r: From διά (G1223) and the base of νόμος (G3551)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1269.d:
διανεύω dianeúō, dee-an-yoo'-o; from G1223 and G3506; to nod (or express by signs) across an intervening
 space:—beckon.
g1269.r: From διά (G1223) and νεύω (G3506)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g127.d:
†αἰδώς aidṓs, ahee-doce'; perhaps from G1 (as a negative particle) and G1492 (through the idea of
 downcast eyes); bashfulness, i.e. (towards men), modesty or (towards
 God) awe:—reverence, shamefacedness.
g127.r: Perhaps from ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and εἴδω (G1492) (through the idea of downcast eyes)|English: Alpha

g1270.d:
διανόημα dianóēma, dee-an-o'-ay-mah; from a compound of G1223 and G3539; something thought through, i.e. a
 sentiment:—thought.
g1270.r: From a compound of διά (G1223) and νοέω (G3539)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1271.d:
διάνοια diánoia, dee-an'-oy-ah; from G1223 and G3563; deep thought, properly, the faculty (mind or its
 disposition), by implication, its exercise:—imagination, mind,
 understanding.
g1271.r: From διά (G1223) and νοῦς (G3563)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1272.d:
διανοίγω dianoígō, dee-an-oy'-go; from G1223 and G455; to open thoroughly, literally (as a first-born) or
 figuratively (to expound):—open.
g1272.r: From διά (G1223) and ἀνοίγω (G455)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1273.d:
διανυκτερεύω dianyktereúō, dee-an-ook-ter-yoo'-o; from G1223 and a derivative of G3571; to sit up the whole
 night:—continue all night.
g1273.r: From διά (G1223) and a derivative of νύξ (G3571)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1274.d: διανύω dianýō, dee-an-oo'-o; from G1223 and ἀνύω anýō (to effect); to accomplish thoroughly:—finish.
g1274.r: From διά (G1223) and anuo (to effect)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1275.d:
διαπαντός diapantós, dee-ap-an-tos'; from G1223 and the genitive case of G3956; through all time, i.e.
 (adverbially) constantly:—alway(-s), continually.
g1275.r: From διά (G1223) and the genit. of πᾶς (G3956)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1276.d:
διαπεράω diaperáō, dee-ap-er-ah'-o; from G1223 and a derivative of the base of G4008; to cross entirely:—go
 over, pass (over), sail over.
g1276.r: From διά (G1223) and a derivative of the base of πέραν (G4008)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1277.d: διαπλέω diapléō, dee-ap-leh'-o; from G1223 and G4126; to sail through:—sail over.
g1277.r: From διά (G1223) and πλέω (G4126)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1278.d:
†διαπονέω diaponéō, dee-ap-on-eh'-o; from G1223 and a derivative of G4192; to toil through, i.e. (passively)
 be worried:—be grieved.
g1278.r: From διά (G1223) and a derivative of πόνος (G4192)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1279.d:
διαπορεύομαι diaporeúomai, dee-ap-or-yoo'-om-ahee; from G1223 and G4198; to travel through:—go through, journey in, pass
 by.
g1279.r: From διά (G1223) and πορεύω (G4198)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g128.d:
Αἰθίοψ Aithíops, ahee-thee'-ops; from αἴθω aíthō (to scorch) and ὤψ ṓps (the face, from G3700); an Æthiopian (as
 a blackamoor):—Ethiopian.
g128.r: From aitho (to scorch) and ops (the face, from ὀπτάνομαι (G3700))|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g1280.d:
διαπορέω diaporéō, dee-ap-or-eh'-o; from G1223 and G639; to be thoroughly nonplussed:—(be in) doubt, be
 (much) perplexed.
g1280.r: From διά (G1223) and ἀπορέω (G639)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1281.d:
διαπραγματεύομαι diapragmateúomai, dee-ap-rag-mat-yoo'-om-ahee; from G1223 and G4231; to thoroughly occupy oneself, i.e. (transitively
 and by implication) to earn in business:—gain by trading.
g1281.r: From διά (G1223) and πραγματεύομαι (G4231)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1282.d:
διαπρίω diapríō, dee-ap-ree'-o; from G1223 and the base of G4249; to saw asunder, i.e. (figuratively) to
 exasperate:—cut (to the heart).
g1282.r: From διά (G1223) and the base of πρίζω (G4249)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1283.d: διαρπάζω diarpázō, dee-ar-pad'-zo; from G1223 and G726; to seize asunder, i.e. plunder:—spoil.
g1283.r: From διά (G1223) and ἁρπάζω (G726)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1284.d: †διαῤῥήσσω diarrhḗssō, dee-ar-hrayce'-so; from G1223 and G4486; to tear asunder:—break, rend.
g1284.r: From διά (G1223) and ῥήγνυμι (G4486)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1285.d:
διασαφέω diasaphéō, dee-as-af-eh'-o; from G1223 and σαφής saphḗs (clear); to clear thoroughly, i.e. (figuratively)
 declare:—tell unto.
g1285.r: From διά (G1223) and saphes (clear)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1286.d:
διασείω diaseíō, dee-as-i'-o; from G1223 and G4579; to shake thoroughly, i.e. (figuratively) to
 intimidate:—do violence to.
g1286.r: From διά (G1223) and σείω (G4579)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1287.d:
διασκορπίζω diaskorpízō, dee-as-kor-pid'-zo; from G1223 and G4650; to dissipate, i.e. (genitive case) to rout or
 separate; specially, to winnow; figuratively, to squander:—disperse,
 scatter (abroad), strew, waste.
g1287.r: From διά (G1223) and σκορπίζω (G4650)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1288.d:
διασπάω diaspáō, dee-as-pah'-o; from G1223 and G4685; to draw apart, i.e. sever or dismember:—pluck
 asunder, pull in pieces.
g1288.r: From διά (G1223) and σπάω (G4685)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1289.d:
διασπείρω diaspeírō, dee-as-pi'-ro; from G1223 and G4687; to sow throughout, i.e. (figuratively) distribute
 in foreign lands:—scatter abroad.
g1289.r: From διά (G1223) and σπείρω (G4687)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g129.d:
αἷμα haîma, hah'-ee-mah; of uncertain derivation; blood, literally (of men or animals),
 figuratively (the juice of grapes) or specially (the atoning blood of
 Christ); by implication, bloodshed, also kindred:—blood.

g1290.d:
διασπορά diasporá, dee-as-por-ah'; from G1289; dispersion, i.e. (specially and concretely) the (converted)
 Israelite resident in Gentile countries:—(which are) scattered
 (abroad).

g1291.d:
†διαστέλλομαι diastéllomai, dee-as-tel'-lom-ahee; middle voice from G1223 and G4724; to set (oneself) apart (figuratively,
 distinguish), i.e. (by implication) to enjoin:—charge, that which was
 (give) commanded(-ment).
g1291.r: Middle voice from διά (G1223) and στέλλω (G4724)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1292.d: διάστημα diástēma, dee-as'-tay-mah; from G1339; an interval:—space.
g1292.r: From διΐστημι (G1339)|English: the space of ... after, go further, be parted

g1293.d: διαστολή diastolḗ, dee-as-tol-ay'; from G1291; a variation:—difference, distinction.
g1293.r: From διαστέλλω (G1291)|English: charge, give commandment, be commanded

g1294.d:
διαστρέφω diastréphō, dee-as-tref'-o; from G1223 and G4762; to distort, i.e. (figuratively) misinterpret, or
 (morally) corrupt:—perverse(-rt), turn away.
g1294.r: From διά (G1223) and στρέφω (G4762)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1295.d:
†διασώζω diasṓzō, dee-as-odze'-o; from G1223 and G4982; to save thoroughly, i.e. (by implication or
 analogy) to cure, preserve, rescue, etc.:—bring safe, escape (safe),
 heal, make perfectly whole, save.
g1295.r: From διά (G1223) and σῴζω (G4982)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1296.d: διαταγή diatagḗ, dee-at-ag-ay'; from G1299; arrangement, i.e. institution:—instrumentality.
g1296.r: From διατάσσω (G1299)|English: command, appoint, ordain, set in order, give order

g1297.d: διάταγμα diátagma, dee-at'-ag-mah; from G1299; an arrangement, i.e. (authoritative) edict:—commandment.
g1297.r: From διατάσσω (G1299)|English: command, appoint, ordain, set in order, give order

g1298.d:
διαταράσσω diatarássō, dee-at-ar-as'-so; from G1223 and G5015; to disturb wholly, i.e. agitate (with
 alarm):—trouble.
g1298.r: From διά (G1223) and ταράσσω (G5015)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1299.d:
διατάσσω diatássō, dee-at-as'-so; from G1223 and G5021; to arrange thoroughly, i.e. (specially) institute,
 prescribe, etc.:—appoint, command, give, (set in) order, ordain.
g1299.r: From διά (G1223) and τάσσω (G5021)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g13.d: Ἄγαβος Ágabos, ag'-ab-os; of Hebrew origin (compare H2285); Agabus, an Israelite:—Agabus.
g13.r: Of Hebrew origin, cf חָגָב (H2285)|English: Hagab

g130.d:
αἱματεκχυσία haimatekchysía, hahee-mat-ek-khoo-see'-ah; from G129 and a derivative of G1632; an effusion of blood:—shedding of
 blood.
g130.r: From αἷμα (G129) and a derivative of ἐκχέω (G1632)|English: blood

g1300.d:
διατελέω diateléō, dee-at-el-eh'-o; from G1223 and G5055; to accomplish thoroughly, i.e. (subjectively) to
 persist:—continue.
g1300.r: From διά (G1223) and τελέω (G5055)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1301.d:
διατηρέω diatēréō, dee-at-ay-reh'-o; from G1223 and G5083; to watch thoroughly, i.e. (positively and
 transitively) to observe strictly, or (negatively and reflexively) to
 avoid wholly:—keep.
g1301.r: From διά (G1223) and τηρέω (G5083)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1303.d:
†διατίθεμαι diatíthemai, dee-at-ith'-em-ahee; middle voice from G1223 and G5087; to put apart, i.e. (figuratively)
 dispose (by assignment, compact, or bequest):—appoint, make,
 testator.
g1303.r: Middle voice from διά (G1223) and τίθημι (G5087)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1304.d:
διατρίβω diatríbō, dee-at-ree'-bo; from G1223 and the base of G5147; to wear through (time), i.e.
 remain:—abide, be, continue, tarry.
g1304.r: From διά (G1223) and the base of τρίβος (G5147)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1305.d: διατροφή diatrophḗ, dee-at-rof-ay'; from a compound of G1223 and G5142; nourishment:—food.
g1305.r: From a compound of διά (G1223) and τρέφω (G5142)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1306.d: διαυγάζω diaugázō, dee-ow-gad'-zo; from G1223 and G826; to glimmer through, i.e. break (as day):—dawn.
g1306.r: From διά (G1223) and αὐγάζω (G826)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1308.d:
διαφέρω diaphérō, dee-af-er'-o; from G1223 and G5342; to bear through, i.e. (literally) transport;
 usually to bear apart, i.e. (objectively) to toss about (figuratively,
 report); subjectively, to "differ", or (by implication) surpass:—be
 better, carry, differ from, drive up and down, be (more) excellent,
 make matter, publish, be of more value.
g1308.r: From διά (G1223) and φέρω (G5342)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1309.d: διαφεύγω diapheúgō, dee-af-yoo'-go; from G1223 and G5343; to flee through, i.e. escape:—escape.
g1309.r: From διά (G1223) and φεύγω (G5343)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g131.d:
αἱμοῤῥέω haimorrhéō, hahee-mor-hreh'-o; from G129 and G4482; to flow blood, i.e. have a hæmorrhage:—diseased
 with an issue of blood.

g1310.d:
διαφημίζω diaphēmízō, dee-af-ay-mid'-zo; from G1223 and a derivative of G5345; to report thoroughly, i.e.
 divulgate:—blaze abroad, commonly report, spread abroad, fame.
g1310.r: From διά (G1223) and a derivative of φήμη (G5345)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1311.d:
διαφθείρω diaphtheírō, dee-af-thi'-ro; from G1225 and G5351; to rot thoroughly, i.e. (by implication) to ruin
 (passively, decay utterly, figuratively, pervert):—corrupt, destroy,
 perish.

g1312.d: διαφθορά diaphthorá, dee-af-thor-ah'; from G1311; decay:—corruption.

g1313.d:
διάφορος diáphoros, dee-af'-or-os; from G1308; varying; also surpassing:—differing, divers, more
 excellent.
g1313.r: From διαφέρω (G1308)|English: be better, be of more value, differ from, should carry, publish, drive up and down, misc

g1314.d: διαφυλάσσω diaphylássō, dee-af-oo-las'-so; from G1223 and G5442; to guard thoroughly, i.e. protect:—keep.
g1314.r: From διά (G1223) and φυλάσσω (G5442)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1315.d:
†διαχειρίζομαι diacheirízomai, dee-akh-i-rid'-zom-ahee; from G1223 and a derivative of G5495; to handle thoroughly, i.e. lay
 violent hands upon:—kill, slay.
g1315.r: From διά (G1223) and a derivative of χείρ (G5495)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1316.d:
διαχωρίζομαι diachōrízomai, dee-akh-o-rid'-zom-ahee; from G1223 and the middle voice of G5563; to remove (oneself) wholly,
 i.e. retire:—depart.
g1316.r: From διά (G1223) and the middle voice of χωρίζω (G5563)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1317.d: διδακτικός didaktikós, did-ak-tik-os'; from G1318; instructive ("didactic"):—apt to teach.

g1318.d:
διδακτός didaktós, did-ak-tos'; from G1321; (subjectively) instructed, or (objectively) communicated by
 teaching:—taught, which … teacheth.

g1319.d:
διδασκαλία didaskalía, did-as-kal-ee'-ah; from G1320; instruction (the function or the information):—doctrine,
 learning, teaching.
g1319.r: From διδάσκαλος (G1320)|English: Master (Jesus), teacher, master, doctor

g132.d: Αἰνέας Ainéas, ahee-neh'-as; of uncertain derivation; Ænĕas, an Israelite:—Æneas.

g1320.d:
διδάσκαλος didáskalos, did-as'-kal-os; from G1321; an instructor (genitive case or specially):—doctor,
 master, teacher.

g1321.d:
διδάσκω didáskō, did-as'-ko; a prolonged (causative) form of a primary verb δάω dáō (to learn); to
 teach (in the same broad application):—teach.
g1321.r: A prolonged (causative) form of a primary verb dao (to learn)|

g1322.d:
διδαχή didachḗ, did-akh-ay'; from G1321; instruction (the act or the matter):—doctrine, hath been
 taught.

g1323.d: δίδραχμον dídrachmon, did'-rakh-mon; from G1364 and G1406; a double drachma (didrachm):—tribute.
g1323.r: From δίς (G1364) and δραχμή (G1406)|English: twice, again

g1324.d:
Δίδυμος Dídymos, did'-oo-mos; prolongation from G1364; double, i.e. twin; Didymus, a
 Christian:—Didymus.

g1325.d:
δίδωμι dídōmi, did'-o-mee; a prolonged form of a primary verb (which is used as an alternative in
 most of the tenses); to give (used in a very wide application,
 properly, or by implication, literally or figuratively; greatly
 modified by the connection):—adventure, bestow, bring forth, commit,
 deliver (up), give, grant, hinder, make, minister, number, offer, have
 power, put, receive, set, shew, smite (+ with the hand), strike (+
 with the palm of the hand), suffer, take, utter, yield.
g1325.r: A prolonged form of a primary verb (which is used as an altern. in most of the tenses)|

g1326.d:
διεγείρω diegeírō, dee-eg-i'-ro; from G1223 and G1453; to wake fully; i.e. arouse (literally or
 figuratively):—arise, awake, raise, stir up.
g1326.r: From διά (G1223) and ἐγείρω (G1453)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1327.d:
διέξοδος diéxodos, dee-ex'-od-os; from G1223 and G1841; an outlet through, i.e. probably an open square
 (from which roads diverge):—highway.
g1327.r: From διά (G1223) and ἔξοδος (G1841)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1328.d: διερμηνευτής diermēneutḗs, dee-er-main-yoo-tace'; from G1329; an explainer:—interpreter.
g1328.r: From διερμηνεύω (G1329)|English: interpret, by interpretation, expound

g1329.d:
διερμηνεύω diermēneúō, dee-er-main-yoo'-o; from G1223 and G2059; to explain thoroughly, by implication, to
 translate:—expound, interpret(-ation).
g1329.r: From διά (G1223) and ἑρμηνεύω (G2059)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g133.d:
αἴνεσις aínesis, ah'-ee-nes-is; from G134; a praising (the act), i.e. (specially) a
 thank(-offering):—praise.

g1330.d:
διέρχομαι diérchomai, dee-er'-khom-ahee; from G1223 and G2064; to traverse (literally):—come, depart, go (about,
 abroad, everywhere, over, through, throughout), pass (by, over,
 through, throughout), pierce through, travel, walk through.
g1330.r: From διά (G1223) and ἔρχομαι (G2064)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1331.d:
διερωτάω dierōtáō, dee-er-o-tah'-o; from G1223 and G2065; to question throughout, i.e. ascertain by
 interrogation:—make enquiry for.
g1331.r: From διά (G1223) and ἐρωτάω (G2065)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1332.d: διετής dietḗs, dee-et-ace'; from G1364 and G2094; of two years (in age):—two years old.
g1332.r: From δίς (G1364) and ἔτος (G2094)|English: twice, again

g1333.d: διετία dietía, dee-et-ee'-a; from G1332; a space of two years (biennium):—two years.

g1334.d: διηγέομαι diēgéomai, dee-ayg-eh'-om-ahee; from G1223 and G2233; to relate fully:—declare, shew, tell.
g1334.r: From διά (G1223) and ἡγέομαι (G2233)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1335.d: †διήγεσις diḗgesis, dee-ayg'-es-is; from G1334; a recital:—declaration.

g1336.r: Neuter of a compound of διά (G1223) and a derivative of an alternate of φέρω (G5342)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1337.d:
διθάλασσος dithálassos, dee-thal'-as-sos; from G1364 and G2281; having two seas, i.e. a sound with a double
 outlet:—where two seas meet.
g1337.r: From δίς (G1364) and θάλασσα (G2281)|English: twice, again

g1338.d:
διϊκνέομαι diïknéomai, dee-ik-neh'-om-ahee; from G1223 and the base of G2425; to reach through, i.e.
 penetrate:—pierce.
g1338.r: From διά (G1223) and the base of ἱκανός (G2425)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1339.d:
διΐστημι diḯstēmi, dee-is'-tay-mee; from G1223 and G2476; to stand apart, i.e. (reflexively) to remove,
 intervene:—go further, be parted, after the space of.
g1339.r: From διά (G1223) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g134.d: αἰνέω ainéō, ahee-neh'-o; from G136; to praise (God):—praise.

g1340.d:
διϊσχυρίζομαι diïschyrízomai, dee-is-khoo-rid'-zom-ahee; from G1223 and a derivative of G2478; to stout it through, i.e.
 asservate:—confidently (constantly) affirm.
g1340.r: From διά (G1223) and a derivative of ἰσχυρός (G2478)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1341.d: δικαιοκρισία dikaiokrisía, dik-ah-yok-ris-ee'-ah; from G1342 and G2920; a just sentence:—righteous judgment.
g1341.r: From δίκαιος (G1342) and κρίσις (G2920)|English: righteous, just, right, meet

g1342.d:
δίκαιος díkaios, dik'-ah-yos; from G1349; equitable (in character or act); by implication, innocent,
 holy (absolutely or relatively):—just, meet, right(-eous).

g1343.d:
δικαιοσύνη dikaiosýnē, dik-ah-yos-oo'-nay; from G1342; equity (of character or act); specially (Christian)
 justification:—righteousness.
g1343.r: From δίκαιος (G1342)|English: righteous, just, right, meet

g1344.d:
δικαιόω dikaióō, dik-ah-yo'-o; from G1342; to render (i.e. show or regard as) just or innocent:—free,
 justify(-ier), be righteous.
g1344.r: From δίκαιος (G1342)|English: righteous, just, right, meet

g1345.d:
δικαίωμα dikaíōma, dik-ah'-yo-mah; from G1344; an equitable deed; by implication, a statute or
 decision:—judgment, justification, ordinance, righteousness.
g1345.r: From δικαιόω (G1344)|English: justify, be freed, be righteous, justifier

g1346.d: δικαίως dikaíōs, dik-ah'-yoce; adverb from G1342; equitably:—justly, (to) righteously(-ness).
g1346.r: From δίκαιος (G1342)|English: righteous, just, right, meet

g1347.d: δικαίωσις dikaíōsis, dik-ah'-yo-sis; from G1344; aquittal (for Christ's sake):—justification.
g1347.r: From δικαιόω (G1344)|English: justify, be freed, be righteous, justifier

g1348.d: δικαστής dikastḗs, dik-as-tace'; from a derivative of G1349; a judger:—judge.
g1348.r: From a derivative of δίκη (G1349)|English: vengeance, judgment, punish

g1349.d:
†δίκη díkē, dee'-kay; probably from G1166; right (as self-evident), i.e. justice (the
 principle, a decision, or its execution):—judgment, punish,
 vengeance.

g135.d:
αἴνιγμα aínigma, ah'-ee-nig-ma; from a derivative of G136 (in its primary sense); an obscure saying
 ("enigma"), i.e. (abstractly) obscureness:—X darkly.
g135.r: From a derivative of αἶνος (G136) (in its primary sense)|English: praise

g1350.d:
δίκτυον díktyon, dik'-too-on; probably from a primary verb δίκω díkō (to cast); a seine (for
 fishing):—net.
g1350.r: Probably from a primary verb diko (to cast)|

g1351.d:
δίλογος dílogos, dil'-og-os; from G1364 and G3056; equivocal, i.e. telling a different
 story:—double-tongued.
g1351.r: From δίς (G1364) and λόγος (G3056)|English: twice, again

g1352.d:
διό dió, dee-o'; from G1223 and G3739; through which thing, i.e. consequently:—for which
 cause, therefore, wherefore.
g1352.r: From διά (G1223) and ὅς (G3739)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1353.d: διοδεύω diodeúō, dee-od-yoo'-o; from G1223 and G3593; to travel through:—go throughout, pass through.
g1353.r: From διά (G1223) and ὁδεύω (G3593)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1354.d: Διονύσιος Dionýsios, dee-on-oo'-see-os; from Διόνυσος Diónysos (Bacchus); reveller; Dionysius, an Athenian:—Dionysius.

g1355.d: διόπερ dióper, dee-op'-er; from G1352 and G4007; on which very account:—wherefore.
g1355.r: From διό (G1352) and περ (G4007)|English: wherefore, therefore, for which cause

g1356.d:
διοπετής diopetḗs, dee-op-et'-ace; from the alternate of G2203 and the alternate of G4098; sky-fallen (i.e.
 an aerolite):—which fell down from Jupiter.
g1356.r: From the alternate of Ζεύς (G2203) and the alternate of πίπτω (G4098)|English: Jupiter

g1357.d:
διόρθωσις diórthōsis, dee-or'-tho-sis; from a compound of G1223 and a derivative of G3717, meaning to
 straighten thoroughly; rectification, i.e. (specially) the Messianic
 restauration:—reformation.
g1357.r: From a compound of διά (G1223) and a derivative of ὀρθός (G3717), meaning to straighten thoroughly|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1358.d: διορύσσω diorýssō, dee-or-oos'-so; from G1223 and G3736; to penetrate burglariously:—break through (up).
g1358.r: From διά (G1223) and ὀρύσσω (G3736)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1359.d:
Διόσκουροι Dióskouroi, dee-os'-koo-roy; from the alternate of G2203 and a form of the base of G2877; sons of
 Jupiter, i.e. the twins Dioscuri:—Castor and Pollux.
g1359.r: From the alternate of Ζεύς (G2203) and a form of the base of κοράσιον (G2877)|English: Jupiter

g136.d:
αἶνος aînos, ah'-ee-nos; apparently a prime word; properly, a story, but used in the sense of
 G1868; praise (of God):—praise.
g136.r: Apparently a primary word, properly, a story, but used in the sense of ἔπαινος (G1868)|English: praise

g1360.d:
διότι dióti, dee-ot'-ee; from G1223 and G3754; on the very account that, or inasmuch as:—because
 (that), for, therefore.
g1360.r: From διά (G1223) and ὅτι (G3754)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1361.d:
Διοτρεφής Diotrephḗs, dee-ot-ref-ace'; from the alternate of G2203 and G5142; Jove-nourished; Diotrephes, an
 opponent of Christianity:—Diotrephes.
g1361.r: From the alternate of Ζεύς (G2203) and τρέφω (G5142)|English: Jupiter

g1362.d:
†διπλοῦς diploûs, dip-looce'; from G1364 and (probably) the base of G4119; two-fold:—double, two-fold
 more.
g1362.r: From δίς (G1364) and (probably) the base of πλείων (G4119)|English: twice, again

g1363.d: διπλόω diplóō, dip-lo'-o; from G1362; to render two-fold:—double.

g1364.d: δίς dís, dece; adverb from G1417; twice:—again, twice.
g1364.r: From δύο (G1417)|English: two, twain, both, two and two

g1365.d:
διστάζω distázō, dis-tad'-zo; from G1364; properly, to duplicate, i.e. (mentally) to waver (in
 opinion):—doubt.

g1366.d: δίστομος dístomos, dis'-tom-os; from G1364 and G4750; double-edged:—with two edges, two-edged.
g1366.r: From δίς (G1364) and στόμα (G4750)|English: twice, again

g1367.d: δισχίλιοι dischílioi, dis-khil'-ee-oy; from G1364 and G5507; two thousand:—two thousand.
g1367.r: From δίς (G1364) and χίλιοι (G5507)|English: twice, again

g1368.d:
†διϋλίζω diÿlízō, dee-oo-lid'-zo; from G1223 and ὑλίζω hylízō hoo-lid'-zo (to filter); to strain out:—strain
 at (probably by misprint).
g1368.r: From διά (G1223) and hulizo {hoo-lid'-zo} (to filter)|English: by, through, with, for, for ... sake, therefore, for this cause, because, misc

g1369.d:
διχάζω dicházō, dee-khad'-zo; from a derivative of G1364; to make apart, i.e. sunder (figuratively,
 alienate):—set at variance.
g1369.r: From a derivative of δίς (G1364)|English: twice, again

g137.d: Αἰνών Ainṓn, ahee-nohn'; of Hebrew origin (a derivative of H5869, place of springs); Ænon, a place in Palestine:—Ænon.
g137.r: Of Hebrew origin, a derivative of עַיִן (H5869)|English: eye, sight, seem, colour, fountain, well, face, pleased, presence, displeased, before, pleased, conceit, think

g1370.d:
διχοστασία dichostasía, dee-khos-tas-ee'-ah; from a derivative of G1364 and G4714; disunion, i.e. (figuratively)
 dissension:—division, sedition.
g1370.r: From a derivative of δίς (G1364) and στάσις (G4714)|English: twice, again

g1371.d:
διχοτομέω dichotoméō, dee-khot-om-eh'-o; from a compound of a derivative of G1364 and a derivative of
 τέμνω témnō (to cut); to bisect, i.e. (by extension) to flog
 severely:—cut asunder (in sunder).
g1371.r: From a compound of a derivative of δίς (G1364) and a derivative of temno (to cut)|English: twice, again

g1372.d:
διψάω dipsáō, dip-sah'-o; from a variation of G1373; to thirst for (literally or
 figuratively):—(be, be a-)thirst(-y).
g1372.r: From a variation of δίψος (G1373)|English: thirst

g1373.d: δίψος dípsos, dip'-sos; of uncertain affinity; thirst:—thirst.

g1374.d:
δίψυχος dípsychos, dip'-soo-khos; from G1364 and G5590; two-spirited, i.e. vacillating (in opinion or
 purpose):—double minded.
g1374.r: From δίς (G1364) and ψυχή (G5590)|English: twice, again
