g2130.r: From εὖ (G2095) and a presumed derivative of μεταδίδωμι (G3330)|English: well, well done, good

g2131.d: Εὐνίκη Euníkē, yoo-nee'-kay; from G2095 and G3529; victorious; Eunice, a Jewess:—Eunice.
g2131.r: From εὖ (G2095) and νίκη (G3529)|English: well, well done, good

g2132.d:
εὐνοέω eunoéō, yoo-no-eh'-o; from a compound of G2095 and G3563; to be well- minded, i.e.
 reconcile:—agree.
g2132.r: From a compound of εὖ (G2095) and νοῦς (G3563)|English: well, well done, good

g2133.d:
εὔνοια eúnoia, yoo'-noy-ah; from the same as G2132; kindness; euphemistically, conjugal
 duty:—benevolence, good will.
g2133.r: From the same as εὐνοέω (G2132)|English: agree

g2134.d: εὐνουχίζω eunouchízō, yoo-noo-khid'-zo; from G2135; to castrate (figuratively, live unmarried):—make…eunuch.

g2135.d:
εὐνοῦχος eunoûchos, yoo-noo'-khos; from εὐνή eunḗ (a bed) and G2192; a castrated person (such being employed in
 Oriental bed-chambers); by extension an impotent or unmarried man; by
 implication, a chamberlain (state-officer):—eunuch.
g2135.r: From eune (a bed) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: have, be, need, misc

g2136.d:
†Εὐοδία Euodía, yoo-od-ee'-ah; from the same as G2137; fine travelling; Euodia, a Christian
 woman:—Euodias.
g2136.r: From the same as εὐοδόω (G2137)|English: prosper, have a prosperous journey

g2137.d:
εὐοδόω euodóō, yoo-od-o'-o; from a compound of G2095 and G3598; to help on the road, i.e.
 (passively) succeed in reaching; figuratively, to succeed in business
 affairs:—(have a) prosper(-ous journey).
g2137.r: From a compound of εὖ (G2095) and ὁδός (G3598)|English: well, well done, good

g2138.d:
εὐπειθής eupeithḗs, yoo-pi-thace'; from G2095 and G3982; good for persuasion, i.e. (intransitively)
 compliant:—easy to be intreated.
g2138.r: From εὖ (G2095) and πείθω (G3982)|English: well, well done, good

g2139.d:
εὐπερίστατος euperístatos, yoo-per-is'-tat-os; from G2095 and a derivative of a presumed compound of G4012 and G2476; 
 well standing around, i.e. (a competitor) thwarting (a racer) in every
 direction (figuratively, of sin in genitive case):—which doth so
 easily beset.
g2139.r: From εὖ (G2095) and a derivative of a presumed compound of περί (G4012) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: well, well done, good

g214.d:
ἀλαλάζω alalázō, al-al-ad'-zo; from ἀλαλή alalḗ ( a shout, "halloo"); to vociferate, i.e. (by implication)
 to wail; figuratively, to clang:—tinkle, wail.

g2140.d:
εὐποιΐα eupoiḯa, yoo-poy-ee'-ah; from a compound of G2095 and G4160; well-doing, i.e. beneficence:—to do
 good.
g2140.r: From a compound of εὖ (G2095) and ποιέω (G4160)|English: well, well done, good

g2141.d:
εὐπορέω euporéō, yoo-por-eh'-o; from a compound of G2090 and the base of G4197; (intransitively) to be
 good for passing through, i.e. (figuratively) have pecuniary
 means:—ability.
g2141.r: From a compound of ἑτοιμάζω (G2090) and the base of πορεία (G4197)|English: prepare, make ready, provide

g2142.d: εὐπορία euporía, yoo-por-ee'-ah; from the same as G2141; pecuniary resources:—wealth.
g2142.r: From the same as εὐπορέω (G2141)|English: his ability

g2143.d:
εὐπρέπεια euprépeia, yoo-prep'-i-ah; from a compound of G2095 and G4241; good suitableness, i.e.
 gracefulness:—grace.
g2143.r: From a compound of εὖ (G2095) and πρέπω (G4241)|English: well, well done, good

g2144.d:
εὐπρόσδεκτος euprósdektos, yoo-pros'-dek-tos; from G2095 and a derivative of G4327; well-received, i.e. approved,
 favorable:—acceptable(-ted).
g2144.r: From εὖ (G2095) and a derivative of προσδέχομαι (G4327)|English: well, well done, good

g2146.d:
εὐπροσωπέω euprosōpéō, yoo-pros-o-peh'-o; from a compound of G2095 and G4383; to be of good countenance, i.e.
 (figuratively) to make a display:—make a fair show.
g2146.r: From a compound of εὖ (G2095) and πρόσωπον (G4383)|English: well, well done, good

g2147.d:
εὑρίσκω heurískō, hyoo-ris'-ko; a prolonged form of a primary
    
    εὕρω heúrō  hyoo'-ro,   which 
                (together with another cognate form)
    
    εὑρέω heuréō  hyoo-reh'-o  is used for it in all the tenses
                except the present and imperfect; 

 to find (literally or figuratively):—find, get, obtain, perceive,
 see.
g2147.r: A prolonged form of a primary heuro {hyoo'-ro}, which (together with another cognate form heureo {hyoo-reh'-o}) is used for it in all the tenses except the present and imperfect|

g2149.d: εὐρύχωρος eurýchōros, yoo-roo'-kho-ros; from εὐρύς eurýs (wide) and G5561; spacious:—broad.
g2149.r: From eurus (wide) and χώρα (G5561)|English: country, region, land, field, ground, coast

g215.d:
ἀλάλητος alálētos, al-al'-ay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G2980; 
 unspeakable:—unutterable, which cannot be uttered.
g215.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of λαλέω (G2980)|English: Alpha

g2150.d: εὐσέβεια eusébeia, yoo-seb'-i-ah; from G2152; piety; specially, the gospel scheme:—godliness, holiness.

g2151.d:
εὐσεβέω eusebéō, yoo-seb-eh'-o; from G2152; to be pious, i.e. (towards God) to worship, or (towards
 parents) to respect (support):—show piety, worship.

g2152.d: εὐσεβής eusebḗs, yoo-seb-ace'; from G2095 and G4576; well-reverent, i.e. pious:—devout, godly.
g2152.r: From εὖ (G2095) and σέβω (G4576)|English: well, well done, good

g2153.d: εὐσεβῶς eusebōs, yoo-seb-oce'; adverb from G2152; piously:—godly.

g2154.d:
εὔσημος eúsēmos, yoo'-say-mos; from G2095 and the base of G4591; well indicated, i.e. (figuratively)
 significant:—easy to be understood.
g2154.r: From εὖ (G2095) and the base of σημαίνω (G4591)|English: well, well done, good

g2155.d:
εὔσπλαγχνος eúsplanchnos, yoo'-splangkh-nos; from G2095 and G4698; well compassioned, i.e. sympathetic:—pitiful,
 tender-hearted.
g2155.r: From εὖ (G2095) and σπλάγχνον (G4698)|English: well, well done, good

g2156.d: εὐσχημόνως euschēmónōs, yoo-skhay-mon'-ose; adverb from G2158; decorously:—decently, honestly.

g2157.d: εὐσχημοσύνη euschēmosýnē, yoo-skhay-mos-oo'-nay; from G2158; decorousness:—comeliness.

g2158.d:
εὐσχήμων euschḗmōn, yoo-skhay'-mone; from G2095 and G4976; well-formed, i.e. (figuratively) decorous, noble
 (in rank):—comely, honourable.
g2158.r: From εὖ (G2095) and σχῆμα (G4976)|English: well, well done, good

g2159.r: From a compound of εὖ (G2095) and a derivative of teino (to stretch)|English: well, well done, good

g216.d: ἄλαλος álalos, al'-al-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G2980; mute:—dumb.
g216.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and λαλέω (G2980)|English: Alpha

g2160.d:
εὐτραπελία eutrapelía, yoo-trap-el-ee'-ah; from a compound of G2095 and a derivative of the base of G5157 (meaning
 well-turned, i.e. ready at repartee, jocose); witticism, i.e. (in a
 vulgar sense) ribaldry:—jesting.
g2160.r: From a compound of εὖ (G2095) and a derivative of the base of τροπή (G5157) (meaning well-turned, i.e. ready at repartee, jocose)|English: well, well done, good

g2161.d:
Εὔτυχος Eútychos, yoo'-too-khos; from G2095 and a derivative of G5177; well- fated, i.e. fortunate;
 Eutychus, a young man:—Eutychus.
g2161.r: From εὖ (G2095) and a derivative of τυγχάνω (G5177)|English: well, well done, good

g2162.d:
εὐφημία euphēmía, yoo-fay-mee'-ah; from G2163; good language ("euphemy"), i.e. praise (repute):—good
 report.

g2163.d: εὔφημος eúphēmos, yoo'-fay-mos; from G2095 and G5345; well spoken of, i.e. reputable:—of good report.
g2163.r: From εὖ (G2095) and φήμη (G5345)|English: well, well done, good

g2164.d:
εὐφορέω euphoréō, yoo-for-eh'-o; from G2095 and G5409; to bear well, i.e. be fertile:—bring forth
 abundantly.
g2164.r: From εὖ (G2095) and φορέω (G5409)|English: well, well done, good

g2165.d:
εὐφραίνω euphraínō, yoo-frah'-ee-no; from G2095 and G5424; to put (middle voice or passively, be) in a good
 frame of mind, i.e. rejoice:—fare, make glad, be (make) merry,
 rejoice.
g2165.r: From εὖ (G2095) and φρήν (G5424)|English: well, well done, good

g2166.d:
Εὐφράτης Euphrátēs, yoo-frat'-ace; of foreign origin (compare H6578); Euphrates, a river of
 Asia:—Euphrates.
g2166.r: Of foreign origin, cf פְּרָת (H6578)|English: Euphrates

g2167.d: εὐφροσύνη euphrosýnē, yoo-fros-oo'-nay; from the same as G2165; joyfulness:—gladness, joy.
g2167.r: From the same as εὐφραίνω (G2165)|English: rejoice, be merry, make merry, fare, make glad

g2168.d:
εὐχαριστέω eucharistéō, yoo-khar-is-teh'-o; from G2170; to be grateful, i.e. (actively) to express gratitude
 (towards); specially, to say grace at a meal:—(give) thank(-ful, -s).

g2169.d:
εὐχαριστία eucharistía, yoo-khar-is-tee'-ah; from G2170; gratitude; actively, grateful language (to God, as an act
 of worship):—thankfulness, (giving of) thanks(-giving).

g217.d: †ἅλας hálas, hal'-as; from G251; salt; figuratively, prudence:—salt.

g2170.d:
εὐχάριστος eucháristos, yoo-khar'-is-tos; from G2095 and a derivative of G5483; well favored, i.e. (by
 implication) grateful:—thankful.
g2170.r: From εὖ (G2095) and a derivative of χαρίζομαι (G5483)|English: well, well done, good

g2171.d:
εὐχή euchḗ, yoo-khay'; from G2172; properly, a wish, expressed as a petition to God, or in
 votive obligation:—prayer, vow.
g2171.r: From εὔχομαι (G2172)|English: wish, pray, can wish, I would

g2172.d:
εὔχομαι eúchomai, yoo'-khom-ahee; middle voice of a primary verb; to wish; by implication, to pray to
 God:—pray, will, wish.
g2172.r: Middle voice of a primary verb|

g2173.d:
εὔχρηστος eúchrēstos, yoo'-khrays-tos; from G2095 and G5543; easily used, i.e. useful:—profitable, meet for
 use.
g2173.r: From εὖ (G2095) and χρηστός (G5543)|English: well, well done, good

g2174.d:
εὐψυχέω eupsychéō, yoo-psoo-kheh'-o; from a compound of G2095 and G5590; to be in good spirits, i.e. feel
 encouraged:—be of good comfort.
g2174.r: From a compound of εὖ (G2095) and ψυχή (G5590)|English: well, well done, good

g2175.d:
εὐωδία euōdía, yoo-o-dee'-ah; from a compound of G2095 and a derivative of G3605; good-scentedness,
 i.e. fragrance:—sweet savour (smell, -smelling).
g2175.r: From a compound of εὖ (G2095) and a derivative of ὄζω (G3605)|English: well, well done, good

g2176.d:
εὐώνυμος euṓnymos, yoo-o'-noo-mos; from G2095 and G3686; properly, well-named (good-omened), i.e. the left
 (which was the lucky side among the pagan Greeks); neuter as
 adverbial, at the left hand:—(on the) left.
g2176.r: From εὖ (G2095) and ὄνομα (G3686)|English: well, well done, good

g2177.d: ἐφάλλομαι ephállomai, ef-al'-lom-ahee; from G1909 and G242; to spring upon:—leap on.
g2177.r: From ἐπί (G1909) and ἅλλομαι (G242)|English: on, in, upon, unto, to, misc

g2178.d: ἐφάπαξ ephápax, ef-ap'-ax; from G1909 and G530; upon one occasion (only):—(at) once (for all).
g2178.r: From ἐπί (G1909) and ἅπαξ (G530)|English: on, in, upon, unto, to, misc

g218.d:
ἀλείφω aleíphō, al-i'-fo; from G1 (as particle of union) and the base of G3045; to oil (with
 perfume):—anoint.
g218.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as particle of union) and the base of λιπαρός (G3045)|English: Alpha

g2180.d:
Ἐφέσιος Ephésios, ef-es'-ee-os; from G2181; an Ephesian or inhabitant of Ephesus:—Ephesian, of
 Ephesus.

g2181.d: Ἔφεσος Éphesos, ef'-es-os; probably of foreign origin; Ephesus, a city of Asia Minor:—Ephesus.

g2182.d:
ἐφευρετής epheuretḗs, ef-yoo-ret'-ace; from a compound of G1909 and G2147; a discoverer, i.e.
 contriver:—inventor.
g2182.r: From a compound of ἐπί (G1909) and εὑρίσκω (G2147)|English: on, in, upon, unto, to, misc

g2183.d:
ἐφημερία ephēmería, ef-ay-mer-ee'-ah; from G2184; diurnality, i.e. (specially) the quotidian rotation or
 class of the Jewish priests' service at the Temple, as distributed by
 families:—course.

g2184.d: ἐφήμερος ephḗmeros, ef-ay'-mer-os; from G1909 and G2250; for a day ("ephemeral"), i.e. diurnal:—daily.
g2184.r: From ἐπί (G1909) and ἡμέρα (G2250)|English: on, in, upon, unto, to, misc

g2185.d:
ἐφικνέομαι ephiknéomai, ef-ik-neh'-om-ahee; from G1909 and a cognate of G2240; to arrive upon, i.e. extend
 to:—reach.
g2185.r: From ἐπί (G1909) and a cognate of ἥκω (G2240)|English: on, in, upon, unto, to, misc

g2186.d:
ἐφίστημι ephístēmi, ef-is'-tay-mee; from G1909 and G2476; to stand upon, i.e. be present (in various
 applications, friendly or otherwise, usually literal); --assault, come
 (in, to, unto, upon), be at hand (instant), present, stand (before,
 by, over).
g2186.r: From ἐπί (G1909) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: on, in, upon, unto, to, misc

g2187.d:
†Ἐφραίμ Ephraím, ef-rah-im'; of Hebrew origin (H669 or better H6085); Ephraim, a place in
 Palestine:—Ephraim.
g2187.r: Of Hebrew origin, אֶפְרַיִם (H669) or better עֶפְרוֹן (H6085)|English: Ephraim, Ephraimite

g2188.d: ἐφφαθά ephphathá, ef-fath-ah'; of Chaldee origin (H6606); be opened!:—Ephphatha.

g2189.d:
ἔχθρα échthra, ekh'-thrah; feminine of G2190; hostility; by implication, a reason for
 opposition:—enmity, hatred.

g219.d:
ἀλεκτοροφωνία alektorophōnía, al-ek-tor-of-o-nee'-ah; from G220 and G5456; cock-crow, i.e. the third
 night-watch:—cockcrowing.

g2190.d:
ἐχθρός echthrós, ech-thros'; from a primary ἔχθω échthō (to hate); hateful (passively, odious, or
 actively, hostile); usually as a noun, an adversary (especially
 Satan):—enemy, foe.
g2190.r: From a primary echtho (to hate); hateful (passively, odious, or actively, hostile)|

g2191.d:
ἔχιδνα échidna, ekh'-id-nah; of uncertain origin; an adder or other poisonous snake (literally or
 figuratively):—viper.

g2192.d:
ἔχω échō, ekh'-o; a primary verb; to hold (used in very various applications, literally
 or figuratively, direct or remote; such as possession; ability,
 contiuity, relation, or condition):—be (able, × hold, possessed
 with), accompany, + begin to amend, can(+ -not), × conceive, count,
 diseased, do + eat, + enjoy, + fear, following, have, hold, keep, +
 lack, + go to law, lie, + must needs, + of necessity, + need, next, +
 recover, + reign, + rest, + return, × sick, take for, + tremble, +
 uncircumcised, use.
g2192.r: Including an alternate form scheo {skheh'-o}, used in certain tenses only), a primary verb|

g2193.d:
ἕως héōs, heh'-oce; of uncertain affinity; a conjunction, preposition and adverb of
 continuance, until (of time and place):—even (until, unto), (as) far
 (as), how long, (un-)til(-l), (hither-, un-, up) to, while(-s).

g2194.d:
Ζαβουλών Zaboulṓn, dzab-oo-lone'; of Hebrew origin (H2074); Zabulon (i.e. Zebulon), a region of
 Palestine:—Zabulon.

g2195.d: Ζακχαῖος Zakchaîos, dzak-chah'-ee-yos; of Hebrew origin (compare H2140); Zacchæus, an Israelite:—Zacchæus.
g2195.r: Of Hebrew origin, cf זַכַּי (H2140)|English: Zaccai, Zabbai

g2196.d: Ζαρά Zará, dzar-ah'; of Hebrew origin (H2226); Zara, (i.e. Zerach), an Israelite:—Zara.
g2196.r: Of Hebrew origin זֶרַח (H2226)|English: Zerah, Zarah

g2197.d:
Ζαχαρίας Zacharías, dzakh-ar-ee'-as; of Hebrew origin (H2148); Zacharias (i.e. Zechariah), the name of two
 Israelites:—Zacharias.

g2198.d:
ζάω záō, dzah'-o; a primary verb; to live (literally or figuratively):—life(-time),
 (a-)live(-ly), quick.

g2199.d: Ζεβεδαῖος Zebedaîos, dzeb-ed-ah'-yos; of Hebrew origin (compare H2067); Zebedæus, an Israelite:—Zebedee.
g2199.r: Of Hebrew origin, cf זַבְדִּי (H2067)|English: Zabdi

g22.d: ἄγαμος ágamos, ag'-am-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G1062; unmarried:—unmarried.
g22.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and γάμος (G1062)|English: Alpha

g220.d: ἀλέκτωρ aléktōr, al-ek'-tore; from ἀλέκω alékō (to ward off); a cock or male fowl:—cock.

g2200.d:
ζεστός zestós, dzes-tos'; from G2204; boiled, i.e. (by implication) calid (figuratively,
 fervent):—hot.

g2201.d:
ζεῦγος zeûgos, dzyoo'-gos; from the same as G2218; a couple, i.e. a team (of oxen yoked together)
 or brace (of birds tied together):—yoke, pair.
g2201.r: From the same as ζυγός (G2218)|English: yoke, pair of balances

g2202.d:
ζευκτηρία zeuktēría, dzook-tay-ree'-ah; feminine of a derivative (at the second stage) from the same as G2218; 
 a fastening (tiller-rope):—band.
g2202.r: From a derivative (at the second stage) from the same as ζυγός (G2218)|English: yoke, pair of balances

g2203.d:
Ζεύς Zeús, dzyooce; of uncertain affinity; in the oblique cases there is used instead of
 it a (probably cognate) name

    Δίς Dís  deece, which is otherwise obsolete;
    
 Zeus or Dis (among the Latins, Jupiter or Jove), the supreme deity of
 the Greeks:—Jupiter.

g2204.d:
ζέω zéō, dzeh'-o; a primary verb; to be hot (boil, of liquids; or glow, of solids), i.e.
 (figuratively) be fervid (earnest):—be fervent.

g2205.d:
ζῆλος zēlos, dzay'-los; from G2204; properly, heat, i.e. (figuratively) "zeal" (in a favorable
 sense, ardor; in an unfavorable one, jealousy, as of a husband
 (figuratively, of God), or an enemy, malice):—emulation, envy(-ing),
 fervent mind, indignation, jealousy, zeal.

g2206.d:
†ζηλόω zēlóō, dzay-lo'-o; from G2205; to have warmth of feeling for or against:—affect, covet
 (earnestly), (have) desire, (move with) envy, be jealous over, (be)
 zealous(-ly affect).
g2206.r: From ζῆλος (G2205)|English: zeal, envying, indignation, envy, fervent mind, jealousy, emulation

g2207.d: ζηλωτής zēlōtḗs, dzay-lo-tace'; from G2206; a "zealot":—zealous.
g2207.r: From ζηλόω (G2206)|English: zealously affect, more with envy, envy, be zealous, affect, desire, covet, covet earnestly, misc

g2209.d:
ζημία zēmía, dzay-mee'-ah; probably akin to the base of G1150 (through the idea of violence); 
 detriment:—damage, loss.
g2209.r: Probably akin to the base of δαμάζω (G1150) (through the idea of violence)|English: tame

g221.d:
Ἀλεξανδρεύς Alexandreús, al-ex-and-reuce'; from Ἀλεξάνδρεια Alexándreia (the city so called); an Alexandreian or inhabitant
 of Alexandria:—of Alexandria, Alexandrian.

g2210.d:
ζημιόω zēmióō, dzay-mee-o'-o; from G2209; to injure, i.e. (reflexively or passively) to experience
 detriment:—be cast away, receive damage, lose, suffer loss.

g2211.d:
Ζηνᾶς Zēnâs, dzay-nas'; probably contracted from a poetic form of G2203 and G1435; Jove-given;
 Zenas, a Christian:—Zenas.
g2211.r: Probably contracted from a poetic form of Ζεύς (G2203) and δῶρον (G1435)|English: Jupiter

g2212.d:
ζητέω zētéō, dzay-teh'-o; of uncertain affinity; to seek (literally or figuratively); specially,
 (by Hebraism) to worship (God), or (in a bad sense) to plot (against
 life):—be (go) about, desire, endeavour, enquire (for), require, (X
 will) seek (after, for, means). Compare G4441.

g2213.d:
ζήτημα zḗtēma, dzay'-tay-mah; from G2212; a search (properly concretely), i.e. (in words) a
 debate:—question.
g2213.r: From ζητέω (G2212)|English: seek, seek for, go about, desire, misc

g2214.d:
†ζήτησις zḗtēsis, dzay'-tay-sis; from G2212; a searching (properly, the act), i.e. a dispute or its
 theme:—question.
g2214.r: From ζητέω (G2212)|English: seek, seek for, go about, desire, misc

g2215.d: ζιζάνιον zizánion, dziz-an'-ee-on; of uncertain origin; darnel or false grain:—tares.

g2216.d:
Ζοροβάβελ Zorobábel, dzor-ob-ab'-el; of Hebrew origin (H2216); Zorobabel (i.e. Zerubbabel), an
 Israelite:—Zorobabel.

g2217.d:
ζόφος zóphos, dzof'-os; akin to the base of G3509; gloom (as shrouding like a
 cloud):—blackness, darkness, mist.
g2217.r: Akin to the base of νέφος (G3509)|English: cloud

g2218.d:
ζυγός zygós, dzoo-gos'; from the root of ζεύγνυμι zeúgnymi (to join, especially by a "yoke"); a
 coupling, i.e. (figuratively) servitude (a law or obligation); also
 (literally) the beam of the balance (as connecting the scales):—pair
 of balances, yoke.
g2218.r: From the root of zeugnumi (to join, especially by a "yoke")|

g2219.d: ζύμη zýmē, dzoo'-may; probably from G2204; ferment (as if boiling up):—leaven.
g2219.r: Probably from ζέω (G2204)|English: be fervent, fervent

g222.d:
Ἀλεξανδρῖνος Alexandrînos, al-ex-an-dree'-nos; from the same as G221; Alexandrine, or belonging to Alexandria:—of
 Alexandria.
g222.r: From the same as Ἀλεξανδρεύς (G221)|English: Alexandrian, born at Alexander

g2220.d: ζυμόω zymóō, dzoo-mo'-o; from G2219; to cause to ferment:—leaven.

g2221.d:
ζωγρέω zōgréō, dzogue-reh'-o; from the same as G2226 and G64; to take alive (make a prisoner of war),
 i.e. (figuratively) to capture or ensnare:—take captive, catch.
g2221.r: From the same as ζῷον (G2226) and ἀγρεύω (G64)|English: beast

g2222.d:
ζωή zōḗ, dzo-ay'; from G2198; life (literally or figuratively):—life(-time). Compare
 G5590.
g2222.r: From ζάω (G2198)|English: live, be alive, alive, quick, lively, not tr, misc

g2223.d:
ζώνη zṓnē, dzo'-nay; probably akin to the base of G2218; a belt; by implication, a
 pocket:—girdle, purse.
g2223.r: Probably akin to the base of ζυγός (G2218)|English: yoke, pair of balances

g2224.d: ζώννυμι zṓnnymi, dzone'-noo-mi; from G2223; to bind about (especially with a belt):—gird.

g2225.d:
†ζωογονέω zōogonéō, dzo-og-on-eh'-o; from the same as G2226 and a derivative of G1096; to engender alive,
 i.e. (by analogy) to rescue (passively, be saved) from death:—live,
 preserve.
g2225.r: From the same as ζῷον (G2226) and a derivative of γίνομαι (G1096)|English: beast

g2226.d: †ζῶον zōon, dzo'-on; neuter of a derivative of G2198; a live thing, i.e. an animal:—beast.
g2226.r: Of a derivative of ζάω (G2198)|English: live, be alive, alive, quick, lively, not tr, misc

g2227.d:
†ζωοποιέω zōopoiéō, dzo-op-oy-eh'-o; from the same as G2226 and G4160; to (re-)vitalize (literally or
 figuratively):—make alive, give life, quicken.
g2227.r: From the same as ζῷον (G2226) and ποιέω (G4160)|English: beast

g2228.d:
ἤ ḗ, ay; a primary particle of distinction between two connected terms; 
 disjunctive, or; comparative, than:—and, but (either), (n-)either,
 except it be, (n-)or (else), rather, save, than, that, what, yea. 
 Often used in connection with other particles. Compare especially
 G2235, G2260, G2273.
g2228.r: A primary particle of distinction between two connected terms|

g2229.d:
ἦ ē, ay; an adverb of confirmation; perhaps intensive of G2228; used only (in
 the New Testament) before G3303; assuredly:—surely.
g2229.r: An adverb of confirmation, perhaps intensive of ἤ (G2228)|English: or, than, either, or else, nor, not tr, misc

g223.d:
Ἀλέξανδρος Aléxandros, al-ex'-an-dros; from the same as (the first part of) G220 and G435; man-defender;
 Alexander, the name of three Israelites and one other man:—Alexander.
g223.r: From the same as (the first part of) ἀλέκτωρ (G220) and ἀνήρ (G435)|English: cock

g2230.d: ἡγεμονεύω hēgemoneúō, hayg-em-on-yoo'-o; from G2232; to act as ruler:—be governor.

g2231.d: ἡγεμονία hēgemonía, hayg-em-on-ee'-ah; from G2232; government, i.e. (in time) official term:—reign.

g2232.d:
ἡγεμών hēgemṓn, hayg-em-ohn'; from G2233; a leader, i.e. chief person (or figuratively, place) of a
 province:—governor, prince, ruler.
g2232.r: From ἡγέομαι (G2233)|English: count, think, esteem, have rule over, be governor, misc

g2233.d:
ἡγέομαι hēgéomai, hayg-eh'-om-ahee; middle voice of a (presumed) strengthened form of G71; to lead, i.e.
 command (with official authority); figuratively, to deem, i.e.
 consider:—account, (be) chief, count, esteem, governor, judge, have
 the rule over, suppose, think.
g2233.r: Middle voice of a (presumed) strengthened form of ἄγω (G71)|English: bring, lead, go, bring forth, misc, vr bring

g2234.d:
ἡδέως hēdéōs, hay-deh'-oce; adverb from a derivative of the base of G2237; sweetly, i.e.
 (figuratively) with pleasure:—gladly.
g2234.r: From a derivative of the base of ἡδονή (G2237)|English: pleasure, lust

g2235.d:
ἤδη ḗdē, ay'-day; apparently from G2228 (or possibly G2229) and G1211; even now:—already,
 (even) now (already), by this time.
g2235.r: Apparently from ἤ (G2228) (or possibly ἦ (G2229)) and δή (G1211)|English: or, than, either, or else, nor, not tr, misc

g2237.d:
ἡδονή hēdonḗ, hay-don-ay'; from ἁνδάνω handánō (to please); sensual delight; by implication,
 desire:—lust, pleasure.

g2238.d:
ἡδύοσμον hēdýosmon, hay-doo'-os-mon; neuter of the compound of the same as G2234 and G3744; a sweet-scented
 plant, i.e. mint:—mint.
g2238.r: From the compound of the same as ἡδέως (G2234) and ὀσμή (G3744)|English: gladly

g2239.d:
ἦθος ēthos, ay'-thos; a strengthened form of G1485; usage, i.e. (plural) moral
 habits:—manners.
g2239.r: A strengthened form of ἔθος (G1485)|English: custom, manner, be wont

g224.d: ἄλευρον áleuron, al'-yoo-ron; from ἀλέω aléō(to grind); flour:—meal.

g2240.d:
ἥκω hḗkō, hay'-ko; a primary verb; to arrive, i.e. be present (literally or
 figuratively):—come.

g2241.d: ἠλί ēlí, ay-lee'; of Hebrew origin (H410 with pronominal suffix); my God:—Eli.
g2241.r: Of Hebrew origin, אֵל (H410) with pronominal suffix|English: God, god, power, mighty, goodly, great, idols, Immanuel, might, strong

g2242.d: Ἡλί Hēlí, hay-lee'; of Hebrew origin (H5941); Heli (i.e. Eli), an Israelite:—Heli.

g2243.d: †Ἡλίας Hēlías, hay-lee'-as; of Hebrew origin (H452); Helias (i.e. Elijah), an Israelite:—Elias.
g2243.r: Of Hebrew origin אֵלִיָּה (H452)|English: Elijah, Eliah

g2244.d: ἡλικία hēlikía, hay-lik-ee'-ah; from the same as G2245; maturity (in years or size):—age, stature.
g2244.r: From the same as ἡλίκος (G2245)|English: what great, how great

g2245.d:
ἡλίκος hēlíkos, hay-lee'-kos; from ἧλιξ hēlix (a comrade, i.e. one of the same age); as big as, i.e.
 (interjectively) how much:—how (what) great.
g2245.r: From helix (a comrade, i.e. one of the same age)|

g2246.d:
ἥλιος hḗlios, hay'-lee-os; from ἕλη hélē (a ray; perhaps akin to the alternate of G138); the sun; by
 implication, light:—+ east, sun.
g2246.r: From hele (a ray, perhaps akin to the alternate of αἱρέω (G138))|English: choose

g2247.d: ἧλος hēlos, hay'-los; of uncertain affinity; a stud, i.e. spike:—nail.

g2248.d: ἡμᾶς hēmâs, hay-mas'; accusative case plural of G1473; us:—our, us, we.
g2248.r: Accusative case plural of ἐγώ (G1473)|English: I, my, me, not tr

g2249.d:
ἡμεῖς hēmeîs, hay-mice'; nominative plural of G1473; we (only used when emphatic):—us, we
 (ourselves).
g2249.r: Nom. plural of ἐγώ (G1473)|English: I, my, me, not tr

g225.d: ἀλήθεια alḗtheia, al-ay'-thi-a; from G227; truth:—true, × truly, truth, verity.

g2250.d:
ἡμέρα hēméra, hay-mer'-ah; feminine (with G5610 implied) of a derivative of ἧμαι hēmai (to sit; akin to
 the base of G1476) meaning tame, i.e. gentle; day, i.e. (literally) the
 time space between dawn and dark, or the whole 24 hours (but several
 days were usually reckoned by the Jews as inclusive of the parts of
 both extremes); figuratively, a period (always defined more or less
 clearly by the context):—age, + alway, (mid-)day (by day, (-ly)), +
 for ever, judgment, (day) time, while, years.
g2250.r: From (with ὥρα (G5610) implied) of a derivative of hemai (to sit, akin to the base of ἑδραῖος (G1476)) meaning tame, i.e. gentle|English: hour, time, season, misc

g2251.d: ἡμέτερος hēméteros, hay-met'-er-os; from G2249; our:—our, your (by a different reading).
g2251.r: From ἡμεῖς (G2249)|English: we, us, we ourselves

g2252.d: ἤμην ḗmēn, ay'-mane; a prolonged form of G2258; I was:—be, was. (Sometimes unexpressed).
g2252.r: A prolonged form of ἦν (G2258)|English: was, were, had been, had, taught, stood, misc

g2253.d:
ἡμιθανής hēmithanḗs, hay-mee-than-ace'; from a presumed compound of the base of G2255 and G2348; half dead, i.e.
 entirely exhausted:—half dead.
g2253.r: From a presumed compound of the base of ἥμισυς (G2255) and θνῄσκω (G2348)|English: half

g2254.d:
ἡμῖν hēmîn, hay-meen'; dative case plural of G1473; to (or for, with, by) us:—our, (for) us,
 we.
g2254.r: Dative case plural of ἐγώ (G1473)|English: I, my, me, not tr

g2255.d:
†ἥμισυ hḗmisy, hay'-mee-soo; neuter of a derivative from an inseparable prefix akin to G260 (through
 the idea of partition involved in connection) and meaning semi-; (as
 noun) half:—half.
g2255.r: Neuter of a derivative from an inseparable pref. akin to ἅμα (G260) (through the idea of partition involved in connection) and meaning semi-|English: together, withal, with, and, misc

g2256.d: ἡμιώριον hēmiṓrion, hay-mee-o'-ree-on; from the base of G2255 and G5610; a half-hour:—half an hour.
g2256.r: From the base of ἥμισυς (G2255) and ὥρα (G5610)|English: half

g2257.d: ἡμῶν hēmōn, hay-mone'; genitive case plural of G1473; of (or from) us:—our (company), us, we.
g2257.r: Genitive case plural of ἐγώ (G1473)|English: I, my, me, not tr

g2258.d:
ἦν ēn, ane; imperfect of G1510; I (thou, etc.) was (wast or were):—+ agree, be, X
 have (+ charge of), hold, use, was(-t), were.
g2258.r: Imperfect of εἰμί (G1510)|English: I am, am, it is I, be, I was, have been, not tr

g2259.d: ἡνίκα hēníka, hay-nee'-kah; of uncertain affinity; at which time:—when.

g226.d:
ἀληθεύω alētheúō, al-ayth-yoo'-o; from G227; to be true (in doctrine and profession):—speak (tell) the
 truth.

g2260.d: ἤπερ ḗper, ay'-per; from G2228 and G4007; than at all (or than perhaps, than indeed):—than.
g2260.r: From ἤ (G2228) and περ (G4007)|English: or, than, either, or else, nor, not tr, misc

g2261.d: ἤπιος ḗpios, ay'-pee-os; probably from G2031; properly, affable, i.e. mild or kind:—gentle.

g2262.d: Ἤρ Ḗr, ayr; of Hebrew origin (H6147); Er, an Israelite:—Er.

g2263.d:
ἤρεμος ḗremos, ay'-rem-os; perhaps by transposition from G2048 (through the idea of stillness); 
 tranquil:—quiet.
g2263.r: Perhaps by transposition from ἔρημος (G2048) (through the idea of stillness)|English: wilderness, desert, desolate, solitary

g2264.d:
†Ἡρώδης Hērṓdēs, hay-ro'-dace; compound of ἥρως hḗrōs (a "hero") and G1491; heroic; Herod, the name of four
 Jewish kings:—Herod.
g2264.r: Compound of heros (a "hero") and εἶδος (G1491)|English: shape, fashion, sight, appearance

g2265.d:
†Ἡρωδιανοί Hērōdianoí, hay-ro-dee-an-oy'; plural of a derivative of G2264; Herodians, i.e. partisans of
 Herod:—Herodians.
g2265.r: Plural of a derivative of Ἡρῴδης (G2264)|English: Herod, Antipas, Herod, the Great, Herod Agrippa

g2266.d: †Ἡρωδιάς Hērōdiás, hay-ro-dee-as'; from G2264; Herodias, a woman of the Heodian family:—Herodias.
g2266.r: From Ἡρῴδης (G2264)|English: Herod, Antipas, Herod, the Great, Herod Agrippa

g2267.d: †Ἡρωδίων Hērōdíōn, hay-ro-dee'-ohn; from G2264; Herodion, a Christian:—Herodion.
g2267.r: From Ἡρῴδης (G2264)|English: Herod, Antipas, Herod, the Great, Herod Agrippa

g2268.d:
Ἡσαΐας Hēsaḯas, hay-sah-ee'-as; of Hebrew origin (H3470); Hesaias (i.e. Jeshajah), an
 Israelite:—Esaias.
g2268.r: Of Hebrew origin יְשַׁעְיָה (H3470)|English: Isaiah, Jeshaiah, Jesaiah

g2269.d: Ἠσαῦ Ēsaû, ay-sow'; of Hebrew origin (H6215); Esau, an Edomite:—Esau.

g227.d:
ἀληθής alēthḗs, al-ay-thace'; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G2990; true (as not
 concealing):—true, truly, truth.
g227.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and λανθάνω (G2990)|English: Alpha

g2270.r: From the same as ἡσύχιος (G2272)|English: quiet, peaceable

g2271.d:
ἡσυχία hēsychía, hay-soo-khee'-ah; feminine of G2272; (as noun) stillness, i.e. desistance from bustle or
 language:—quietness, silence.

g2272.d:
ἡσύχιος hēsýchios, hay-soo'-khee-os; a prolonged form of a compound probably of a derivative of the base of
 G1476 and perhaps G2192; properly, keeping one's seat (sedentary), i.e.
 (by implication) still (undisturbed, undisturbing):—peaceable, quiet.
g2272.r: A prolonged form of a compound probably of a derivative of the base of ἑδραῖος (G1476) and perhaps ἔχω (G2192)|English: steadfast, settled

g2273.d: ἤτοι ḗtoi, ay'-toy; from G2228 and G5104; either indeed:—whether.
g2273.r: From ἤ (G2228) and τοι (G5104)|English: or, than, either, or else, nor, not tr, misc

g2274.d:
†ἡττάω hēttáō, hayt-tah'-o; from the same as G2276; to make worse, i.e. vanquish (literally or
 figuratively); by implication, to rate lower:—be inferior, overcome.
g2274.r: From the same as ἥσσων (G2276)|English: worse, less

g2275.d:
ἥττημα hḗttēma, hayt'-tay-mah; from G2274; a deterioration, i.e. (objectively) failure or
 (subjectively) loss:—diminishing, fault.

g2277.d:
ἤτω ḗtō, ay'-to; third person singular imperative of G1510; let him (or it) be:—let …
 be.
g2277.r: Present imperative third person singular of εἰμί (G1510)|English: I am, am, it is I, be, I was, have been, not tr

g2278.d: ἠχέω ēchéō, ay-kheh'-o; from G2279; to make a loud noise, i.e. reverberate:—roar, sound.

g2279.d:
†ἦχος ēchos, ay'-khos; of uncertain affinity; a loud or confused noise ("echo"), i.e. roar;
 figuratively, a rumor:—fame, sound.

g228.d: ἀληθινός alēthinós, al-ay-thee-nos'; from G227; truthful:—true.

g2280.d: Θαδδαῖος Thaddaîos, thad-dah'-yos; of uncertain origin; Thaddæus, one of the Apostles:—Thaddæus.

g2281.d:
θάλασσα thálassa, thal'-as-sah; probably prolonged from G251; the sea (genitive case or
 specially):—sea.

g2282.d:
θάλπω thálpō, thal'-po; probably akin to θάλλω thállō (to warm); to brood, i.e. (figuratively) to
 foster:—cherish.

g2283.d: Θάμαρ Thámar, tham'-ar; of Hebrew origin (H8559); Thamar (i.e. Tamar), an Israelitess:—Thamar.

g2284.d: θαμβέω thambéō, tham-beh'-o; from G2285; to stupefy (with surprise), i.e. astound:—amaze, astonish.
g2284.r: From θάμβος (G2285)|English: be amazed, be astonished, wonder

g2285.d:
θάμβος thámbos, tham'-bos; akin to an obsolete τάφω táphō (to dumbfound); stupefaction (by surprise),
 i.e. astonishment:—X amazed, + astonished, wonder.
g2285.r: Akin to an obsolete tapho (to dumbfound)|

g2286.d: θανάσιμος thanásimos, than-as'-ee-mos; from G2288; fatal, i.e. poisonous:—deadly.

g2287.d:
θανατήφορος thanatḗphoros, than-at-ay'-for-os; from (the feminine form of) G2288 and G5342; death-bearing, i.e.
 fatal:—deadly.
g2287.r: From (the feminine form of) θάνατος (G2288) and φέρω (G5342)|English: death, deadly

g2288.d:
θάνατος thánatos, than'-at-os; from G2348; (properly, an adjective used as a noun) death (literally or
 figuratively):—X deadly, (be…) death.
g2288.r: From θνῄσκω (G2348)|English: be dead, die, dead man, dead

g2289.d:
θανατόω thanatóō, than-at-o'-o; from G2288 to kill (literally or figuratively):—become dead, (cause to
 be) put to death, kill, mortify.

g229.d: ἀλήθω alḗthō, al-ay'-tho; from the same as G224; to grind:—grind.
g229.r: From the same as ἄλευρον (G224)|English: meal

g2290.d: θάπτω tháptō, thap'-to; a primary verb; to celebrate funeral rites, i.e. inter:—bury.

g2291.d:
Θάρα Thára, thar'-ah; of Hebrew origin (H8646); Thara (i.e. Terach), the father of
 Abraham:—Thara.
g2291.r: Of Hebrew origin תֶּרַח (H8646)|English: Terah, Tarah, Tahath

g2292.d:
θαῤῥέω tharrhéō, thar-hreh'-o; another form for G2293; to exercise courage:—be bold, × boldly, have
 confidence, be confident. Compare G5111.
g2292.r: Another form for θαρσέω (G2293)|English: be of good cheer, be of good comfort

g2293.d: θαρσέω tharséō, thar-seh'-o; from G2294; to have courage:—be of good cheer (comfort). Compare G2292.

g2294.d:
θάρσος thársos, thar'-sos; akin (by transposition) to θράσος thrásos (daring); boldness
 (subjectively):—courage.

g2295.d:
θαῦμα thaûma, thos'-mah; apparently from a form of G2300; wonder (properly concrete; but by
 implication, abstract):—admiration.
g2295.r: Apparently from a form of θεάομαι (G2300)|English: see, behold, look, look upon

g2296.d:
†θαυμάζω thaumázō, thou-mad'-zo; from G2295; to wonder; by implication, to admire:—admire, have in
 admiration, marvel, wonder.

g2297.d:
θαυμάσιος thaumásios, thow-mas'-ee-os; from G2295; wondrous, i.e. (neuter as noun) a miracle:—wonderful
 thing.

g2298.d:
θαυμαστός thaumastós, thow-mas-tos'; from G2296; wondered at, i.e. (by implication)
 wonderful:—marvel(-lous).
g2298.r: From θαυμάζω (G2296)|English: marvel, wonder, have in admiration, admire, marvelled

g2299.d: θεά theá, theh-ah'; feminine of G2316; a female deity:—goddess.
g2299.r: From of θεός (G2316)|English: God, god, godly, God-ward, misc

g23.d:
ἀγανακτέω aganaktéō, ag-an-ak-teh'-o; from ἄγαν ágan (much) and ἄχθος áchthos (grief; akin to the base of G43); to be
 greatly afflicted, i.e. (figuratively) indignant:—be much (sore)
 displeased, have (be moved with, with) indignation.
g23.r: From agan (much) and achthos (grief, akin to the base of ἀγκάλη (G43))|English: arm

g230.d:
ἀληθῶς alēthōs, al-ay-thoce'; adverb from G227; truly:—indeed, surely, of a surety, truly, of a (in)
 truth, verily, very.

g2300.d:
θεάομαι theáomai, theh-ah'-om-ahee; a prolonged form of a primary verb; to look closely at, i.e. (by
 implication) perceive (literally or figuratively); by extension to
 visit:—behold, look (upon), see. Compare G3700.
g2300.r: A prolonged form of a primary verb|

g2301.d: †θεατρίζω theatrízō, theh-at-rid'-zo; from G2302; to expose as a spectacle:—make a gazing stock.

g2302.d:
θέατρον théatron, theh'-at-ron; from G2300; a place for public show ("theatre"), i.e. general
 audience-room; by implication, a show itself
 (figuratively):—spectacle, theatre.
g2302.r: From θεάομαι (G2300)|English: see, behold, look, look upon

g2303.d:
θεῖον theîon, thi'-on; probably neuter of G2304 (in its original sense of flashing); 
 sulphur:—brimstone.
g2303.r: Probably of θεῖος (G2304) (in its original sense of flashing)|English: divine, Godhead

g2304.d: θεῖος theîos, thi'-os; from G2316; godlike (neuter as noun, divinity):—divine, godhead.
g2304.r: From θεός (G2316)|English: God, god, godly, God-ward, misc

g2305.d: θειότης theiótēs, thi-ot'-ace; from G2304; divinity (abstractly):—godhead.

g2306.d: θειώδης theiṓdēs, thi-o'-dace; from G2303 and 1491; sulphur-like, i.e. sulphurous:—brimstone.

g2307.d:
θέλημα thélēma, thel'-ay-mah; from the prolonged form of G2309; a determination (properly, the
 thing), i.e. (actively) choice (specially, purpose, decree;
 abstractly, volition) or (passively) inclination:—desire, pleasure,
 will.
g2307.r: From the prolonged form of θέλω (G2309)|English: will/would, will/would have, desire, desirous, list, to will, misc

g2308.d: θέλησις thélēsis, thel'-ay-sis; from G2309; determination (properly, the act), i.e. option:—will.
g2308.r: From θέλω (G2309)|English: will/would, will/would have, desire, desirous, list, to will, misc

g2309.d:
†θέλω thélō, thel'-o; apparently strengthened from the alternate form of G138; to determine
 (as an active option from subjective impulse; whereas G1014 properly
 denotes rather a passive acquiescence in objective considerations),
 i.e. choose or prefer (literally or figuratively); by implication, to
 wish, i.e. be inclined to (sometimes adverbially, gladly);
 impersonally for the future tense, to be about to; by Hebraism, to
 delight in:—desire, be disposed (forward), intend, list, love, mean,
 please, have rather, (be) will (have, -ling, - ling(-ly)).
g2309.r: Apparently strengthened from the alternate form of αἱρέω (G138)|English: choose

g231.d:
ἁλιεύς halieús, hal-ee-yoos'; from G251; a sailor (as engaged on the salt water), i.e. (by
 implication) a fisher:—fisher(-man).

g2310.d:
†θεμέλιος themélios, them-el'-ee-os; from a derivative of G5087; something put down, i.e. a substruction (of
 a building, etc.), (literally or figuratively):—foundation.
g2310.r: From a derivative of τίθημι (G5087)|English: lay, put, lay down, make, appoint, kneel down, misc

g2311.d:
θεμελιόω themelióō, them-el-ee-o'-o; from G2310; to lay a basis for, i.e. (literally) erect, or
 (figuratively) consolidate:—(lay the) found(- ation), ground, settle.

g2312.d: θεοδίδακτος theodídaktos, theh-od-id'-ak-tos; from G2316 and G1321; divinely instructed:—taught of God.
g2312.r: From θεός (G2316) and διδάσκω (G1321)|English: God, god, godly, God-ward, misc

g2314.d: θεομάχος theomáchos, theh-om'-akh-os; from G2316 and G3164; an opponent of deity:—to fight against God.
g2314.r: From θεός (G2316) and μάχομαι (G3164)|English: God, god, godly, God-ward, misc

g2315.d:
θεόπνευστος theópneustos, theh-op'-nyoo-stos; from G2316 and a presumed derivative of G4154; divinely breathed
 in:—given by inspiration of God.
g2315.r: From θεός (G2316) and a presumed derivative of πνέω (G4154)|English: God, god, godly, God-ward, misc

g2316.d:
θεός theós, theh'-os; of uncertain affinity; a deity, especially (with G3588) the supreme
 Divinity; figuratively, a magistrate; by Hebraism, very:—X exceeding,
 God, god(-ly, -ward).
g2316.r: Of uncertain affinity; a deity, especially (with ὁ (G3588)) the supreme Divinity|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g2317.d: θεοσέβεια theosébeia, theh-os-eb'-i-ah; from G2318; devoutness, i.e. piety:—godliness.

g2318.d: θεοσεβής theosebḗs, theh-os-eb-ace'; from G2316 and G4576; reverent of God, i.e. pious:—worshipper of God.
g2318.r: From θεός (G2316) and σέβω (G4576)|English: God, god, godly, God-ward, misc

g2319.d:
θεοστυγής theostygḗs, theh-os-too-gace'; from G2316 and the base of G4767; hateful to God, i.e. impious:—hater
 of God.
g2319.r: From θεός (G2316) and the base of στυγητός (G4767)|English: God, god, godly, God-ward, misc

g232.d:
ἁλιεύω halieúō, hal-ee-yoo'-o; from G231; to be a fisher, i.e. (by implication) to fish:—go
 a-fishing.

g2320.d: θεότης theótēs, theh-ot'-ace; from G2316; divinity (abstractly):—godhead.
g2320.r: From θεός (G2316)|English: God, god, godly, God-ward, misc

g2321.d:
Θεόφιλος Theóphilos, theh-of'-il-os; from G2316 and G5384; friend of God; Theophilus, a
 Christian:—Theophilus.
g2321.r: From θεός (G2316) and φίλος (G5384)|English: God, god, godly, God-ward, misc

g2322.d:
θεραπεία therapeía, ther-ap-i'-ah; from G2323; attendance (specially, medical, i.e. cure); figuratively
 and collectively, domestics:—healing, household.

g2323.d:
θεραπεύω therapeúō, ther-ap-yoo'-o; from the same as G2324; to wait upon menially, i.e. (figuratively) to
 adore (God), or (specially) to relieve (of disease):—cure, heal,
 worship.
g2323.r: From the same as θεράπων (G2324)|English: servant

g2324.d:
θεράπων therápōn, ther-ap'-ohn; apparently a participle from an otherwise obsolete derivative of the
 base of G2330; a menial attendant (as if cherishing):—servant.
g2324.r: Apparently a participle from an otherwise obsolete derivative of the base of θέρος (G2330)|English: summer

g2325.d: θερίζω therízō, ther-id'-zo; from G2330 (in the sense of the crop); to harvest:—reap.
g2325.r: From θέρος (G2330) (in the sense of the crop)|English: summer

g2326.d: θερισμός therismós, ther-is-mos'; from G2325; reaping, i.e. the crop:—harvest.

g2327.d: θεριστής theristḗs, ther-is-tace'; from G2325; a harvester:—reaper.

g2328.d: θερμαίνω thermaínō, ther-mah'-ee-no; from G2329; to heat (oneself):—(be) warm(-ed, self).

g2329.d: θέρμη thérmē, ther'-may; from the base of G2330; warmth:—heat.
g2329.r: From the base of θέρος (G2330)|English: summer

g233.d: ἁλίζω halízō, hal-id'-zo; from G251; to salt:—salt.

g2330.d: θέρος théros, ther'-os; from a primary θέρω thérō (to heat); properly, heat, i.e. summer:—summer.

g2331.d:
Θεσσαλονικεύς Thessalonikeús, thes-sal-on-ik-yoos'; from G2332; a Thessalonican, i.e. inhabitant of
 Thessalonice:—Thessalonian.

g2332.d:
Θεσσαλονίκη Thessaloníkē, thes-sal-on-ee'-kay; from Θεσσαλός Thessalós (a Thessalian) and G3529; Thessalonice, a place in Asia
 Minor:—Thessalonica.
g2332.r: From Thessalos (a Thessalian) and νίκη (G3529)|English: victory

g2333.d: Θευδᾶς Theudâs, thyoo-das'; of uncertain origin; Theudas, an Israelite:—Theudas.

g2334.d:
θεωρέω theōréō, theh-o-reh'-o; from a derivative of G2300 (perhaps by addition of G3708); to be a
 spectator of, i.e. discern, (literally, figuratively (experience) or
 intensively (acknowledge)):—behold, consider, look on, perceive, see. 
 Compare G3700.
g2334.r: From a derivative of θεάομαι (G2300) (perhaps by add. of ὁράω (G3708))|English: see, behold, look, look upon

g2335.d:
θεωρία theōría, theh-o-ree'-ah; from the same as G2334; spectatorship, i.e. (concretely) a
 spectacle:—sight.
g2335.r: From the same as θεωρέω (G2334)|English: see, behold, perceive, consider, look on

g2336.d: θήκη thḗkē, thay'-kay; from G5087; a receptacle, i.e. scabbard:—sheath.
g2336.r: From τίθημι (G5087)|English: lay, put, lay down, make, appoint, kneel down, misc

g2337.d:
θηλάζω thēlázō, thay-lad'-zo; from θηλή thēlḗ (the nipple); to suckle, (by implication) to suck:—(give)
 suck(-ling).

g2338.d: θῆλυς thēlys, thay'-loos; from the same as G2337; female:—female, woman.
g2338.r: From the same as θηλάζω (G2337)|English: give suck, suck, suckling

g2339.d:
θήρα thḗra, thay'-rah; from θήρ thḗr (a wild animal, as game); hunting, i.e. (figuratively)
 destruction:—trap.
g2339.r: From ther (a wild animal, as game)|

g234.d: †ἀλίσγεμα alísgema, al-is'-ghem-ah; from ἀλισγέω alisgéō (to soil); (ceremonially) defilement:—pollution.

g2340.d:
θηρεύω thēreúō, thay-ryoo'-o; from G2339; to hunt (an animal), i.e. (figuratively) to carp
 at:—catch.

g2341.d:
θηριομαχέω thēriomachéō, thay-ree-om-akh-eh'-o; from a compound of G2342 and G3164; to be a beast-fighter (in the
 gladiatorial show), i.e. (figuratively) to encounter (furious
 men):—fight with wild beasts.
g2341.r: From a compound of θηρίον (G2342) and μάχομαι (G3164)|English: beast, wild beast, venomous beast

g2342.d:
θηρίον thēríon, thay-ree'-on; diminutive from the same as G2339; a dangerous animal:—(venomous,
 wild) beast.
g2342.r: Diminutive from the same as θήρα (G2339)|English: trap

g2343.d:
θησαυρίζω thēsaurízō, thay-sow-rid'-zo; from G2344; to amass or reserve (literally or figuratively):—lay up
 (treasure), (keep) in store, (heap) treasure (together, up).

g2344.d:
θησαυρός thēsaurós, thay-sow-ros'; from G5087; a deposit, i.e. wealth (literally or
 figuratively):—treasure.
g2344.r: From τίθημι (G5087)|English: lay, put, lay down, make, appoint, kneel down, misc

g2345.d:
θιγγάνω thingánō, thing-gan'-o; a prolonged form of an obsolete primary θίγω thígō (to finger); to
 manipulate, i.e. have to do with; by implication, to injure:—handle,
 touch.
g2345.r: A prolonged form of an obsolete primary thigo (to finger)|

g2346.d:
θλίβω thlíbō, thlee'-bo; akin to the base of G5147; to crowd (literally or
 figuratively):—afflict, narrow, throng, suffer tribulation, trouble.
g2346.r: Akin to the base of τρίβος (G5147)|English: path

g2347.d:
†θλῖψις thlîpsis, thlip'-sis; from G2346; pressure (literally or figuratively):—afflicted(-tion),
 anguish, burdened, persecution, tribulation, trouble.
g2347.r: From θλίβω (G2346)|English: trouble, afflict, narrow, throng, suffer tribulation

g2348.d:
θνήσκω thnḗskō, thnay'-sko; a strengthened form of a simpler primary θάνω thánō than'-o (which is used
 for it only in certain tenses); to die (literally or
 figuratively):—be dead, die.
g2348.r: A strengthened form of a simpler primary thano {than'-o} (which is used for it only in certain tenses)|

g2349.d: θνητός thnētós, thnay-tos'; from G2348; liable to die:—mortal(-ity).
g2349.r: From θνῄσκω (G2348)|English: be dead, die, dead man, dead

g235.d:
ἀλλά allá, al-lah'; neuter plural of G243; properly, other things, i.e. (adverbially)
 contrariwise (in many relations):—and, but (even), howbeit, indeed,
 nay, nevertheless, no, notwithstanding, save, therefore, yea, yet.
g235.r: Neuter plural of ἄλλος (G243)|English: other(s), another, some, one, misc

g2350.d:
θορυβέω thorybéō, thor-oo-beh'-o; from G2351; to be in tumult, i.e. disturb, clamor:—make ado (a noise),
 trouble self, set on an uproar.

g2351.d: θόρυβος thórybos, thor'-oo-bos; from the base of G2360; a disturbance:—tumult, uproar.
g2351.r: From the base of θροέω (G2360)|English: trouble

g2352.d: θραύω thraúō, throw'-o; a primary verb; to crush:—bruise. Compare G4486.

g2353.d: θρέμμα thrémma, threm'-mah; from G5142; stock (as raised on a farm):—cattle.
g2353.r: From τρέφω (G5142)|English: feed, nourish, bring up

g2354.d: θρηνέω thrēnéō, thray-neh'-o; from G2355; to bewail:—lament, mourn.

g2356.d:
θρησκεία thrēskeía, thrace-ki'-ah; from a derivative of G2357; ceremonial observance:—religion,
 worshipping.
g2356.r: From a derivative of θρησκός (G2357)|English: religious

g2357.d:
θρησκός thrēskós, thrace'-kos; probably from the base of G2360; ceremonious in worship (as
 demonstrative), i.e. pious:—religious.
g2357.r: Probably from the base of θροέω (G2360)|English: trouble

g2358.d:
θριαμβεύω thriambeúō, three-am-byoo'-o; from a prolonged compound of the base of G2360; and a derivative of G680
 (meaning a noisy iambus, sung in honor of Bacchus); to make an
 acclamatory procession, i.e. (figuratively) to conquer or (by
 Hebraism) to give victory:—(cause) to triumph (over).
g2358.r: From a prolonged compound of the base of θροέω (G2360)|English: trouble

g2359.d:
θρίξ thríx, threeks; genitive case τριχός trichós, etc.; of uncertain derivation; hair:—hair. 
 Compare G2864.
g2359.r: Genitive case trichos, etc., of uncertain derivation|

g236.d: ἀλλάσσω allássō, al-las'-so; from G243; to make different:—change.
g236.r: From ἄλλος (G243)|English: other(s), another, some, one, misc

g2360.d:
θροέω throéō, thro-eh'-o; from θρέομαι thréomai to wail; to clamor, i.e. (by implication) to
 frighten:—trouble.

g2361.d: θρόμβος thrómbos, throm'-bos; perhaps from G5142 (in the sense of thickening); a clot:—great drop.
g2361.r: Perhaps from τρέφω (G5142) (in the sense of thickening)|English: feed, nourish, bring up

g2362.d:
θρόνος thrónos, thron'-os; from θράω thráō (to sit); a stately seat ("throne"); by implication, power
 or (concretely) a potentate:—seat, throne.
g2362.r: From thrao (to sit), a stately seat (|

g2363.d: Θυάτειρα Thyáteira, thoo-at'-i-rah; of uncertain derivation; Thyatira, a place in Asia Minor:—Thyatira.

g2364.d:
θυγάτηρ thygátēr, thoo-gat'-air; apparently a primary word (compare "daughter"); a female child, or (by
 Hebraism) descendant (or inhabitant):—daughter.

g2365.d: θυγάτριον thygátrion, thoo-gat'-ree-on; from G2364; a daughterling:—little (young) daughter.

g2366.d: θύελλα thýella, thoo'-el-lah; from G2380 (in the sense of blowing) a storm:—tempest.
g2366.r: From θύω (G2380) (in the sense of blowing)|English: kill, sacrifice, do sacrifice, slay

g2367.d:
θύϊνος thýïnos, thoo'-ee-nos; from a derivative of G2380 (in the sense of blowing; denoting a certain
 fragrant tree); made of citron-wood:—thyine.
g2367.r: From a derivative of θύω (G2380) (in the sense of blowing, denoting a certain fragrant tree)|English: kill, sacrifice, do sacrifice, slay

g2368.d:
θυμίαμα thymíama, thoo-mee'-am-ah; from G2370; an aroma, i.e. fragrant powder burnt in religious service;
 by implication, the burning itself:—incense, odour.

g2369.d:
θυμιαστήριον thymiastḗrion, thoo-mee-as-tay'-ree-on; from a derivative of G2370; a place of fumigation, i.e. the alter of
 incense (in the Temple):—censer.
g2369.r: From a derivative of θυμιάω (G2370)|English: burn incense

g237.d: ἀλλαχόθεν allachóthen, al-lakh-oth'-en; from G243; from elsewhere:—some other way.
g237.r: From ἄλλος (G243)|English: other(s), another, some, one, misc

g2370.d:
θυμιάω thymiáō, thoo-mee-ah'-o; from a derivative of G2380 (in the sense of smoking); to fumigate, i.e.
 offer aromatic fumes:—burn incense.
g2370.r: From a derivative of θύω (G2380) (in the sense of smoking)|English: kill, sacrifice, do sacrifice, slay

g2371.d:
θυμομαχέω thymomachéō, thoo-mom-akh-eh'-o; from a presumed compound of G2372 and G3164; to be in a furious fight,
 i.e. (figuratively) to be exasperated:—be highly displeased.
g2371.r: From a presumed compound of θυμός (G2372) and μάχομαι (G3164)|English: wrath, fierceness, indignation

g2372.d:
θυμός thymós, thoo-mos'; from G2380; passion (as if breathing hard):—fierceness, indignation,
 wrath. Compare G5590.
g2372.r: From θύω (G2380)|English: kill, sacrifice, do sacrifice, slay

g2373.d: θυμόω thymóō, tho-mo'-o; from G2372; to put in a passion, i.e. enrage:—be wroth.

g2374.d:
θύρα thýra, thoo'-rah; apparently a primary word (compare "door"); a portal or entrance (the
 opening or the closure, literally or figuratively):—door, gate.

g2375.d: θυρεός thyreós, thoo-reh-os'; from G2374; a large shield (as door-shaped):—shield.

g2376.d: θυρίς thyrís, thoo-rece'; from G2374; an aperture, i.e. window:—window.

g2377.d:
θυρωρός thyrōrós, thoo-ro-ros'; from G2374 and οὖρος oûros (a watcher); a gate- warden:—that kept the door,
 porter.
g2377.r: From θύρα (G2374) and ouros (a watcher)|English: door, gate

g2378.d:
θυσία thysía, thoo-see'-ah; from G2380; sacrifice (the act or the victim, literally or
 figuratively):—sacrifice.
g2378.r: From θύω (G2380)|English: kill, sacrifice, do sacrifice, slay

g2379.d:
θυσιαστήριον thysiastḗrion, thoo-see-as-tay'-ree-on; from a derivative of G2378; a place of sacrifice, i.e. an altar
 (special or genitive case, literal or figurative):—altar.
g2379.r: From a derivative of θυσία (G2378)|English: sacrifice

g238.d:
ἀλληγορέω allēgoréō, al-lay-gor-eh'-o; from G243 and ἀγορέω agoréō (to harangue (compare G58)); to allegorize:—be an
 allegory (the Greek word itself).
g238.r: From ἄλλος (G243) and agoreo (to harangue, cf ἀγορά (G58))|English: other(s), another, some, one, misc

g2380.d:
θύω thýō, thoo'-o; a primary verb; properly, to rush (breathe hard, blow, smoke), i.e.
 (by implication) to sacrifice (properly, by fire, but genitive case);
 by extension to immolate (slaughter for any purpose):—kill, (do)
 sacrifice, slay.

g2381.d:
Θωμᾶς Thōmâs, tho-mas'; of Chaldee origin (compare H8380); the twin; Thomas, a
 Christian:—Thomas.
g2381.r: Of Aramaic origin, cf תְּאוֹמִים (H8380)|English: twin

g2382.d:
θώραξ thṓrax, tho'-rax; of uncertain affinity; the chest ("thorax"), i.e. (by implication) a
 corslet:—breast-plate.

g2383.d: †Ἰάειρος Iáeiros, ee-ah'-i-ros; of Hebrew origin (H2971); Jairus (i.e. Jair), an Israelite:—Jairus.

g2384.d:
Ἰακώβ Iakṓb, ee-ak-obe'; of Hebrew origin (H3290); Jacob (i.e. Ja`akob), the progenitor of the
 Israelites:—also an Israelite:—Jacob.

g2385.d:
Ἰάκωβος Iákōbos, ee-ak'-o-bos; the same as G2384 Græcized; Jacobus, the name of three
 Israelites:—James.
g2385.r: The same as Ἰακώβ (G2384) Graecised|English: Jacob

g2386.d: ἴαμα íama, ee'-am-ah; from G2390; a cure (the effect):—healing.

g2387.d: Ἰαμβρῆς Iambrēs, ee-am-brace'; of Egyptian origin; Jambres, an Egyptian:—Jambres.

g2388.d: Ἰαννά Ianná, ee-an-nah'; probably of Hebrew origin (compare H3238); Janna, an Israelite:—Janna.
g2388.r: Probably of Hebrew origin, cf יָנָה (H3238)|English: oppress, vex, destroy, oppressor, proud, do wrong, oppression, thrust out

g2389.d: Ἰαννῆς Iannēs, ee-an-nace'; of Egyptian origin; Jannes, an Egyptian:—Jannes.

g239.d:
ἀλληλουϊα allēlouïa, al-lay-loo'-ee-ah; of Hebrew origin (imperative of H1984 and H3050); praise ye Jah!, an
 adoring exclamation:—alleluiah.
g239.r: Of Hebrew origin from הָלַל (H1984) and יָהּ (H3050)|English: praise, glory, boast, mad, shine, foolish, fools, commended, rage, celebrate, give, marriage, renowned

g2390.d:
ἰάομαι iáomai, ee-ah'-om-ahee; middle voice of apparently a primary verb; to cure (literally or
 figuratively):—heal, make whole.
g2390.r: Middle voice of apparently a primary verb|

g2391.d: †Ἰάρεδ Iáred, ee-ar'-ed; of Hebrew origin (H3382); Jared (i.e. Jered), an antediluvian:—Jared.
g2391.r: Of Hebrew origin יֶרֶד (H3382)|English: Jared, Jered

g2392.d: ἴασις íasis, ee'-as-is; from G2390; curing (the act):—cure, heal(-ing).

g2393.d: ἴασπις íaspis, ee'-as-pis; probably of foreign origin (see H3471); "jasper", a gem:—jasper.
g2393.r: Probably of foreign origin, see יָֽשְׁפִה (H3471)|English: jasper

g2394.d:
Ἰάσων Iásōn, ee-as'-oan; future active participle masculine of G2390; about to cure; Jason, a
 Christian:—Jason.
g2394.r: Future active participle masculine of ἰάομαι (G2390)|English: heal, make whole

g2395.d: ἰατρός iatrós, ee-at-ros'; from G2390; a physician:—physician.

g2396.d:
ἴδε íde, id'-eh; second person singular imperative active of G1492; used as an
 interjection to denote surprise; lo!:—behold, lo, see.
g2396.r: Second person singular imperative active of εἴδω (G1492)|English: know, cannot tell, know how, wist, misc, see, behold, look, perceive

g2398.d:
ἴδιος ídios, id'-ee-os; of uncertain affinity; pertaining to self, i.e. one's own; by
 implication, private or separate:—X his acquaintance, when they were
 alone, apart, aside, due, his (own, proper, several), home, (her, our,
 thine, your) own (business), private(-ly), proper, severally, their
 (own).

g2399.d:
ἰδιώτης idiṓtēs, id-ee-o'-tace; from G2398; a private person, i.e. (by implication) an ignoramus
 (compare "idiot"):—ignorant, rude, unlearned.
g2399.r: From ἴδιος (G2398)|English: his own, their own, privately, apart, your own, his, own, not tr, misc

g24.d: ἀγανάκτησις aganáktēsis, ag-an-ak'-tay-sis; from G23; indignation:—indignation.
g24.r: From ἀγανακτέω (G23)|English: have indignation, be much displeased, with indignation, be sore displeased

g240.d:
ἀλλήλων allḗlōn, al-lay'-lone; Genitive plural from G243 reduplicated; one another:—each other,
 mutual, one another, (the other), (them-, your-)selves, (selves)
 together (sometimes with G3326 or G4314).
g240.r: Gen. plural from ἄλλος (G243) reduplicated|English: other(s), another, some, one, misc

g2400.d:
ἰδού idoú, id-oo'; second person singular imperative middle voice of G1492; used as
 imperative lo!; --behold, lo, see.
g2400.r: Second person singular imperative middle voice of εἴδω (G1492)|English: know, cannot tell, know how, wist, misc, see, behold, look, perceive

g2401.d:
Ἰδουμαία Idoumaía, id-oo-mah'-yah; of Hebrew origin (H123); Idumæa (i.e. Edom), a region East (and South)
 of Palestine:—Idumæa.
g2401.r: Of Hebrew origin אֱדֹם (H123)|English: Edom, Edomites, Idumea

g2402.d: ἱδρώς hidrṓs, hid-roce'; a strengthened form of a primary idos (sweat); perspiration:—sweat.
g2402.r: A strengthened form of a primary idos (sweat)|

g2403.d:
†Ἰεζαβήλ Iezabḗl, ee-ed-zab-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H348); Jezabel (i.e. Jezebel), a Tyrian woman (used
 as a synonym of a termagant or false teacher):—Jezabel.

g2404.d:
Ἱεράπολις Hierápolis, hee-er-ap'-ol-is; from G2413 and G4172; holy city; Hierapolis, a place in Asia
 Minor:—Hierapolis.

g2405.d:
ἱερατεία hierateía, hee-er-at-i'-ah; from G2407; priestliness, i.e. the sacerdotal function:—office of the
 priesthood, priest's office.
g2405.r: From ἱερατεύω (G2407)|English: execute the priest's office

g2406.d:
ἱεράτευμα hieráteuma, hee-er-at'-yoo-mah; from G2407; the priestly fraternity, i.e. sacerdotal order
 (figuratively):—priesthood.
g2406.r: From ἱερατεύω (G2407)|English: execute the priest's office

g2407.d:
ἱερατεύω hierateúō, hee-er-at-yoo'-o; prolongation from G2409; to be a priest, i.e. perform his
 functions:—execute the priest's office.
g2407.r: Prolongation from ἱερεύς (G2409)|English: priest, high priest

g2408.d:
Ἱερεμίας Hieremías, hee-er-em-ee'-as; of Hebrew origin (H3414); Hieremias (i.e. Jermijah), an
 Israelite:—Jeremiah.

g2409.d: ἱερεύς hiereús, hee-er-yooce'; from G2413; a priest (literally or figuratively):—(high) priest.

g241.d: ἀλλογενής allogenḗs, al-log-en-ace'; from G243 and G1085; foreign, i.e. not a Jew:—stranger.
g241.r: From ἄλλος (G243) and γένος (G1085)|English: other(s), another, some, one, misc

g2410.d: Ἱεριχώ Hierichṓ, hee-er-ee-kho'; of Hebrew origin (H3405); Jericho, a place in Palestine:—Jericho.

g2411.d:
ἱερόν hierón, hee-er-on'; neuter of G2413; a sacred place, i.e. the entire precincts (whereas
 G3485 denotes the central sanctuary itself) of the Temple (at Jerusalem
 or elsewhere):—temple.

g2412.d: ἱεροπρεπής hieroprepḗs, hee-er-op-rep-ace'; from G2413 and the same as G4241; reverent:—as becometh holiness.
g2412.r: From ἱερός (G2413) and the same as πρέπω (G4241)|English: holy

g2413.d: ἱερός hierós, hee-er-os'; of uncertain affinity; sacred:—holy.

g2414.d:
Ἱεροσόλυμα Hierosólyma, hee-er-os-ol'-oo-mah; of Hebrew origin (H3389); Hierosolyma (i.e. Jerushalaim), the capitol
 of Palestine:—Jerusalem. Compare G2419.

g2415.d:
Ἱεροσολυμίτης Hierosolymítēs, hee-er-os-ol-oo-mee'-tace; from G2414; a Hierosolymite, i.e. inhabitant of Hierosolyma:—of
 Jerusalem.

g2416.d: ἱεροσυλέω hierosyléō, hee-er-os-ool-eh'-o; from G2417; to be a temple-robber (figuratively):—commit sacrilege.
g2416.r: From ἱερόσυλος (G2417)|English: robber of the churches

g2417.d: ἱερόσυλος hierósylos, hee-er-os'-oo-los; from G2411 and G4813; a temple-despoiler:—robber of churches.

g2418.d:
ἱερουργέω hierourgéō, hee-er-oorg-eh'-o; from a compound of G2411 and the base of G2041; to be a temple-worker,
 i.e. officiate as a priest (figuratively):—minister.
g2418.r: From a compound of ἱερόν (G2411) and the base of ἔργον (G2041)|English: temple

g2419.d:
†Ἱερουσαλήμ Hierousalḗm, hee-er-oo-sal-ame'; of Hebrew origin (H3389); Hierusalem (i.e. Jerushalem), the capitol of
 Palestine:—Jerusalem. Compare G2414.

g242.d:
ἅλλομαι hállomai, hal'-lom-ahee; middle voice of apparently a primary verb; to jump; figuratively, to
 gush:—leap, spring up.
g242.r: Middle voice of apparently a primary verb|

g2420.d:
ἱερωσύνη hierōsýnē, hee-er-o-soo'-nay; from G2413; sacredness, i.e. (by implication) the priestly
 office:—priesthood.

g2421.d: Ἰεσσαί Iessaí, es-es-sah'-ee; of Hebrew origin (H3448); Jessæ (i.e. Jishai), an Israelite:—Jesse.

g2422.d:
Ἰεφθάε Iephtháe, ee-ef-thah'-eh; of Hebrew origin (H3316); Jephthaë (i.e. Jiphtach), an
 Israelite:—Jephthah.
g2422.r: Of Hebrew origin יִפְתָּח (H3316)|English: Jephthah, Jiphtah

g2423.d:
Ἰεχονίας Iechonías, ee-ekh-on-ee'-as; of Hebrew origin (H3204); Jechonias (i.e. Jekonjah), an
 Israelite:—Jechonias.

g2424.d:
Ἰησοῦς Iēsoûs, ee-ay-sooce'; of Hebrew origin (H3091); Jesus (i.e. Jehoshua), the name of our Lord
 and two (three) other Israelites:—Jesus.

g2425.d:
ἱκανός hikanós, hik-an-os'; from ἵκω híkō ( ἱκάνω hikánō or ἱκνέομαι hiknéomai, akin to G2240) (to arrive); competent
 (as if coming in season), i.e. ample (in amount) or fit (in
 character):—able, + content, enough, good, great, large, long
 (while), many, meet, much, security, sore, sufficient, worthy.
g2425.r: From hiko [hikano or hikneomai, akin to ἥκω (G2240)] (to arrive)|English: come

g2426.d: ἱκανότης hikanótēs, hik-an-ot'-ace; from G2425; ability:—sufficiency.
g2426.r: From ἱκανός (G2425)|English: many, much, worthy, long, sufficient, misc

g2427.d: ἱκανόω hikanóō, hik-an-o'-o; from G2425; to enable, i.e. qualify:—make able (meet).
g2427.r: From ἱκανός (G2425)|English: many, much, worthy, long, sufficient, misc

g2428.d:
ἱκετηρία hiketēría, hik-et-ay-ree'-ah; from a derivative of the base of G2425 (through the idea of approaching
 for a favor); intreaty:—supplication.
g2428.r: From a derivative of the base of ἱκανός (G2425) (through the idea of approaching for a favour)|English: many, much, worthy, long, sufficient, misc

g2429.d: †ἱκμάς hikmás, hik-mas'; of uncertain affinity; dampness:—moisture.

g243.d:
ἄλλος állos, al'-los; a primary word; "else," i.e. different (in many applications):—more,
 one (another), (an-, some an-)other(-s, -wise).

g2430.d:
Ἰκόνιον Ikónion, ee-kon'-ee-on; perhaps from G1504; image-like; Iconium, a place in Asia
 Minor:—Iconium.

g2431.d:
ἱλαρός hilarós, hil-ar-os'; from the same as G2436; propitious or merry ("hilarious"), i.e. prompt
 or willing:—cheerful.
g2431.r: From the same as ἵλεως (G2436)|English: be it far, merciful

g2432.d: ἱλαρότης hilarótēs, hil-ar-ot'-ace; from G2431; alacrity:—cheerfulness.

g2433.d:
ἱλάσκομαι hiláskomai, hil-as'-kom-ahee; middle voice from the same as G2436; to conciliate, i.e. (transitively)
 to atone for (sin), or (intransitively) be propitious:—be merciful,
 make reconciliation for.
g2433.r: Middle voice from the same as ἵλεως (G2436)|English: be it far, merciful

g2434.d: ἱλασμός hilasmós, hil-as-mos'; atonement, i.e. (concretely) an expiator:—propitiation.

g2435.d:
†ἱλαστήριον hilastḗrion, hil-as-tay'-ree-on; neuter of a derivative of G2433; an expiatory (place or thing), i.e.
 (concretely) an atoning victim, or (specially) the lid of the Ark (in
 the Temple):—mercyseat, propitiation.
g2435.r: From a derivative of ἱλάσκομαι (G2433)|English: be merciful, make reconciliation

g2436.d:
ἵλεως híleōs, hil'-eh-oce; perhaps from the alternate form of G138; cheerful (as attractive), i.e.
 propitious; adverbially (by Hebraism) God be gracious!, i.e. (in
 averting some calamity) far be it:—be it far, merciful.
g2436.r: Perhaps from the alternate form of αἱρέω (G138)|English: choose

g2437.d:
Ἰλλυρικόν Illyrikón, il-loo-ree-kon'; neuter of an adjective from a name of uncertain derivation; (the)
 Illyrican (shore), i.e. (as a name itself) Illyricum, a region of
 Europe:—Illyricum.
g2437.r: From an adjective from a name of uncertain derivation|

g2438.d:
ἱμάς himás, hee-mas'; perhaps from the same as G260; a strap, i.e. (specially) the tie (of a
 sandal) or the lash (of a scourge):—latchet, thong.
g2438.r: Perhaps from the same as ἅμα (G260)|English: together, withal, with, and, misc

g2439.d: ἱματίζω himatízō, him-at-id'-zo; from G2440; to dress:—clothe.
g2439.r: From ἱμάτιον (G2440)|English: garment, raiment, clothes, cloke, robe, vesture, apparel, not tr

g244.d:
ἀλλοτριεπίσκοπος allotriepískopos, al-lot-ree-ep-is'-kop-os; from G245 and G1985; overseeing others' affairs, i.e. a meddler
 (specially, in Gentile customs):—busybody in other men's matters.
g244.r: From ἀλλότριος (G245) and ἐπίσκοπος (G1985)|English: stranger, another man's, strange, other men's, other, alien

g2440.d:
ἱμάτιον himátion, him-at'-ee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of ennumi (to put on); a dress (inner
 or outer):—apparel, cloke, clothes, garment, raiment, robe, vesture.
g2440.r: From a presumed derivative of ennumi (to put on)|

g2441.d: ἱματισμός himatismós, him-at-is-mos'; from G2439; clothing:—apparel (X -led), array, raiment, vesture.

g2443.d:
ἵνα hína, hin'-ah; probably from the same as the former part of G1438 (through the
 demonstrative idea; compare G3588); in order that (denoting the purpose
 or the result):—albeit, because, to the intent (that), lest, so as,
 (so) that, (for) to. Compare G3363.
g2443.r: Probably from the same as the former part of ἑαυτοῦ (G1438) (through the demonstrative idea, cf ὁ (G3588))|English: himself, themselves, yourselves, ourselves, his, their, itself, misc

g2445.d:
Ἰόππη Ióppē, ee-op'-pay; of Hebrew origin (H3305); Joppe (i.e. Japho), a place in
 Palestine:—Joppa.
g2445.r: Of Hebrew origin יָפוֹה (H3305)|English: Joppa, Japho

g2446.d:
Ἰορδάνης Iordánēs, ee-or-dan'-ace; of Hebrew origin (H3383); the Jordanes (i.e. Jarden), a river of
 Palestine:—Jordan.

g2447.d:
ἰός iós, ee-os'; perhaps from εἶμι eîmi (to go) or ἵημι híēmi (to send); rust (as if emitted by
 metals); also venom (as emitted by serpents):—poison, rust.
g2447.r: Perhaps from eimi (to go) or hiemi (to send)|

g2449.d:
Ἰουδαία Ioudaía, ee-oo-dah'-yah; feminine of G2453 (with G1093 implied); the Judæan land (i.e. Judæa),
 a region of Palestine:—Judæa.
g2449.r: Feminine of Ἰουδαῖος (G2453) (with γῆ (G1093) implied)|English: Jew, of Judea, Jewess

g245.d:
ἀλλότριος allótrios, al-lot'-ree-os; from G243; another's, i.e. not one's own; by extension foreign, not
 akin, hostile:—alien, (an-)other (man's, men's), strange(-r).
g245.r: From ἄλλος (G243)|English: other(s), another, some, one, misc

g2450.d: Ἰουδαΐζω Ioudaḯzō, ee-oo-dah-id'-zo; from G2453; to become a Judæan, i.e. "Judaize":—live as the Jews.
g2450.r: From Ἰουδαῖος (G2453)|English: Jew, of Judea, Jewess

g2451.d: Ἰουδαϊκός Ioudaïkós, ee-oo-dah-ee-kos'; from G2453; Judaïc, i.e. resembling a Judæan:—Jewish.
g2451.r: From Ἰουδαῖος (G2453)|English: Jew, of Judea, Jewess

g2452.d:
Ἰουδαϊκῶς Ioudaïkōs, ee-oo-dah-ee-koce'; adverb from G2451; Judaïcally or in a manner resembling a Judæan:—as
 do the Jews.

g2453.d:
Ἰουδαῖος Ioudaîos, ee-oo-dah'-yos; from G2448 (in the sense of G2455 as a country); Judæan, i.e. belonging
 to Jehudah:—Jew(-ess), of Judæa.
g2453.r: From Ἰούδα (G2448) (in the sense of Ἰούδας (G2455) as a country)|English: Juda

g2454.d:
Ἰουδαϊσμός Ioudaïsmós, ee-oo-dah-is-mos'; from G2450; "Judaism", i.e. the Jewish faith and usages:—Jews'
 religion.
g2454.r: From ἰουδαΐζω (G2450)|English: to live as do the Jews

g2455.d:
Ἰούδας Ioúdas, ee-oo-das'; of Hebrew origin (H3063); Judas (i.e. Jehudah), the name of ten
 Israelites; also of the posterity of one of them and its
 region:—Juda(-h, -s); Jude.
g2455.r: Of Hebrew origin יְהוּדָה (H3063)|English: Judah, Bethlehemjudah

g2456.d: Ἰουλία Ioulía, ee-oo-lee'-ah; feminine of the same as G2457; Julia, a Christian woman:—Julia.
g2456.r: Feminine of the same as Ἰούλιος (G2457)|English: Julius

g2457.d: Ἰούλιος Ioúlios, ee-oo'-lee-os; of Latin origin; Julius, a centurion:—Julius.

g2458.d: †Ἰουνιᾶς Iouniâs, ee-oo-nee'-as; of Latin origin; Junias, a Christian:—Junias.

g2459.d:
Ἰοῦστος Ioûstos, ee-ooce'-tos; of Latin origin ("just"); Justus, the name of three
 Christian:—Justus.

g246.d:
ἀλλόφυλος allóphylos, al-lof'-oo-los; from G243 and G5443; foreign, i.e. (specially) Gentile:—one of another
 nation.
g246.r: From ἄλλος (G243) and φυλή (G5443)|English: other(s), another, some, one, misc

g2460.d: ἱππεύς hippeús, hip-yooce'; from G2462; an equestrian, i.e. member of a cavalry corps:—horseman.

g2461.d: †ἱππικόν hippikón, hip-pee-kon'; neuter of a derivative of G2462; the cavalry force:—horse(-men).
g2461.r: Neuter of a derivative of ἵππος (G2462)|English: horse

g2462.d: ἵππος híppos, hip'-pos; of uncertain affinity; a horse:—horse.

g2463.d:
ἶρις îris, ee'-ris; perhaps from G2046 (as a symbol of the female messenger of the pagan
 deities); a rainbow ("iris"):—rainbow.
g2463.r: Perhaps from εἶπον (G2046) (as a symbol of the female messenger of the pagan deities)|English: say, speak, tell, speak of, call

g2464.d:
Ἰσαάκ Isaák, ee-sah-ak'; of Hebrew origin (H3327); Isaac (i.e. Jitschak), the son of
 Abraham:—Isaac.

g2465.d: ἰσάγγελος isángelos, ee-sang'-el-los; from G2470 and G32; like an angel, i.e. angelic:—equal unto the angels.
g2465.r: From ἴσος (G2470) and ἄγγελος (G32)|English: equal, agree together, as much, like

g2469.r: Of Hebrew origin probably אִישׁ (H377) and קִרְיָה (H7149)|English: shew yourselves men

g247.d: ἄλλως állōs, al'-loce; adverb from G243; differently:—otherwise.
g247.r: From ἄλλος (G243)|English: other(s), another, some, one, misc

g2470.d:
ἴσος ísos, ee'-sos; probably from G1492 (through the idea of seeming); similar (in amount
 and kind):—+ agree, as much, equal, like.
g2470.r: Probably from εἴδω (G1492) (through the idea of seeming)|English: know, cannot tell, know how, wist, misc, see, behold, look, perceive

g2471.d:
ἰσότης isótēs, ee-sot'-ace; likeness (in condition or proportion); by implication,
 equity:—equal(-ity).

g2472.d: ἰσότιμος isótimos, ee-sot'-ee-mos; from G2470 and G5092; of equal value or honor:—like precious.
g2472.r: From ἴσος (G2470) and τιμή (G5092)|English: equal, agree together, as much, like

g2473.d: ἰσόψυχος isópsychos, ee-sop'-soo-khos; from G2470 and G5590; of similar spirit:—likeminded.
g2473.r: From ἴσος (G2470) and ψυχή (G5590)|English: equal, agree together, as much, like

g2474.d:
Ἰσραήλ Israḗl, is-rah-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H3478); Israel (i.e. Jisrael), the adopted name of
 Jacob, including his descendants (literally or figuratively):—Israel.
g2474.r: Of Hebrew origin יִשְׂרָאֵל (H3478)|English: Israel, Israelites

g2475.d:
Ἰσραηλίτης Israēlítēs, is-rah-ale-ee'-tace; from G2474; an "Israelite", i.e. descendant of Israel (literally or
 figuratively):—Israelite.

g2476.d:
†ἵστημι hístēmi, his'-tay-mee; a prolonged form of a primary στάω stáō stah'-o (of the same meaning, and
 used for it in certain tenses); to stand (transitively or
 intransitively), used in various applications (literally or
 figuratively):—abide, appoint, bring, continue, covenant, establish,
 hold up, lay, present, set (up), stanch, stand (by, forth, still, up). 
 Compare G5087.
g2476.r: A prolonged form of a primary stao {stah'-o} (of the same meaning, and used for it in certain tenses)|

g2477.d:
ἱστορέω historéō, his-tor-eh'-o; from a derivative of G1492; to be knowing (learned), i.e. (by
 implication) to visit for information (interview):—see.
g2477.r: From a derivative of εἴδω (G1492)|English: know, cannot tell, know how, wist, misc, see, behold, look, perceive

g2478.d:
ἰσχυρός ischyrós, is-khoo-ros'; from G2479; forcible (literally or figuratively):—boisterous,
 mighty(-ier), powerful, strong(-er, man), valiant.
g2478.r: From ἰσχύς (G2479)|English: strength, power, might, ability, mightily, mighty

g2479.r: From a derivative of is (force, cf eschon, a form of ἔχω (G2192))|English: have, be, need, misc

g248.d: ἀλοάω aloáō, al-o-ah'-o; from the same as G257; to tread out grain:—thresh, tread out the corn.
g248.r: From the same as ἅλων (G257)|English: floor

g2480.d:
ἰσχύω ischýō, is-khoo'-o; from G2479; to have (or exercise) force (literally or
 figuratively):—be able, avail, can do(-not), could, be good, might,
 prevail, be of strength, be whole, + much work.
g2480.r: From ἰσχύς (G2479)|English: strength, power, might, ability, mightily, mighty

g2481.d: ἴσως ísōs, ee'-soce; adverb from G2470; likely, i.e. perhaps:—it may be.
g2481.r: From ἴσος (G2470)|English: equal, agree together, as much, like

g2482.d: Ἰταλία Italía, ee-tal-ee'-ah; probably of foreign origin; Italia, a region of Europe:—Italy.

g2483.d: Ἰταλικός Italikós, ee-tal-ee-kos'; from G2482; Italic, i.e. belonging to Italia:—Italian.

g2484.d:
†Ἰτουραΐα Itouraḯa, ee-too-rah'-yah; of Hebrew origin (H3195); Ituræa (i.e. Jetur), a region of
 Palestine:—Ituræa.

g2485.d: ἰχθύδιον ichthýdion, ikh-thoo'-dee-on; diminutive from G2486; a petty fish:—little (small) fish.

g2486.d: ἰχθύς ichthýs, ikh-thoos'; of uncertain affinity; a fish:—fish.

g2487.d:
ἴχνος íchnos, ikh'-nos; from ἰκνέομαι iknéomai (to arrive; compare G2240); a track
 (figuratively):—step.
g2487.r: From ikneomai (to arrive, cf ἥκω (G2240))|English: come

g2488.d:
†Ἰωάθαμ Iōátham, ee-o-ath'-am; of Hebrew origin (H3147); Joatham (i.e. Jotham), an
 Israelite:—Joatham.

g2489.d: Ἰωάννα Iōánna, ee-o-an'-nah; feminine of the same as G2491; Joanna, a Christian:—Joanna.
g2489.r: Of the same as Ἰωάννης (G2491)|English: John (the Baptist), John (the apostle), John (Mark), John (the chief priest)

g249.d:
ἄλογος álogos, al'-og-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G3056; irrational:—brute,
 unreasonable.
g249.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and λόγος (G3056)|English: Alpha

g2491.d:
Ἰωάννης Iōánnēs, ee-o-an'-nace; of Hebrew origin (H3110); Joannes (i.e. Jochanan), the name of four
 Israelites:—John.

g2492.d: Ἰώβ Iṓb, ee-obe'; of Hebrew origin (H347); Job (i.e. Ijob), a patriarch:—Job.

g2493.d: Ἰωήλ Iōḗl, ee-o-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H3100); Joel, an Israelite:—Joel.

g2494.d: †Ἰωνάν Iōnán, ee-o-nan'; probably for G2491 or G2495; Jonan, an Israelite:—Jonan.
g2494.r: Probably for Ἰωάννης (G2491) or Ἰωνᾶς (G2495)|English: John (the Baptist), John (the apostle), John (Mark), John (the chief priest)

g2495.d:
Ἰωνᾶς Iōnâs, ee-o-nas'; of Hebrew origin (H3124); Jonas (i.e. Jonah), the name of two
 Israelites:—Jonas.

g2496.d: †Ἰωράμ Iōrám, ee-o-ram'; of Hebrew origin (H3141); Joram, an Israelite:—Joram.

g2497.d: †Ἰωρείμ Iōreím, ee-o-rime'; perhaps for G2496; Jorim, an Israelite:—Jorim.

g2498.d:
Ἰωσαφάτ Iōsaphát, ee-o-saf-at'; of Hebrew origin (H3092); Josaphat (i.e. Jehoshaphat), an
 Israelite:—Josaphat.

g25.d: ἀγαπάω agapáō, ag-ap-ah'-o; perhaps from ἄγαν ágan (much) (or compare H5689); to love (in a social or moral sense):—(be-)love(-ed). Compare G5368.
g25.r: Perhaps from agan (much) [or cf φιλέω (G5368)]|English: love, kiss

g250.d: ἀλόη alóē, al-o-ay'; of foreign origin (compare G174); aloes (the gum):—aloes.
g250.r: Of foreign origin [cf אֲהָלִים (H174)]|English: aloes, trees of lign aloes

g2500.d:
Ἰωσῆς Iōsēs, ee-o-sace'; perhaps for G2501; Joses, the name of two Israelites:—Joses. Compare
 G2499.
g2500.r: Perhaps for Ἰωσήφ (G2501)|English: Joseph (husband of Mary), Joseph (son of Jacob), Joseph of Arimathaea, Joseph (son of Judas), Joseph of Barsabas, Joseph son of Jonan, Joseph (son of Mattathias)

g2501.d:
†Ἰωσήφ Iōsḗph, ee-o-safe'; of Hebrew origin (H3130); Joseph, the name of seven
 Israelites:—Joseph.

g2502.d: Ἰωσίας Iōsías, ee-o-see'-as; of Hebrew origin (H2977); Josias (i.e. Joshiah), an Israelite:—Josias.

g2503.d:
ἰῶτα iōta, ee-o'-tah; of Hebrew origin (the tenth letter of the Hebrew alphabet); "iota",
 the name of the eighth letter of the Greek alphabet, put
 (figuratively) for a very small part of anything:—jot.
g2503.r: Of Hebrew origin [the tenth letter of the Hebrew alphabet]|

g2504.d:
κἀγώ kagṓ, kag-o'; from G2532 and G1473;  so also the dative case
 
    κἀμοί kamoí  kam-oy', and accusative case
    κἀμέ kamé  kam-eh'
    
 and (or also, even, etc.) I, (to) me:—(and, even, even so, so) I 
 (also, in like wise), both me, me also.
g2504.r: From καί (G2532) and ἐγώ (G1473) (so also the dative case kamoi {kam-oy'}, and accusative case kame {kam-eh'}|English: and, also, even, both, then, so, likewise, not tr., misc

g2505.d:
καθά kathá, kath-ah'; from G2596 and the neuter plural of G3739; according to which things,
 i.e. just as:—as.
g2505.r: From κατά (G2596) and the neuter plural of ὅς (G3739)|English: according to, after, against, in, by, daily, as, misc

g2506.d:
καθαίρεσις kathaíresis, kath-ah'-ee-res-is; from G2507; demolition; figuratively, extinction:—destruction, pulling
 down.
g2506.r: From καθαιρέω (G2507)|English: take down, destroy, put down, pull down, cast down

g2507.d:
καθαιρέω kathairéō, kath-ahee-reh'-o; from G2596 and G138 (including its alternate); to lower (or with
 violence) demolish (literally or figuratively):—cast (pull, put,
 take) down, destroy.
g2507.r: From κατά (G2596) and αἱρέω (G138) (including its alternate)|English: according to, after, against, in, by, daily, as, misc

g2508.d:
καθαίρω kathaírō, kath-ah'-ee-ro; from G2513; to cleanse, i.e. (specially) to prune; figuratively, to
 expiate:—purge.

g2509.d: †καθάπερ katháper, kath-ap'-er; from G2505 and G4007; exactly as:—(even, as well) as.

g2510.d: καθάπτω katháptō, kath-ap'-to; from G2596 and G680; to seize upon:—fasten on.
g2510.r: From κατά (G2596) and ἅπτομαι (G680)|English: according to, after, against, in, by, daily, as, misc

g2511.d:
καθαρίζω katharízō, kath-ar-id'-zo; from G2513; to cleanse (literally or figuratively):—(make) clean(-se),
 purge, purify.

g2512.d:
καθαρισμός katharismós, kath-ar-is-mos'; from G2511; a washing off, i.e. (ceremonially) ablution, (morally)
 expiation:—cleansing, + purge, purification(-fying).
g2512.r: From καθαρίζω (G2511)|English: cleanse, make clean, be clean, purge, purify

g2513.d:
καθαρός katharós, kath-ar-os'; of uncertain affinity; clean (literally or figuratively):—clean,
 clear, pure.

g2514.d: καθαρότης katharótēs, kath-ar-ot'-ace; from G2513; cleanness (ceremonially):—purification.

g2515.d:
καθέδρα kathédra, kath-ed'-rah; from G2596 and the same as G1476; a bench (literally or
 figuratively):—seat.
g2515.r: From κατά (G2596) and the same as ἑδραῖος (G1476)|English: according to, after, against, in, by, daily, as, misc

g2516.d: καθέζομαι kathézomai, kath-ed'-zom-ahee; from G2596 and the base of G1476; to sit down:—sit.
g2516.r: From κατά (G2596) and the base of ἑδραῖος (G1476)|English: according to, after, against, in, by, daily, as, misc

g2517.d:
καθεξῆς kathexēs, kath-ex-ace'; from G2596 and G1836; thereafter, i.e. consecutively; as a noun (by
 ellipsis of noun) a subsequent person or time:—after(-ward), by (in)
 order.
g2517.r: From κατά (G2596) and ἑξῆς (G1836)|English: according to, after, against, in, by, daily, as, misc

g2518.d:
καθεύδω katheúdō, kath-yoo'-do; from G2596 and εὕδω heúdō (to sleep); to lie down to rest, i.e. (by
 implication) to fall asleep (literally or figuratively):—(be
 a-)sleep.
g2518.r: From κατά (G2596) and heudo (to sleep)|English: according to, after, against, in, by, daily, as, misc

g2519.d:
καθηγητής kathēgētḗs, kath-ayg-ay-tace'; from a compound of G2596 and G2233; a guide, i.e. (figuratively) a
 teacher:—master.
g2519.r: From a compound of κατά (G2596) and ἡγέομαι (G2233)|English: according to, after, against, in, by, daily, as, misc

g252.d: ἁλυκός halykós, hal-oo-kos'; from G251; briny:—salt.

g2520.d:
καθήκω kathḗkō, kath-ay'-ko; from G2596 and G2240; to reach to, i.e. (neuter of present active
 participle, figuratively as adjective) becoming:—convenient, fit.
