†λαός laós, lah-os'; apparently a primary word; a people (in general; thus differing from
 G1218, which denotes one's own populace):—people.

g2993.d:
Λαοδίκεια Laodíkeia, lah-od-ik'-i-ah; from a compound of G2992 and G1349; Laodicia, a place in Asia
 Minor:—Laodicea.
g2993.r: From a compound of λαός (G2992) and δίκη (G1349)|English: people

g2994.d: Λαοδικεύς Laodikeús, lah-od-ik-yooce'; from G2993; a Laodicean, i.e. inhabitant of Laodicia:—Laodicean.

g2995.d: λάρυγξ lárynx, lar'-oongks; of uncertain derivation; the throat ("larynx"):—throat.

g2996.d: †Λασαία Lasaía, las-ah'-yah; of uncertain origin; Lasæa, a place in Crete:—Lasea.

g2998.d:
λατομέω latoméō, lat-om-eh'-o; from the same as the first part of G2991 and the base of G5114; to
 quarry:—hew.
g2998.r: From the same as the first part of λαξευτός (G2991) and the base of τομός (G5114)|English: hewn in stone

g2999.d: λατρεία latreía, lat-ri'-ah; from G3000; ministration of God, i.e. worship:—(divine) service.
g2999.r: From λατρεύω (G3000)|English: serve, worship, do the service, worshipper

g3.d: †Ἀβαδδών Abaddṓn, ab-ad-dohn'; of Hebrew origin (H11); a destroying angel:—Abaddon.

g30.d:
†ἀγγεῖον angeîon, ang-eye'-on; from ἄγγος ángos (a pail, perhaps as bent; compare the base of G43); a
 receptacle:—vessel.
g30.r: From aggos (a pail, perhaps as bent, cf base of ἀγκάλη (G43))|English: arm

g3000.d:
λατρεύω latreúō, lat-ryoo'-o; from λάτρις látris (a hired menial); to minister (to God), i.e. render
 religious homage:—serve, do the service, worship(-per).

g3001.d: λάχανον láchanon, lakh'-an-on; from λαχαίνω lachaínō (to dig); a vegetable:—herb.

g3003.d:
†λεγεών legeṓn, leg-eh-ohn'; of Latin origin; a "legion", i.e. Roman regiment
 (figuratively):—legion.

g3004.d:
†λέγω légō, leg'-o; a primary verb; properly, to "lay" forth, i.e. (figuratively) relate
 (in words (usually of systematic or set discourse; whereas G2036 and
 G5346 generally refer to an individual expression or speech
 respectively; while G4483 is properly to break silence merely, and G2980
 means an extended or random harangue)); by implication, to mean:—ask,
 bid, boast, call, describe, give out, name, put forth, say(-ing, on),
 shew, speak, tell, utter.

g3005.d: λεῖμμα leîmma, lime'-mah; from G3007; a remainder:—remnant.
g3005.r: From λείπω (G3007)|English: lack, be wanting, want, be destitute

g3006.d: λεῖος leîos, li'-os; apparently a primary word; smooth, i.e. "level":—smooth.

g3007.d:
λείπω leípō, li'-po; a primary verb; to leave, i.e. (intransitively or passively) to fail
 or be absent:—be destitute (wanting), lack.

g3008.d:
λειτουργέω leitourgéō, li-toorg-eh'-o; from G3011; to be a public servant, i.e. (by analogy) to perform
 religious or charitable functions (worship, obey, relieve):—minister.
g3008.r: From λειτουργός (G3011)|English: minister, he that ministers

g3009.d:
λειτουργία leitourgía, li-toorg-ee'-ah; from G3008; public function (as priest ("liturgy") or
 almsgiver):—ministration(-try), service.

g301.d: Ἀμώς Amṓs, am-oce'; of Hebrew origin (H531); Amos, an Israelite:—Amos.

g3010.d:
λειτουργικός leitourgikós, li-toorg-ik-os'; from the same as G3008; functional publicly ("liturgic"); i.e.
 beneficient:—ministering.
g3010.r: From the same as λειτουργέω (G3008)|English: minister

g3011.d:
λειτουργός leitourgós, li-toorg-os'; from a derivative of G2992 and G2041; a public servant, i.e. a
 functionary in the Temple or Gospel, or (genitive case) a worshipper
 (of God) or benefactor (of man):—minister(-ed).
g3011.r: From a derivative of λαός (G2992) and ἔργον (G2041)|English: people

g3012.d: λέντιον léntion, len'-tee-on; of Latin origin; a "linen" cloth, i.e. apron:—towel.

g3013.d: λεπίς lepís, lep-is'; from λέπω lépō (to peel); a flake:—scale.

g3014.d: λέπρα lépra, lep'-rah; from the same as G3013; scaliness, i.e. "leprosy":—leprosy.
g3014.r: From the same as λεπίς (G3013)|English: scale

g3015.d: λεπρός leprós, lep-ros'; from the same as G3014; scaly, i.e. leprous (a leper):—leper.
g3015.r: From the same as λέπρα (G3014)|English: leprosy

g3016.d:
†λεπτόν leptón, lep-ton'; neuter of a derivative of the same as G3013; something scaled (light),
 i.e. a small coin:—mite.
g3016.r: Neuter of a derivative of the same as λεπίς (G3013)|English: scale

g3017.d:
†Λευΐ Leuḯ, lyoo'-ee; of Hebrew origin (H3878); Levi, the name of three Israelites:—Levi. 
 Compare G3018.

g3019.d: †Λευΐτης Leuḯtēs, lyoo-ee'-tace; from G3017; a Levite, i.e. descendant of Levi:—Levite.

g302.d:
ἄν án, an; a primary particle, denoting a supposition, wish, possibility or
 uncertainty:—(what-, where-, wither-, who-)soever. Usually
 unexpressed except by the subjunctive or potential mood. Also
 contracted for G1437.

g3020.d: †Λευϊτικός Leuïtikós, lyoo-it'-ee-kos; from G3019; Levitic, i.e. relating to the Levites:—Levitical.

g3021.d: λευκαίνω leukaínō, lyoo-kah'-ee-no; from G3022; to whiten:—make white, whiten.

g3022.d: λευκός leukós, lyoo-kos'; from λύκη lýkē ("light"); white:—white.

g3023.d: †λέων léōn, leh-ohn'; a primary word; a "lion":—lion.

g3024.d: λήθη lḗthē, lay'-thay; from G2990; forgetfulness:—+ forget.
g3024.r: From λανθάνω (G2990)|English: be hid, be ignorant of, unawares

g3025.d: ληνός lēnós, lay-nos'; apparently a primary word; a trough, i.e. wine-vat:—winepress.

g3026.d:
λῆρος lēros, lay'-ros; apparently a primary word; twaddle, i.e. an incredible story:—idle
 tale.

g3027.d: λῃστής lēistḗs, lace-tace'; from ληΐζομαι lēḯzomai (to plunder); a brigand:—robber, thief.

g3028.d: †λῆμψις lēmpsis, lape'-sis; from G2983; receipt (the act):—receiving.
g3028.r: From λαμβάνω (G2983)|English: receive, take, have, catch, not tr, misc

g3029.d:
λίαν lían, lee'-an; of uncertain affinity; much (adverbially):—exceeding, great(-ly),
 sore, very (+ chiefest).

g303.d:
†ἀνά aná, an-ah'; a primary preposition and adverb; properly, up; but (by extension)
 used (distributively) severally, or (locally) at (etc.):—and, apiece,
 by, each, every (man), in, through.

g3030.d:
λίβανος líbanos, lib'-an-os; of foreign origin (H3828); the incense-tree, i.e. (by implication)
 incense itself:—frankincense.
g3030.r: Of foreign origin לְבוֹנָה (H3828)|English: frankincense, incense

g3031.d:
λιβανωτός libanōtós, lib-an-o-tos'; from G3030; frankincense, i.e. (by extension) a censer for burning
 it:—censer.

g3032.d: Λιβερτῖνος Libertînos, lib-er-tee'-nos; of Latin origin; a Roman freedman:—Libertine.

g3033.d: Λιβύη Libýē, lib-oo'-ay; probably from G3047; Libye, a region of Africa:—Libya.

g3034.d: λιθάζω litházō, lith-ad'-zo; from G3037; to lapidate:—stone.
g3034.r: From λίθος (G3037)|English: stone, one stone, another, stumbling stone, mill stone

g3035.d: λίθινος líthinos, lith-ee'-nos; from G3037; stony, i.e. made of stone:—of stone.
g3035.r: From λίθος (G3037)|English: stone, one stone, another, stumbling stone, mill stone

g3036.d:
λιθοβολέω lithoboléō, lith-ob-ol-eh'-o; from a compound of G3037 and G906; to throw stones, i.e.
 lapidate:—stone, cast stones.
g3036.r: From a compound of λίθος (G3037) and βάλλω (G906)|English: stone, one stone, another, stumbling stone, mill stone

g3037.d:
λίθος líthos, lee'-thos; apparently a primary word; a stone (literally or
 figuratively):—(mill-, stumbling-)stone.

g3038.d:
λιθόστρωτος lithóstrōtos, lith-os'-tro-tos; from G3037 and a derivative of G4766; stone-strewed, i.e. a tessellated
 mosaic on which the Roman tribunal was placed:—Pavement.
g3038.r: From λίθος (G3037) and a derivative of στρωννύω (G4766)|English: stone, one stone, another, stumbling stone, mill stone

g3039.d:
λικμάω likmáō, lik-mah'-o; from λικμός likmós, the equivalent of λίκνον líknon (a winnowing fan or basket); to
 winnow, i.e. (by analogy), to triturate:—grind to powder.
g3039.r: From likmos, the equivalent of liknon (a winnowing fan or basket)|

g304.d: ἀναβαθμός anabathmós, an-ab-ath-mos'; from G305 (compare G898); a stairway:—stairs.
g304.r: From ἀναβαίνω (G305) [cf βαθμός (G898)]|English: go up, come up, ascend, ascend up, climb up, spring up, grow up, come, enter, arise, rise up, misc, vr ascend

g3040.d: λιμήν limḗn, lee-mane'; apparently a primary word; a harbor:—haven. Compare G2568.

g3041.d:
λίμνη límnē, lim'-nay; probably from G3040 (through the idea of nearness of shore); a pond
 (large or small):—lake.
g3041.r: Probably from λιμήν (G3040) (through the idea of nearness of shore)|English: haven, the fair havens

g3042.d:
λιμός limós, lee-mos'; probably from G3007 (through the idea of destitution); a scarcity of
 food:—dearth, famine, hunger.
g3042.r: Probably from λείπω (G3007) (through the idea of destitution)|English: lack, be wanting, want, be destitute

g3043.d: λίνον línon, lee'-non; probably a primary word; flax, i.e. (by implication) "linen":—linen.

g3044.d: †Λίνος Línos, lee'-nos; perhaps from G3043; Linus, a Christian:—Linus.

g3045.d: λιπαρός liparós, lip-ar-os'; from λίπος lípos (grease); fat, i.e. (figuratively) sumptuous:—dainty.

g3046.d: λίτρα lítra, lee'-trah; of Latin origin (libra); a pound in weight:—pound.

g3047.d:
λίψ líps, leeps; probably from λείβω leíbō (to pour a "libation"); the south(- west) wind (as
 bringing rain, i.e. (by extension) the south quarter):—southwest.

g3048.d:
λογία logía, log-ee'-ah; from G3056 (in the commercial sense); a contribution:—collection,
 gathering.
g3048.r: From λόγος (G3056) (in the commercial sense)|English: word, saying, account, speech, Word (Christ), thing, not tr, misc

g3049.d:
λογίζομαι logízomai, log-id'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G3056; to take an inventory, i.e. estimate (literally
 or figuratively):—conclude, (ac-)count (of), + despise, esteem,
 impute, lay, number, reason, reckon, suppose, think (on).
g3049.r: Middle voice from λόγος (G3056)|English: word, saying, account, speech, Word (Christ), thing, not tr, misc

g305.d:
ἀναβαίνω anabaínō, an-ab-ah'-ee-no; from G303 and the base of G939; to go up (literally or
 figuratively):—arise, ascend (up), climb (go, grow, rise, spring) up,
 come (up).
g305.r: From ἀνά (G303) and the base of βάσις (G939)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3050.d: λογικός logikós, log-ik-os'; from G3056; rational ("logical"):—reasonable, of the word.
g3050.r: From λόγος (G3056)|English: word, saying, account, speech, Word (Christ), thing, not tr, misc

g3051.d: λόγιον lógion, log'-ee-on; neuter of G3052; an utterance (of God):—oracle.

g3052.d: λόγιος lógios, log'-ee-os; from G3056; fluent, i.e. an orator:—eloquent.
g3052.r: From λόγος (G3056)|English: word, saying, account, speech, Word (Christ), thing, not tr, misc

g3053.d:
λογισμός logismós, log-is-mos'; from G3049; computation, i.e. (figuratively) reasoning (conscience,
 conceit):—imagination, thought.
g3053.r: From λογίζομαι (G3049)|English: think, impute, reckon, count, account, suppose, reason, number, misc

g3054.d:
λογομαχέω logomachéō, log-om-akh-eh'-o; from a compound of G3056 and G3164; to be disputatious (on
 trifles):—strive about words.
g3054.r: From a compound of λόγος (G3056) and μάχομαι (G3164)|English: word, saying, account, speech, Word (Christ), thing, not tr, misc

g3055.d:
λογομαχία logomachía, log-om-akh-ee'-ah; from the same as G3054; disputation about trifles
 ("logomachy"):—strife of words.
g3055.r: From the same as λογομαχέω (G3054)|English: strive about words

g3056.d:
λόγος lógos, log'-os; from G3004; something said (including the thought); by implication, a
 topic (subject of discourse), also reasoning (the mental faculty) or
 motive; by extension, a computation; specially, (with the article in
 John) the Divine Expression (i.e. Christ):—account, cause,
 communication, × concerning, doctrine, fame, × have to do, intent,
 matter, mouth, preaching, question, reason, + reckon, remove,
 say(-ing), shew, × speaker, speech, talk, thing, + none of these
 things move me, tidings, treatise, utterance, word, work.
g3056.r: From λέγω (G3004)|English: say, speak, call, tell, misc

g3057.d: λόγχη lónchē, long'-khay; perhaps a primary word; a "lance":—spear.

g3058.d: λοιδορέω loidoréō, loy-dor-eh'-o; from G3060; to reproach, i.e. vilify:—revile.

g3059.d: λοιδορία loidoría, loy-dor-ee'-ah; from G3060; slander or vituperation:—railing, reproach(-fully).

g306.d: †ἀναβάλλομαι anabállomai, an-ab-al'-lom-ahee; middle voice from G303 and G906; to put off (for oneself):—defer.
g306.r: Middle voice from ἀνά (G303) and βάλλω (G906)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3060.d: λοίδορος loídoros, loy'-dor-os; from λοιδός loidós (mischief); abusive, i.e. a blackguard:—railer, reviler.

g3061.d:
λοιμός loimós, loy'-mos; of uncertain affinity; a plague (literally, the disease, or
 figuratively, a pest):—pestilence(-t).

g3062.d:
†λοιποί loipoí, loy-poy'; masculine plural of a derivative of G3007; remaining ones:—other,
 which remain, remnant, residue, rest.
g3062.r: Masculine plural of a derivative of λείπω (G3007)|English: lack, be wanting, want, be destitute

g3065.d: Λουκᾶς Loukâs, loo-kas'; contracted from Latin Lucanus; Lucas, a Christian:—Lucas, Luke.

g3066.d: Λούκιος Loúkios, loo'-kee-os; of Latin origin; illuminative; Lucius, a Christian:—Lucius.

g3067.d: λουτρόν loutrón, loo-tron'; from G3068; a bath, i.e. (figuratively), baptism:—washing.

g3068.d:
λούω loúō, loo'-o; a primary verb; to bathe (the whole person; whereas G3538 means to wet
 a part only, and G4150 to wash, cleanse garments exclusively):—wash.

g3069.d:
Λύδδα Lýdda, lud'-dah; of Hebrew origin (H3850); Lydda (i.e. Lod), a place in
 Palestine:—Lydda.

g307.d:
ἀναβιβάζω anabibázō, an-ab-ee-bad'-zo; from G303 and a derivative of the base of G939; to cause to go up, i.e.
 haul (a net):—draw.
g307.r: From ἀνά (G303) and a derivative of the base of βάσις (G939)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3070.d:
Λυδία Lydía, loo-dee'-ah; properly, feminine of Ludios (of foreign origin) (a Lydian, in Asia
 Minor); Lydia, a Christian woman:—Lydia.
g3070.r: Properly, feminine of Ludios [of foreign origin] (a Lydian, in Asia Minor)|

g3071.d:
Λυκαονία Lykaonía, loo-kah-on-ee'-ah; perhaps remotely from G3074; Lycaonia, a region of Asia
 Minor:—Lycaonia.

g3072.d:
Λυκαονιστί Lykaonistí, loo-kah-on-is-tee'; adverb from a derivative of G3071; Lycaonistically, i.e. in the
 language of the Lycaonians:—in the speech of Lycaonia.
g3072.r: From a derivative of Λυκαονία (G3071)|English: Lycaonia

g3073.d: Λυκία Lykía, loo-kee'-ah; probably remotely from G3074; Lycia, a province of Asia Minor:—Lycia.

g3074.d:
λύκος lýkos, loo'-kos; perhaps akin to the base of G3022 (from the whitish hair); a
 wolf:—wolf.
g3074.r: Perhaps akin to the base of λευκός (G3022) (from the whitish hair)|English: white

g3075.r: Middle voice from a probably derivative of λύω (G3089) (meaning filth)|English: loose, break, unloose, destroy, dissolve, put off, melt, break up, break down

g3076.d:
λυπέω lypéō, loo-peh'-o; from G3077; to distress; reflexively or passively, to be sad:—cause
 grief, grieve, be in heaviness, (be) sorrow(-ful), be (make) sorry.
g3076.r: From λύπη (G3077)|English: sorrow, heaviness, grievous, grudging, grief

g3077.d:
λύπη lýpē, loo'-pay; apparently a primary word; sadness:—grief, grievous, + grudgingly,
 heaviness, sorrow.

g3078.d:
Λυσανίας Lysanías, loo-san-ee'-as; from G3080 and ἀνία anía (trouble); grief-dispelling; Lysanias, a governor
 of Abilene:—Lysanias.
g3078.r: From λύσις (G3080) and ania (trouble)|English: to be loosed

g3079.d: Λυσίας Lysías, loo-see'-as; of uncertain affinity; Lysias, a Roman:—Lysias.

g308.d:
ἀναβλέπω anablépō, an-ab-lep'-o; from G303 and G991; to look up; by implication, to recover sight:—look
 (up), see, receive sight.
g308.r: From ἀνά (G303) and βλέπω (G991)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3080.d: λύσις lýsis, loo'-sis; from G3089; a loosening, i.e. (specially), divorce:—to be loosed.
g3080.r: From λύω (G3089)|English: loose, break, unloose, destroy, dissolve, put off, melt, break up, break down

g3081.d:
†λυσιτελεῖ lysiteleî, loo-sit-el-i'; third person singular present indicative active of a derivative of a
 compound of G3080 and G5056; impersonally, it answers the purpose, i.e.
 is advantageous:—it is better.
g3081.r: Third person singular present indicative active of a derivative of a compound of λύσις (G3080) and τέλος (G5056)|English: to be loosed

g3082.d: Λύστρα Lýstra, loos'-trah; of uncertain origin; Lystra, a place in Asia Minor:—Lystra.

g3083.d:
λύτρον lýtron, loo'-tron; from G3089; something to loosen with, i.e. a redemption price
 (figuratively, atonement):—ransom.
g3083.r: From λύω (G3089)|English: loose, break, unloose, destroy, dissolve, put off, melt, break up, break down

g3084.d: λυτρόω lytróō, loo-tro'-o; from G3083; to ransom (literally or figuratively):—redeem.

g3085.d: λύτρωσις lýtrōsis, loo'-tro-sis; from G3084; a ransoming (figuratively):—+ redeemed, redemption.

g3086.d: λυτρωτής lytrōtḗs, loo-tro-tace'; from G3084; a redeemer (figuratively):—deliverer.

g3087.d: λυχνία lychnía, lookh-nee'-ah; from G3088; a lamp-stand (literally or figuratively):—candlestick.

g3088.d:
λύχνος lýchnos, lookh'-nos; from the base of G3022; a portable lamp or other illuminator (literally
 or figuratively):—candle, light.
g3088.r: From the base of λευκός (G3022)|English: white

g3089.d:
λύω lýō, loo'-o; a primary verb; to "loosen" (literally or figuratively):—break (up),
 destroy, dissolve, (un-)loose, melt, put off. Compare G4486.

g309.d: ἀνάβλεψις anáblepsis, an-ab'-lep-sis; from G308; restoration of sight:—recovery of sight.
g309.r: From ἀναβλέπω (G308)|English: receive sight, look up, look, see

g3090.d: Λωΐς Lōḯs, lo-ece'; of uncertain origin; Lois, a Christian woman:—Lois.

g3091.d: Λώτ Lṓt, lote; of Hebrew origin (H3876); Lot, a patriarch:—Lot.

g3092.d: Μαάθ Maáth, mah-ath'; probably of Hebrew origin; Maath, an Israelite:—Maath.

g3093.d:
†Μαγδαλά Magdalá, mag-dal-ah'; of Chaldee origin (compare H4026); the tower; Magdala (i.e. Migdala), a
 place in Palestine:—Magdala.
g3093.r: Of Aramaic origin cf מִגְדָּל (H4026)|English: tower, castles, flowers, pulpit

g3094.d:
Μαγδαληνή Magdalēnḗ, mag-dal-ay-nay'; feminine of a derivative of G3093; a female Magdalene, i.e. inhabitant
 of Magdala:—Magdalene.
g3094.r: From a derivative of Μαγαδάν (G3093)|English: Magdala

g3096.d: μαγεύω mageúō, mag-yoo'-o; from G3097; to practice magic:—use sorcery.

g3097.d:
μάγος mágos, mag'-os; of foreign origin (H7248); a Magian, i.e. Oriental scientist; by
 implication, a magician:—sorcerer, wise man.
g3097.r: Of foreign origin רב  מג (H7248)|English: Rabmag

g3098.d:
Μαγώγ Magṓg, mag-ogue'; of Hebrew origin (H4031); Magog, a foreign nation, i.e. (figuratively)
 an Antichristian party:—Magog.

g3099.d:
†Μαδιάν Madián, mad-ee-on'; of Hebrew origin (H4080); Madian (i.e. Midian), a region of
 Arabia:—Madian.
g3099.r: Of Hebrew origin מִדְיָן (H4080)|English: Midian, Midianite

g31.d: ἀγγελία angelía, ang-el-ee'-ah; from G32; an announcement, i.e. (by implication) precept:—message.

g310.d: ἀναβοάω anaboáō, an-ab-o-ah'-o; from G303 and G994; to halloo:—cry (aloud, out).
g310.r: From ἀνά (G303) and βοάω (G994)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3100.d:
μαθητεύω mathēteúō, math-ayt-yoo'-o; from G3101; intransitively, to become a pupil; transitively, to
 disciple, i.e. enrol as scholar:—be disciple, instruct, teach.

g3101.d: μαθητής mathētḗs, math-ay-tes'; from G3129; a learner, i.e. pupil:—disciple.

g3102.d: μαθήτρια mathḗtria, math-ay'-tree-ah; feminine from G3101; a female pupil:—disciple.

g3103.d:
†Μαθουσάλα Mathousála, math-oo-sal'-ah; of Hebrew origin (H4968); Mathusala (i.e. Methushelach), an
 antediluvian:—Mathusala.

g3105.d:
μαίνομαι maínomai, mah'-ee-nom-ahee; middle voice from a primary μάω máō (to long for; through the idea of
 insensate craving); to rave as a "maniac":—be beside self (mad).
g3105.r: Middle voice from a primary mao (to long for, through the idea of insensate craving)|

g3106.d:
μακαρίζω makarízō, mak-ar-id'-zo; from G3107; to beatify, i.e. pronounce (or esteem) fortunate:—call
 blessed, count happy.

g3107.d:
μακάριος makários, mak-ar'-ee-os; a prolonged form of the poetical μάκαρ mákar (meaning the same); supremely
 blest; by extension, fortunate, well off:—blessed, happy(X -ier).
g3107.r: A prolonged form of the poetical makar (meaning the same)|

g3108.d:
μακαρισμός makarismós, mak-ar-is-mos'; from G3106; beatification, i.e. attribution of good
 fortune:—blessedness.
g3108.r: From μακαρίζω (G3106)|English: call blessed, count happy

g3109.d: Μακεδονία Makedonía, mak-ed-on-ee'-ah; from G3110; Macedonia, a region of Greece:—Macedonia.

g311.d: ἀναβολή anabolḗ, an-ab-ol-ay'; from G306; a putting off:—delay.

g3110.d:
Μακεδών Makedṓn, mak-ed'-ohn; of uncertain derivation; a Macedon (Macedonian), i.e. inhabitant of
 Macedonia:—of Macedonia, Macedonian.

g3111.d:
μάκελλον mákellon, mak'-el-lon; of Latin origin (macellum); a butcher's stall, meat market or
 provision-shop:—shambles.

g3112.d:
μακράν makrán, mak-ran'; feminine accusative case singular of G3117 (G3598 being implied); at a
 distance (literally or figuratively):—(a-)far (off), good (great) way
 off.
g3112.r: Feminine accusative case singular of μακρός (G3117) (3598 being implied)|English: long, far

g3113.d: μακρόθεν makróthen, mak-roth'-en; adverb from G3117; from a distance or afar:—afar off, from far.

g3114.d:
μακροθυμέω makrothyméō, mak-roth-oo-meh'-o; from the same as G3116; to be long-spirited, i.e. (objectively)
 forbearing or (subjectively) patient:—bear (suffer) long, be
 longsuffering, have (long) patience, be patient, patiently endure.
g3114.r: From the same as μακροθύμως (G3116)|English: patiently

g3115.d:
μακροθυμία makrothymía, mak-roth-oo-mee'-ah; from the same as G3116; longanimity, i.e. (objectively) forbearance or
 (subjectively) fortitude:—longsuffering, patience.
g3115.r: From the same as μακροθύμως (G3116)|English: patiently

g3116.d:
†μακροθυμώς makrothymṓs, mak-roth-oo-moce'; adverb of a compound of G3117 and G2372; with long (enduring) temper,
 i.e. leniently:—patiently.
g3116.r: From a compound of μακρός (G3117) and θυμός (G2372)|English: long, far

g3117.d:
μακρός makrós, mak-ros'; from G3372; long (in place (distant) or time (neuter plural)):—far,
 long.

g3118.d: μακροχρόνιος makrochrónios, mak-rokh-ron'-ee-os; from G3117 and G5550; long-timed, i.e. long-lived:—live long.
g3118.r: From μακρός (G3117) and χρόνος (G5550)|English: long, far

g3119.d: μαλακία malakía, mal-ak-ee'-ah; from G3120; softness, i.e. enervation (debility):—disease.

g312.d:
ἀναγγέλλω anangéllō, an-ang-el'-lo; from G303 and the base of G32; to announce (in detail):—declare,
 rehearse, report, show, speak, tell.
g312.r: From ἀνά (G303) and the base of ἄγγελος (G32)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3120.d:
μαλακός malakós, mal-ak-os'; of uncertain affinity; soft, i.e. fine (clothing); figuratively, a
 catamite:—effeminate, soft.

g3121.d:
Μαλελεήλ Maleleḗl, mal-el-eh-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H4111); Maleleel (i.e. Mahalalel), an
 antediluvian:—Maleleel.

g3122.d:
μάλιστα málista, mal'-is-tah; neuter plural of the superlative of an apparently primary adverb μάλα mála
 (very); (adverbially) most (in the greatest degree) or
 particularly:—chiefly, most of all, (e-)specially.
g3122.r: Neuter plural of the superlative of an apparently primary adverb mala (very)|

g3123.d:
μᾶλλον mâllon, mal'-lon; neuter of the comparative of the same as G3122; (adverbially) more (in
 a greater degree)) or rather:—+ better, × far, (the) more (and more),
 (so) much (the more), rather.
g3123.r: Neuter of the comparative of the same as μάλιστα (G3122)|English: specially, especially, chiefly, most of all

g3124.d: Μάλχος Málchos, mal'-khos; of Hebrew origin (H4429); Malchus, an Israelite:—Malchus.
g3124.r: Of Hebrew origin מֶלֶךְ (H4429)|English: Melech, Hammelech

g3125.d: μάμμη mámmē, mam'-may; of natural origin ("mammy"); a grandmother:—grandmother.

g3126.d:
μαμμωνᾶς mammōnâs, mam-mo-nas'; of Chaldee origin (confidence, i.e. wealth, personified); mammonas,
 i.e. avarice (deified):—mammon.
g3126.r: Of Aramaic origin (confidence, i.e. wealth, personified)|

g3127.d: Μαναήν Manaḗn, man-ah-ane'; of uncertain origin; Manaën, a Christian:—Manaen.

g3128.d:
†Μανασσῆς Manassēs, man-as-sace'; of Hebrew origin (H4519); Mannasses (i.e. Menashsheh), an
 Israelite:—Manasses.

g3129.d:
μανθάνω manthánō, man-than'-o; prolongation from a primary verb, another form of which,
 μαθέω mathéō, is used as an alternate in certain tenses; to learn
 (in any way):—learn, understand.
g3129.r: Prolongation from a primary verb, another form of which, matheo, is used as an alternate in certain tenses|

g313.d:
ἀναγεννάω anagennáō, an-ag-en-nah'-o; from G303 and G1080; to beget or (by extension) bear (again):—beget,
 (bear) × (again).
g313.r: From ἀνά (G303) and γεννάω (G1080)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3130.d: μανία manía, man-ee'-ah; from G3105; craziness:—(+ make) × mad.
g3130.r: From μαίνομαι (G3105)|English: be mad, be beside (one's) self

g3131.d: μάννα mánna, man'-nah; of Hebrew origin (H4478); manna (i.e. man), an edible gum:—manna.

g3132.d:
μαντεύομαι manteúomai, mant-yoo'-om-ahee; from a derivative of G3105 (meaning a prophet, as supposed to rave
 through inspiration); to divine, i.e. utter spells (under pretense of
 foretelling:—by soothsaying.
g3132.r: From a derivative of μαίνομαι (G3105) (meaning a prophet, as supposed to rave through inspiration)|English: be mad, be beside (one's) self

g3133.d:
μαραίνω maraínō, mar-ah'-ee-no; of uncertain affinity; to extinguish (as fire), i.e. (figuratively and
 passively) to pass away:—fade away.

g3134.d:
†μαρὰν ἀθά maràn athá, mar'-an ath'-ah; of Chaldee origin (meaning our Lord has come); maranatha, i.e. an
 exclamation of the approaching divine judgment:—Maran-atha.
g3134.r: Of Aramaic origin (meaning our Lord has come)|

g3135.d: μαργαρίτης margarítēs, mar-gar-ee'-tace; from μάργαρος márgaros (a pearl-oyster); a pearl:—pearl.

g3136.d:
Μάρθα Mártha, mar'-thah; probably of Chaldee origin (meaning mistress); Martha, a Christian
 woman:—Martha.

g3137.d:
†Μαρία María, mar-ee'-ah; of Hebrew origin (H4813); Maria or Mariam (i.e. Mirjam), the name of
 six Christian females:—Mary.

g3138.d: Μάρκος Márkos, mar'-kos; of Latin origin; Marcus, a Christian:—Marcus, Mark.

g3139.d: μάρμαρος mármaros, mar'-mar-os; from μαρμαίρω marmaírō (to glisten); marble (as sparkling white):—marble.

g314.d: ἀναγινώσκω anaginṓskō, an-ag-in-oce'-ko; from G303 and G1097; to know again, i.e. (by extension) to read:—read.
g314.r: From ἀνά (G303) and γινώσκω (G1097)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3140.d:
μαρτυρέω martyréō, mar-too-reh'-o; from G3144; to be a witness, i.e. testify (literally or
 figuratively):—charge, give (evidence), bear record, have (obtain,
 of) good (honest) report, be well reported of, testify, give (have)
 testimony, (be, bear, give, obtain) witness.

g3141.d:
μαρτυρία martyría, mar-too-ree'-ah; from G3144; evidence given (judicially or genitive case):—record,
 report, testimony, witness.

g3142.d:
μαρτύριον martýrion, mar-too'-ree-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G3144; something evidential, i.e.
 (genitive case) evidence given or (specially), the Decalogue (in the
 sacred Tabernacle):—to be testified, testimony, witness.
g3142.r: From a presumed derivative of μάρτυς (G3144)|English: witness, martyr, record

g3143.d:
μαρτύρομαι martýromai, mar-too'-rom-ahee; middle voice from G3144; to be adduced as a witness, i.e.
 (figuratively) to obtest (in affirmation or exhortation):—take to
 record, testify.
g3143.r: Middle voice from μάρτυς (G3144)|English: witness, martyr, record

g3144.d:
μάρτυς mártys, mar'-toos; of uncertain affinity; a witness (literally (judicially) or
 figuratively (genitive case)); by analogy, a "martyr":—martyr,
 record, witness.

g3145.d: μασσάομαι massáomai, mas-sah'-om-ahee; from a primary μάσσω mássō (to handle or squeeze); to chew:—gnaw.
g3145.r: From a primary masso (to handle or squeeze)|

g3146.d: μαστιγόω mastigóō, mas-tig-o'-o; from G3148; to flog (literally or figuratively):—scourge.

g3147.d: μαστίζω mastízō, mas-tid'-zo; from G3149; to whip (literally):—scourge.

g3148.d:
μάστιξ mástix, mas'-tix; probably from the base of G3145 (through the idea of contact); a whip
 (literally, the Roman flagellum for criminals; figuratively, a
 disease):—plague, scourging.
g3148.r: Probably from the base of μασάομαι (G3145) (through the idea of contact)|English: gnaw

g3149.d:
μαστός mastós, mas-tos'; from the base of G3145; a (properly, female) breast (as if kneaded
 up):—pap.
g3149.r: From the base of μασάομαι (G3145)|English: gnaw

g315.d: ἀναγκάζω anankázō, an-ang-kad'-zo; from G318; to necessitate:—compel, constrain.
g315.r: From ἀνάγκη (G318)|English: necessity, must needs, distress, must of necessity, need, necessary, needful

g3150.d: ματαιολογία mataiología, mat-ah-yol-og-ee'-ah; from G3151; random talk, i.e. babble:—vain jangling.

g3151.d:
ματαιολόγος mataiológos, mat-ah-yol-og'-os; from G3152 and G3004; an idle (i.e. senseless or mischievous) talker,
 i.e. a wrangler:—vain talker.
g3151.r: From μάταιος (G3152) and λέγω (G3004)|English: vain, vanities

g3152.d:
μάταιος mátaios, mat'-ah-yos; from the base of G3155; empty, i.e. (literally) profitless, or
 (specially), an idol:—vain, vanity.
g3152.r: From the base of μάτην (G3155)|English: in vain

g3153.d:
ματαιότης mataiótēs, mat-ah-yot'-ace; from G3152; inutility; figuratively, transientness; morally,
 depravity:—vanity.

g3154.d:
ματαιόω mataióō, mat-ah-yo'-o; from G3152; to render (passively, become) foolish, i.e. (morally)
 wicked or (specially), idolatrous:—become vain.

g3155.d:
μάτην mátēn, mat'-ane; accusative case of a derivative of the base of G3145 (through the idea
 of tentative manipulation, i.e. unsuccessful search, or else of
 punishment); folly, i.e. (adverbially) to no purpose:—in vain.
g3155.r: Accus. of a derivative of the base of μασάομαι (G3145) (through the idea of tentative manipulation, i.e. unsuccessful search, or else of punishment)|English: gnaw

g3157.d:
†Ματθάν Matthán, mat-than'; of Hebrew origin (H4977); Matthan (i.e. Mattan), an
 Israelite:—Matthan.

g316.d:
ἀναγκαῖος anankaîos, an-ang-kah'-yos; from G318; necessary; by implication, close (of kin):—near, necessary,
 necessity, needful.
g316.r: From ἀνάγκη (G318)|English: necessity, must needs, distress, must of necessity, need, necessary, needful

g3160.d:
Ματταθά Mattathá, mat-tath-ah'; probably a shortened form of G3161 (compare H4992); Mattatha (i.e.
 Mattithjah), an Israelite:—Mattatha.
g3160.r: Probably a shortened form of Ματταθίας (G3161) cf מַתַּתָּה (H4992)|English: Mattathias

g3161.d:
Ματταθίας Mattathías, mat-tath-ee'-as; of Hebrew origin (H4993); Mattathias (i.e. Mattithjah), an Israelite
 and a Christian:—Mattathias.

g3162.d:
μάχαιρα máchaira, makh'-ahee-rah; probably feminine of a presumed derivative of G3163; a knife, i.e.
 dirk; figuratively, war, judicial punishment:—sword.
g3162.r: From a presumed derivative of μάχη (G3163)|English: fighting, strife, striving

g3163.d:
μάχη máchē, makh'-ay; from G3164; a battle, i.e. (figuratively) controversy:—fighting,
 strive, striving.

g3164.d:
μάχομαι máchomai, makh'-om-ahee; middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to war, i.e.
 (figuratively) to quarrel, dispute:—fight, strive.
g3164.r: Middle voice of an apparently root word|

g3165.d: μέ mé, meh; a shorter (and probably original) form of G1691; me:—I, me, my.
g3165.r: A shorter (and probably originally) from of ἐμέ (G1691)|English: me, I, my, myself

g3167.d:
μεγαλεῖος megaleîos, meg-al-i'-os; from G3173; magnificent, i.e. (neuter, plural as noun) a conspicuous
 favor, or (subjectively) perfection:—great things, wonderful works.

g3168.d:
μεγαλειότης megaleiótēs, meg-al-i-ot'-ace; from G3167; superbness, i.e. glory or splendor:—magnificence, majesty,
 mighty power.
g3168.r: From μεγαλεῖος (G3167)|English: great thing, wonderful work

g3169.d:
μεγαλοπρεπής megaloprepḗs, meg-al-op-rep-ace'; from G3173 and G4241; befitting greatness or magnificence
 (majestic):—excellent.
g3169.r: From μέγας (G3173) and πρέπω (G4241)|English: great, loud, misc

g317.d: ἀναγκαστῶς anankastōs, an-ang-kas-toce'; adverb from a derivative of G315; compulsorily:—by constraint.
g317.r: From a derivative of ἀναγκάζω (G315)|English: compel, constrain

g3170.d:
μεγαλύνω megalýnō, meg-al-oo'-no; from G3173; to make (or declare) great, i.e. increase or (figuratively)
 extol:—enlarge, magnify, shew great.

g3171.d: μεγάλως megálōs, meg-al'-oce; adverb from G3173; much:—greatly.

g3172.d:
μεγαλωσύνη megalōsýnē, meg-al-o-soo'-nay; from G3173; greatness, i.e. (figuratively) divinity (often God
 himself):—majesty.

g3173.d:
μέγας mégas, meg'-as; (including the prolonged forms, feminine μεγάλη megálē, plural
 μεγάλοι megáloi, etc.; compare also G3176, G3187); big (literally or
 figuratively, in a very wide application):—(+ fear) exceedingly,
 great(-est), high, large, loud, mighty, + (be) sore (afraid), strong,
 × to years.
g3173.r: [including the prolonged forms, feminine megale, plural megaloi, etc., cf also μέγιστος (G3176), μείζων (G3187)]|English: exceeding great

g3174.d: μέγεθος mégethos, meg'-eth-os; from G3173; magnitude (figuratively):—greatness.

g3175.d: †μεγιστᾶνες megistânes, meg-is-tan'-es; plural from G3176; grandees:—great men, lords.

g3177.d:
μεθερμηνεύω methermēneúō, meth-er-mane-yoo'-o; from G3326 and G2059; to explain over, i.e. translate:—(by)
 interpret(-ation).
g3177.r: From μετά (G3326) and ἑρμηνεύω (G2059)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3178.d:
μέθη méthē, meth'-ay; apparently a primary word; an intoxicant, i.e. (by implication)
 intoxication:—drunkenness.

g3179.d:
μεθίστημι methístēmi, meth-is'-tay-mee; from G3326 and G2476; to transfer, i.e. carry away, depose or
 (figuratively) exchange, seduce:—put out, remove, translate, turn
 away.
g3179.r: From μετά (G3326) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g318.r: From ἀνά (G303) and the base of ἀγκάλη (G43)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3180.d:
μεθοδεία methodeía, meth-od-i'-ah; from a compound of G3326 and G3593 (compare "method"); travelling over,
 i.e. travesty (trickery):—wile, lie in wait.
g3180.r: From a compound of μετά (G3326) and ὁδεύω (G3593) [cf "method"]|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3182.d: μεθύσκω methýskō, meth-oos'-ko; a prolonged (transitive) form of G3184; to intoxicate:—be drunk(-en).
g3182.r: A prolonged (transitive) form of μεθύω (G3184)|English: be drunken, have well drunk, be made drunk

g3183.d: μέθυσος méthysos, meth'-oo-sos; from G3184; tipsy, i.e. (as noun) a sot:—drunkard.
g3183.r: From μεθύω (G3184)|English: be drunken, have well drunk, be made drunk

g3184.d:
μεθύω methýō, meth-oo'-o; from another form of G3178; to drink to intoxication, i.e. get
 drunk:—drink well, make (be) drunk(-en).
g3184.r: From another form of μέθη (G3178)|English: drunkenness

g3187.d:
μείζων meízōn, mide'-zone; irregular comparative of G3173; larger (literally or figuratively,
 specially, in age):—elder, greater(-est), more.
g3187.r: Irregular comparative of μέγας (G3173)|English: great, loud, misc

g3188.d: μέλαν mélan, mel'-an; neuter of G3189 as noun; ink:—ink.

g3189.d: μέλας mélas, mel'-as; apparently a primary word; black:—black.

g319.d:
†ἀναγνωρίζομαι anagnōrízomai, an-ag-no-rid'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G303 and G1107; to make (oneself) known:—be made
 known.
g319.r: Middle voice from ἀνά (G303) and γνωρίζω (G1107)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3190.d: †Μελεᾶς Meleâs, mel-eh-as'; of uncertain origin; Meleas, an Israelite:—Meleas.

g3191.d:
μελετάω meletáō, mel-et-ah'-o; from a presumed derivative of G3199; to take care of, i.e. (by
 implication) revolve in the mind:—imagine, (pre-)meditate.
g3191.r: From a presumed derivative of μέλει (G3199)|English: care, take care

g3192.d: μέλι méli, mel'-ee; apparently a primary word; honey:—honey.

g3194.d: †Μελίτη Melítē, mel-ee'-tay; of uncertain origin; Melita, an island in the Mediterranean:—Melita.

g3195.d:
μέλλω méllō, mel'-lo; a strengthened form of G3199 (through the idea of expectation); to
 intend, i.e. be about to be, do, or suffer something (of persons or
 things, especially events; in the sense of purpose, duty, necessity,
 probability, possibility, or hesitation):—about, after that, be
 (almost), (that which is, things, + which was for) to come, intend,
 was to (be), mean, mind, be at the point, (be) ready, + return, shall
 (begin), (which, that) should (after, afterwards, hereafter) tarry,
 which was for, will, would, be yet.
g3195.r: A strengthened form of μέλει (G3199) (through the idea of expectation)|English: care, take care

g3196.d: μέλος mélos, mel'-os; of uncertain affinity; a limb or part of the body:—member.

g3197.d:
Μελχί Melchí, mel-khee'; of Hebrew origin (H4428 with pronominal suffix, my king); Melchi (i.e.
 Malki), the name of two Israelites:—Melchi.
g3197.r: Of Hebrew or מֶלֶךְ (H4428) with pronominal suf., my king|English: king, royal, Hammelech, Malcham, Moloch

g3198.d:
Μελχισεδέκ Melchisedék, mel-khis-ed-ek'; of Hebrew origin (H4442); Melchisedek (i.e. Malkitsedek), a
 patriarch:—Melchisedec.

g32.d:
†ἄγγελος ággelos, ang'-el-os; from ἀγγέλλω aggéllō (probably derived from G71; compare G34) (to bring
 tidings); a messenger; especially an "angel"; by implication, a
 pastor:—angel, messenger.
g32.r: From aggello [probably derived from ἄγω (G71), cf ἀγέλη (G34)] (to bring tidings)|English: bring, lead, go, bring forth, misc, vr bring

g320.d: ἀνάγνωσις anágnōsis, an-ag'-no-sis; from G314; (the act of) reading:—reading.

g3200.d: μεμβράνα membrána, mem-bran'-ah; of Latin origin ("membrane"); a (written) sheep-skin:—parchment.

g3201.d: μέμφομαι mémphomai, mem'-fom-ahee; middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to blame:—find fault.
g3201.r: Middle voice of an apparently root word|

g3202.d:
μεμψίμοιρος mempsímoiros, mem-psim'-oy-ros; from a presumed derivative of G3201 and μοῖρα moîra (fate; akin to the base
 of G3313); blaming fate, i.e. querulous (discontented):—complainer.
g3202.r: From a presumed derivative of μέμφομαι (G3201) and moira (fate, akin to the base of μέρος (G3313))|English: find fault

g321.d:
ἀνάγω anágō, an-ag'-o; from G303 and G71; to lead up; by extension to bring out; specially, to
 sail away:—bring (again, forth, up again), depart, launch (forth),
 lead (up), loose, offer, sail, set forth, take up.
g321.r: From ἀνά (G303) and ἄγω (G71)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g322.d:
ἀναδείκνυμι anadeíknymi, an-ad-ike'-noo-mee; from G303 and G1166; to exhibit, i.e. (by implication) to indicate,
 appoint:—appoint, shew.
g322.r: From ἀνά (G303) and δεικνύω (G1166)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g323.d: ἀνάδειξις anádeixis, an-ad'-ike-sis; from G322; (the act of) exhibition:—shewing.

g324.d: ἀναδέχομαι anadéchomai, an-ad-ekh'-om-ahee; from G303 and G1209; to entertain (as a guest):—receive.
g324.r: From ἀνά (G303) and δέχομαι (G1209)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g325.d: ἀναδίδωμι anadídōmi, an-ad-eed'-om-ee; from G303 and G1325; to hand over:—deliver.
g325.r: From ἀνά (G303) and δίδωμι (G1325)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g326.d: ἀναζάω anazáō, an-ad-zah'-o; from G303 and G2198; to recover life (literally or figuratively):—(be a-)live again, revive.
g326.r: From ἀνά (G303) and ζάω (G2198)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g327.d: ἀναζητέω anazētéō, an-ad-zay-teh'-o; from G303 and G2212; to search out:—seek.
g327.r: From ἀνά (G303) and ζητέω (G2212)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g328.d: ἀναζώννυμι anazṓnnymi, an-ad-zone'-noo-mee; from G303 and G2224; to gird afresh:—gird up.
g328.r: From ἀνά (G303) and ζώννυμι (G2224)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g329.d:
ἀναζωπυρέω anazōpyréō, an-ad-zo-poor-eh'-o; from G303 and a compound of the base of G2226 and G4442; to
 re-enkindle:—stir up.
g329.r: From ἀνά (G303) and a compound of the base of ζῷον (G2226) and πῦρ (G4442)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g33.d: ἄγε áge, ag'-eh; imperative of G71; properly, lead, i.e. come on:—go to.
g33.r: Imperative of ἄγω (G71)|English: bring, lead, go, bring forth, misc, vr bring

g330.d: ἀναθάλλω anathállō, an-ath-al'-lo; from G303 and θάλλω thállō (to flourish); to revive:—flourish again.
g330.r: From ἀνά (G303) and thallo (to flourish)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3303.d:
μέν mén, men; a primary particle; properly, indicative of affirmation or concession
 (in fact); usually followed by a contrasted clause with G1161 (this
 one, the former, etc.):—even, indeed, so, some, truly, verily. Often
 compounded with other particles in an intensive or asseverative sense.

g3304.d:
†μενοῦνγε menoûnge, men-oon'-geh; from G3203 and G3767 and G1065; so then at least:—nay but, yea doubtless
 (rather, verily).
g3304.r: From  (G3203) and οὖν (G3767) and γέ (G1065)|English: no entry

g3305.d:
μέντοι méntoi, men'-toy; from G3203 and G5104; indeed though, i.e. however:—also, but, howbeit,
 nevertheless, yet.

g3306.d:
μένω ménō, men'-o; a primary verb; to stay (in a given place, state, relation or
 expectancy):—abide, continue, dwell, endure, be present, remain,
 stand, tarry (for), × thine own.

g3307.d:
μερίζω merízō, mer-id'-zo; from G3313; to part, i.e. (literally) to apportion, bestow, share, or
 (figuratively) to disunite, differ:—deal, be difference between,
 distribute, divide, give participle
g3307.r: From μέρος (G3313)|English: part, portion, coast, behalf, respect, misc

g3308.d: μέριμνα mérimna, mer'-im-nah; from G3307 (through the idea of distraction); solicitude:—care.
g3308.r: From μερίζω (G3307) (through the idea of distraction)|English: divide, distribute, deal, be difference between, give part

g3309.d: μεριμνάω merimnáō, mer-im-nah'-o; from G3308; to be anxious about:—(be, have) care(-ful), take thought.

g331.d:
ἀνάθεμα anáthema, an-ath'-em-ah; from G394; a (religious) ban or (concretely) excommunicated (thing or
 person):—accused, anathema, curse, × great.

g3310.d:
μερίς merís, mer-ece'; feminine of G3313; a portion, i.e. province, share or (abstractly)
 participation:—part (X -akers).
g3310.r: From μέρος (G3313)|English: part, portion, coast, behalf, respect, misc

g3311.d: μερισμός merismós, mer-is-mos'; from G3307; a separation or distribution:—dividing asunder, gift.
g3311.r: From μερίζω (G3307)|English: divide, distribute, deal, be difference between, give part

g3312.d: μεριστής meristḗs, mer-is-tace'; from G3307; an apportioner (administrator):—divider.
g3312.r: From μερίζω (G3307)|English: divide, distribute, deal, be difference between, give part

g3313.d:
μέρος méros, mer'-os; from an obsolete but more primary form of μείρομαι meíromai (to get as a
 section or allotment); a division or share (literally or figuratively,
 in a wide application):—behalf, course, coast, craft, particular (+
 -ly), part (+ -ly), piece, portion, respect, side, some sort(-what).
g3313.r: From an obsolete but more primary form of meiromai (to get as a section or allotment)|

g3314.d: μεσημβρία mesēmbría, mes-ame-bree'-ah; from G3319 and G2250; midday; by implication, the south:—noon, south.
g3314.r: From μέσος (G3319) and ἡμέρα (G2250)|English: midst, among, from among, midnight, misc

g3315.d:
μεσιτεύω mesiteúō, mes-it-yoo'-o; from G3316; to interpose (as arbiter), i.e (by implication) to ratify
 (as surety):—confirm.

g3316.d:
μεσίτης mesítēs, mes-ee'-tace; from G3319; a go-between, i.e. (simply) an internunciator, or (by
 implication) a reconciler (intercessor):—mediator.
g3316.r: From μέσος (G3319)|English: midst, among, from among, midnight, misc

g3317.d:
μεσονύκτιον mesonýktion, mes-on-ook'-tee-on; neuter of compound of G3319 and G3571; midnight (especially as a
 watch):—midnight.
g3317.r: Neuter of compound of μέσος (G3319) and νύξ (G3571)|English: midst, among, from among, midnight, misc

g3318.d:
Μεσοποταμία Mesopotamía, mes-op-ot-am-ee'-ah; from G3319 and G4215; Mesopotamia (as lying between the Euphrates and
 the Tigris; compare 0763), a region of Asia:—Mesopotamia.
g3318.r: From μέσος (G3319) and ποταμός (G4215)|English: midst, among, from among, midnight, misc

g3319.d:
μέσος mésos, mes'-os; from G3326; middle (as an adjective or (neuter) noun):—among, × before
 them, between, + forth, mid(-day, -night), midst, way.
g3319.r: From μετά (G3326)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g332.d:
ἀναθεματίζω anathematízō, an-ath-em-at-id'-zo; from G331; to declare or vow under penalty of execration:—(bind under
 a) curse, bind with an oath.
g332.r: From ἀνάθεμα (G331)|English: accursed, anathema, bind under a great curse

g3320.d: μεσότοιχον mesótoichon, mes-ot'-oy-khon; from G3319 and G5109; a partition (figuratively):—middle wall.
g3320.r: From μέσος (G3319) and τοῖχος (G5109)|English: midst, among, from among, midnight, misc

g3321.d: μεσουράνημα mesouránēma, mes-oo-ran'-ay-mah; from a presumed compound of G3319 and G3772; mid-sky:—midst of heaven.
g3321.r: From a presumed compound of μέσος (G3319) and οὐρανός (G3772)|English: midst, among, from among, midnight, misc

g3322.d:
μεσόω mesóō, mes-o'-o; from G3319; to form the middle, i.e. (in point of time), to be half-way
 over:—be about the midst.
g3322.r: From μέσος (G3319)|English: midst, among, from among, midnight, misc

g3323.d:
Μεσσίας Messías, mes-see'-as; of Hebrew origin (H4899); the Messias (i.e. Mashiach), or
 Christ:—Messias.
g3323.r: Of Hebrew origin מָשִׁיחַ (H4899), see Χριστός (G5547) Christos|English: anointed, Messiah

g3324.d: μεστός mestós, mes-tos'; of uncertain derivation; replete (literally or figuratively):—full.

g3325.d: μεστόω mestóō, mes-to'-o; from G3324; to replenish, i.e. (by implication) to intoxicate:—fill.

g3326.d:
μετά metá, met-ah'; a primary preposition (often used adverbially); properly, denoting
 accompaniment; "amid" (local or causal); modified variously according
 to the case (genitive association, or accusative succession) with
 which it is joined; occupying an intermediate position between G575 or
 G1537 and G1519 or G4314; less intimate than G1722 and less close than
 G4862):—after(-ward), × that he again, against, among, × and,
 + follow, hence, hereafter, in, of, (up-)on, + our, × and
 setting, since, (un-)to, + together, when, with (+ -out). Often used
 in composition, in substantially the same relations of participation
 or proximity, and transfer or sequence.

g3327.d:
μεταβαίνω metabaínō, met-ab-ah'-ee-no; from G3326 and the base of G939; to change place:—depart, go, pass,
 remove.
g3327.r: From μετά (G3326) and the base of βάσις (G939)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3328.d:
μεταβάλλω metabállō, met-ab-al'-lo; from G3326 and G906; to throw over, i.e. (middle voice figuratively) to
 turn about in opinion:—change mind.
g3328.r: From μετά (G3326) and βάλλω (G906)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3329.d: μετάγω metágō, met-ag'-o; from G3326 and G718; to lead over, i.e. transfer (direct):—turn about.
g3329.r: From μετά (G3326) and ἁρμόζω (G718)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g333.d:
ἀναθεωρέω anatheōréō, an-ath-eh-o-reh'-o; from G303 and G2334; to look again (i.e. attentively) at (literally or
 figuratively):—behold, consider.
g333.r: From ἀνά (G303) and θεωρέω (G2334)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3330.d: μεταδίδωμι metadídōmi, met-ad-id'-o-mee; from G3326 and G1325; to give over, i.e. share:—give, impart.
g3330.r: From μετά (G3326) and δίδωμι (G1325)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3331.d:
μετάθεσις metáthesis, met-ath'-es-is; from G3346; transposition, i.e. transferral (to heaven),
 disestablishment (of a law):—change, removing, translation.
g3331.r: From μετατίθημι (G3346)|English: translate, carry over, remove, change, turn

g3332.d: μεταίρω metaírō, met-ah'-ee-ro; from G3326 and G142; to betake oneself, i.e. remove (locally):—depart.
g3332.r: From μετά (G3326) and αἴρω (G142)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3333.d:
μετακαλέω metakaléō, met-ak-al-eh'-o; from G3326 and G2564; to call elsewhere, i.e. summon:—call (for,
 hither).
g3333.r: From μετά (G3326) and καλέω (G2564)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3334.d:
μετακινέω metakinéō, met-ak-ee-neh'-o; from G3326 and G2795; to stir to a place elsewhere, i.e. remove
 (figuratively):—move away.
g3334.r: From μετά (G3326) and κινέω (G2795)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3335.d:
μεταλαμβάνω metalambánō, met-al-am-ban'-o; from G3326 and G2983; to participate; genitive case, to accept (and
 use):—eat, have, be partaker, receive, take.
g3335.r: From μετά (G3326) and λαμβάνω (G2983)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3336.r: From μεταλαμβάνω (G3335)|English: be partaker, eat, have, take, receive

g3337.d: μεταλλάσσω metallássō, met-al-las'-so; from G3326 and G236; to exchange:—change.
g3337.r: From μετά (G3326) and ἀλλάσσω (G236)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3338.d:
†μεταμέλλομαι metaméllomai, met-am-el'-lom-ahee; from G3326 and the middle voice of G3199; to care afterwards, i.e.
 regret:—repent (self).
g3338.r: From μετά (G3326) and the middle voice of μέλει (G3199)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3339.d:
μεταμορφόω metamorphóō, met-am-or-fo'-o; from G3326 and G3445; to transform (literally or figuratively,
 "metamorphose"):—change, transfigure, transform.
g3339.r: From μετά (G3326) and μορφόω (G3445)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3340.d:
μετανοέω metanoéō, met-an-o-eh'-o; from G3326 and G3539; to think differently or afterwards, i.e.
 reconsider (morally, feel compunction):—repent.
g3340.r: From μετά (G3326) and νοέω (G3539)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3341.d:
μετάνοια metánoia, met-an'-oy-ah; from G3340; (subjectively) compunction (for guilt, including
 reformation); by implication, reversal (of (another's)
 decision):—repentance.

g3342.d:
μεταξύ metaxý, met-ax-oo'; from G3326 and a form of G4862; betwixt (of place or person); (of time)
 as adjective, intervening, or (by implication) adjoining:—between,
 mean while, next.
g3342.r: From μετά (G3326) and a form of σύν (G4862)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3343.d:
μεταπέμπω metapémpō, met-ap-emp'-o; from G3326 and G3992; to send from elsewhere, i.e. (middle voice) to
 summon or invite:—call (send) for.
g3343.r: From μετά (G3326) and πέμπω (G3992)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3344.d:
†μεταστρέφω metastréphō, met-as-tref'-o; from G3326 and G4762; to turn across, i.e. transmute or (figuratively)
 corrupt:—pervert, turn.
g3344.r: From μετά (G3326) and στρέφω (G4762)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3345.r: From μετά (G3326) and a derivative of σχῆμα (G4976)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3346.d:
μετατίθημι metatíthēmi, met-at-ith'-ay-mee; from G3326 and G5087; to transfer, i.e. (literally) transport, (by
 implication) exchange, (reflexively) change sides, or (figuratively)
 pervert:—carry over, change, remove, translate, turn.
g3346.r: From μετά (G3326) and τίθημι (G5087)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3347.d: μετέπειτα metépeita, met-ep'-i-tah; from G3326 and G1899; thereafter:—afterward.
g3347.r: From μετά (G3326) and ἔπειτα (G1899)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3348.d:
μετέχω metéchō, met-ekh'-o; from G3326 and G2192; to share or participate; by implication, belong
 to, eat (or drink):—be partaker, pertain, take part, use.
g3348.r: From μετά (G3326) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3349.d:
μετεωρίζω meteōrízō, met-eh-o-rid'-zo; from a compound of G3326 and a collateral form of G142 or perhaps rather
 G109 (compare "meteor"); to raise in mid-air, i.e. (figuratively)
 suspend (passively, fluctuate or be anxious):—be of doubtful mind.
g3349.r: From a compound of μετά (G3326) and a collateral form of αἴρω (G142) or perhaps rather ἀήρ (G109) (cf "meteor")|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g335.d:
ἀναίδεια anaídeia, an-ah'-ee-die-ah'; from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle (compare G427)) and G127; 
 impudence, i.e. (by implication) importunity:—importunity.
g335.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle [cf ἄνευ (G427)]) and αἰδώς (G127)|English: Alpha

g3350.d:
μετοικεσία metoikesía, met-oy-kes-ee'-ah; from a derivative of a compound of G3326 and G3624; a change of abode,
 i.e. (specially), expatriation:—X brought, carried(-ying) away
 (in-)to.
g3350.r: From a derivative of a compound of μετά (G3326) and οἶκος (G3624)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g3351.d:
μετοικίζω metoikízō, met-oy-kid'-zo; from the same as G3350; to transfer as a settler or captive, i.e
 colonize or exile:—carry away, remove into.
g3351.r: From the same as μετοικεσία (G3350)|English: carrying away into, carried away to, be brought to

g3352.d: μετοχή metochḗ, met-okh-ay'; from G3348; participation, i.e. intercourse:—fellowship.
g3352.r: From μετέχω (G3348)|English: be partaker, take part, use, pertain

g3353.d:
μέτοχος métochos, met'-okh-os; from G3348; participant, i.e. (as noun) a sharer; by implication, an
 associate:—fellow, partaker, partner.
g3353.r: From μετέχω (G3348)|English: be partaker, take part, use, pertain

g3354.d:
μετρέω metréō, met-reh'-o; from G3358; to measure (i.e. ascertain in size by a fixed standard); by
 implication, to admeasure (i.e. allot by rule):—figuratively, to
 estimate:—measure, mete.

g3355.d:
μετρητής metrētḗs, met-ray-tace'; from G3354; a measurer, i.e. (specially), a certain standard measure of
 capacity for liquids:—firkin.

g3356.d:
μετριοπαθέω metriopathéō, met-ree-op-ath-eh'-o; from a compound of the base of G3357 and G3806; to be moderate in
 passion, i.e. gentle (to treat indulgently):—have compassion.
g3356.r: From a compound of the base of μετρίως (G3357) and πάθος (G3806)|English: a little

g3357.d:
μετρίως metríōs, met-ree'-oce; adverb from a derivative of G3358; moderately, i.e. slightly:—a
 little.
g3357.r: From a derivative of μέτρον (G3358)|English: measure

g3358.d:
μέτρον métron, met'-ron; an apparently primary word; a measure ("metre"), literally or
 figuratively; by implication, a limited portion (degree):—measure.

g3359.d:
μέτωπον métōpon, met'-o-pon; from G3326 and ops (the face); the forehead (as opposite the
 countenance):—forehead.
g3359.r: From μετά (G3326) and ops (the face)|English: with, after, among, hereafter, afterward, against, not tr, misc

g336.d: ἀναίρεσις anaíresis, an-ah'-ee-res-is; from G337; (the act of) killing:—death.
g336.r: From ἀναιρέω (G337)|English: kill, slay, put to death, take up, do, take away

g3360.d:
μέχρι méchri, mekh'-ree; from G3372; as far as, i.e. up to a certain point (as a preposition, of
 extent (denoting the terminus, whereas G891 refers especially to the
 space of time or place intervening) or conjunction):—till, (un-)to,
 until.

g3361.d:
μή mḗ, may; a primary particle of qualified negation (whereas G3756 expresses an
 absolute denial); (adverb) not, (conjunction) lest; also (as an
 interrogative implying a negative answer (whereas G3756 expects an
 affirmative one)) whether:—any but (that), × forbear, + God forbid, +
 lack, lest, neither, never, no (X wise in), none, nor, (can-)not,
 nothing, that not, un(-taken), without. Often used in compounds in
 substantially the same relations. See also G3362, G3363, G3364, G3372,
 G3373, G3375, G3378.
g3361.r: A primary particle of qualified negation (whereas οὐ (G3756) expresses an absolute denial)|English: not, no, cannot, misc

g3364.d:
οὐ μή ou mḗ, oo may; i.e. G3756 and G3361; a double negative strengthening the denial; not at
 all:—any more, at all, by any (no) means, neither, never, no (at
 all), in no case (wise), nor ever, not (at all, in any wise). Compare
 G3378.
g3364.r: From οὐ (G3756) and μή (G3361)|English: not, no, cannot, misc

g3365.d:
μηδαμῶς mēdamōs, may-dam-oce'; adverb from a compound of G3361 and ἀμός amós (somebody); by no means:—not
 so.
g3365.r: From a compound of μή (G3361) and amos (somebody)|English: not, no, that not, God forbid, lest, neither, no man, but, none, not translated, misc

g3366.d:
μηδέ mēdé, may-deh'; from G3361 and G1161; but not, not even; in a continued negation,
 nor:—neither, nor (yet), (no) not (once, so much as).
g3366.r: From μή (G3361) and δέ (G1161)|English: not, no, that not, God forbid, lest, neither, no man, but, none, not translated, misc

g3367.d:
μηδείς mēdeís, may-dice'; from G3361 and G1520; not even one (man, woman, thing):—any (man,
 thing), no (man), none, not (at all, any man, a whit), nothing,
 + without delay.
g3367.r: From μή (G3361) and εἷς (G1520)|English: not, no, that not, God forbid, lest, neither, no man, but, none, not translated, misc

g3368.d: μηδέποτε mēdépote, may-dep'-ot-eh; from G3366 and G4218; not even ever:—never.
g3368.r: From μηδέ (G3366) and ποτέ (G4218)|English: neither, nor, not, nor yet, not once, no not, not so much as

g3369.d: μηδέπω mēdépō, may-dep'-o; from G3366 and G4452; not even yet:—not yet.
g3369.r: From μηδέ (G3366) and πώς (G4452)|English: neither, nor, not, nor yet, not once, no not, not so much as

g337.d:
ἀναιρέω anairéō, an-ahee-reh'-o; from G303 and (the active of) G138; to take up, i.e. adopt; by
 implication, to take away (violently), i.e. abolish, murder:—put to
 death, kill, slay, take away, take up.
g337.r: From ἀνά (G303) and (the active of) αἱρέω (G138)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3370.d:
Μῆδος Mēdos, may'-dos; of foreign origin (compare H4074); a Median, or inhabitant of
 Media:—Mede.
g3370.r: Of foreign origin cf מָדַי (H4074)|English: Medes, Media, Madai

g3371.d:
μηκέτι mēkéti, may-ket'-ee; from G3361 and G2089; no further:—any longer, (not) henceforth,
 hereafter, no henceforward (longer, more, soon), not any more.
g3371.r: From μή (G3361) and ἔτι (G2089)|English: not, no, that not, God forbid, lest, neither, no man, but, none, not translated, misc

g3372.d: μῆκος mēkos, may'-kos; probably akin to G3173; length (literally or figuratively) length.
g3372.r: Probably akin to μέγας (G3173)|English: great, loud, misc

g3373.d: μηκύνω mēkýnō, may-koo'-no; from G3372; to lengthen, i.e. (middle voice) to enlarge:—grow up.

g3374.d: μηλωτή mēlōtḗ, may-lo-tay'; from μῆλον mēlon (a sheep); a sheep-skin:—sheepskin.

g3375.d:
μήν mḗn, mane; a stronger form of G3303; a particle of affirmation (only with G2229);
 assuredly:—+ surely.
g3375.r: A stronger form of μέν (G3303)|English: indeed, verily, truly, not tr, misc

g3376.d: μήν mḗn, mane; a primary word; a month:—month.

g3377.d:
μηνύω mēnýō, may-noo'-o; probably from the same base as G3145 and G3415 (i.e. μάω máō, to strive); to
 disclose (through the idea of mental effort and thus calling to mind),
 i.e. report, declare, intimate:—shew, tell.
g3377.r: Probably from the same base as μασάομαι (G3145) and μνάομαι (G3415) (i.e. mao, to strive)|English: gnaw

g3379.d:
μήποτε mḗpote, may'-pot-eh; from G3361 and G4218; not ever; also if (or lest) ever (or perhaps):—if
 peradventure, lest (at any time, haply), not at all, whether or not.
g3379.r: From μή (G3361) and ποτέ (G4218)|English: not, no, that not, God forbid, lest, neither, no man, but, none, not translated, misc

g338.d:
ἀναίτιος anaítios, an-ah'-ee-tee-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G159 (in the sense of G156); 
 innocent:—blameless, guiltless.
g338.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and αἴτιος (G159) (in the sense of αἰτία (G156))|English: Alpha

g3380.d: μήπω mḗpō, may'-po; from G3361 and G4452; not yet:—not yet.
g3380.r: From μή (G3361) and πώς (G4452)|English: not, no, that not, God forbid, lest, neither, no man, but, none, not translated, misc

g3382.d: μηρός mērós, may-ros'; perhaps a primary word; a thigh:—thigh.

g3383.d:
μήτε mḗte, may'-teh; from G3361 and G5037; not too, i.e. (in continued negation) neither or
 nor; also, not even:—neither, (n-)or, so as much.
g3383.r: From μή (G3361) and τέ (G5037)|English: not, no, that not, God forbid, lest, neither, no man, but, none, not translated, misc

g3384.d:
μήτηρ mḗtēr, may'-tare; apparently a primary word; a "mother" (literally or figuratively,
 immediate or remote):—mother.

g3385.d:
μήτι mḗti, may'-tee; from G3361 and the neuter of G5100; whether at all:—not (the particle
 usually not expressed, except by the form of the question).
g3385.r: From μή (G3361) and the neuter of τις (G5100)|English: not, no, that not, God forbid, lest, neither, no man, but, none, not translated, misc

g3388.d: μήτρα mḗtra, may'-trah; from G3384; the matrix:—womb.

g3389.d:
†μητραλῴας mētralṓias, may-tral-o'-as; from G3384 and the base of G257; a mother-thresher, i.e.
 matricide:—murderer of mothers.
g3389.r: From μήτηρ (G3384) and the base of ἅλων (G257)|English: mother

g339.d:
ἀνακαθίζω anakathízō, an-ak-ath-id'-zo; from G303 and G2523; properly, to set up, i.e. (reflexively) to sit
 up:—sit up.
g339.r: From ἀνά (G303) and καθίζω (G2523)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3392.d:
μιαίνω miaínō, me-ah'-ee-no; perhaps a primary verb; to sully or taint, i.e. contaminate
 (ceremonially or morally):—defile.

g3393.d:
μίασμα míasma, mee'-as-mah; from G3392 ("miasma"); (morally) foulness (properly, the
 effect):—pollution.

g3394.d: μιασμός miasmós, mee-as-mos'; from G3392; (morally) contamination (properly, the act):—uncleanness.

g3395.d: †μίγμα mígma, mig'-mah; from G3396; a compound:—mixture.

g3396.d: μίγνυμι mígnymi, mig'-noo-mee; a primary verb; to mix:—mingle.

g3398.d:
μικρός mikrós, mik-ros'; apparently a primary word; small (in size, quantity, number or
 (figuratively) dignity):—least, less, little, small.

g3399.d: Μίλητος Mílētos, mil'-ay-tos; of uncertain origin; Miletus, a city of Asia Minor:—Miletus.

g34.d: ἀγέλη agélē, ag-el'-ay; from G71 (compare G32); a drove:—herd.
g34.r: From ἄγω (G71) [cf ἄγγελος (G32)]|English: bring, lead, go, bring forth, misc, vr bring

g340.d: ἀνακαινίζω anakainízō, an-ak-ahee-nid'-zo; from G303 and a derivative of G2537; to restore:—renew.
g340.r: From ἀνά (G303) and a derivative of καινός (G2537)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3400.d: μίλιον mílion, mil'-ee-on; of Latin origin; a thousand paces, i.e. a "mile":—mile.

g3401.d: μιμέομαι miméomai, mim-eh'-om-ahee; middle voice from μῖμος mîmos (a "mimic"); to imitate:—follow.

g3402.d: μιμητής mimētḗs, mim-ay-tace'; from G3401; an imitator:—follower.

g3403.r: A prolonged form of μνάομαι (G3415) (from which some of the tenses are borrowed)|English: remember, be mindful, be had in remembrance, in remembrance, come in remembrance

g3404.d:
μισέω miséō, mis-eh'-o; from a primary μῖσος mîsos (hatred); to detest (especially to persecute); by
 extension, to love less:—hate(-ful).

g3405.d: μισθαποδοσία misthapodosía, mis-thap-od-os-ee'-ah; from G3406; requital (good or bad):—recompence of reward.

g3406.d:
μισθαποδότης misthapodótēs, mis-thap-od-ot'-ace; from G3409 and G591; a remunerator[1]:—rewarder.

    
    
        1. Edited by BLB [A spelling error was made in the original document "renumerator"]

g3407.d: μίσθιος místhios, mis'-thee-os; from G3408; a wage-earner:—hired servant.

g3408.d:
μισθός misthós, mis-thos'; apparently a primary word; pay for service (literally or
 figuratively), good or bad:—hire, reward, wages.

g3409.d: μισθόω misthóō, mis-tho'-o; from G3408; to let out for wages, i.e. (middle voice) to hire:—hire.

g341.d: ἀνακαινόω anakainóō, an-ak-ahee-no'-o; from G303 and a derivative of G2537; to renovate:—renew.
g341.r: From ἀνά (G303) and a derivative of καινός (G2537)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3410.d: μίσθωμα místhōma, mis'-tho-mah; from G3409; a rented building:—hired house.

g3411.d: μισθωτός misthōtós, mis-tho-tos'; from G3409; a wage-worker (good or bad):—hired servant, hireling.

g3412.d:
Μιτυλήνη Mitylḗnē, mit-oo-lay'-nay; for μυτιλήνη mytilḗnē (abounding in shellfish); Mitylene (or Mytilene), a town
 on the island of Lesbos:—Mitylene.

g3413.d: Μιχαήλ Michaḗl, mikh-ah-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H4317); Michael, an archangel:—Michael.

g3414.d: μνᾶ mnâ, mnah; of Latin origin; a mna (i.e. mina), a certain weight:—pound.

g3415.d:
μνάομαι mnáomai, mnah'-om-ahee; middle voice of a derivative of G3306 or perhaps of the base of G3145
 (through the idea of fixture in the mind or of mental grasp); to bear
 in mind, i.e. recollect; by implication, to reward or punish:—be
 mindful, remember, come (have) in remembrance. Compare G3403.
g3415.r: Middle voice of a derivative of μένω (G3306) or perhaps of the base of μασάομαι (G3145) (through the idea of fixture in the mind or of mental grasp)|English: abide, remain, dwell, continue, tarry, endure, misc

g3416.d: Μνάσων Mnásōn, mnah'-sohn; of uncertain origin; Mnason, a Christian:—Mnason.

g3417.d:
μνεία mneía, mni'-ah; from G3415 or G3403; recollection; by implication, recital:—mention,
 remembrance.
g3417.r: From μνάομαι (G3415) or μιμνῄσκομαι (G3403)|English: remember, be mindful, be had in remembrance, in remembrance, come in remembrance

g3418.d:
μνῆμα mnēma, mnay'-mah; from G3415; a memorial, i.e. sepulchral monument
 (burial-place):—grave, sepulchre, tomb.
g3418.r: From μνάομαι (G3415)|English: remember, be mindful, be had in remembrance, in remembrance, come in remembrance

g3419.d:
μνημεῖον mnēmeîon, mnay-mi'-on; from G3420; a remembrance, i.e. cenotaph (place of interment):—grave,
 sepulchre, tomb.

g342.d: ἀνακαίνωσις anakaínōsis, an-ak-ah'-ee-no-sis; from G341; renovation:—renewing.

g3420.d: μνήμη mnḗmē, mnay'-may; from G3403; memory:—remembrance.

g3421.d:
μνημονεύω mnēmoneúō, mnay-mon-yoo'-o; from a derivative of G3420; to exercise memory, i.e. recollect; by
 implication, to punish; also to rehearse:—make mention; be mindful,
 remember.
g3421.r: From a derivative of μνήμη (G3420)|English: remembrance

g3422.d: μνημόσυνον mnēmósynon, mnay-mos'-oo-non; from G3421; a reminder (memorandum), i.e. record:—memorial.
g3422.r: From μνημονεύω (G3421)|English: remember, be mindful, make mention

g3423.d:
μνηστεύω mnēsteúō, mnace-tyoo'-o; from a derivative of G3415; to give a souvenir (engagement present),
 i.e. betroth:—espouse.
g3423.r: From a derivative of μνάομαι (G3415)|English: remember, be mindful, be had in remembrance, in remembrance, come in remembrance

g3424.d:
μογιλάλος mogilálos, mog-il-al'-os; from G3425 and G2980; hardly talking, i.e. dumb (tongue-tied):—having
 an impediment in his speech.

g3425.d: μόγις mógis, mog'-is; adverb from a primary μόγος mógos (toil); with difficulty:—hardly.

g3426.d:
μόδιος módios, mod'-ee-os; of Latin origin; a modius, i.e. certain measure for things dry (the
 quantity or the utensil):—bushel.

g3427.d: μοί moí, moy; the simpler form of G1698; to me:—I, me, mine, my.
g3427.r: The simpler form of ἐμοί (G1698)|English: me, I, mine, my

g3428.d:
μοιχαλίς moichalís, moy-khal-is'; a prolonged form of the feminine of G3432; an adulteress (literally or
 figuratively):—adulteress(-ous, -y).
g3428.r: A prolonged form of the feminine of μοιχός (G3432)|English: adulterer

g3429.d: †μοιχάω moicháō, moy-khah'-o; from G3432; (middle voice) to commit adultery:—commit adultery.

g343.d:
ἀνακαλύπτω anakalýptō, an-ak-al-oop'-to; from G303 (in the sense of reversal) and G2572; to unveil:—open,
 (un-)taken away.
g343.r: From ἀνά (G303) (in the sense of reversal) and καλύπτω (G2572)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3430.d: μοιχεία moicheía, moy-khi'-ah; from G3431; adultery:—adultery.
g3430.r: From μοιχεύω (G3431)|English: commit adultery, in adultery

g3431.d: μοιχεύω moicheúō, moy-khyoo'-o; from G3432; to commit adultery:—commit adultery.

g3432.d:
μοιχός moichós, moy-khos'; perhaps a primary word; a (male) paramour; figuratively,
 apostate:—adulterer.

g3433.d:
μόλις mólis, mol'-is; probably by variation for G3425; with difficulty:—hardly, scarce(-ly),
 + with much work.
g3433.r: Probably by var. for μόγις (G3425)|English: hardly

g3434.d: Μολόχ Molóch, mol-okh'; of Hebrew origin (H4432); Moloch (i.e. Molek), an idol:—Moloch.

g3435.d: μολύνω molýnō, mol-oo'-no; probably from G3189; to soil (figuratively):—defile.

g3436.d: μολυσμός molysmós, mol-oos-mos'; from G3435; a stain; i.e. (figuratively) immorality:—filthiness.

g3437.d: μομφή momphḗ, mom-fay'; from G3201; blame, i.e. (by implication), a fault:—quarrel.

g3438.d:
μονή monḗ, mon-ay'; from G3306; a staying, i.e. residence (the act or the place):—abode,
 mansion.
g3438.r: From μένω (G3306)|English: abide, remain, dwell, continue, tarry, endure, misc

g3439.d: μονογενής monogenḗs, mon-og-en-ace'; from G3441 and G1096; only-born, i.e. sole:—only (begotten, child).
g3439.r: From μόνος (G3441) and γίνομαι (G1096)|English: only, alone, by (one's) self

g344.d: ἀνακάμπτω anakámptō, an-ak-amp'-to; from G303 and G2578; to turn back:—(re-)turn.
g344.r: From ἀνά (G303) and κάμπτω (G2578)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3441.d:
μόνος mónos, mon'-os; probably from G3306; remaining, i.e. sole or single; by implication,
 mere:—alone, only, by themselves.
g3441.r: Probably from μένω (G3306)|English: abide, remain, dwell, continue, tarry, endure, misc

g3442.d: μονόφθαλμος monóphthalmos, mon-of'-thal-mos; from G3441 and G3788; one-eyed:—with one eye.
g3442.r: From μόνος (G3441) and ὀφθαλμός (G3788)|English: only, alone, by (one's) self

g3443.d: μονόω monóō, mon-o'-o; from G3441; to isolate, i.e. bereave:—be desolate.
g3443.r: From μόνος (G3441)|English: only, alone, by (one's) self

g3444.d:
μορφή morphḗ, mor-fay'; perhaps from the base of G3313 (through the idea of adjustment of
 parts); shape; figuratively, nature:—form.
g3444.r: Perhaps from the base of μέρος (G3313) (through the idea of adjustment of parts)|English: part, portion, coast, behalf, respect, misc

g3445.d: μορφόω morphóō, mor-fo'-o; from the same as G3444; to fashion (figuratively):—form.
g3445.r: From the same as μορφή (G3444)|English: form

g3446.d:
μόρφωσις mórphōsis, mor'-fo-sis; from G3445; formation, i.e. (by implication), appearance (semblance or
 (concretely) formula):—form.

g3447.d: μοσχοποιέω moschopoiéō, mos-khop-oy-eh'-o; from G3448 and G4160; to fabricate the image of a bullock:—make a calf.

g3448.d: μόσχος móschos, mos'-khos; probably strengthened for όσχος óschos (a shoot); a young bullock:—calf.

g3449.d:
†μόχθος móchthos, mokh'-thos; from the base of G3425; toil, i.e. (by implication)
 sadness:—painfulness, travail.
g3449.r: From the base of μόγις (G3425)|English: hardly

g345.d:
†ἀνακεῖμαι anakeîmai, an-ak-i'-mahee; from G303 and G2749; to recline (as a corpse or at a meal):—guest,
 lean, lie, sit (down, at meat), at the table.
g345.r: From ἀνά (G303) and κεῖμαι (G2749)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3450.d: μοῦ moû, moo; the simpler form of G1700; of me:—I, me, mine (own), my.
g3450.r: The simpler form of ἐμοῦ (G1700)|English: me, my, mine

g3451.d: μουσικός mousikós, moo-sik-os'; from Μοῦσα Moûsa (a Muse); "musical", i.e. (as noun) a minstrel:—musician.

g3452.d: μυελός myelós, moo-el-os'; perhaps a primary word; the marrow:—marrow.

g3453.d:
μυέω myéō, moo-eh'-o; from the base of G3466; to initiate, i.e. (by implication) to
 teach:—instruct.
g3453.r: From the base of μυστήριον (G3466)|English: mystery

g3454.d:
μῦθος mŷthos, moo'-thos; perhaps from the same as G3453 (through the idea of tuition); a tale,
 i.e. fiction ("myth"):—fable.
g3454.r: Perhaps from the same as μυέω (G3453) (through the idea of tuition)|English: instruct

g3455.d:
μυκάομαι mykáomai, moo-kah'-om-ahee; from a presumed derivative of μύζω mýzō ( to "moo"); to bellow
 (roar):—roar.
g3455.r: From a presumed derivative of muzo ( to "moo")|

g3456.d:
μυκτηρίζω myktērízō, mook-tay-rid'-zo; from a derivative of the base of G3455 (meaning snout, as that whence
 lowing proceeds); to make mouths at, i.e. ridicule:—mock.
g3456.r: From a derivative of the base of μυκάομαι (G3455) (meaning snout, as that whence lowing proceeds)|English: roar

g3457.d: μυλικός mylikós, moo-lee-kos'; from G3458; belonging to a mill:—mill(-stone).

g3458.d:
†μύλος mýlos, moo'-los; probably ultimately from the base of G3433 (through the idea of
 hardship); a "mill", i.e. (by implication), a grinder
 (millstone):—millstone.
g3458.r: Probably ultimately from the base of μόλις (G3433) (through the idea of hardship)|English: scarce, scarcely, hardly, have much work

g346.d:
†ἀνακεφαλαίομαι anakephalaíomai, an-ak-ef-al-ah'-ee-om-ahee; from G303 and G2775 (in its original sense); to sum up:—briefly
 comprehend, gather together in one.
g346.r: From ἀνά (G303) and κεφαλιόω (G2775) (in its original sense)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3460.d: Μύρα Mýra, moo'-rah; of uncertain derivation; Myra, a place in Asia Minor:—Myra.

g3461.d:
†μυριάς myriás, moo-ree'-as; from G3463; a ten-thousand; by extension, a "myriad" or indefinite
 number:—ten thousand.

g3462.d: μυρίζω myrízō, moo-rid'-zo; from G3464; to apply (perfumed) unguent to:—anoint.

g3463.d:
μύριοι mýrioi, moo'-ree-oi; plural of an apparently primary word (properly, meaning very many); 
 ten thousand; by extension, innumerably many:—ten thousand.
g3463.r: Plural of an apparently primary word (properly, meaning very many)|

g3464.d:
μύρον mýron, moo'-ron; probably of foreign origin (compare H4753, G4666); "myrrh", i.e. (by
 implication) perfumed oil:—ointment.
g3464.r: Probably of foreign origin [cf מֹר (H4753), מִפְרָשׂ (H4666)]|English: myrrh

g3465.d: Μυσία Mysía, moo-see'-ah; of uncertain origin; Mysia, a region of Asia Minor:—Mysia.

g3466.d:
μυστήριον mystḗrion, moos-tay'-ree-on; from a derivative of μύω mýō (to shut the mouth); a secret or "mystery"
 (through the idea of silence imposed by initiation into religious
 rites):—mystery.
g3466.r: From a derivative of muo (to shut the mouth)|

g3467.d:
μυωπάζω myōpázō, moo-ope-ad'-zo; from a compound of the base of G3466 and ὤψ ṓps (the face; from G3700); to
 shut the eyes, i.e. blink (see indistinctly):—cannot see far off.
g3467.r: From a compound of the base of μυστήριον (G3466) and ops (the face, from ὀπτάνομαι (G3700))|English: mystery

g3468.d:
μώλωψ mṓlōps, mo'-lopes; from μῶλος mōlos ("moil"; probably akin to the base of G3433) and probably
 ὤψ ṓps (the face; from G3700); a mole ("black eye") or blow-mark:—stripe.
g3468.r: From molos ("moil", probably akin to the base of μόλις (G3433)) and probably ops (the face, from ὀπτάνομαι (G3700))|English: scarce, scarcely, hardly, have much work

g3469.d: †μωμάομαι mōmáomai, mo-mah'-om-ahee; from G3470; to carp at, i.e. censure (discredit):—blame.

g347.d: ἀνακλίνω anaklínō, an-ak-lee'-no; from G303 and G2827; to lean back:—lay, (make) sit down.
g347.r: From ἀνά (G303) and κλίνω (G2827)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3470.d:
μῶμος mōmos, mo'-mos; perhaps from G3201; a flaw or blot, i.e. (figuratively) disgraceful
 person:—blemish.

g3471.d:
μωραίνω mōraínō, mo-rah'-ee-no; from G3474; to become insipid; figuratively, to make (passively, act)
 as a simpleton:—become fool, make foolish, lose savour.

g3472.d: μωρία mōría, mo-ree'-ah; from G3474; silliness, i.e. absurdity:—foolishness.

g3473.d:
μωρολογία mōrología, mo-rol-og-ee'-ah; from a compound of G3474 and G3004; silly talk, i.e.
 buffoonery:—foolish talking.
g3473.r: From a compound of μωρός (G3474) and λέγω (G3004)|English: foolish, fool, foolishness

g3474.d:
μωρός mōrós, mo-ros'; probably from the base of G3466; dull or stupid (as if shut up), i.e.
 heedless, (morally) blockhead, (apparently) absurd:—fool(-ish, X
 -ishness).
g3474.r: Probably from the base of μυστήριον (G3466)|English: mystery

g3475.d:
Μωσεύς Mōseús, moce-yoos'; of Hebrew origin; (H4872); Moseus, Moses, or Mouses (i.e. Mosheh), the
 Hebrew lawgiver:—Moses.

g3476.d:
Ναασσών Naassṓn, nah-as-sone'; of Hebrew origin (H5177); Naasson (i.e. Nachshon), an
 Israelite:—Naasson.

g3477.d:
Ναγγαί Nangaí, nang-gah'-ee; probably of Hebrew origin (compare H5052); Nangæ (i.e. perhaps
 Nogach), an Israelite:—Nagge.
g3477.r: Probably of Hebrew origin cf נֹגַהּ (H5052)|English: Nogah

g3479.d: Ναζαρηνός Nazarēnós, nad-zar-ay-nos'; from G3478; a Nazarene, i.e. inhabitant of Nazareth:—of Nazareth.

g3480.d:
Ναζωραῖος Nazōraîos, nad-zo-rah'-yos; from G3478; a Nazoræan, i.e. inhabitant of Nazareth; by extension, a
 Christian:—Nazarene, of Nazareth.

g3481.d: †Ναθάν Nathán, nath-an'; of Hebrew origin (H5416); Nathan, an Israelite:—Nathan.

g3482.d:
Ναθαναήλ Nathanaḗl, nath-an-ah-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H5417); Nathanaël (i.e. Nathanel), an Israelite and
 Christian:—Nathanael.

g3483.d:
ναί naí, nahee; a primary particle of strong affirmation; yes:—even so, surely,
 truth, verily, yea, yes.
g3483.r: A primary particle of strong affirmation|

g3484.d:
Ναΐν Naḯn, nah-in'; probably of Hebrew origin (compare H4999); Nain, a place in
 Palestine:—Nain.
g3484.r: Probably of Hebrew origin cf נָאָה (H4999)]|English: habitations, pastures, houses, places

g3485.d:
ναός naós, nah-os'; from a primary ναίω naíō (to dwell); a fane, shrine, temple:—shrine,
 temple. Compare G2411.

g3486.d: Ναούμ Naoúm, nah-oom'; of Hebrew origin (H5151); Naum (i.e. Nachum), an Israelite:—Naum.

g3487.d: νάρδος nárdos, nar'dos; of foreign origin (compare H5373); "nard":—(spike-)nard.
g3487.r: Of foreign origin cf נֵרְדְּ (H5373)|English: spikenard

g3488.d:
Νάρκισσος Nárkissos, nar'-kis-sos; a flower of the same name, from νάρκη nárkē (stupefaction, as a "narcotic"); 
 Narcissus, a Roman:—Narcissus.
g3488.r: A flower of the same name, from narke (stupefaction, as a "narcotic")|

g3489.d:
ναυαγέω nauagéō, now-ag-eh'-o; from a compound of G3491 and G71; to be shipwrecked (stranded,
 "navigate"), literally or figuratively:—make (suffer) shipwreck.
g3489.r: From a compound of ναῦς (G3491) and ἄγω (G71)|English: ship

g349.d: ἀνακράζω anakrázō, an-ak-rad'-zo; from G303 and G2896; to scream up (aloud):—cry out.
