g349.r: From ἀνά (G303) and κράζω (G2896)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3490.d: ναύκληρος naúklēros, now'-klay-ros; from G3491 and G2819 ("clerk"); a captain:—owner of a ship.

g3491.d: ναῦς naûs, nowce; from νάω náō or νέω néō (to float); a boat (of any size):—ship.

g3492.d: ναύτης naútēs, now'-tace; from G3491; a boatman, i.e. seaman:—sailor, shipman.

g3493.d: Ναχώρ Nachṓr, nakh-ore'; of Hebrew origin (H5152); Nachor, the grandfather of Abraham:—Nachor.

g3494.d:
νεανίας neanías, neh-an-ee'-as; from a derivative of G3501; a youth (up to about forty years):—young
 man.
g3494.r: From a derivative of νέος (G3501)|English: new, younger, young man, new man, young women, younger man, young

g3495.d: νεανίσκος neanískos, neh-an-is'-kos; from the same as G3494; a youth (under forty):—young man.
g3495.r: From the same as νεανίας (G3494)|English: young man

g3498.d:
νεκρός nekrós, nek-ros'; from an apparently primary νέκυς nékys (a corpse); dead (literally or
 figuratively; also as noun):—dead.
g3498.r: From an apparently primary nekus (a corpse)|

g3499.d:
νεκρόω nekróō, nek-ro'-o; from G3498; to deaden, i.e. (figuratively) to subdue:—be dead,
 mortify.

g35.d:
ἀγενεαλόγητος agenealógētos, ag-en-eh-al-og'-ay-tos; from G1 (as negative particle) and G1075; unregistered as to
 birth:—without descent.
g35.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as negative particle) and γενεαλογέω (G1075)|English: Alpha

g350.d:
ἀνακρίνω anakrínō, an-ak-ree'-no; from G303 and G2919; properly, to scrutinize, i.e. (by implication)
 investigate, interrogate, determine:—ask, question, discern, examine,
 judge, search.
g350.r: From ἀνά (G303) and κρίνω (G2919)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3500.d: νέκρωσις nékrōsis, nek'-ro-sis; from G3499; decease; figuratively, impotency:—deadness, dying.

g3503.d: νεότης neótēs, neh-ot'-ace; from G3501; newness, i.e. youthfulness:—youth.
g3503.r: From νέος (G3501)|English: new, younger, young man, new man, young women, younger man, young

g3504.d:
νεόφυτος neóphytos, neh-of'-oo-tos; from G3501 and a derivative of G5453; newly planted, i.e. (figuratively)
 a young convert ("neophyte"):—novice.
g3504.r: From νέος (G3501) and a derivative of φύω (G5453)|English: new, younger, young man, new man, young women, younger man, young

g3506.d:
νεύω neúō, nyoo'-o; apparently a primary verb; to "nod", i.e. (by analogy),
 signal:—beckon.

g3507.d: †νεφέλη nephélē, nef-el'-ay; from G3509; properly, cloudiness, i.e. (concretely) a cloud:—cloud.

g3508.d:
†Νεφθαλείμ Nephthaleím, nef-thal-ime'; of Hebrew origin (H5321); Nephthaleim (i.e. Naphthali), a tribe in
 Palestine:—Nephthalim.

g3509.d: νέφος néphos, nef'-os; apparently a primary word; a cloud:—cloud.

g351.d: ἀνάκρισις anákrisis, an-ak'-ree-sis; from G350; a (judicial) investigation:—examination.
g351.r: From ἀνακρίνω (G350)|English: examine, judge, ask question, search, discern

g3510.d:
νεφρός nephrós, nef-ros'; of uncertain affinity; a kidney (plural), i.e. (figuratively) the
 inmost mind:—reins.

g3511.d:
νεωκόρος neōkóros, neh-o-kor'-os; from a form of G3485 and κορέω koréō (to sweep); a temple-servant, i.e. (by
 implication) a votary:—worshipper.
g3511.r: From a form of ναός (G3485) and koreo (to sweep)|English: temple, a shrine

g3512.d:
νεωτερικός neōterikós, neh-o-ter'-ik-os; from the comparative of G3501; appertaining to younger persons, i.e.
 juvenile:—youthful.
g3512.r: From the comparative of νέος (G3501)|English: new, younger, young man, new man, young women, younger man, young

g3513.d:
νή nḗ, nay; probably an intensive form of G3483; a particle of attestation
 (accompanied by the object invoked or appealed to in confirmation); as
 sure as:—I protest by.
g3513.r: Probably an intensive form of ναί (G3483)|English: yea, even so, yes, truth, verily, surely

g3514.d: νήθω nḗthō, nay'-tho; from νέω néō (of like meaning); to spin:—spin.

g3515.d:
νηπιάζω nēpiázō, nay-pee-ad'-zo; from G3516; to act as a babe, i.e. (figuratively) innocently:—be a
 child.

g3516.d:
νήπιος nḗpios, nay'-pee-os; from an obsolete particle νή- nḗ- (implying negation) and G2031; not
 speaking, i.e. an infant (minor); figuratively, a simple-minded
 person, an immature Christian:—babe, child (+ -ish).
g3516.r: From an obsolete particle ne- (implying negation) and ἔπος (G2031)|English: say

g3517.d:
Νηρεύς Nēreús, nare-yoos'; apparently from a derivative of the base of G3491 (meaning wet); 
 Nereus, a Christian:—Nereus.
g3517.r: Apparently from a derivative of the base of ναῦς (G3491) (meaning wet)|English: ship

g3518.d: Νηρί Nērí, nay-ree'; of Hebrew origin (H5374); Neri (i.e. Nerijah), an Israelite:—Neri.

g3519.d: νησίον nēsíon, nay-see'-on; diminutive of G3520; an islet:—island.

g352.d:
ἀνακύπτω anakýptō, an-ak-oop'-to; from G303 (in the sense of reversal) and G2955; to unbend, i.e. rise;
 figuratively, be elated:—lift up, look up.
g352.r: From ἀνά (G303) (in the sense of reversal) and κύπτω (G2955)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3520.d: νῆσος nēsos, nay'-sos; probably from the base of G3491; an island:—island, isle.
g3520.r: Probably from the base of ναῦς (G3491)|English: ship

g3521.d:
νηστεία nēsteía, nace-ti'-ah; from G3522; abstinence (from lack of food, or voluntary and religious);
 specially, the fast of the Day of Atonement:—fast(-ing).

g3522.d: νηστεύω nēsteúō, nace-tyoo'-o; from G3523; to abstain from food (religiously):—fast.

g3523.d:
νῆστις nēstis, nace'-tis; from the inseparable negative particle νή- nḗ- (not) and G2068; not eating,
 i.e. abstinent from food (religiously):—fasting.
g3523.r: From the insep. negative particle ne- (not) and ἐσθίω (G2068)|English: eat, live, devour

g3524.d: †νηφάλεος nēpháleos, nay-fal'-eh-os; from G3525; sober, i.e. (figuratively) circumspect:—sober.

g3525.d:
νήφω nḗphō, nay'-fo; of uncertain affinity; to abstain from wine (keep sober), i.e.
 (figuratively) be discreet:—be sober, watch.

g3526.d: Νίγερ Níger, neeg'-er; of Latin origin; black; Niger, a Christian:—Niger.

g3527.d: Νικάνωρ Nikánōr, nik-an'-ore; probably from G3528; victorious; Nicanor, a Christian:—Nicanor.
g3527.r: Probably from νικάω (G3528)|English: overcome, conquer, prevail, get the victory

g3528.d:
νικάω nikáō, nik-ah'-o; from G3529; to subdue (literally or figuratively):—conquer, overcome,
 prevail, get the victory.

g3529.d:
νίκη níkē, nee'-kay; apparently a primary word; conquest (abstractly), i.e. (figuratively)
 the means of success:—victory.

g353.d: ἀναλαμβάνω analambánō, an-al-am-ban'-o; from G303 and G2983; to take up:—receive up, take (in, unto, up).
g353.r: From ἀνά (G303) and λαμβάνω (G2983)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3530.d:
Νικόδημος Nikódēmos, nik-od'-ay-mos; from G3534 and G1218; victorious among his people; Nicodemus, an
 Israelite:—Nicodemus.

g3531.d: Νικολαΐτης Nikolaḯtēs, nik-ol-ah-ee'-tace; from G3532; a Nicolaite, i.e. adherent of Nicolaus:—Nicolaitane.

g3532.d:
Νικόλαος Nikólaos, nik-ol'-ah-os; from G3534 and G2994; victorious over the people; Nicolaus, a
 heretic:—Nicolaus.

g3533.d:
Νικόπολις Nikópolis, nik-op'-ol-is; from G3534 and G4172; victorious city; Nicopolis, a place in
 Macedonia:—Nicopolis.

g3534.d:
νῖκος nîkos, nee'-kos; from G3529; a conquest (concretely), i.e. (by implication)
 triumph:—victory.

g3536.d:
†Νινευΐτης Nineuḯtēs, nin-yoo-ee'-tace; from G3535; a Ninevite, i.e. inhabitant of Nineveh:—of Nineve,
 Ninevite.

g3537.d: νιπτήρ niptḗr, nip-tare'; from G3538; a ewer:—bason.

g3538.d:
νίπτω níptō, nip'-to; to cleanse (especially the hands or the feet or the face);
 ceremonially, to perform ablution:—wash. Compare G3068.
g3538.r: To cleanse (especially the hands or the feet or the face)|

g3539.d:
†νοιέω noiéō, noy-eh'-o; from G3563; to exercise the mind (observe), i.e. (figuratively) to
 comprehend, heed:—consider, perceive, think, understand.

g354.d: †ἀνάληψις análēpsis, an-al'-ape-sis; from G353; ascension:—taking up.
g354.r: From ἀναλαμβάνω (G353)|English: take up, receive up, take, take in, take into

g3540.d:
νόημα nóēma, no'-ay-mah; from G3539; a perception, i.e. purpose, or (by implication) the
 intellect, disposition, itself:—device, mind, thought.
g3540.r: From νοέω (G3539)|English: understand, perceive, consider, think

g3541.d: νόθος nóthos, noth'-os; of uncertain affinity; a spurious or illegitimate son:—bastard.

g3542.d:
νομή nomḗ, nom-ay'; feminine from the same as G3551; pasture, i.e. (the act) feeding
 (figuratively, spreading of a gangrene), or (the food) pasturage:—X
 eat, pasture.
g3542.r: From the same as νόμος (G3551)|English: law

g3543.d:
νομίζω nomízō, nom-id'-zo; from G3551; properly, to do by law (usage), i.e. to accustom
 (passively, be usual); by extension, to deem or regard:—suppose,
 thing, be wont.

g3544.d:
νομικός nomikós, nom-ik-os'; from G3551; according (or pertaining) to law, i.e. legal
 (ceremonially); as noun, an expert in the (Mosaic) law:—about the
 law, lawyer.

g3545.d:
νομίμως nomímōs, nom-im'-oce; adverb from a derivative of G3551; legitimately (specially, agreeably
 to the rules of the lists):—lawfully.
g3545.r: Adverb from a derivative of νόμος (G3551)|English: law

g3546.d:
νόμισμα nómisma, nom'-is-mah; from G3543; what is reckoned as of value (after the Latin numisma),
 i.e. current coin:—money.
g3546.r: From νομίζω (G3543)|English: suppose, think, be wont

g3547.d:
νομοδιδάσκαλος nomodidáskalos, nom-od-id-as'-kal-os; from G3551 and G1320; an expounder of the (Jewish) law, i.e. a
 Rabbi:—doctor (teacher) of the law.

g3548.d:
νομοθεσία nomothesía, nom-oth-es-ee'-ah; from G3550; legislation (specially, the institution of the Mosaic
 code):—giving of the law.

g3549.d:
νομοθετέω nomothetéō, nom-oth-et-eh'-o; from G3550; to legislate, i.e. (passively) to have (the Mosaic)
 enactments injoined, be sanctioned (by them):—establish, receive the
 law.

g355.d:
ἀναλίσκω analískō, an-al-is'-ko; from G303 and a form of the alternate of G138; properly, to use up, i.e.
 destroy:—consume.
g355.r: From ἀνά (G303) and a form of the alternate of αἱρέω (G138)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3550.d: νομοθέτης nomothétēs, nom-oth-et'-ace; from G3551 and a derivative of G5087; a legislator:—lawgiver.
g3550.r: From νόμος (G3551) and a derivative of τίθημι (G5087)|English: law

g3551.d:
νόμος nómos, nom'-os; from a primary νέμω némō (to parcel out, especially food or grazing to
 animals); law (through the idea of prescriptive usage), genitive case
 (regulation), specially, (of Moses (including the volume); also of the
 Gospel), or figuratively (a principle):—law.
g3551.r: From a primary nemo (to parcel out, especially food or grazing to animals)|

g3552.d:
νοσέω noséō, nos-eh'-o; from G3554; to be sick, i.e. (by implication, of a diseased appetite)
 to hanker after (figuratively, to harp upon):—dote.

g3554.d:
νόσος nósos, nos'-os; of uncertain affinity; a malady (rarely figuratively, of moral
 disability):—disease, infirmity, sickness.

g3555.d: νοσσιά nossiá, nos-see-ah'; from G3502; a brood (of chickens):—brood.

g3556.d: νοσσίον nossíon, nos-see'-on; diminutive of G3502; a birdling:—chicken.

g3557.d:
†νοσφίζομαι nosphízomai, nos-fid'-zom-ahee; middle voice from νοσφί nosphí (apart or clandestinely); to sequestrate for
 oneself, i.e. embezzle:—keep back, purloin.
g3557.r: Middle voice from nosphi (apart or clandestinely)|

g3558.d:
νότος nótos, not'-os; of uncertain affinity; the south(-west) wind; by extension, the
 southern quarter itself:—south (wind).

g3559.d:
νουθεσία nouthesía, noo-thes-ee'-ah; from G3563 and a derivative of G5087; calling attention to, i.e. (by
 implication) mild rebuke or warning:—admonition.
g3559.r: From νοῦς (G3563) and a derivative of τίθημι (G5087)|English: mind, understanding

g356.d: ἀναλογία analogía, an-al-og-ee'-ah; from a compound of G303 and G3056; proportion:—proportion.
g356.r: From a compound of ἀνά (G303) and λόγος (G3056)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3560.d:
νουθετέω nouthetéō, noo-thet-eh'-o; from the same as G3559; to put in mind, i.e. (by implication) to
 caution or reprove gently:—admonish, warn.
g3560.r: From the same as νουθεσία (G3559)|English: admonition

g3561.d:
†νουμηνία noumēnía, noo-may-nee'-ah; feminine of a compound of G3501 and G3376 (as noun by implication, of
 G2250); the festival of new moon:—new moon.
g3561.r: From of a compound of νέος (G3501) and μήν (G3376) (as noun by implication of ἡμέρα (G2250))|English: new, younger, young man, new man, young women, younger man, young

g3562.d:
νουνεχῶς nounechōs, noon-ekh-oce'; adverb from a comparative of the accusative case of G3563 and G2192; in
 a mind-having way, i.e. prudently:—discreetly.
g3562.r: From a comparative of the accusative case of νοῦς (G3563) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: mind, understanding

g3563.d:
νοῦς noûs, nooce; probably from the base of G1097; the intellect, i.e. mind (divine or
 human; in thought, feeling, or will); by implication, meaning:—mind,
 understanding. Compare G5590.
g3563.r: Probably from the base of γινώσκω (G1097)|English: know, perceive, understand, misc

g3564.d:
Νυμφᾶς Nymphâs, noom-fas'; probably contracted for a compound of G3565 and G1435; nymph-given (i.e.
 -born); Nymphas, a Christian:—Nymphas.
g3564.r: Probably contracted for a compound of νύμφη (G3565) and δῶρον (G1435)|English: bride, daughter in law

g3565.d:
νύμφη nýmphē, noom-fay'; from a primary but obsolete verb νύπτω nýptō (to veil as a bride; compare
 Latin "nupto," to marry); a young married woman (as veiled), including
 a betrothed girl; by implication, a son's wife:—bride, daughter in
 law.
g3565.r: From a primary but obsolete verb nupto (to veil as a bride, cf Latin "nupto," to marry)|

g3566.d: νυμφίος nymphíos, noom-fee'-os; from G3565; a bride-groom (literally or figuratively):—bridegroom.
g3566.r: From νύμφη (G3565)|English: bride, daughter in law

g3567.d: νυμφών nymphṓn, noom-fohn'; from G3565; the bridal room:—bridechamber.
g3567.r: From νύμφη (G3565)|English: bride, daughter in law

g3568.d:
†νῦν nŷn, noon; a primary particle of present time; "now" (as adverb of date, a
 transition or emphasis); also as noun or adjective present or
 immediate:—henceforth, + hereafter, of late, soon, present, this
 (time). See also G3569, G3570.
g3568.r: A primary particle of present time|

g357.d:
ἀναλογίζομαι analogízomai, an-al-og-id'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G356; to estimate, i.e. (figuratively)
 contemplate:—consider.

g3570.d: νυνί nyní, noo-nee'; a prolonged form of G3568 for emphasis; just now:—now.
g3570.r: A prolonged form of νῦν (G3568) for emphasis|English: now, present, henceforth, this, this time, misc

g3571.d: νύξ nýx, noox; a primary word; "night" (literally or figuratively):—(mid-)night.

g3572.d: νύσσω nýssō, noos'-so; apparently a primary word; to prick ("nudge"):—pierce.

g3573.d:
νυστάζω nystázō, noos-tad'-zo; from a presumed derivative of G3506; to nod, i.e. (by implication) to
 fall asleep; figuratively, to delay:—slumber.
g3573.r: From a presumed derivative of νεύω (G3506)|English: beckon

g3574.d:
νυχθήμερον nychthḗmeron, nookh-thay'-mer-on; from G3571 and G2250; a day-and-night, i.e. full day of twenty-four
 hours:—night and day.
g3574.r: From νύξ (G3571) and ἡμέρα (G2250)|English: night, midnight

g3575.d: Νῶε Nōe, no'-eh; of Hebrew origin (H5146); Noë, (i.e. Noäch), a patriarch:—Noe.

g3576.d:
νωθρός nōthrós, no-thros'; from a derivative of G3541; sluggish, i.e. (literally) lazy, or
 (figuratively) stupid:—dull, slothful.
g3576.r: From a derivative of νόθος (G3541)|English: bastard

g3577.d: νῶτος nōtos, no'-tos; of uncertain affinity; the back:—back.

g3578.d:
ξενία xenía, xen-ee'-ah; from G3581; hospitality, i.e. (by implication) a place of
 entertainment:—lodging.

g3579.d:
ξενίζω xenízō, xen-id'-zo; from G3581; to be a host (passively, a guest); by implication, be
 (make, appear) strange:—entertain, lodge, (think it) strange.

g358.d:
ἄναλος ánalos, an'-al-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G251; saltless, i.e. insipid:—X
 lose saltness.
g358.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and ἅλς (G251)|English: Alpha

g3580.d: ξενοδοχέω xenodochéō, xen-od-okh-eh'-o; from a compound of G3581 and G1209; to be hospitable:—lodge strangers.
g3580.r: From a compound of ξένος (G3581) and δέχομαι (G1209)|English: stranger, strange, host

g3581.d:
ξένος xénos, xen'-os; apparently a primary word; foreign (literally, alien, or figuratively,
 novel); by implication, a guest or (vice-versa) entertainer:—host,
 strange(-r).

g3582.d:
ξέστης xéstēs, xes'-tace; as if from ξέω xéō (properly, to smooth; by implication, (of friction) to
 boil or heat); a vessel (as fashioned or for cooking) (or perhaps by
 corruption from the Latin sextarius, the sixth of a modius, i.e. about
 a pint), i.e. (specially), a measure for liquids or solids, (by
 analogy, a pitcher):—pot.
g3582.r: As if from xeo (properly, to smooth, by implication [of friction] to boil or heat)|

g3583.d:
ξηραίνω xēraínō, xay-rah'-ee-no; from G3584; to desiccate; by implication, to shrivel, to mature:—dry
 up, pine away, be ripe, wither (away).
g3583.r: From ξηρός (G3584)|English: withered, dry, dry land, land

g3584.d:
ξηρός xērós, xay-ros'; from the base of G3582 (through the idea of scorching); arid; by
 implication, shrunken, earth (as opposed to water):—dry land,
 withered.
g3584.r: From the base of ξέστης (G3582) (through the idea of scorching)|English: pot

g3585.d: ξύλινος xýlinos, xoo'-lin-os; from G3586; wooden:—of wood.
g3585.r: From ξύλον (G3586)|English: tree, staff, wood, stocks

g3586.r: From another form of the base of ξέστης (G3582)|English: pot

g3587.d:
ξυράω xyráō, xoo-rah'-o; from a derivative of the same as G3586 (meaning a razor); to shave or
 "shear" the hair:—shave.
g3587.r: From a derivative of the same as ξύλον (G3586) (meaning a razor)|English: tree, staff, wood, stocks

g3588.d:
ὁ ho, ho; the definite article; the (sometimes to be
 supplied, at others omitted, in English idiom):—the, this, that, one,
 he, she, it, etc.
g3588.r: In all their inflections, the definite article|

g3589.d: †ὀγδοήκοντα ogdoḗkonta, og-do-ay'-kon-tah; from G3590; ten times eight:—fourscore.

g359.d: ἀνάλυσις análysis, an-al'-oo-sis; from G360; departure:—departure.

g3590.d: ὄγδοος ógdoos, og'-do-os; from G3638; the eighth:—eighth.

g3591.d:
ὄγκος ónkos, ong'-kos; probably from the same as G43; a mass (as bending or bulging by its
 load), i.e. burden (hindrance):—weight.
g3591.r: Probably from the same as ἀγκάλη (G43)|English: arm

g3592.d:
ὅδε hóde, hod'-eh; from G3588 and G1161; the same, i.e. this or that one (plural these or
 those); often used as a personal pronoun:—he, she, such, these, thus.
g3592.r: From ὁ (G3588) and δέ (G1161)|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g3593.d: ὁδεύω hodeúō, hod-yoo'-o; from G3598; to travel:—journey.
g3593.r: From ὁδός (G3598)|English: way, way side, journey, highway, misc

g3594.d:
ὁδηγέω hodēgéō, hod-ayg-eh'-o; from G3595; to show the way (literally or figuratively
 (teach)):—guide, lead.

g3595.d:
ὁδηγός hodēgós, hod-ayg-os'; from G3598 and G2233; a conductor (literally or figuratively
 (teacher)):—guide, leader.
g3595.r: From ὁδός (G3598) and ἡγέομαι (G2233)|English: way, way side, journey, highway, misc

g3596.d:
ὁδοιπορέω hodoiporéō, hod-oy-por-eh'-o; from a compound of G3598 and G4198; to be a wayfarer, i.e. travel:—go
 on a journey.
g3596.r: From a compound of ὁδός (G3598) and πορεύω (G4198)|English: way, way side, journey, highway, misc

g3597.d: ὁδοιπορία hodoiporía, hod-oy-por-ee'-ah; from the same as G3596; travel:—journey(-ing).
g3597.r: From the same as ὁδοιπορέω (G3596)|English: go on (one's) journey

g3598.d:
ὁδός hodós, hod-os'; apparently a primary word; a road; by implication, a progress (the
 route, act or distance); figuratively, a mode or means:—journey,
 (high-)way.

g3599.d: ὀδούς odoús, od-ooce; perhaps from the base of G2068; a "tooth":—tooth.
g3599.r: Perhaps from the base of ἐσθίω (G2068)|English: eat, live, devour

g36.d:
ἀγενής agenḗs, ag-en-ace'; from G1 (as negative particle) and G1085; properly, without kin, i.e.
 (of unknown descent, and by implication) ignoble:—base things.
g36.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as negative particle) and γένος (G1085)|English: Alpha

g360.d:
ἀναλύω analýō, an-al-oo'-o; from G303 and G3089; to break up, i.e. depart (literally or
 figuratively):—depart, return.
g360.r: From ἀνά (G303) and λύω (G3089)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3600.d: ὀδυνάω odynáō, od-oo-nah'-o; from G3601; to grieve:—sorrow, torment.

g3601.d: ὀδύνη odýnē, od-oo'-nay; from G1416; grief (as dejecting):—sorrow.

g3602.d:
ὀδυρμός odyrmós, od-oor-mos'; from a derivative of the base of G1416; moaning, i.e.
 lamentation:—mourning.
g3602.r: From a derivative of the base of δύνω (G1416)|English: set

g3604.d: Ὀζίας Ozías, od-zee'-as; of Hebrew origin (H5818); Ozias (i.e. Uzzijah), an Israelite:—Ozias.

g3605.d:
ὄζω ózō, od'-zo; a primary verb (in a strengthened form); to scent (usually an ill
 "odor"):—stink.
g3605.r: A root word (in a strengthened form)|

g3606.d:
ὅθεν hóthen, hoth'-en; from G3739 with the directive enclitic of source; from which place or
 source or cause (adverb or conjunction):—from thence, (from) whence,
 where(-by, -fore, -upon).
g3606.r: From ὅς (G3739) with the directive enclitic of source|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g3607.d:
ὀθόνη othónē, oth-on'-ay; of uncertain affinity; a linen cloth, i.e. (especially) a
 sail:—sheet.

g3608.d:
ὀθόνιον othónion, oth-on'-ee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G3607; a linen bandage:—linen
 clothes.
g3608.r: From a presumed derivative of ὀθόνη (G3607)|English: sheet

g3609.d:
οἰκεῖος oikeîos, oy-ki'-os; from G3624; domestic, i.e. (as noun), a relative, adherent:—(those) of
 the (his own) house(-hold).
g3609.r: From οἶκος (G3624)|English: house, household, home, at home, misc

g361.d:
ἀναμάρτητος anamártētos, an-am-ar'-tay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G264; 
 sinless:—that is without sin.
g361.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ἁμαρτάνω (G264)|English: Alpha

g3610.d:
†οἰκέτης oikétēs, oy-ket'-ace; from G3611; a fellow resident, i.e. menial domestic:—(household)
 servant.

g3611.d:
οἰκέω oikéō, oy-keh'-o; from G3624; to occupy a house, i.e. reside (figuratively, inhabit,
 remain, inhere); by implication, to cohabit:—dwell. See also G3625.
g3611.r: From οἶκος (G3624)|English: house, household, home, at home, misc

g3612.d: οἴκημα oíkēma, oy'-kay-mah; from G3611; a tenement, i.e. (specially), a jail:—prison.

g3613.d:
οἰκητήριον oikētḗrion, oy-kay-tay'-ree-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G3611 (equivalent to G3612); a
 residence (literally or figuratively):—habitation, house.
g3613.r: From a presumed derivative of οἰκέω (G3611) (equivalent to οἴκημα (G3612))|English: dwell

g3614.d:
οἰκία oikía, oy-kee'-ah; from G3624; properly, residence (abstractly), but usually (concretely)
 an abode (literally or figuratively); by implication, a family
 (especially domestics):—home, house(-hold).
g3614.r: From οἶκος (G3624)|English: house, household, home, at home, misc

g3615.d:
†οἰκιακός oikiakós, oy-kee-ak-os'; from G3614; familiar, i.e. (as noun) relatives:—they (them) of (his
 own) household.
g3615.r: From οἰκία (G3614)|English: house, at home, household, from the house

g3616.d: οἰκοδεσποτέω oikodespotéō, oy-kod-es-pot-eh'-o; from G3617; to be the head of (i.e. rule) a family:—guide the house.
g3616.r: From οἰκοδεσπότης (G3617)|English: householder, goodman of the house, master of the house, goodman

g3617.d:
οἰκοδεσπότης oikodespótēs, oy-kod-es-pot'-ace; from G3624 and G1203; the head of a family:—goodman (of the house),
 householder, master of the house.
g3617.r: From οἶκος (G3624) and δεσπότης (G1203)|English: house, household, home, at home, misc

g3618.d:
οἰκοδομέω oikodoméō, oy-kod-om-eh'-o; from the same as G3619; to be a house-builder, i.e. construct or
 (figuratively) confirm:—(be in) build(-er, -ing, up), edify,
 embolden.
g3618.r: From the same as οἰκοδομή (G3619)|English: edifying, building, edification, wherewith (one) may edify

g3619.r: Feminine (abstract) of a compound of οἶκος (G3624) and the base of δῶμα (G1430)|English: house, household, home, at home, misc

g362.d: ἀναμένω anaménō, an-am-en'-o; from G303 and G3306; to await:—wait for.
g362.r: From ἀνά (G303) and μένω (G3306)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3620.d: οἰκοδομία oikodomía, oy-kod-om-ee'-ah; from the same as G3619; confirmation:—edifying.
g3620.r: From the same as οἰκοδομή (G3619)|English: edifying, building, edification, wherewith (one) may edify

g3621.d: †οἰκονομέω oikonoméō, oy-kon-om-eh'-o; from G3623; to manage (a house, i.e. an estate):—be steward.

g3622.d:
οἰκονομία oikonomía, oy-kon-om-ee'-ah; from G3623; administration (of a household or estate); specially, a
 (religious) "economy":—dispensation, stewardship.

g3623.d:
οἰκονόμος oikonómos, oy-kon-om'-os; from G3624 and the base of G3551; a house-distributor (i.e. manager), or
 overseer, i.e. an employee in that capacity; by extension, a fiscal
 agent (treasurer); figuratively, a preacher (of the
 Gospel):—chamberlain, governor, steward.
g3623.r: From οἶκος (G3624) and the base of νόμος (G3551)|English: house, household, home, at home, misc

g3624.d:
οἶκος oîkos, oy'-kos; of uncertain affinity; a dwelling (more or less extensive, literal or
 figurative); by implication, a family (more or less related, literally
 or figuratively):—home, house(-hold), temple.

g3625.d:
οἰκουμένη oikouménē, oy-kou-men'-ay; feminine participle present passive of G3611 (as noun, by implication,
 of G1093); land, i.e. the (terrene part of the) globe; specially, the
 Roman empire:—earth, world.
g3625.r: Feminine participle present passive of οἰκέω (G3611) (as noun, by implication of γῆ (G1093))|English: dwell

g3626.d:
†οἰκουρός oikourós, oy-koo-ros'; from G3624 and οὖρος oûros (a guard; be "ware"); a stayer at home, i.e.
 domestically inclined (a "good housekeeper"):—keeper at home.
g3626.r: From οἶκος (G3624) and ouros (a guard, be "ware")|English: house, household, home, at home, misc

g3627.d: †οἰκτείρω oikteírō, oyk-ti'-ro; from οἶκτος oîktos (pity); to exercise pity:—have compassion on.

g3628.d: οἰκτιρμός oiktirmós, oyk-tir-mos'; from G3627; pity:—mercy.
g3628.r: From οἰκτίρω (G3627)|English: have compassion on, have compassion

g3629.d: οἰκτίρμων oiktírmōn, oyk-tir'-mone; from G3627; compassionate:—merciful, of tender mercy.
g3629.r: From οἰκτίρω (G3627)|English: have compassion on, have compassion

g363.d:
†ἀναμιμνήσκω anamimnḗskō, an-am-im-nace'-ko; from G303 and G3403; to remind; (reflexively) to recollect:—call to
 mind, (bring to , call to, put in), remember(-brance).
g363.r: From ἀνά (G303) and μιμνῄσκομαι (G3403)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3630.d:
οἰνοπότης oinopótēs, oy-nop-ot'-ace; from G3631 and a derivative of the alternate of G4095; a
 tippler:—winebibber.
g3630.r: From οἶνος (G3631) and a derivative of the alternate of πίνω (G4095)|English: wine, winepress

g3631.d:
οἶνος oînos, oy'-nos; a primary word (or perhaps of Hebrew origin (H3196)); "wine" (literally
 or figuratively):—wine.
g3631.r: A primary word (or perhaps of Hebrew origin יַיִן (H3196))|English: wine, banqueting, winebibbers

g3632.d:
οἰνοφλυγία oinophlygía, oy-nof-loog-ee'-ah; from G3631 and a form of the base of G5397; an overflow (or surplus) of
 wine, i.e. vinolency (drunkenness):—excess of wine.
g3632.r: From οἶνος (G3631) and a form of the base of φλύαρος (G5397)|English: wine, winepress

g3633.d:
οἴομαι oíomai, oy'-om-ahee; middle voice apparently from G3634; to make like (oneself), i.e.
 imagine (be of the opinion):—suppose, think.
g3633.r: Middle voice apparently from οἷος (G3634)|English: such as, as, which, what manner, so as, what manner of man, what

g3634.d:
οἷος hoîos, hoy'-os; probably akin to G3588, G3739, and G3745; such or what sort of (as a
 correlation or exclamation); especially the neuter (adverbially) with
 negative, not so:—so (as), such as, what (manner of), which.
g3634.r: Probably akin to ὁ (G3588), ὅς (G3739), and ὅσος (G3745)|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g3635.d: ὀκνέω oknéō, ok-neh'-o; from ὄκνος óknos (hesitation); to be slow (figuratively, loath):—delay.

g3636.d:
ὀκνηρός oknērós, ok-nay-ros'; from G3635; tardy, i.e. indolent; (figuratively) irksome:—grievous,
 slothful.

g3637.d: ὀκταήμερος oktaḗmeros, ok-tah-ay'-mer-os; from G3638 and G2250; an eight-day old person or act:—the eighth day.
g3637.r: From ὀκτώ (G3638) and ἡμέρα (G2250)|English: eight, eighteen

g3638.d: ὀκτώ oktṓ, ok-to'; a primary numeral; "eight":—eight.

g3639.d:
ὄλεθρος ólethros, ol'-eth-ros; from a primary ὄλλυμι óllymi (to destroy; a prolonged form); ruin, i.e.
 death, punishment:—destruction.
g3639.r: From a primary ollumi (to destroy, a prolonged form)|

g364.d: ἀνάμνησις anámnēsis, an-am'-nay-sis; from G363; recollection:—remembrance (again).
g364.r: From ἀναμιμνῄσκω (G363)|English: call to remembrance, call to mind, bring to remembrance, remember, put to remembrance

g3640.d:
†ὀλιγόπιστος oligópistos, ol-ig-op'-is-tos; from G3641 and G4102; incredulous, i.e. lacking confidence (in
 Christ):—of little faith.
g3640.r: From ὀλίγος (G3641) and πίστις (G4102)|English: few, (a) little, small, few things, almost, a while, misc

g3641.d:
†ὀλίγος olígos, ol-ee'-gos; of uncertain affinity; puny (in extent, degree, number, duration or
 value); especially neuter (adverbially) somewhat:—+ almost,
 brief(-ly), few, (a) little, + long, a season, short, small, a while.

g3642.d:
ὀλιγόψυχος oligópsychos, ol-ig-op'-soo-khos; from G3641 and G6590; little-spirited, i.e.
 faint-hearted:—feebleminded.
g3642.r: From ὀλίγος (G3641) and ψυχή (G5590)|English: few, (a) little, small, few things, almost, a while, misc

g3643.d:
ὀλιγωρέω oligōréō, ol-ig-o-reh'-o; from a compound of G3641 and ὤρα ṓra ("care"); to have little regard for,
 i.e. to disesteem:—despise.
g3643.r: From a compound of ὀλίγος (G3641) and ora ("care")|English: few, (a) little, small, few things, almost, a while, misc

g3644.d: ὀλοθρευτής olothreutḗs, ol-oth-ryoo-tace'; from G3645; a ruiner, i.e. (specially), a venomous serpent:—destroyer.

g3645.d: ὀλοθρεύω olothreúō, ol-oth-ryoo'-o; from G3639; to spoil, i.e. slay:—destroy.

g3646.d:
ὁλοκαύτωμα holokaútōma, hol-ok-ow'-to-mah; from a derivative of a compound of G3650 and a derivative of G2545; a
 wholly-consumed sacrifice ("holocaust"):—(whole) burnt offering.
g3646.r: From a derivative of a compound of ὅλος (G3650) and a derivative of καίω (G2545)|English: all, whole, every whit, altogether, throughout

g3647.d: ὁλοκληρία holoklēría, hol-ok-lay-ree'-ah; from G3648; integrity, i.e. physical wholeness:—perfect soundness.

g3648.d:
ὁλόκληρος holóklēros, hol'-ok'-lay-ros; from G3650 and G2819; complete in every part, i.e. perfectly sound (in
 body):—entire, whole.
g3648.r: From ὅλος (G3650) and κλῆρος (G2819)|English: all, whole, every whit, altogether, throughout

g3649.d:
ὀλολύζω ololýzō, ol-ol-odd'-zo; a reduplicated primary verb; to "howl" or "halloo", i.e.
 shriek:—howl.

g365.d: ἀνανεόω ananeóō, an-an-neh-o'-o; from G303 and a derivative of G3501; to renovate, i.e. reform:—renew.
g365.r: From ἀνά (G303) and a derivative of νέος (G3501)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3650.d:
ὅλος hólos, hol'-os; a primary word; "whole" or "all", i.e. complete (in extent, amount,
 time or degree), especially (neuter) as noun or adverb:—all,
 altogether, every whit, + throughout, whole.

g3651.d:
ὁλοτελής holotelḗs, hol-ot-el-ace'; from G3650 and G5056; complete to the end, i.e. absolutely
 perfect:—wholly.
g3651.r: From ὅλος (G3650) and τέλος (G5056)|English: all, whole, every whit, altogether, throughout

g3652.d:
Ὀλυμπᾶς Olympâs, ol-oom-pas'; probably a contraction from Ὀλυμπιόδωρος Olympiódōros (Olympian-bestowed, i.e.
 heaven-descended); Olympas, a Christian:—Olympas.
g3652.r: Probably a contraction from Olumpiodoros (Olympian-bestowed, i.e. heaven-descended)|

g3653.d:
ὄλυνθος ólynthos, ol'-oon-thos; of uncertain derivation; an unripe (because out of season)
 fig:—untimely fig.

g3654.d:
ὅλως hólōs, hol'-oce; adverb from G3650; completely, i.e. altogether; (by analogy),
 everywhere; (negatively) not by any means:—at all, commonly, utterly.
g3654.r: From ὅλος (G3650)|English: all, whole, every whit, altogether, throughout

g3655.d: ὄμβρος ómbros, om'-bros; of uncertain affinity; a thunder storm:—shower.

g3656.d:
ὁμιλέω homiléō, hom-il-eh'-o; from G3658; to be in company with, i.e. (by implication) to
 converse:—commune, talk.

g3657.d:
ὁμιλία homilía, hom-il-ee'-ah; from G3658; companionship ("homily"), i.e. (by implication)
 intercourse:—communication.

g3658.d:
ὅμιλος hómilos, hom'-il-os; from the base of G3674 and a derivative of the alternate of G138
 (meaning a crowd); association together, i.e. a multitude:—company.
g3658.r: From the base of ὁμοῦ (G3674) and a derivative of the alternate of αἱρέω (G138) (meaning a crowd)|English: together

g3659.d: ὄμμα ómma, om'-mah; from G3700; a sight, i.e. (by implication) the eye:—eye.
g3659.r: From ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g366.d:
ἀνανήφω ananḗphō, an-an-ay'-fo; from G303 and G3525; to become sober again, i.e. (figuratively) regain
 (one's) senses:—recover self.
g366.r: From ἀνά (G303) and νήφω (G3525)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3660.d:
ὀμνύω omnýō, om-noo'-o; a prolonged form of a primary,
             but obsolete ὄμω ómō, for which
             another prolonged form
    ὀμόω omóō  om-o'-o  is used in certain tenses; 

 to swear, i.e. take (or declare on) oath:—swear.
g3660.r: A prolonged form of a primary but obsolete omo, for which another prolonged form (omoo {om-o'-o}) is used in certain tenses|

g3661.d:
ὁμοθυμαδόν homothymadón, hom-oth-oo-mad-on'; adverb from a compound of the base of G3674 and G2372; 
 unanimously:—with one accord (mind).
g3661.r: From a compound of the base of ὁμοῦ (G3674) and θυμός (G2372)|English: together

g3663.d:
ὁμοιοπαθής homoiopathḗs, hom-oy-op-ath-ace'; from G3664 and the alternate of G3958; similarly affected:—of (subject
 to) like passions.
g3663.r: From ὅμοιος (G3664) and the alternate of πάσχω (G3958)|English: like

g3664.d:
ὅμοιος hómoios, hom'-oy-os; from the base of G3674; similar (in appearance or character):—like, +
 manner.
g3664.r: From the base of ὁμοῦ (G3674)|English: together

g3665.d: ὁμοιότης homoiótēs, hom-oy-ot'-ace; from G3664; resemblance:—like as, similitude.

g3666.d:
ὁμοιόω homoióō, hom-oy-o'-o; from G3664; to assimilate, i.e. compare; passively, to become
 similar:—be (make) like, (in the) liken(-ess), resemble.

g3667.d:
ὁμοίωμα homoíōma, hom-oy'-o-mah; from G3666; a form; abstractly, resemblance:—made like to, likeness,
 shape, similitude.
g3667.r: From ὁμοιόω (G3666)|English: liken, make like, be like, in the likeness of, resemble

g3668.d: ὁμοίως homoíōs, hom-oy'-oce; adverb from G3664; similarly:—likewise, so.

g3669.d: ὁμοίωσις homoíōsis, hom-oy'-o-sis; from G3666; assimilation, i.e. resemblance:—similitude.
g3669.r: From ὁμοιόω (G3666)|English: liken, make like, be like, in the likeness of, resemble

g367.d:
Ἀνανίας Ananías, an-an-ee'-as; of Hebrew origin (H2608); Ananias, the name of three
 Israelites:—Ananias.

g3670.d:
ὁμολογέω homologéō, hom-ol-og-eh'-o; from a compound of the base of G3674 and G3056; to assent, i.e.
 covenant, acknowledge:—con- (pro-)fess, confession is made, give
 thanks, promise.
g3670.r: From a compound of the base of ὁμοῦ (G3674) and λόγος (G3056)|English: together

g3671.d: ὁμολογία homología, hom-ol-og-ee'-ah; from the same as G3670; acknowledgment:—con- (pro-)fession, professed.
g3671.r: From the same as ὁμολογέω (G3670)|English: confess, profess, promise, give thanks, confession is made, acknowledgeth

g3672.d:
ὁμολογουμένως homologouménōs, hom-ol-og-ow-men'-oce; adverb of present passive participle of G3670; confessedly:—without
 controversy.
g3672.r: From present passive participle of ὁμολογέω (G3670)|English: confess, profess, promise, give thanks, confession is made, acknowledgeth

g3673.d:
ὁμότεχνος homótechnos, hom-ot'-ekh-nos; from the base of G3674 and G5078; a fellow-artificer:—of the same
 craft.
g3673.r: From the base of ὁμοῦ (G3674) and τέχνη (G5078)|English: together

g3674.d:
ὁμοῦ homoû, hom-oo'; genitive case of ὁμός homós (the same; akin to G260) as adverb; at the same
 place or time:—together.
g3674.r: Genitive case of homos (the same, akin to ἅμα (G260)) as adv|English: together, withal, with, and, misc

g3675.d:
ὁμόφρων homóphrōn, hom-of'-rone; from the base of G3674 and G5424; like-minded, i.e. harmonious:—of one
 mind.
g3675.r: From the base of ὁμοῦ (G3674) and φρήν (G5424)|English: together

g3676.d:
ὅμως hómōs, hom'-oce; adverb from the base of G3674; at the same time, i.e. (conjunctionally)
 notwithstanding, yet still:—and even, nevertheless, though but.
g3676.r: From the base of ὁμοῦ (G3674)|English: together

g3677.d: ὄναρ ónar, on'-ar; of uncertain derivation; a dream:—dream.

g3678.d: ὀνάριον onárion, on-ar'-ee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G3688; a little ass:—young ass.
g3678.r: From a presumed derivative of ὄνος (G3688)|English: ass

g3679.d:
ὀνειδίζω oneidízō, on-i-did'-zo; from G3681; to defame, i.e. rail at, chide, taunt:—cast in teeth,
 (suffer) reproach, revile, upbraid.

g368.d:
ἀναντίῤῥητος anantírrhētos, an-an-tir'-hray-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a
 compound of G473 and G4483; indisputable:—cannot be spoken against.
g368.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a compound of ἀντί (G473) and ῥέω (G4483)|English: Alpha

g3680.d: ὀνειδισμός oneidismós, on-i-dis-mos'; from G3679; contumely:—reproach.
g3680.r: From ὀνειδίζω (G3679)|English: upbraid, reproach, revile, cast in (one's) teeth, suffer reproach

g3681.d:
ὄνειδος óneidos, on'-i-dos; probably akin to the base of G3686; notoriety, i.e. a taunt
 (disgrace):—reproach.
g3681.r: Probably akin to the base of ὄνομα (G3686)|English: name, named, called, surname, named, not tr

g3682.d: Ὀνήσιμος Onḗsimos, on-ay'-sim-os; from G3685; profitable; Onesimus, a Christian:—Onesimus.

g3683.d:
Ὀνησίφορος Onēsíphoros, on-ay-sif'-or-os; from a derivative of G3685 and G5411; profit-bearer; Onesiphorus, a
 Christian:—Onespiphorus.
g3683.r: From a derivative of ὀνίνημι (G3685) and φόρος (G5411)|English: have joy

g3684.d:
ὀνικός onikós, on-ik-os'; from G3688; belonging to a ass, i.e. large (so as to be turned by a
 ass):—millstone.

g3685.d:
ὀνίνημι onínēmi, on-in'-ay-mee; a prolonged form of an apparently primary verb ( ὄνομαι ónomai, to slur); 
 for which another prolonged form ( ὀνάω onáō) is used as an alternate in
 some tenses (unless indeed it be identical with the base of G3686
 through the idea of notoriety); to gratify, i.e. (middle voice) to
 derive pleasure or advantage from:—have joy.
g3685.r: A prolonged form of an apparently primary verb (onomai, to slur), for which another prolonged form (onao) is used as an alternate in some tenses [unless indeed it be identical with the base of ὄνομα (G3686) through the idea of notoriety]|English: name, named, called, surname, named, not tr

g3686.d:
ὄνομα ónoma, on'-om-ah; from a presumed derivative of the base of G1097 (compare G3685); a
 "name" (literally or figuratively) (authority, character):—called, (+
 sur-)name(-d).
g3686.r: From a presumed derivative of the base of γινώσκω (G1097) (cf ὀνίνημι (G3685))|English: know, perceive, understand, misc

g3687.d:
ὀνομάζω onomázō, on-om-ad'-zo; from G3686; to name, i.e. assign an appellation; by extension, to
 utter, mention, profess:—call, name.
g3687.r: From ὄνομα (G3686)|English: name, named, called, surname, named, not tr

g3688.d: ὄνος ónos, on'-os; apparently a primary word; a donkey:—an ass.

g3689.d:
ὄντως óntōs, on'-toce; adverb of the oblique cases of G5607; really:—certainly, clean,
 indeed, of a truth, verily.
g3689.r: From the oblique cases of ὤν (G5607)|English: being, when ... was, which is, that is, not tr, misc

g369.d: ἀναντιῤῥήτως anantirrhḗtōs, an-an-tir-hray'-toce; adverb from G368; promptly:—without gainsaying.
g369.r: From ἀναντίρρητος (G368)|English: can not be spoken against

g3690.d: ὄξος óxos, oz-os; from G3691; vinegar, i.e. sour wine:—vinegar.

g3691.d:
ὀξύς oxýs, oz-oos'; probably akin to the base of G188 ("acid"); keen; by analogy,
 rapid:—sharp, swift.
g3691.r: Probably akin to the base of ἀκμήν (G188) ["acid"]|English: yet

g3692.d:
ὀπή opḗ, op-ay'; probably from G3700; a hole (as if for light), i.e. cavern; by analogy,
 a spring (of water):—cave, place.
g3692.r: Probably from ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g3693.d:
ὄπισθεν ópisthen, op'-is-then; from ὄπις ópis (regard; from G3700) with enclitic of source; from the rear
 (as a secure aspect), i.e. at the back (adverb and preposition of
 place or time):—after, backside, behind.
g3693.r: From opis (regard, from ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)) with enclitic of source|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g3694.d:
ὀπίσω opísō, op-is'-o; from the same as G3693 with enclitic of direction; to the back, i.e.
 aback (as adverb or preposition of time or place; or as noun):—after,
 back(-ward), (+ get) behind, + follow.
g3694.r: From the same as ὄπισθεν (G3693) with enclitic of direction|English: behind, after, backside

g3695.d:
ὁπλίζω hoplízō, hop-lid'-zo; from G3696; to equip (with weapons (middle voice and
 figuratively)):—arm self.

g3696.d:
ὅπλον hóplon, hop'-lon; probably from a primary ἕπω hépō (to be busy about); an implement or
 utensil or tool (literally or figuratively, especially, offensive for
 war):—armour, instrument, weapon.
g3696.r: Probably from a primary hepo (to be busy about)|

g3697.d:
ὁποῖος hopoîos, hop-oy'-os; from G3739 and G4169; of what kind that, i.e. how (as) great (excellent)
 (specially, as an indefinite correlative to the definite antecedent
 G5108 of quality):—what manner (sort) of, such as whatsoever.
g3697.r: From ὅς (G3739) and ποῖος (G4169)|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g3699.d:
ὅπου hópou, hop'-oo; from G3739 and G4225; what(-ever) where, i.e. at whichever spot:—in
 what place, where(-as, -soever), whither (+ soever).
g3699.r: From ὅς (G3739) and πού (G4225)|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g37.d:
ἁγιάζω hagiázō, hag-ee-ad'-zo; from G40; to make holy, i.e. (ceremonially) purify or consecrate;
 (mentally) to venerate:—hallow, be holy, sanctify.
g37.r: From ἅγιος (G40)|English: holy, saints, Holy One, misc

g370.d: ἀνάξιος anáxios, an-ax'-ee-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G514; unfit:—unworthy.
g370.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and ἄξιος (G514)|English: Alpha

g3700.d:
ὀπτάνομαι optánomai, op-tan'-om-ahee; a (middle voice) prolonged form of the primary (middle voice)
    ὄπτομαι óptomai  op'-tom-ahee;  which is used for it in certain
                  tenses; and both as alternate of
                  G3708; 

 to gaze (i.e. with wide-open eyes, as at something remarkable; and
 thus differing from G991, which denotes simply voluntary observation;
 and from G1492, which expresses merely mechanical, passive or casual
 vision; while G2300, and still more emphatically its intensive G2334,
 signifies an earnest but more continued inspection; and G4648 a
 watching from a distance):—appear, look, see, shew self.
g3700.r: A (middle voice) prolonged form of the primary (middle voice) optomai {op'-tom-ahee}, which is used for it in certain tenses, and both as alternate of ὁράω (G3708)|English: see, take heed, behold, perceive, not tr

g3701.d:
ὀπτασία optasía, op-tas-ee'-ah; from a presumed derivative of G3700; visuality, i.e. (concretely) an
 apparition:—vision.
g3701.r: From a presumed derivative of ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g3702.d:
ὀπτός optós, op-tos'; from an obsolete verb akin to ἕπσω hépsō (to "steep"); cooked, i.e.
 roasted:—broiled.
g3702.r: From an obsolete verb akin to hepso (to "steep")|

g3703.d:
ὀπώρα opṓra, op-o'-rah; apparently from the base of G3796 and G5610; properly, even-tide of the
 (summer) season (dog-days), i.e. (by implication) ripe fruit:—fruit.
g3703.r: Apparently from the base of ὀψέ (G3796) and ὥρα (G5610)|English: in the end, even, at even

g3704.d:
ὅπως hópōs, hop'-oce; from G3739 and G4459; what(-ever) how, i.e. in the manner that (as
 adverb or conjunction of coincidence, intentional or
 actual):—because, how, (so) that, to, when.
g3704.r: From ὅς (G3739) and πῶς (G4459)|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g3705.d:
ὅραμα hórama, hor'-am-ah; from G3708; something gazed at, i.e. a spectacle (especially
 supernatural):—sight, vision.
g3705.r: From ὁράω (G3708)|English: see, take heed, behold, perceive, not tr

g3706.d:
ὅρασις hórasis, hor'-as-is; from G3708; the act of gazing, i.e. (externally) an aspect or
 (internally) an inspired appearance:—sight, vision.
g3706.r: From ὁράω (G3708)|English: see, take heed, behold, perceive, not tr

g3707.d:
ὁρατός horatós, hor-at-os'; from G3708; gazed at, i.e. (by implication) capable of being
 seen:—visible.
g3707.r: From ὁράω (G3708)|English: see, take heed, behold, perceive, not tr

g3708.d:
†ὁράω horáō, hor-ah'-o; properly, to stare at (compare G3700), i.e. (by implication) to discern
 clearly (physically or mentally); by extension, to attend to; by
 Hebraism, to experience; passively, to appear:—behold, perceive, see,
 take heed.
g3708.r: Properly, to stare at [cf ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)]|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g3709.d:
ὀργή orgḗ, or-gay'; from G3713; properly, desire (as a reaching forth or excitement of the
 mind), i.e. (by analogy), violent passion (ire, or (justifiable)
 abhorrence); by implication punishment:—anger, indignation,
 vengeance, wrath.

g371.d: ἀναξίως anaxíōs, an-ax-ee'-oce; adverb from G370; irreverently:—unworthily.

g3710.d:
ὀργίζω orgízō, or-gid'-zo; from G3709; to provoke or enrage, i.e. (passively) become
 exasperated:—be angry (wroth).
g3710.r: From ὀργή (G3709)|English: wrath, anger, vengeance, indignation

g3711.d: ὀργίλος orgílos, org-ee'-los; from G3709; irascible:—soon angry.
g3711.r: From ὀργή (G3709)|English: wrath, anger, vengeance, indignation

g3712.d: ὀργυιά orguiá, org-wee-ah'; from G3713; a stretch of the arms, i.e. a fathom:—fathom.

g3713.d:
†ὀρέγομαι orégomai, or-eg'-om-ahee; middle voice of apparently a prolonged form of an obsolete primary
 (compare G3735); to stretch oneself, i.e. reach out after (long
 for):—covet after, desire.
g3713.r: Middle voice of apparently a prolonged form of an obsolete primary [cf ὄρος (G3735)]|English: mountain, mount, hill

g3714.d:
ὀρεινός oreinós, or-i-nos; from G3735; mountainous, i.e. (feminine by implication, of G5561) the
 Highlands (of Judæa):—hill country.

g3715.d: ὄρεξις órexis, or'-ex-is; from G3713; excitement of the mind, i.e. longing after:—lust.

g3716.d:
ὀρθοποδέω orthopodéō, or-thop-od-eh'-o; from a compound of G3717 and G4228; to be straight-footed, i.e.
 (figuratively) to go directly forward:—walk uprightly.
g3716.r: From a compound of ὀρθός (G3717) and πούς (G4228)|English: upright, straight

g3717.d:
ὀρθός orthós, or-thos'; probably from the base of G3735; right (as rising), i.e.
 (perpendicularly) erect (figuratively, honest), or (horizontally)
 level or direct:—straight, upright.
g3717.r: Probably from the base of ὄρος (G3735)|English: mountain, mount, hill

g3718.d:
ὀρθοτομέω orthotoméō, or-thot-om-eh'-o; from a compound of G3717 and the base of G5114, to make a straight cut,
 i.e. (figuratively) to dissect (expound) correctly (the divine
 message):—rightly divide.
g3718.r: From a compound of ὀρθός (G3717) and the base of τομός (G5114)|English: upright, straight

g3719.d:
ὀρθρίζω orthrízō, or-thrid'-zo; from G3722; to use the dawn, i.e. (by implication) to repair
 betimes:—come early in the morning.
g3719.r: From ὄρθρος (G3722)|English: early in the morning

g372.d: ἀνάπαυσις anápausis, an-ap'-ow-sis; from G373; intermission; by implication, recreation:—rest.
g372.r: From ἀναπαύω (G373)|English: rest, refresh, take rest, give rest, take ease

g3720.d:
ὀρθρινός orthrinós, or-thrin-os'; from G3722; relating to the dawn, i.e. matutinal (as an epithet of
 Venus, especially brilliant in the early day):—morning.
g3720.r: From ὄρθρος (G3722)|English: early in the morning

g3722.d:
ὄρθρος órthros, or'-thros; from the same as G3735; dawn (as sun-rise, rising of light); by
 extension, morn:—early in the morning.
g3722.r: From the same as ὄρος (G3735)|English: mountain, mount, hill

g3723.d:
ὀρθῶς orthōs, or-thoce'; adverb from G3717; in a straight manner, i.e. (figuratively) correctly
 (also morally):—plain, right(-ly).

g3724.d:
ὁρίζω horízō, hor-id'-zo; from G3725; to mark out or bound ("horizon"), i.e. (figuratively) to
 appoint, decree, specify:—declare, determine, limit, ordain.

g3725.d:
ὅριον hórion, hor'-ee-on; neuter of a derivative of an apparently primary ὅρος hóros (a bound or
 limit); a boundary-line, i.e. (by implication) a frontier
 (region):—border, coast.
g3725.r: From a derivative of an apparently primary horos (a bound or limit)|

g3726.d:
†ὁρκίζω horkízō, hor-kid'-zo; from G3727; to put on oath, i.e. make swear; by analogy, to solemnly
 enjoin:—adjure, charge.

g3727.d:
ὅρκος hórkos, hor'-kos; from ἕρκος hérkos (a fence; perhaps akin to G3725); a limit, i.e. (sacred)
 restraint (specially, an oath):—oath.
g3727.r: From herkos (a fence, perhaps akin to ὅριον (G3725))|English: coast, border

g3728.d:
ὁρκωμοσία horkōmosía, hor-ko-mos-ee'ah; from a compound of G3727 and a derivative of G3660; asseveration on
 oath:—oath.
g3728.r: From a compound of ὅρκος (G3727) and a derivative of ὀμνύω (G3660)|English: oath

g3729.d:
ὁρμάω hormáō, hor-mah'-o; from G3730; to start, spur or urge on, i.e. (reflexively) to dash or
 plunge:—run (violently), rush.

g373.d:
ἀναπαύω anapaúō, an-ap-ow'-o; from G303 and G3973; (reflexively) to repose (literally or figuratively
 (be exempt), remain); by implication, to refresh:—take ease, refresh,
 (give, take) rest.
g373.r: From ἀνά (G303) and παύω (G3973)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3730.d: ὁρμή hormḗ, hor-may'; of uncertain affinity; a violent impulse, i.e. onset:—assault.

g3731.d: ὅρμημα hórmēma, hor'-may-mah; from G3730; an attack, i.e. (abstractly) precipitancy:—violence.

g3732.d: ὄρνεον órneon, or'-neh-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G3733; a birdling:—bird, fowl.
g3732.r: From a presumed derivative of ὄρνις (G3733)|English: hen

g3733.d:
ὄρνις órnis, or'-nis; probably from a prolonged form of the base of G3735; a bird (as rising
 in the air), i.e. (specially), a hen (or female domestic fowl):—hen.
g3733.r: Probably from a prolonged form of the base of ὄρος (G3735)|English: mountain, mount, hill

g3734.d:
ὁροθεσία horothesía, hor-oth-es-ee'-ah; from a compound of the base of G3725 and a derivative of G5087; a
 limit-placing, i.e. (concretely) boundary-line:—bound.
g3734.r: From a compound of the base of ὅριον (G3725) and a derivative of τίθημι (G5087)|English: coast, border

g3735.r: Probably from an obsolete oro (to rise or "rear", perhaps akin to αἴρω (G142), cf ὄρνις (G3733))|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g3736.d: ὀρύσσω orýssō, or-oos'-so; apparently a primary verb; to "burrow" in the ground, i.e. dig:—dig.

g3737.d:
ὀρφανός orphanós, or-fan-os'; of uncertain affinity; bereaved ("orphan"), i.e.
 parentless:—comfortless, fatherless.

g3738.d:
ὀρχέομαι orchéomai, or-kheh'-om-ahee; middle voice from ὄρχος órchos (a row or ring); to dance (from the ranklike
 or regular motion):—dance.
g3738.r: Middle voice from orchos (a row or ring)|

g3739.d:
ὅς hós, hos; probably a primary word (or perhaps a form of the article G3588); the
 relatively (sometimes demonstrative) pronoun, who, which, what,
 that:—one, (an-, the) other, some, that, what, which, who(-m, -se),
 etc. See also G3757.
g3739.r: Probably a primary word (or perhaps a form of the article ὁ (G3588))|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g374.d: ἀναπείθω anapeíthō, an-ap-i'-tho; from G303 and G3982; to incite:—persuade.
g374.r: From ἀνά (G303) and πείθω (G3982)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3740.d:
ὁσάκις hosákis, hos-ak'-is; multiple adverb from G3739; how (i.e. with G302, so) many times as:—as
 oft(-en) as.
g3740.r: Multiple adverb from ὅς (G3739)|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g3741.d: ὅσιος hósios, hos'-ee-os; of uncertain affinity; properly, right (by intrinsic or divine character; thus distinguished from G1342, which refers rather to human statutes and relations; from G2413, which denotes formal consecration; and from G40, which relates to purity from defilement), i.e. hallowed (pious, sacred, sure):—holy, mercy, shalt be.

g3742.d: ὁσιότης hosiótēs, hos-ee-ot'-ace; from G3741; piety:—holiness.
g3742.r: From ὅσιος (G3741)|English: holy, Holy One, mercies, shall be

g3743.d: ὁσίως hosíōs, hos-ee-oce'; adverb from G3741; piously:—holily.
g3743.r: From ὅσιος (G3741)|English: holy, Holy One, mercies, shall be

g3744.d: ὀσμή osmḗ, os-may'; from G3605; fragrance (literally or figuratively):—odour, savour.

g3745.d:
ὅσος hósos, hos'-os; by reduplication from G3739; as (much, great, long, etc.) as:—all
 (that), as (long, many, much) (as), how great (many, much),
 (in-)asmuch as, so many as, that (ever), the more, those things, what
 (great, -soever), wheresoever, wherewithsoever, which, × while,
 who(-soever).
g3745.r: By reduplication from ὅς (G3739)|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g3747.d: ὀστέον ostéon, os-teh'-on; of uncertain affinity; a bone:—bone.

g3748.d:
ὅστις hóstis, hos'-tis; from G3739 and G5100; which some, i.e. any that; also (definite) which
 same:—X and (they), (such) as, (they) that, in that they,
 what(-soever), whereas ye, (they) which, who(-soever). Compare G3754.
g3748.r: From ὅς (G3739) and τις (G5100)|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g3749.d:
ὀστράκινος ostrákinos, os-tra'-kin-os; from ὄστρακον óstrakon ("oyster") (a tile, i.e. terra cotta); earthen-ware,
 i.e. clayey; by implication, frail:—of earth, earthen.
g3749.r: From ostrakon ["oyster"] (a tile, i.e. terra cotta)|

g375.d: ἀναπέμπω anapémpō, an-ap-em'-po; from G303 and G3992; to send up or back:—send (again).
g375.r: From ἀνά (G303) and πέμπω (G3992)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3750.d: ὄσφρησις ósphrēsis, os'-fray-sis; from a derivative of G3605; smell (the sense):—smelling.
g3750.r: From a derivative of ὄζω (G3605)|English: stink

g3751.d:
ὀσφῦς osphŷs, os-foos'; of uncertain affinity; the loin (externally), i.e. the hip; internally
 (by extension) procreative power:—loin.

g3752.d:
ὅταν hótan, hot'-an; from G3753 and G302; whenever (implying hypothesis or more or less
 uncertainty); also causatively (conjunctionally) inasmuch as:—as long
 (soon) as, that, + till, when(-soever), while.
g3752.r: From ὅτε (G3753) and ἄν (G302)|English: when, while, as soon as, after that, after, that

g3753.d:
ὅτε hóte, hot'-eh; from G3739 and G5037; at which (thing) too, i.e. when:—after (that), as
 soon as, that, when, while.
g3753.r: From ὅς (G3739) and τέ (G5037)|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g3754.d:
ὅτι hóti, hot'-ee; neuter of G3748 as conjunction; demonstrative, that (sometimes
 redundant); causative, because:—as concerning that, as though,
 because (that), for (that), how (that), (in) that, though, why.
g3754.r: Neuter of ὅστις (G3748) as conjunction; demonst. that (sometimes redundant)|English: which, who, whosoever, that, whatsoever, whosoever, whatsoever, misc

g3756.d:
οὐ ou, oo; a primary word; the absolute negative (compare G3361) adverb; no or
 not:—+ long, nay, neither, never, no (X man), none, (can-)not, +
 nothing, + special, un(-worthy), when, + without, + yet but. See also
 G3364, G3372.
g3756.r: A primary word, the absolute negative [cf μή (G3361)] adverb|English: not, no, that not, God forbid, lest, neither, no man, but, none, not translated, misc

g3757.d:
οὗ hoû, hoo; genitive case of G3739 as adverb; at which place, i.e.
 where:—where(-in), whither(-soever).
g3757.r: Genitive case of ὅς (G3739) as adverb|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g3758.d: οὐά ouá, oo-ah'; a primary exclamation of surprise; "ah":—ah.

g3759.d: οὐαί ouaí, oo-ah'-ee; a primary exclamation of grief; "woe":—alas, woe.

g376.d:
†ἀνάπηρος anápēros, an-ap'-ay-ros; from G303 (in the sense of intensity) and πῆρος pēros (maimed); 
 crippled:—maimed.
g376.r: From ἀνά (G303) (in the sense of intensity) and peros (maimed)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3760.d: οὐδαμῶς oudamōs, oo-dam-oce'; adverb from (the feminine) of G3762; by no means:—not.
g3760.r: From (the feminine) of οὐδείς (G3762)|English: no man, nothing, none, no, any man, any, man, neither any man, misc

g3761.d:
οὐδέ oudé, oo-deh'; from G3756 and G1161; not however, i.e. neither, nor, not even:—neither
 (indeed), never, no (more, nor, not), nor (yet), (also, even, then)
 not (even, so much as), + nothing, so much as.
g3761.r: From οὐ (G3756) and δέ (G1161)|English: not, no, cannot, misc

g3762.d:
†οὐδείς oudeís, oo-dice'; from G3761 and G1520; not even one (man, woman or thing), i.e. none,
 nobody, nothing:—any (man), aught, man, neither any (thing), never
 (man), no (man), none (+ of these things), not (any, at all, -thing),
 nought.
g3762.r: From οὐδέ (G3761) and εἷς (G1520)|English: neither, nor, not, no not, not so much as, then not, not tr, misc

g3763.d:
οὐδέποτε oudépote, oo-dep'-ot-eh; from G3761 and G4218; not even at any time, i.e. never at all:—neither
 at any time, never, nothing at any time.
g3763.r: From οὐδέ (G3761) and ποτέ (G4218)|English: neither, nor, not, no not, not so much as, then not, not tr, misc

g3764.d:
οὐδέπω oudépō, oo-dep'-o; from G3761 and G4452; not even yet:—as yet not, never before (yet),
 (not) yet.
g3764.r: From οὐδέ (G3761) and πώς (G4452)|English: neither, nor, not, no not, not so much as, then not, not tr, misc

g3765.d:
οὐκέτι oukéti, ook-et'-ee; from G3756 and G2089; not yet, no longer:—after that (not), (not) any
 more, henceforth (hereafter) not, no longer (more), not as yet (now),
 now no more (not), yet (not).
g3765.r: From οὐ (G3756) and ἔτι (G2089)|English: not, no, cannot, misc

g3766.d:
οὐκοῦν oukoûn, ook-oon'; from G3756 and G3767; is it not therefore that, i.e. (affirmatively)
 hence or so:—then.
g3766.r: From οὐ (G3756) and οὖν (G3767)|English: not, no, cannot, misc

g3767.d:
οὖν oûn, oon; apparently a primary word; (adverbially) certainly, or
 (conjunctionally) accordingly:—and (so, truly), but, now (then), so
 (likewise then), then, therefore, verily, wherefore.

g3768.d: οὔπω oúpō, oo'-po; from G3756 and G4452; not yet:—hitherto not, (no…) as yet, not yet.
g3768.r: From οὐ (G3756) and πώς (G4452)|English: not, no, cannot, misc

g3769.d: οὐρά ourá, oo-rah'; apparently a primary word; a tail:—tail.

g377.d:
ἀναπίπτω anapíptō, an-ap-ip'-to; from G303 and G4098; to fall back, i.e. lie down, lean back:—lean, sit
 down (to meat).
g377.r: From ἀνά (G303) and πίπτω (G4098)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3770.d:
οὐράνιος ouránios, oo-ran'-ee-os; from G3772; celestial, i.e. belonging to or coming from the
 sky:—heavenly.
g3770.r: From οὐρανός (G3772)|English: heaven, air, sky, heavenly

g3771.d: οὐρανόθεν ouranóthen, oo-ran-oth'-en; from G3772 and the enclitic of source; from the sky:—from heaven.
g3771.r: From οὐρανός (G3772) and the enclitic of source|English: heaven, air, sky, heavenly

g3772.d:
οὐρανός ouranós, oo-ran-os'; perhaps from the same as G3735 (through the idea of elevation); the
 sky; by extension, heaven (as the abode of God); by implication,
 happiness, power, eternity; specially, the Gospel
 (Christianity):—air, heaven(-ly), sky.
g3772.r: Perhaps from the same as ὄρος (G3735) (through the idea of elevation); the sky|English: mountain, mount, hill

g3773.d:
Οὐρβανός Ourbanós, oor-ban-os'; of Latin origin; Urbanus (of the city, "urbane"), a
 Christian:—Urbanus.

g3774.d: Οὐρίας Ourías, oo-ree'-as; of Hebrew origin (H223); Urias (i.e. Urijah), a Hittite:—Urias.
g3774.r: Of Hebrew origin אוּרִיָּה (H223)|English: Uriah, Urijah

g3775.d: οὖς oûs, ooce; apparently a primary word; the ear (physically or mentally):—ear.

g3776.d:
οὐσία ousía, oo-see'-ah; from the feminine of G5607; substance, i.e. property
 (possessions):—goods, substance.
g3776.r: From the feminine of ὤν (G5607)|English: being, when ... was, which is, that is, not tr, misc

g3777.d:
οὔτε oúte, oo'-teh; from G3756 and G5037; not too, i.e. neither or nor; by analogy, not
 even:—neither, none, nor (yet), (no, yet) not, nothing.
g3777.r: From οὐ (G3756) and τέ (G5037)|English: not, no, cannot, misc

g3778.d:
οὗτος hoûtos, hoo'-tos; from the article G3588 and G846; the he (she or it), i.e. this or that
 (often with article repeated):—he (it was that), hereof, it, she,
 such as, the same, these, they, this (man, same, woman), which, who.
g3778.r: From the article ὁ (G3588) and αὐτός (G846)|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g3779.d:
οὕτω hoútō, hoo'-to; adverb from G3778; in this way (referring to what precedes or
 follows):—after that, after (in) this manner, as, even (so), for all
 that, like(-wise), no more, on this fashion(-wise), so (in like
 manner), thus, what.
g3779.r: From οὗτος (G3778)|English: this, these, he, the same, this man, she, they, misc

g378.r: From ἀνά (G303) and πληρόω (G4137)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3780.d: οὐχί ouchí, oo-khee'; intensive of G3756; not indeed:—nay, not.
g3780.r: Intensive of οὐ (G3756)|English: not, no, cannot, misc

g3781.d:
ὀφειλέτης opheilétēs, of-i-let'-ace; from G3784; an ower, i.e. person indebted; figuratively, a delinquent;
 morally, a transgressor (against God):—debtor, which owed, sinner.
g3781.r: From ὀφείλω (G3784)|English: ought, owe, be bound, be (one's) duty, be a debtor, be guilty, be indebted, misc

g3782.d:
ὀφειλή opheilḗ, of-i-lay'; from G3784; indebtedness, i.e. (concretely) a sum owed; figuratively,
 obligation, i.e. (conjugal) duty:—debt, due.
g3782.r: From ὀφείλω (G3784)|English: ought, owe, be bound, be (one's) duty, be a debtor, be guilty, be indebted, misc

g3783.d:
ὀφείλημα opheílēma, of-i'-lay-mah; from (the alternate of) G3784; something owed, i.e. (figuratively) a
 due; morally, a fault:—debt.
g3783.r: From (the alternate of) ὀφείλω (G3784)|English: ought, owe, be bound, be (one's) duty, be a debtor, be guilty, be indebted, misc

g3784.d:
ὀφείλω opheílō, of-i'-lo; probably from the base of G3786 (through the idea of accruing); to owe
 (pecuniarily); figuratively, to be under obligation (ought, must,
 should); morally, to fail in duty:—behove, be bound, (be) debt(-or),
 (be) due(-ty), be guilty (indebted), (must) need(-s), ought, owe,
 should. See also G3785.
g3784.r: Or (in certain tenses) its prolonged form opheileo {of-i-leh'-o}; probably from the base of ὄφελος (G3786) (through the idea of accruing)|English: it profiteth, it advantageth

g3785.d:
ὄφελον óphelon, of'-el-on; first person singular of a past tense of G3784; I ought (wish), i.e.
 (interjection) oh that!:—would (to God).
g3785.r: First person singular of a past tense of ὀφείλω (G3784)|English: ought, owe, be bound, be (one's) duty, be a debtor, be guilty, be indebted, misc

g3786.d:
ὄφελος óphelos, of'-el-os; from ὀφέλλω ophéllō (to heap up, i.e. accumulate or benefit); 
 gain:—advantageth, profit.
g3786.r: From ophello (to heap up, i.e. accumulate or benefit)|

g3787.d:
†ὀφθαλμοδουλεία ophthalmodouleía, of-thal-mod-oo-li'-ah; from G3788 and G1397; sight-labor, i.e. that needs watching
 (remissness):—eye-service.
g3787.r: From ὀφθαλμός (G3788) and δουλεία (G1397)|English: eye, sight

g3788.d:
ὀφθαλμός ophthalmós, of-thal-mos'; from G3700; the eye (literally or figuratively); by implication,
 vision; figuratively, envy (from the jealous side-glance):—eye,
 sight.
g3788.r: From ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g3789.d:
ὄφις óphis, of'-is; probably from G3700 (through the idea of sharpness of vision); a snake,
 figuratively, (as a type of sly cunning) an artful malicious person,
 especially Satan:—serpent.
g3789.r: Probably from ὀπτάνομαι (G3700) (through the idea of sharpness of vision)|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g379.d:
ἀναπολόγητος anapológētos, an-ap-ol-og'-ay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G626; 
 indefensible:—without an excuse, inexcusable.
g379.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ἀπολογέομαι (G626)|English: Alpha

g3790.d:
ὀφρῦς ophrŷs, of-roos'; perhaps from G3700 (through the idea of the shading or proximity to the
 organ of vision); the eye-"brow" or forehead, i.e. (figuratively) the
 brink of a precipice:—brow.
g3790.r: Perhaps from ὀπτάνομαι (G3700) (through the idea of the shading or proximity to the organ of vision)|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g3791.d: ὀχλέω ochléō, okh-leh'-o; from G3793; to mob, i.e. (by implication) to harass:—vex.
g3791.r: From ὄχλος (G3793)|English: people, multitude, press, company, number of people, number

g3792.d:
ὀχλοποιέω ochlopoiéō, okh-lop-oy-eh'-o; from G3793 and G4160; to make a crowd, i.e. raise a public
 disturbance:—gather a company.
g3792.r: From ὄχλος (G3793) and ποιέω (G4160)|English: people, multitude, press, company, number of people, number

g3793.d:
ὄχλος óchlos, okh'los; from a derivative of G2192 (meaning a vehicle); a throng (as borne
 along); by implication, the rabble; by extension, a class of people;
 figuratively, a riot:—company, multitude, number (of people), people,
 press.
g3793.r: From a derivative of ἔχω (G2192) (meaning a vehicle)|English: have, be, need, misc

g3794.d:
ὀχύρωμα ochýrōma, okh-oo'-ro-mah; from a remote derivative of G2192 (meaning to fortify, through the idea
 of holding safely); a castle (figuratively, argument):—stronghold.
g3794.r: From a remote derivative of ἔχω (G2192) (meaning to fortify, through the idea of holding safely)|English: have, be, need, misc

g3795.d:
ὀψάριον opsárion, op-sar'-ee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of G3702; a relish to other
 food (as if cooked sauce), i.e. (specially), fish (presumably salted
 and dried as a condiment):—fish.
g3795.r: From a presumed derivative of the base of ὀπτός (G3702)|English: broiled

g3796.r: From the same as ὀπίσω (G3694) (through the idea of backwardness); (adverbially) late in the day|English: after, behind, back, back, follow, backward

g3797.d: ὄψιμος ópsimos, op'-sim-os; from G3796; later, i.e. vernal (showering):—latter.
g3797.r: From ὀψέ (G3796)|English: in the end, even, at even

g3798.d:
†ὄψιος ópsios, op'-see-os; from G3796; late; feminine (as noun) afternoon (early eve) or nightfall
 (later eve):—even(-ing, (-tide)).
g3798.r: From ὀψέ (G3796)|English: in the end, even, at even

g3799.d:
ὄψις ópsis, op'-sis; from G3700; properly, sight (the act), i.e. (by implication) the
 visage, an external show:—appearance, countenance, face.
g3799.r: From ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g38.d:
ἁγιασμός hagiasmós, hag-ee-as-mos'; from G37; properly, purification, i.e. (the state) purity; concretely
 (by Hebraism) a purifier:—holiness, sanctification.
g38.r: From ἁγιάζω (G37)|English: sanctify, hallow, be holy

g380.d:
ἀναπτύσσω anaptýssō, an-ap-toos'-o; from G303 (in the sense of reversal) and G4428; to unroll (a scroll or
 volume):—open.
g380.r: From ἀνά (G303) (in the sense of reversal) and πτύσσω (G4428)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3800.d:
ὀψώνιον opsṓnion, op-so'-nee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of the same as G3795; rations for a
 soldier, i.e. (by extension) his stipend or pay:—wages.
g3800.r: From a presumed derivative of the same as ὀψάριον (G3795)|English: fish, small fish

g3802.d: παγιδεύω pagideúō, pag-id-yoo'-o; from G3803; to ensnare (figuratively):—entangle.

g3803.d:
παγίς pagís, pag-ece'; from G4078; a trap (as fastened by a noose or notch); figuratively, a
 trick or statagem (temptation):—snare.

g3804.d:
πάθημα páthēma, path'-ay-mah; from a presumed derivative of G3806; something undergone, i.e. hardship
 or pain; subjectively, an emotion or influence:—affection,
 affliction, motion, suffering.
g3804.r: From a presumed derivative of πάθος (G3806)|English: inordinate affection, affection, lust

g3805.d:
παθητός pathētós, path-ay-tos'; from the same as G3804; liable (i.e. doomed) to experience
 pain:—suffer.
g3805.r: From the same as πάθημα (G3804)|English: suffering, affliction, affection, motion

g3806.d:
πάθος páthos, path'-os; from the alternate of G3958; properly, suffering ("pathos"), i.e.
 (subjectively) a passion (especially concupiscence):—(inordinate)
 affection, lust.
g3806.r: From the alternate of πάσχω (G3958)|English: suffer, be vexed, passion, feel

g3807.d:
παιδαγωγός paidagōgós, pahee-dag-o-gos'; from G3816 and a reduplicated form of G71; a boy-leader, i.e. a servant
 whose office it was to take the children to school; (by implication,
 (figuratively) a tutor ("pædagogue")):—instructor, schoolmaster.
g3807.r: From παῖς (G3816) and a reduplicated form of ἄγω (G71)|English: servant, child, son (Christ), son, manservant, maid, maiden, young man

g3808.d: παιδάριον paidárion, pahee-dar'-ee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G3816; a little boy:—child, lad.
g3808.r: From a presumed derivative of παῖς (G3816)|English: servant, child, son (Christ), son, manservant, maid, maiden, young man

g3809.d:
παιδεία paideía, pahee-di'-ah; from G3811; tutorage, i.e. education or training; by implication,
 disciplinary correction:—chastening, chastisement, instruction,
 nurture.
g3809.r: From παιδεύω (G3811)|English: chasten, chastise, learn, teach, instruct

g381.d: ἀνάπτω anáptō, an-ap'-to; from G303 and G681; to enkindle:—kindle, light.
g381.r: From ἀνά (G303) and ἅπτω (G681)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3810.d:
παιδευτής paideutḗs, pahee-dyoo-tace'; from G3811; a trainer, i.e. teacher or (by implication)
 discipliner:—which corrected, instructor.
g3810.r: From παιδεύω (G3811)|English: chasten, chastise, learn, teach, instruct

g3811.d:
παιδεύω paideúō, pahee-dyoo'-o; from G3816; to train up a child, i.e. educate, or (by implication),
 discipline (by punishment):—chasten(-ise), instruct, learn, teach.
g3811.r: From παῖς (G3816)|English: servant, child, son (Christ), son, manservant, maid, maiden, young man

g3812.d: παιδιόθεν paidióthen, pahee-dee-oth'-en; adverb (of source) from G3813; from infancy:—of a child.
g3812.r: From (of source) from παιδίον (G3813)|English: child, little child, young child, damsel

g3813.r: From dimin. of παῖς (G3816)|English: servant, child, son (Christ), son, manservant, maid, maiden, young man

g3814.d:
παιδίσκη paidískē, pahee-dis'-kay; feminine diminutive of G3816; a girl, i.e. (specially), a female slave
 or servant:—bondmaid(-woman), damsel, maid(-en).
g3814.r: From diminutive of παῖς (G3816)|English: servant, child, son (Christ), son, manservant, maid, maiden, young man

g3815.d: παίζω paízō, paheed'-zo; from G3816; to sport (as a boy):—play.
g3815.r: From παῖς (G3816)|English: servant, child, son (Christ), son, manservant, maid, maiden, young man

g3816.d:
παῖς paîs, paheece; perhaps from G3817; a boy (as often beaten with impunity), or (by
 analogy), a girl, and (genitive case) a child; specially, a slave or
 servant (especially a minister to a king; and by eminence to
 God):—child, maid(-en), (man) servant, son, young man.

g3817.d:
παίω paíō, pah'-yo; a primary verb; to hit (as if by a single blow and less violently than
 G5180); specially, to sting (as a scorpion):—smite, strike.
g3817.r: A primary verb; to hit (as if by a single blow and less violently than τύπτω (G5180))|English: smite, beat, strike, wound

g3819.r: Probably another form for πάλιν (G3825) (through the idea of retrocession)|English: again

g382.d:
ἀναρίθμητος anaríthmētos, an-ar-ith'-may-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G705; unnumbered,
 i.e. without number:—innumerable.
g382.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of ἀριθμέω (G705)|English: Alpha

g3820.d: παλαιός palaiós, pal-ah-yos'; from G3819; antique, i.e. not recent, worn out:—old.
g3820.r: From πάλαι (G3819)|English: long ago, any while, a great while ago, old, in time past, of old

g3821.d: παλαιότης palaiótēs, pal-ah-yot'-ace; from G3820; antiquatedness:—oldness.

g3822.d:
παλαιόω palaióō, pal-ah-yo'-o; from G3820; to make (passively, become) worn out, or declare
 obsolete:—decay, make (wax) old.

g3823.d: πάλη pálē, pal'-ay; from πάλλω pállō (to vibrate; another form for G906); wrestling:—+ wrestle.
g3823.r: From pallo (to vibrate, another form for βάλλω (G906))|English: cast, put, thrust, cast out, lay, lie, misc

g3824.d:
παλιγγενεσία palingenesía, pal-ing-ghen-es-ee'-ah; from G3825 and G1078; (spiritual) rebirth (the state or the act), i.e.
 (figuratively) spiritual renovation; specially, Messianic
 restoration:—regeneration.

g3825.d:
πάλιν pálin, pal'-in; probably from the same as G3823 (through the idea of oscillatory
 repetition); (adverbially) anew, i.e. (of place) back, (of time) once
 more, or (conjunctionally) furthermore or on the other hand:—again.
g3825.r: Probably from the same as πάλη (G3823) (through the idea of oscillatory repetition)|English: wrestle

g3826.d:
παμπληθεί pamplētheí, pam-play-thi'; dative case (adverb) of a compound of G3956 and G4128; in full
 multitude, i.e. concertedly or simultaneously:—all at once.
g3826.r: Dative case (adverb) of a compound of πᾶς (G3956) and πλῆθος (G4128)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3828.d:
Παμφυλία Pamphylía, pam-fool-ee'-ah; from a compound of G3956 and G4443; every-tribal, i.e. heterogeneous
 (G5561 being implied); Pamphylia, a region of Asia Minor:—Pamphylia.
g3828.r: From a compound of πᾶς (G3956) and πυρά (G4443), every-tribal, i.e. heterogeneous (5561 being implied)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3829.r: From a presumed compound of πᾶς (G3956) and a derivative of δέχομαι (G1209)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g383.d: ἀνασείω anaseíō, an-as-i'-o; from G303 and G4579; figuratively, to excite:—move, stir up.
g383.r: From ἀνά (G303) and σείω (G4579)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3830.d: πανδοχεύς pandocheús, pan-dokh-yoos'; from the same as G3829; an innkeeper (warden of a caravanserai):—host.
g3830.r: From the same as πανδοχεῖον (G3829)|English: inn

g3831.d:
πανήγυρις panḗgyris, pan-ay'-goo-ris; from G3956 and a derivative of G58; a mass-meeting, i.e. (figuratively)
 universal companionship:—general assembly.
g3831.r: From πᾶς (G3956) and a derivative of ἀγορά (G58)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3832.d: †πανοικί panoikí, pan-oy-kee'; adverb from G3956 and G3624; with the whole family:—with all his house.
g3832.r: From πᾶς (G3956) and οἶκος (G3624)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3833.d:
πανοπλία panoplía, pan-op-lee'-ah; from a compound of G3956 and G3696; full armor ("panoply"):—all (whole)
 armour.
g3833.r: From a compound of πᾶς (G3956) and ὅπλον (G3696)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3834.d:
πανουργία panourgía, pan-oorg-ee'-ah; from G3835; adroitness, i.e. (in a bad sense) trickery or
 sophistry:—(cunning) craftiness, subtilty.

g3835.d: πανοῦργος panoûrgos, pan-oor'-gos; from G3956 and G2041; all-working, i.e. adroit (shrewd):—crafty.
g3835.r: From πᾶς (G3956) and ἔργον (G2041)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3837.d:
†πανταχοῦ pantachoû, pan-takh-oo'; genitive case (as adverb of place) of a presumed derivative of G3956; 
 universally:—in all places, everywhere.
g3837.r: Genitive case (as adverb of place) of a presumed derivative of πᾶς (G3956)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3838.d:
παντελής pantelḗs, pan-tel-ace'; from G3956 and G5056; full-ended, i.e. entire (neuter as noun,
 completion):—+ in (no) wise, uttermost.
g3838.r: Adverb (of manner) from πᾶς (G3956) and τέλος (G5056)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3839.d: †πάντη pántē, pan'-tay; adverb (of manner) from G3956; wholly:—always.
g3839.r: Adverb (of manner) from πᾶς (G3956)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g384.r: From ἀνά (G303) (in the sense of reversal) and a derivative of σκεῦος (G4632)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3840.d:
πάντοθεν pántothen, pan-toth'-en; adverb (of source) from G3956; from (i.e. on) all sides:—on every
 side, round about.
g3840.r: Adverb (of source) from πᾶς (G3956)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3841.d:
παντοκράτωρ pantokrátōr, pan-tok-rat'-ore; from G3956 and G2904; the all-ruling, i.e. God (as absolute and
 universal sovereign):—Almighty, Omnipotent.
g3841.r: From πᾶς (G3956) and κράτος (G2904)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3842.d:
πάντοτε pántote, pan'-tot-eh; from G3956 and G3753; every when, i.e. at all times:—alway(-s),
 ever(-more).
