g3842.r: From πᾶς (G3956) and ὅτε (G3753)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3843.d:
πάντως pántōs, pan'-toce; adverb from G3956; entirely; specially, at all events, (with negative,
 following) in no event:—by all means, altogether, at all, needs, no
 doubt, in (no) wise, surely.
g3843.r: From πᾶς (G3956)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3844.d:
παρά pará, par-ah'; a primary preposition; properly, near; i.e. (with genitive case) from
 beside (literally or figuratively), (with dative case) at (or in) the
 vicinity of (objectively or subjectively), (with accusative case) to
 the proximity with (local (especially beyond or opposed to) or causal
 (on account of):—above, against, among, at, before, by, contrary to,
 × friend, from, + give (such things as they), + that (she) had,
 × his, in, more than, nigh unto, (out) of, past, save,
 side…by, in the sight of, than, (there-)fore, with.

g3845.d:
παραβαίνω parabaínō, par-ab-ah'-ee-no; from G3844 and the base of G939; to go contrary to, i.e. violate a
 command:—(by) transgress(-ion).
g3845.r: From παρά (G3844) and the base of βάσις (G939)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3846.d:
παραβάλλω parabállō, par-ab-al'-lo; from G3844 and G906; to throw alongside, i.e. (reflexively) to reach a
 place, or (figuratively) to liken:—arrive, compare.
g3846.r: From παρά (G3844) and βάλλω (G906)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3847.d: παράβασις parábasis, par-ab'-as-is; from G3845; violation:—breaking, transgression.
g3847.r: From παραβαίνω (G3845)|English: transgression, fall by transgression

g3848.d: παραβάτης parabátēs, par-ab-at'-ace; from G3845; a violator:—breaker, transgress(-or).

†παρεισδύνω pareisdýnō, par-ice-doo'-no; from G3844 and a compound of G1519 and G1416; to settle in alongside,
 i.e. lodge stealthily:—creep in unawares.
g3921.r: From παρά (G3844) and a compound of εἰς (G1519) and δύνω (G1416)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3922.d:
παρεισέρχομαι pareisérchomai, par-ice-er'-khom-ahee; from G3844 and G1525; to come in alongside, i.e. supervene additionally
 or steathily:—come in privily, enter.
g3922.r: From παρά (G3844) and εἰσέρχομαι (G1525)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3923.d:
παρεισφέρω pareisphérō, par-ice-fer'-o; from G3844 and G1533; to bear in alongside, i.e. introduce
 simultaneously:—give.
g3923.r: From παρά (G3844) and εἰσφέρω (G1533)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3924.d:
παρεκτός parektós, par-ek-tos'; from G3844 and G1622; near outside, i.e. besides:—except, saving,
 without.
g3924.r: From παρά (G3844) and ἐκτός (G1622)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3925.d:
παρεμβολή parembolḗ, par-em-bol-ay'; from a compound of G3844 and G1685; a throwing in beside
 (juxtaposition), i.e. (specially), battle-array, encampment or
 barracks (tower Antonia):—army, camp, castle.
g3925.r: From a compound of παρά (G3844) and ἐμβάλλω (G1685)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3926.d: παρενοχλέω parenochléō, par-en-okh-leh'-o; from G3844 and G1776; to harass further, i.e. annoy:—trouble.
g3926.r: From παρά (G3844) and ἐνοχλέω (G1776)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3927.d:
παρεπίδημος parepídēmos, par-ep-id'-ay-mos; from G3844 and the base of G1927; an alien alongside, i.e. a resident
 foreigner:—pilgrim, stranger.
g3927.r: From παρά (G3844) and the base of ἐπιδημέω (G1927)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3928.d:
παρέρχομαι parérchomai, par-er'-khom-ahee; from G3844 and G2064; to come near or aside, i.e. to approach (arrive),
 go by (or away), (figuratively) perish or neglect, (causative)
 avert:—come (forth), go, pass (away, by, over), past, transgress.
g3928.r: From παρά (G3844) and ἔρχομαι (G2064)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3929.d: πάρεσις páresis, par'-es-is; from G2935; praetermission, i.e. toleration:—remission.

g393.d:
ἀνατέλλω anatéllō, an-at-el'-lo; from G303 and the base of G5056; to (cause to) arise:—(a-, make to)
 rise, at the rising of, spring (up), be up.
g393.r: From ἀνά (G303) and the base of τέλος (G5056)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3930.d:
παρέχω paréchō, par-ekh'-o; from G3844 and G2192; to hold near, i.e. present, afford, exhibit,
 furnish occasion:—bring, do, give, keep, minister, offer, shew, +
 trouble.
g3930.r: From παρά (G3844) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3931.d:
παρηγορία parēgoría, par-ay-gor-ee'-ah; from a compound of G3844 and a derivative of G58 (meaning to harangue an
 assembly); an address alongside, i.e. (specially),
 consolation:—comfort.
g3931.r: From a compound of παρά (G3844) and a derivative of ἀγορά (G58) (meaning to harangue an assembly)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3932.d: παρθενία parthenía, par-then-ee'-ah; from G3933; maidenhood:—virginity.

g3933.d:
παρθένος parthénos, par-then'-os; of unknown origin; a maiden; by implication, an unmarried
 daughter:—virgin.

g3934.d:
Πάρθος Párthos, par'-thos; probably of foreign origin; a Parthian, i.e. inhabitant of
 Parthia:—Parthian.

g3935.d: παρίημι paríēmi, par-ee'-ay-mi; from G3844 and hiemi (to send); to let by, i.e. relax:—hang down.
g3935.r: From παρά (G3844) and hiemi (to send)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3936.d:
παρίστημι parístēmi, par-is'-tay-mee; from G3844 and G2476; to stand beside, i.e. (transitively) to exhibit,
 proffer, (specially), recommend, (figuratively) substantiate; or
 (intransitively) to be at hand (or ready), aid:—assist, bring before,
 command, commend, give presently, present, prove, provide, shew, stand
 (before, by, here, up, with), yield.
g3936.r: From παρά (G3844) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3937.d:
Παρμενᾶς Parmenâs, par-men-as'; probably by contraction for Παρμενίδης Parmenídēs (a derivative of a compound of
 G3844 and G3306); constant; Parmenas, a Christian:—Parmenas.
g3937.r: Probably by contraction for Parmenides (a derivative of a compound of παρά (G3844) and μένω (G3306))|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3938.d: πάροδος párodos, par'-od-os; from G3844 and G3598; a by-road, i.e. (actively) a route:—way.
g3938.r: From παρά (G3844) and ὁδός (G3598)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3939.d:
παροικέω paroikéō, par-oy-keh'-o; from G3844 and G3611; to dwell near, i.e. reside as a
 foreigner:—sojourn in, be a stranger.
g3939.r: From παρά (G3844) and οἰκέω (G3611)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g394.d:
†ἀνατίθεμαι anatíthemai, an-at-ith'-em-ahee; from G303 and the middle voice of G5087; to set forth (for oneself), i.e
 propound:—communicate, declare.
g394.r: From ἀνά (G303) and the middle voice of τίθημι (G5087)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3940.d: παροικία paroikía, par-oy-kee'-ah; from G3941; foreign residence:—sojourning, × as strangers.

g3941.d:
πάροικος pároikos, par'-oy-kos; from G3844 and G3624; having a home near, i.e. (as noun) a by-dweller
 (alien resident):—foreigner, sojourn, stranger.
g3941.r: From παρά (G3844) and οἶκος (G3624)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3942.d:
παροιμία paroimía, par-oy-mee'-ah; from a compound of G3844 and perhaps a derivative of G3633; apparently a
 state alongside of supposition, i.e. (concretely) an adage; specially,
 an enigmatical or fictitious illustration:—parable, proverb.
g3942.r: From a compound of παρά (G3844) and perhaps a derivative of οἴομαι (G3633)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3943.d:
πάροινος pároinos, par'-oy-nos; from G3844 and G3631; staying near wine, i.e. tippling (a toper):—given
 to wine.
g3943.r: From παρά (G3844) and οἶνος (G3631)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3944.d:
παροίχομαι paroíchomai, par-oy'-khom-ahee; from G3844 and οἴχομαι oíchomai (to depart); to escape along, i.e. be
 gone:—past.
g3944.r: From παρά (G3844) and oichomai (to depart)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3945.d: παρομοιάζω paromoiázō, par-om-oy-ad'-zo; from G3946; to resemble:—be like unto.

g3946.d: παρόμοιος parómoios, par-om'-oy-os; from G3844 and G3664; alike nearly, i.e. similar:—like.
g3946.r: From παρά (G3844) and ὅμοιος (G3664)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3947.d:
παροξύνω paroxýnō, par-ox-oo'-no; from G3844 and a derivative of G3691; to sharpen alongside, i.e.
 (figuratively) to exasperate:—easily provoke, stir.
g3947.r: From παρά (G3844) and a derivative of ὀξύς (G3691)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3948.d:
παροξυσμός paroxysmós, par-ox-oos-mos'; from G3947 ("paroxysm"); incitement (to good), or dispute (in
 anger):—contention, provoke unto.

g3949.d:
παροργίζω parorgízō, par-org-id'-zo; from G3844 and G3710; to anger alongside, i.e. enrage:—anger, provoke
 to wrath.
g3949.r: From παρά (G3844) and ὀργίζω (G3710)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g395.d:
ἀνατολή anatolḗ, an-at-ol-ay'; from G393; a rising of light, i.e. dawn (figuratively); by implication,
 the east (also in plural):—dayspring, east, rising.
g395.r: From ἀνατέλλω (G393)|English: be up, rise, spring up, make rise, at the rising of, spring, arise

g3950.d: παροργισμός parorgismós, par-org-is-mos'; from G3949; rage:—wrath.
g3950.r: From παροργίζω (G3949)|English: anger, provoke to wrath

g3951.d:
παροτρύνω parotrýnō, par-ot-roo'-no; from G3844 and ὀτρύνω otrýnō (to spur); to urge along, i.e. stimulate (to
 hostility):—stir up.
g3951.r: From παρά (G3844) and otruno (to spur)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3952.d:
παρουσία parousía, par-oo-see'-ah; from the present participle of G3918; a being near, i.e. advent (often,
 return; specially, of Christ to punish Jerusalem, or finally the
 wicked); (by implication) physically, aspect:—coming, presence.
g3952.r: From the present participle of πάρειμι (G3918)|English: be present, come, present, be present here, be here, such things as one hath, he that lacketh

g3953.d:
παροψίς paropsís, par-op-sis'; from G3844 and the base of G3795; a side-dish (the
 receptacle):—platter.
g3953.r: From παρά (G3844) and the base of ὀψάριον (G3795)|English: of, with, from, by ... side, at, than, misc

g3954.d:
παῤῥησία parrhēsía, par-rhay-see'-ah; from G3956 and a derivative of G4483; all out-spokenness, i.e.
 frankness, bluntness, publicity; by implication, assurance:—bold (X
 -ly, -ness, -ness of speech), confidence,
 × freely, × openly, × plainly(-ness).
g3954.r: From πᾶς (G3956) and a derivative of ῥέω (G4483)|English: all, all things, every, all men, whosoever, everyone, whole, every man, all manner of, no, any, every thing, whatsoever, always, any thing, daily, no, not tr

g3955.d:
παῤῥησιάζομαι parrhēsiázomai, par-hray-see-ad'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G3954; to be frank in utterance, or confident in
 spirit and demeanor:—be (wax) bold, (preach, speak) boldly.
g3955.r: Middle voice from παρρησία (G3954)|English: boldness, confidence, openly, plainly, openly, boldly, misc

g3956.d:
πᾶς pâs, pas; including all the forms of declension; apparently a primary word; all,
 any, every, the whole:—all (manner of, means), alway(-s), any (one),
 × daily, + ever, every (one, way), as many as, + no(-thing), X
 thoroughly, whatsoever, whole, whosoever.
g3956.r: Including all the forms of declension|

g3957.d:
πάσχα páscha, pas'-khah; of Chaldee origin (compare H6453); the Passover (the meal, the day, the
 festival or the special sacrifices connected with it):—Easter,
 Passover.
g3957.r: Of Aramaic origin cf פֶּסַח (H6453)|English: passover, passover offerings

g3958.d:
πάσχω páschō, pas'-kho; apparently a primary verb; to experience a sensation or impression
 (usually painful):—feel, passion, suffer, vex.

g3959.d: Πάταρα Pátara, pat'-ar-ah; probably of foreign origin; Patara, a place in Asia Minor:—Patara.

g396.d:
ἀνατρέπω anatrépō, an-at-rep'-o; from G303 and the base of G5157; to overturn (figuratively):—overthrow,
 subvert.
g396.r: From ἀνά (G303) and the base of τροπή (G5157)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3960.d:
πατάσσω patássō, pat-as'-so; probably prolongation from G3817; to knock (gently or with a weapon or
 fatally):—smite, strike. Compare G5180.
g3960.r: Probably prolongation from παίω (G3817)|English: smite, strike

g3961.d:
πατέω patéō, pat-eh'-o; from a derivative probably of G3817 (meaning a "path"); to trample
 (literally or figuratively):—tread (down, under foot).
g3961.r: From a derivative probably of παίω (G3817) (meaning a "path")|English: smite, strike

g3962.d:
†πατήρ patḗr, pat-ayr'; apparently a primary word; a "father" (literally or figuratively, near
 or more remote):—father, parent.

g3963.d:
Πάτμος Pátmos, pat'-mos; of uncertain derivation; Patmus, an islet in the
 Mediterranean:—Patmos.

g3965.d:
πατριά patriá, pat-ree-ah'; as if feminine of a derivative of G3962; paternal descent, i.e.
 (concretely) a group of families or a whole race (nation):—family,
 kindred, lineage.
g3965.r: A derivative of πατήρ (G3962)|English: Father, father

g3966.d: πατριάρχης patriárchēs, pat-ree-arkh'-ace; from G3965 and G757; a progenitor ("patriarch"):—patriarch.
g3966.r: From πατριά (G3965) and ἄρχω (G757)|English: lineage, kindred, family

g3967.d: πατρικός patrikós, pat-ree-kos'; from G3962; paternal, i.e. ancestral:—of fathers.

g3968.d:
πατρίς patrís, pat-rece'; from G3902; a father-land, i.e. native town; (figuratively) heavenly
 home:—(own) country.

g3969.d:
†Πατροβᾶς Patrobâs, pat-rob'-as; perhaps a contraction for Πατρόβιος Patróbios (a compound of G3962 and G979); 
 father's life; Patrobas, a Christian:—Patrobas.
g3969.r: Perhaps countr. for Patrobios (a compound of πατήρ (G3962) and βίος (G979))|English: Father, father

g397.d:
ἀνατρέφω anatréphō, an-at-ref'-o; from G303 and G5142; to rear (physically or mentally):—bring up,
 nourish (up).
g397.r: From ἀνά (G303) and τρέφω (G5142)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3970.d:
πατροπαράδοτος patroparádotos, pat-rop-ar-ad'-ot-os; from G3962 and a derivative of G3860 (in the sense of handing over or
 down); traditionary:—received by tradition from fathers.
g3970.r: From πατήρ (G3962) and a derivative of παραδίδωμι (G3860) (in the sense of handing over or down)|English: Father, father

g3971.d: πατρῷος patrōios, pat-ro'-os; from G3962; paternal, i.e. hereditary:—of fathers.

g3972.d:
Παῦλος Paûlos, pow'-los; of Latin origin; (little; but remotely from a derivative of G3973,
 meaning the same); Paulus, the name of a Roman and of an
 apostle:—Paul, Paulus.

g3973.d:
παύω paúō, pow'-o; a primary verb ("pause"); to stop (transitively or intransitively),
 i.e. restrain, quit, desist, come to an end:—cease, leave, refrain.

g3974.d: Πάφος Páphos, paf'-os; of uncertain derivation; Paphus, a place in Cyprus:—Paphos.

g3975.d:
παχύνω pachýnō, pakh-oo'-no; from a derivative of G4078 (meaning thick); to thicken, i.e. (by
 implication) to fatten (figuratively, stupefy or render callous):—wax
 gross.
g3975.r: From a derivative of πήγνυμι (G4078) (meaning thick)|English: pitch

g3976.d: πέδη pédē, ped'-ay; ultimately from G4228; a shackle for the feet:—fetter.

g3977.d:
πεδινός pedinós, ped-ee-nos'; from a derivative of G4228 (meaning the ground); level (as easy for the
 feet):—plain.
g3977.r: From a derivative of πούς (G4228) (meaning the ground)|English: foot, footstool

g3978.d:
πεζεύω pezeúō, ped-zyoo'-o; from the same as G3979; to foot a journey, i.e. travel by land:—go
 afoot.
g3978.r: From the same as πεζῇ (G3979)|English: on foot, afoot

g3979.d:
πεζῇ pezēi, ped-zay'; dative case feminine of a derivative of G4228 (as adverb); foot-wise,
 i.e. by walking:—a- (on) foot.
g3979.r: Dative case feminine of a derivative of πούς (G4228) (as adv)|English: foot, footstool

g398.d:
ἀναφαίνω anaphaínō, an-af-ah'-ee-no; from G303 and G5316; to show, i.e. (reflexively) appear, or (passively)
 to have pointed out:—(should) appear, discover.
g398.r: From ἀνά (G303) and φαίνω (G5316)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3980.d:
πειθαρχέω peitharchéō, pi-tharkh-eh'-o; from a compound of G3982 and G757; to be persuaded by a ruler, i.e.
 (genitive case) to submit to authority; by analogy, to conform to
 advice:—hearken, obey (magistrates).
g3980.r: From a compound of πείθω (G3982) and ἄρχω (G757)|English: persuade, trust, obey, have confidence, believe, be confident, misc

g3981.r: From πείθω (G3982)|English: persuade, trust, obey, have confidence, believe, be confident, misc

g3982.d:
πείθω peíthō, pi'-tho; a primary verb; to convince (by argument, true or false); by analogy,
 to pacify or conciliate (by other fair means); reflexively or
 passively, to assent (to evidence or authority), to rely (by inward
 certainty):—agree, assure, believe, have confidence, be (wax)
 conflent, make friend, obey, persuade, trust, yield.

g3983.d:
πεινάω peináō, pi-nah'-o; from the same as G3993 (through the idea of pinching toil; "pine"); to
 famish (absolutely or comparatively); figuratively, to crave:—be an
 hungered.
g3983.r: From the same as πένης (G3993) (through the idea of pinching toil; "pine")|English: poor

g3984.d:
πεῖρα peîra, pi'-rah; from the base of G4008 (through the idea of piercing); a test, i.e.
 attempt, experience:—assaying, trial.
g3984.r: From the base of πέραν (G4008) (through the idea of piercing)|English: other side, beyond, over, on the other side, farther side

g3985.d:
πειράζω peirázō, pi-rad'-zo; from G3984; to test (objectively), i.e. endeavor, scrutinize, entice,
 discipline:—assay, examine, go about, prove, tempt(-er), try.

g3986.d:
πειρασμός peirasmós, pi-ras-mos'; from G3985; a putting to proof (by experiment (of good), experience (of
 evil), solicitation, discipline or provocation); by implication,
 adversity:—temptation, × try.
g3986.r: From πειράζω (G3985)|English: tempt, try, tempter, prove, assay, examine, go about

g3987.d:
†πειράω peiráō, pi-rah'-o; from G3984; to test (subjectively), i.e. (reflexively) to
 attempt:—assay.

g3988.d:
πεισμονή peismonḗ, pice-mon-ay'; from a presumed derivative of G3982; persuadableness, i.e.
 credulity:—persuasion.
g3988.r: From a presumed derivative of πείθω (G3982)|English: persuade, trust, obey, have confidence, believe, be confident, misc

g3989.d: πέλαγος pélagos, pel'-ag-os; of uncertain affinity; deep or open sea, i.e. the main:—depth, sea.

g399.d:
ἀναφέρω anaphérō, an-af-er'-o; from G303 and G5342; to take up (literally or figuratively):—bear,
 bring (carry, lead) up, offer (up).
g399.r: From ἀνά (G303) and φέρω (G5342)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g3990.d:
πελεκίζω pelekízō, pel-ek-id'-zo; from a derivative of G4141 (meaning an axe); to chop off (the head),
 i.e. truncate:—behead.
g3990.r: From a derivative of πλήσσω (G4141) (meaning an axe)|English: smite

g3991.d: πέμπτος pémptos, pemp'-tos; from G4002; fifth:—fifth.
g3991.r: From πέντε (G4002)|English: five, three score and fifteen, fifty thousand

g3992.d:
πέμπω pémpō, pem'-po; apparently a primary verb; to dispatch (from the subjective view or
 point of departure, whereas ἵημι híēmi (as a stronger form of εἶμι eîmi) refers
 rather to the objective point or terminus ad quem, and G4724 denotes
 properly, the orderly motion involved), especially on a temporary
 errand; also to transmit, bestow, or wield:—send, thrust in.

g3993.d:
πένης pénēs, pen'-ace; from a primary πένω pénō (to toil for daily subsistence); starving, i.e.
 indigent:—poor. Compare G4434.
g3993.r: From a primary peno (to toil for daily subsistence)|

g3994.d: πενθερά pentherá, pen-ther-ah'; feminine of G3995; a wife's mother:—mother in law, wife's mother.

g3995.d: πενθερός pentherós, pen-ther-os'; of uncertain affinity; a wife's father:—father in law.

g3996.d: πενθέω penthéō, pen-theh'-o; from G3997; to grieve (the feeling or the act):—mourn, (be-)wail.

g3997.d: πένθος pénthos, pen'-thos; strengthened from the alternate of G3958; grief:—mourning, sorrow.
g3997.r: Strengthened from the alternate of πάσχω (G3958)|English: suffer, be vexed, passion, feel

g3998.d: †πενιχρός penichrós, pen-tikh-ros'; prolongation from the base of G3993; necessitous:—poor.
g3998.r: Prolongation from the base of πένης (G3993)|English: poor

g3999.d: πεντάκις pentákis, pen-tak-ece'; multiplicative adverb from G4002; five times:—five times.
g3999.r: Multiplicative adverb from πέντε (G4002)|English: five, three score and fifteen, fifty thousand

g4.d:
ἀβαρής abarḗs, ab-ar-ace'; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G922; weightless, i.e.
 (figuratively) not burdensome:—from being burdensome.
g4.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and βάρος (G922)|English: Alpha

g40.d:
ἅγιος hágios, hag'-ee-os; from ἅγος hágos (an awful thing) (compare G53, G2282); sacred (physically,
 pure, morally blameless or religious, ceremonially,
 consecrated):—(most) holy (one, thing), saint.
g40.r: From hagos (an awful thing) [cf ἁγνός (G53), θάλπω (G2282)]|English: pure, chaste, clear

g400.d: ἀναφωνέω anaphōnéō, an-af-o-neh'-o; from G303 and G5455; to exclaim:—speak out.
g400.r: From ἀνά (G303) and φωνέω (G5455)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g4000.d: πεντακισχίλιοι pentakischílioi, pen-tak-is-khil'-ee-oy; from G3999 and G5507; five times a thousand:—five thousand.

g4012.d:

 matter, circumstance or general period):—(there-)about, above,
 against, at, on behalf of, × and his company, which concern, (as)
 concerning, for, × how it will go with, ((there-, where-)) of, on,
 over, pertaining (to), for sake, × (e-)state, (as) touching,
 (where-)by (in), with. In comparative, it retains substantially the
 same meaning of circuit (around), excess (beyond), or completeness
 (through).

περπερεύομαι perpereúomai, per-per-yoo'-om-ahee; middle voice from πέρπερος pérperos (braggart; perhaps by reduplication of the
 base of G4008); to boast:—vaunt itself.
g4068.r: Middle voice from perperos (braggart, perhaps by reduplication of the base of πέραν (G4008))|English: other side, beyond, over, on the other side, farther side

g4069.d: Περσίς Persís, per-sece'; a Persian woman; Persis, a Christian female:—Persis.

g407.d: †ἀνδρίζομαι andrízomai, an-drid'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G435; to act manly:—quit like men.
g407.r: Middle voice from ἀνήρ (G435)|English: man, husband, sir, fellow, not tr

g4070.d:
πέρυσι pérysi, per'-oo-si; adverb from G4009; the by-gone, i.e. (as noun) last year:—+ a year
 ago.
g4070.r: From πέρας (G4009)|English: end, utmost part, uttermost part

g4071.d:
πετεινόν peteinón, pet-i-non'; neuter of a derivative of G4072; a flying animal, i.e. bird:—bird,
 fowl.
g4071.r: From a derivative of πέτομαι (G4072)|English: fly, flying

g4072.d: †πέτομαι pétomai, pet'-om-ahee; middle voice of a primary verb; to fly:—fly(-ing).
g4072.r: Middle voice of a primary verb|

g4073.d:
πέτρα pétra, pet'-ra; feminine of the same as G4074; a (mass of) rock (literally or
 figuratively):—rock.
g4073.r: From the same as Πέτρος (G4074)|English: Peter, stone

g4074.d:
Πέτρος Pétros, pet'-ros; apparently a primary word; a (piece of) rock (larger than G3037); as a
 name, Petrus, an apostle:—Peter, rock. Compare G2786.

g4075.d: πετρώδης petrṓdēs, pet-ro'-dace; from G4073 and G1491; rock-like, i.e. rocky:—stony.

g4076.d: πήγανον pḗganon, pay'-gan-on; from G4078; rue (from its thick or fleshy leaves):—rue.

g4077.d:
πηγή pēgḗ, pay-gay'; probably from G4078 (through the idea of gushing plumply); a fount
 (literally or figuratively), i.e. source or supply (of water, blood,
 enjoyment) (not necessarily the original spring):—fountain, well.
g4077.r: Probably from πήγνυμι (G4078) (through the idea of gushing plumply)|English: pitch

g4078.d:
πήγνυμι pḗgnymi, payg'-noo-mee; a prolonged form of a primary verb (which in its simpler form occurs
 only as an alternate in certain tenses); to fix ("peg"), i.e.
 (specially) to set up (a tent):—pitch.
g4078.r: A prolonged form of a primary verb (which in its simpler form occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses)|

g4079.d:
πηδάλιον pēdálion, pay-dal'-ee-on; neuter of a (presumed) derivative of πηδόν pēdón (the blade of an oar; from
 the same as G3976); a "pedal", i.e. helm:—rudder.
g4079.r: From a (presumed) derivative of pedon (the blade of an oar, from the same as πέδη (G3976))|English: fetter

g408.d:
Ἀνδρόνικος Andrónikos, an-dron'-ee-kos; from G435 and G3534; man of victory; Andronicos, an
 Israelite:—Adronicus.
g408.r: From ἀνήρ (G435) and νῖκος (G3534)|English: man, husband, sir, fellow, not tr

g4080.d:
πηλίκος pēlíkos, pay-lee'-kos; a quantitative form (the feminine) of the base of G4225; how much (as
 an indefinite), i.e. in size or (figuratively) dignity:—how great
 (large).
g4080.r: A quantitative form (the feminine) of the base of πού (G4225)|English: a certain place, about

g4081.d: πηλός pēlós, pay-los'; perhaps a primary word; clay:—clay.

g4082.d: πήρα pḗra, pay'-rah; of uncertain affinity; a wallet or leather pouch for food:—scrip.

g4083.d:
πῆχυς pēchys, pay'-khoos; of uncertain affinity; the fore-arm, i.e. (as a measure) a
 cubit:—cubit.

g4084.d:
πιάζω piázō, pee-ad'-zo; probably another form of G971; to squeeze, i.e. seize (gently by the
 hand (press), or officially (arrest), or in hunting
 (capture)):—apprehend, catch, lay hand on, take. Compare G4085.
g4084.r: Probably another form of βιάζω (G971)|English: suffer violence, press

g4085.d: πιέζω piézō, pee-ed'-zo; another form for G4084; to pack:—press down.
g4085.r: Another form for πιάζω (G4084)|English: take, catch, apprehend, lay hand on

g4086.d:
πιθανολογία pithanología, pith-an-ol-og-ee'-ah; from a compound of a derivative of G3982 and G3056; persuasive
 language:—enticing words.
g4086.r: From a compound of a derivative of πείθω (G3982) and λόγος (G3056)|English: persuade, trust, obey, have confidence, believe, be confident, misc

g4087.d: πικραίνω pikraínō, pik-rah'-ee-no; from G4089; to embitter (literally or figuratively):—be (make) bitter.

g4088.d:
πικρία pikría, pik-ree'-ah; from G4089; acridity (especially poison), literally or
 figuratively:—bitterness.

g4089.d:
πικρός pikrós, pik-ros'; perhaps from G4078 (through the idea of piercing); sharp (pungent),
 i.e. acrid (literally or figuratively):—bitter.
g4089.r: Perhaps from πήγνυμι (G4078) (through the idea of piercing)|English: pitch

g409.d: ἀνδροφόνος androphónos, an-drof-on'-os; from G435 and G5408; a murderer:—manslayer.
g409.r: From ἀνήρ (G435) and φόνος (G5408)|English: man, husband, sir, fellow, not tr

g4090.d: πικρῶς pikrōs, pik-roce'; adverb from G4089; bitterly, i.e. (figuratively) violently:—bitterly.

g4091.d: Πιλᾶτος Pilâtos, pil-at'-os; of Latin origin; close-pressed, i.e. firm; Pilatus, a Roman:—Pilate.

g4092.d:
πίμπρημι pímprēmi, pim'-pray-mee; a reduplicated and prolonged form of a
 primary πρέω préō preh'-o; which occurs only as an alternate in certain
 tenses); to fire, i.e. burn (figuratively and passively, become
 inflamed with fever):—be (X should have) swollen.
g4092.r: A reduplicated and prolonged form of a primary preo {preh'-o}; which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses)|

g4093.d: πινακίδιον pinakídion, pin-ak-id'-ee-on; diminutive of G4094; a tablet (for writing on):—writing table.

g4094.d: πίναξ pínax, pin'-ax; apparently a form of G4109; a plate:—charger, platter.
g4094.r: Apparently a form of πλάξ (G4109)|English: table

g4095.d:
πίνω pínō, pee'-no; a prolonged form of
    πίω píō  pee'-o; which (together with another form)
    πόω póō  po'-o; occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses; 

 to imbibe (literally or figuratively):—drink.
g4095.r: A prolonged form of pio {pee'-o}; which (together with another form poo {po'-o}, occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses|

g4096.d:
πιότης piótēs, pee-ot'-ace; from πίων píōn (fat; perhaps akin to the alternate of G4095 through the idea
 of repletion);

 plumpness, i.e. (by implication) richness
 (oiliness):—fatness.
g4096.r: From pion (fat, perhaps akin to the alternate of πίνω (G4095) through the idea of repletion)|English: drink, drink of

g4097.d:
πιπράσκω pipráskō, pip-ras'-ko; contracted from περάω peráō (to traverse; from the base of G4008); to traffic
 (by travelling), i.e. dispose of as merchandise or into slavery
 (literally or figuratively):—sell.
g4097.r: A reduplicated and prolonged form of prao {prah'-o}, (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses), contracted from perao (to traverse, from the base of πέραν (G4008))|English: other side, beyond, over, on the other side, farther side

g4098.d:
†πίπτω píptō, pip'-to; probably akin to G4072 through the idea of alighting; to fall
 (literally or figuratively):—fail, fall (down), light on.
g4098.r: A reduplicated and contracted form of peto {pet'-o}, (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses), probably akin to πέτομαι (G4072) through the idea of alighting|English: fly, flying

g4099.d: Πισιδία Pisidía, pis-id-ee'-ah; probably of foreign origin; Pisidia, a region of Asia Minor:—Pisidia.

g41.d: ἁγιότης hagiótēs, hag-ee-ot'-ace; from G40; sanctity (i.e. properly, the state):—holiness.
g41.r: From ἅγιος (G40)|English: holy, saints, Holy One, misc

g410.d:
ἀνέγκλητος anénklētos, an-eng'-klay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G1458; unaccused,
 i.e. (by implication) irreproachable:—blameless.
g410.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of ἐγκαλέω (G1458)|English: Alpha

g4100.d:
πιστεύω pisteúō, pist-yoo'-o; from G4102; to have faith (in, upon, or with respect to, a person or
 thing), i.e. credit; by implication, to entrust (especially one's
 spiritual well-being to Christ):—believe(-r), commit (to trust), put
 in trust with.
g4100.r: From πίστις (G4102)|English: faith, assurance, believe, belief, them that believe, fidelity

g4101.d: πιστικός pistikós, pis-tik-os'; from G4102; trustworthy, i.e. genuine (unadulterated):—spike-(nard).
g4101.r: From πίστις (G4102)|English: faith, assurance, believe, belief, them that believe, fidelity

g4102.d:
πίστις pístis, pis'-tis; from G3982; persuasion, i.e. credence; moral conviction (of religious
 truth, or the truthfulness of God or a religious teacher), especially
 reliance upon Christ for salvation; abstractly, constancy in such
 profession; by extension, the system of religious (Gospel) truth
 itself:—assurance, belief, believe, faith, fidelity.
g4102.r: From πείθω (G3982)|English: persuade, trust, obey, have confidence, believe, be confident, misc

g4103.d:
πιστός pistós, pis-tos'; from G3982; objectively, trustworthy; subjectively,
 trustful:—believe(-ing, -r), faithful(-ly), sure, true.
g4103.r: From πείθω (G3982)|English: persuade, trust, obey, have confidence, believe, be confident, misc

g4104.d: πιστόω pistóō, pis-to'-o; from G4103; to assure:—assure of.
g4104.r: From πιστός (G4103)|English: faithful, believe, believing, true, faithfully, believer, sure not tr

g4105.d:
πλανάω planáō, plan-ah'-o; from G4106; to (properly, cause to) roam (from safety, truth, or
 virtue):—go astray, deceive, err, seduce, wander, be out of the way.
g4105.r: From πλάνη (G4106)|English: error, to deceive, deceit, delusion

g4107.d:
πλανήτης planḗtēs, plan-ay'-tace; from G4108; a rover ("planet"), i.e. (figuratively) an erratic
 teacher:—wandering.

g4108.d:
πλάνος plános, plan'-os; of uncertain affinity; roving (as a tramp), i.e. (by implication) an
 impostor or misleader; --deceiver, seducing.

g4109.d:
πλάξ pláx, plax; from G4111; a moulding-board, i.e. flat surface ("plate", or tablet,
 literally or figuratively):—table.

g411.d:
ἀνεκδιήγητος anekdiḗgētos, an-ek-dee-ay'-gay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G1555; not
 expounded in full, i.e. indescribable:—unspeakable.
g411.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ἐκδιηγέομαι (G1555)|English: Alpha

g4110.d: πλάσμα plásma, plas'-mah; from G4111; something moulded:—thing formed.

g4111.d: πλάσσω plássō, plas'-so; a primary verb; to mould, i.e. shape or fabricate:—form.

g4112.d:
πλαστός plastós, plas-tos'; from G4111; moulded, i.e. (by implication) artificial or (figuratively)
 fictitious (false):—feigned.

g4113.d: πλατεῖα plateîa, plat-i'-ah; feminine of G4116; a wide "plat" or "place", i.e. open square:—street.

g4114.d: πλάτος plátos, plat'-os; from G4116; width:—breadth.

g4115.d: πλατύνω platýnō, plat-oo'-no; from G4116; to widen (literally or figuratively):—make broad, enlarge.

g4116.d: πλατύς platýs, plat-oos'; from G4111; spread out "flat" ("plot"), i.e. broad:—wide.

g4117.d: πλέγμα plégma, pleg'-mah; from G4120; a plait (of hair):—broidered hair.

g4119.d:
πλείων pleíōn, pli-own; comparative of G4183; more in quantity, number, or quality; also (in
 plural) the major portion:—X above, + exceed, more excellent,
 further, (very) great(-er), long(-er), (very) many, greater (more)
 part, + yet but.
g4119.r: Comparative of πολύς (G4183)|English: many, much, great, misc

g412.d:
ἀνεκλάλητος aneklálētos, an-ek-lal'-ay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G1583; not
 spoken out, i.e. (by implication) unutterable:—unspeakable.
g412.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ἐκλαλέω (G1583)|English: Alpha

g4120.d: πλέκω plékō, plek'-o; a primary word; to twine or braid:—plait.

g4121.d:
πλεονάζω pleonázō, pleh-on-ad'-zo; from G4119; to do, make or be more, i.e. increase (transitively or
 intransitively); by extension, to superabound:—abound, abundant, make
 to increase, have over.
g4121.r: From πλείων (G4119)|English: more, many, greater, further, most, more part, not tr, misc

g4122.d:
πλεονεκτέω pleonektéō, pleh-on-cek-teh'-o; from G4123; to be covetous, i.e. (by implication) to over-reach:—get
 an advantage, defraud, make a gain.

g4123.d:
πλεονέκτης pleonéktēs, pleh-on-ek'-tace; from G4119 and G2192; holding (desiring) more, i.e. eager for gain
 (avaricious, hence a defrauder):—covetous.
g4123.r: From πλείων (G4119) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: more, many, greater, further, most, more part, not tr, misc

g4124.d:
πλεονεξία pleonexía, pleh-on-ex-ee'-ah; from G4123; avarice, i.e. (by implication) fraudulency,
 extortion:—covetous(-ness) practices, greediness.

g4125.d: πλευρά pleurá, plyoo-rah'; of uncertain affinity; a rib, i.e. (by extension) side:—side.

g4126.d:
πλέω pléō, pleh'-o; probably a form of G4150 (through the idea of plunging through the
 water); to pass in a vessel:—sail. See also G4130.
g4126.r: Another form for pleuo {plyoo'-o}, which is used as an alternate in certain tenses, probably a form of πλύνω (G4150) (through the idea of plunging through the water)|English: wash

g4127.d:
πληγή plēgḗ, play-gay'; from G4141; a stroke; by implication, a wound; figuratively, a
 calamity:—plague, stripe, wound(-ed).

g4128.d:
πλῆθος plēthos, play'-thos; from G4130; a fulness, i.e. a large number, throng, populace:—bundle,
 company, multitude.
g4128.r: From πίμπλημι (G4130)|English: fill, accomplish, furnish, full ... come

g4129.d:
πληθύνω plēthýnō, play-thoo'-no; from another form of G4128; to increase (transitively or
 intransitively):—abound, multiply.
g4129.r: From another form of πλῆθος (G4128)|English: multitude, company, bundle

g413.d:
ἀνέκλειπτος anékleiptos, an-ek'-lipe-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G1587; not
 left out, i.e. (by implication) inexhaustible:—that faileth not.
g413.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ἐκλείπω (G1587)|English: Alpha

g4131.d: πλήκτης plḗktēs, plake'-tace; from G4141; a smiter, i.e. pugnacious (quarrelsome):—striker.

g4132.d: πλήμμυρα plḗmmyra, plame-moo'-rah; prolonged from G4130; flood-tide, i.e. (by analogy) a freshet:—flood.
g4132.r: Prolonged from πίμπλημι (G4130)|English: fill, accomplish, furnish, full ... come

g4133.d:
πλήν plḗn, plane; from G4119; moreover (besides), i.e. albeit, save that, rather,
 yet:—but (rather), except, nevertheless, notwithstanding, save, than.
g4133.r: From πλείων (G4119)|English: more, many, greater, further, most, more part, not tr, misc

g4134.d: πλήρης plḗrēs, play'-race; from G4130; replete, or covered over; by analogy, complete:—full.
g4134.r: From πίμπλημι (G4130)|English: fill, accomplish, furnish, full ... come

g4135.d:
πληροφορέω plērophoréō, play-rof-or-eh'-o; from G4134 and G5409; to carry out fully (in evidence), i.e. completely
 assure (or convince), entirely accomplish:—most surely believe, fully
 know (persuade), make full proof of.

g4136.d: πληροφορία plērophoría, play-rof-or-ee'-ah; from G4135; entire confidence:—(full) assurance.
g4136.r: From πληροφορέω (G4135)|English: be fully persuaded, be most surely believed, be fully known, make full proof of

g4137.d:
πληρόω plēróō, play-ro'-o; from G4134; to make replete, i.e. (literally) to cram (a net), level up
 (a hollow), or (figuratively) to furnish (or imbue, diffuse,
 influence), satisfy, execute (an office), finish (a period or task),
 verify (or coincide with a prediction), etc.:—accomplish, × after,
 (be) complete, end, expire, fill (up), fulfil, (be, make) full (come),
 fully preach, perfect, supply.

g4138.d:
πλήρωμα plḗrōma, play'-ro-mah; from G4137; repletion or completion, i.e. (subjectively) what fills (as
 contents, supplement, copiousness, multitude), or (objectively) what
 is filled (as container, performance, period):—which is put in to
 fill up, piece that filled up, fulfilling, full, fulness.
g4138.r: From πληρόω (G4137)|English: fulfil, fill, be full, complete, end, misc

g4139.d:
πλησίον plēsíon, play-see'-on; neuter of a derivative of πέλας pélas (near); (adverbially) close by; as
 noun, a neighbor, i.e. fellow (as man, countryman, Christian or
 friend):—near, neighbour.
g4139.r: Neuter of a derivative of pelas (near)|

g414.d: †ἀνεκτότερος anektóteros, an-ek-tot'-er-os; comparative of a derivative of G430; more endurable:—more tolerable.
g414.r: A derivative of ἀνέχω (G430) (found only in the comparative in the NT)|English: suffer, bear with, forbear, endure

g4140.d:
πλησμονή plēsmonḗ, place-mon-ay'; from a presumed derivative of G4130; a filling up, i.e. (figuratively)
 gratification:—satisfying.
g4140.r: From a presumed derivative of πίμπλημι (G4130)|English: fill, accomplish, furnish, full ... come

g4141.r: Apparently another form of πλάσσω (G4111) (through the idea of flattening out)|English: form

g4142.d:
πλοιάριον ploiárion, ploy-ar'-ee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G4143; a boat:—boat, little (small)
 ship.
g4142.r: From a presumed derivative of πλοῖον (G4143)|English: ship, shipping

g4143.d: πλοῖον ploîon, ploy'-on; from G4126; a sailer, i.e. vessel:—ship(-ing).

g4144.d: πλόος plóos, plo'-os; from G4126; a sail, i.e. navigation:—course, sailing, voyage.

g4145.d: πλούσιος ploúsios, ploo'-see-os; from G4149; wealthy; figuratively, abounding with:—rich.

g4146.d: πλουσίως plousíōs, ploo-see'-oce; adverb from G4145; copiously:—abundantly, richly.

g4147.d:
πλουτέω ploutéō, ploo-teh'-o; from G4148; to be (or become) wealthy (literally or figuratively):—be
 increased with goods, (be made, wax) rich.

g4148.d: πλουτίζω ploutízō, ploo-tid'-zo; from G4149; to make wealthy (figuratively):—en- (make) rich.

g4149.d:
πλοῦτος ploûtos, ploo'-tos; from the base of G4130; wealth (as fulness), i.e. (literally) money,
 possessions, or (figuratively) abundance, richness, (specially),
 valuable bestowment:—riches.
g4149.r: From the base of πίμπλημι (G4130)|English: fill, accomplish, furnish, full ... come

g415.d: ἀνελεήμων aneleḗmōn, an-eleh-ay'-mone; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G1655; merciless:—unmerciful.
g415.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and ἐλεήμων (G1655)|English: Alpha

g4150.d:
πλύνω plýnō, ploo'-no; a prolonged form of an obsolete πλύω plýō (to "flow"); to "plunge", i.e.
 launder clothing:—wash. Compare G3068, G3538.
g4150.r: A prolonged form of an obsolete pluo (to "flow")|

g4151.d:
πνεῦμα pneûma, pnyoo'-mah; from G4154; a current of air, i.e. breath (blast) or a breeze; by
 analogy or figuratively, a spirit, i.e. (human) the rational soul, (by
 implication) vital principle, mental disposition, etc., or
 (superhuman) an angel, demon, or (divine) God, Christ's spirit, the
 Holy Spirit:—ghost, life, spirit(-ual, -ually), mind. Compare G5590.

g4152.d:
πνευματικός pneumatikós, pnyoo-mat-ik-os'; from G4151; non-carnal, i.e. (humanly) ethereal (as opposed to gross),
 or (dæmoniacally) a spirit (concretely), or (divinely) supernatural,
 regenerate, religious:—spiritual. Compare G5591.
g4152.r: From πνεῦμα (G4151)|English: Spirit, Holy Ghost, Spirit (of God), Spirit (of the Lord), (My) Spirit, Spirit (of truth), Spirit (of Christ), human (spirit), (evil) spirit, spirit (general), spirit, (Jesus' own) spirit, (Jesus' own) ghost

g4153.d:
πνευματικῶς pneumatikōs, pnyoo-mat-ik-oce'; adverb from G4152; non-physically, i.e. divinely,
 figuratively:—spiritually.

g4154.d: πνέω pnéō, pneh'-o; a primary word; to breathe hard, i.e. breeze:—blow. Compare G5594.

g4155.d:
πνίγω pnígō, pnee'-go; strengthened from G4154; to wheeze, i.e. (causative, by implication) to
 throttle or strangle (drown):—choke, take by the throat.

g4156.d:
πνικτός pniktós, pnik-tos'; from G4155; throttled, i.e. (neuter concretely) an animal choked to
 death (not bled):—strangled.
g4156.r: From πνίγω (G4155)|English: take by the throat, choke

g4157.d: πνοή pnoḗ, pno-ay'; from G4154; respiration, a breeze:—breath, wind.

g4158.d:
ποδήρης podḗrēs, pod-ay'-race; from G4228 and another element of uncertain affinity; a dress (G2066
 implied) reaching the ankles:—garment down to the foot.
g4158.r: From πούς (G4228) and another element of uncertain affinity|English: foot, footstool

g4159.d:
πόθεν póthen, poth'-en; from the base of G4213 with enclitic adverb of origin; from which (as
 interrogative) or what (as relative) place, state, source or
 cause:—whence.
g4159.r: From the base of πόσις (G4213) with enclitic adverb of origin|English: drink

g416.d: ἀνεμίζω anemízō, an-em-id'-zo; from G417; to toss with the wind:—drive with the wind.

g4160.d:
ποιέω poiéō, poy-eh'-o; apparently a prolonged form of an obsolete primary; to make or do (in
 a very wide application, more or less direct):—abide, + agree,
 appoint, × avenge, + band together, be, bear, + bewray, bring (forth),
 cast out, cause, commit, + content, continue, deal, + without any
 delay, (would) do(-ing), execute, exercise, fulfil, gain, give, have,
 hold, × journeying, keep, + lay wait, + lighten the ship, make, X
 mean, + none of these things move me, observe, ordain, perform,
 provide, + have purged, purpose, put, + raising up, × secure, shew, X
 shoot out, spend, take, tarry, + transgress the law, work, yield. 
 Compare G4238.
g4160.r: Apparently a prolonged form of an obsolete primary|

g4161.d:
ποίημα poíēma, poy'-ay-mah; from G4160; a product, i.e. fabric (literally or figuratively):—thing
 that is made, workmanship.
g4161.r: From ποιέω (G4160)|English: do, make, bring forth, commit, cause, work, show, bear, keep, fulfil, deal, perform, not tr, misc

g4162.d: ποίησις poíēsis, poy'-ay-sis; from G4160; action, i.e. performance (of the law):—deed.
g4162.r: From ποιέω (G4160)|English: do, make, bring forth, commit, cause, work, show, bear, keep, fulfil, deal, perform, not tr, misc

g4163.d: ποιητής poiētḗs, poy-ay-tace'; from G4160; a performer; specially, a "poet"; --doer, poet.
g4163.r: From ποιέω (G4160)|English: do, make, bring forth, commit, cause, work, show, bear, keep, fulfil, deal, perform, not tr, misc

g4164.d:
ποικίλος poikílos, poy-kee'-los; of uncertain derivation; motley, i.e. various in character:—divers,
 manifold.

g4165.d:
ποιμαίνω poimaínō, poy-mah'-ee-no; from G4166; to tend as a shepherd of (figuratively, superviser):—feed
 (cattle), rule.

g4166.d:
ποιμήν poimḗn, poy-mane'; of uncertain affinity; a shepherd (literally or
 figuratively):—shepherd, pastor.

g4167.d:
ποίμνη poímnē, poym'-nay; contraction from G4165; a flock (literally or figuratively):—flock,
 fold.
g4167.r: Contraction from ποιμαίνω (G4165)|English: feed, rule, feed cattle

g4168.d:
ποίμνιον poímnion, poym'-nee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G4167; a flock, i.e. (figuratively)
 group (of believers):—flock.
g4168.r: Neuter of a presumed derivative of ποίμνη (G4167)|English: flock, fold

g4169.d:
ποῖος poîos, poy'-os; from the base of G4226 and G3634; individualizing interrogative (of
 character) what sort of, or (of number) which one:—what (manner of),
 which.
g4169.r: From the base of ποῦ (G4226) and οἷος (G3634)|English: where, whither

g417.d:
ἄνεμος ánemos, an'-em-os; from the base of G109; wind; (plural) by implication, (the four)
 quarters (of the earth):—wind.
g417.r: From the base of ἀήρ (G109)|English: air

g4170.d:
πολεμέω poleméō, pol-em-eh'-o; from G4171; to be (engaged) in warfare, i.e. to battle (literally or
 figuratively):—fight, (make) war.

g4171.d:
πόλεμος pólemos, pol'-em-os; from πέλομαι pélomai (to bustle); warfare (literally or figuratively; a single
 encounter or a series):—battle, fight, war.

g4172.d:
πόλις pólis, pol'-is; probably from the same as G4171, or perhaps from G4183; a town
 (properly, with walls, of greater or less size):—city.
g4172.r: Probably from the same as πόλεμος (G4171), or perhaps from πολύς (G4183)|English: war, battle, fight

g4173.d:
πολιτάρχης politárchēs, pol-it-ar'-khace; from G4172 and G757; a town-officer, i.e. magistrate:—ruler of the
 city.

g4174.d:
πολιτεία politeía, pol-ee-ti'-ah; from G4177 ("polity"); citizenship; concretely, a
 community:—commonwealth, freedom.

g4175.d:
πολίτευμα políteuma, pol-it'-yoo-mah; from G4176; a community, i.e. (abstractly) citizenship
 (figuratively):—conversation.
g4175.r: From πολιτεύομαι (G4176)|English: live, let (one's) conversation be

g4176.d:
†πολιτεύομαι politeúomai, pol-it-yoo'-om-ahee; middle voice of a derivative of G4177; to behave as a citizen
 (figuratively):—let conversation be, live.
g4176.r: Middle voice of a derivative of πολίτης (G4177)|English: citizen

g4177.d: πολίτης polítēs, pol-ee'-tace; from G4172; a townsman:—citizen.

g4178.d:
πολλάκις pollákis, pol-lak'-is; multiplicative adverb from G4183; many times, i.e.
 frequently:—oft(-en, -entimes, -times).
g4178.r: Multiplicative adverb from πολύς (G4183)|English: many, much, great, misc

g4179.d:
πολλαπλασίων pollaplasíōn, pol-lap-las-ee'-ohn; from G4183 and probably a derivative of G4120; manifold, i.e. (neuter as
 noun) very much more:—manifold more.
g4179.r: From πολύς (G4183) and probably a derivative of πλέκω (G4120)|English: many, much, great, misc

g418.d:
ἀνένδεκτος anéndektos, an-en'-dek-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of the same as G1735; 
 unadmitted, i.e. (by implication) not supposable:—impossible.
g418.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of the same as ἐνδέχομαι (G1735)|English: Alpha

g4180.d:
πολυλογία polylogía, pol-oo-log-ee'-ah; from a compound of G4183 and G3056; loquacity, i.e. prolixity:—much
 speaking.
g4180.r: From a compound of πολύς (G4183) and λόγος (G3056)|English: many, much, great, misc

g4181.d:
πολυμερῶς polymerōs, pol-oo-mer'-oce; adverb from a compound of G4183 and G3313; in many portions, i.e.
 variously as to time and agency (piecemeal):—at sundry times.
g4181.r: From a compound of πολύς (G4183) and μέρος (G3313)|English: many, much, great, misc

g4182.d: πολυποίκιλος polypoíkilos, pol-oo-poy'-kil-os; from G4183 and G4164; much variegated, i.e. multifarious:—manifold.
g4182.r: From πολύς (G4183) and ποικίλος (G4164)|English: many, much, great, misc

g4183.d:
πολύς polýs, pol-oos'; including the forms from the alternate πολλός pollós; (singular) much (in any
 respect) or (plural) many; neuter (singular) as adverbial, largely;
 neuter (plural) as adverb or noun often, mostly, largely:—abundant, +
 altogether, common, + far (passed, spent), (+ be of a) great (age,
 deal, -ly, while), long, many, much, oft(-en (-times)), plenteous,
 sore, straitly. Compare G4118, G4119.
g4183.r: Including the forms from the alternate pollos|

g4184.d:
πολύσπλαγχνος polýsplanchnos, pol-oo'-splankh-nos; from G4183 and G4698 (figuratively); extremely compassionate:—very
 pitiful.
g4184.r: From πολύς (G4183) and σπλάγχνον (G4698) (figuratively)|English: many, much, great, misc

g4185.d:
πολυτελής polytelḗs, pol-oo-tel-ace'; from G4183 and G5056; extremely expensive:—costly, very precious, of
 great price.
g4185.r: From πολύς (G4183) and τέλος (G5056)|English: many, much, great, misc

g4186.d: πολύτιμος polýtimos, pol-oot'-ee-mos; from G4183 and G5092; extremely valuable:—very costly, of great price.
g4186.r: From πολύς (G4183) and τιμή (G5092)|English: many, much, great, misc

g4187.d:
πολυτρόπως polytrópōs, pol-oot-rop'-oce; adverb from a compound of G4183 and G5158; in many ways, i.e. variously
 as to method or form:—in divers manners.
g4187.r: From a compound of πολύς (G4183) and τρόπος (G5158)|English: many, much, great, misc

g4188.d: πόμα póma, pom'-ah; from the alternate of G4095; a beverage:—drink.
g4188.r: From the alternate of πίνω (G4095)|English: drink, drink of

g4189.d:
πονηρία ponēría, pon-ay-ree'-ah; from G4190; depravity, i.e. (specially), malice; plural (concretely)
 plots, sins:—iniquity, wickedness.
g4189.r: From πονηρός (G4190)|English: evil, wicked, wicked one, evil things, misc

g419.d:
†ἀνεξερεύνητος anexereúnētos, an-ex-er-yoo'-nay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G1830; not
 searched out, i.e. (by implication) inscrutable:—unsearchable.
g419.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ἐξεραυνάω (G1830)|English: Alpha

g4190.d:
πονηρός ponērós, pon-ay-ros'; from a derivative of G4192; hurtful, i.e. evil (properly, in effect or
 influence, and thus differing from G2556, which refers rather to
 essential character, as well as from G4550, which indicates degeneracy
 from original virtue); figuratively, calamitous; also (passively) ill,
 i.e. diseased; but especially (morally) culpable, i.e. derelict,
 vicious, facinorous; neuter (singular) mischief, malice, or (plural)
 guilt; masculine (singular) the devil, or (plural) sinners:—bad,
 evil, grievous, harm, lewd, malicious, wicked(-ness). See also G4191.
g4190.r: From a derivative of πόνος (G4192)|English: pain

g4192.d: πόνος pónos, pon'-os; from the base of G3993; toil, i.e. (by implication) anguish:—pain.
g4192.r: From the base of πένης (G3993)|English: poor

g4193.d: Ποντικός Pontikós, pon-tik-os'; from G4195; a Pontican, i.e. native of Pontus:—born in Pontus.

g4194.d: Πόντιος Póntios, pon'-tee-os; of Latin origin; apparently bridged; Pontius, a Roman:—Pontius.

g4195.d:
Πόντος Póntos, pon'-tos; of Latin origin; 

 a sea; Pontus, a region of Asia Minor:—Pontus.

g4196.d:
Πόπλιος Póplios, pop'-lee-os; of Latin origin; apparently "popular"; Poplius (i.e. Publius), a
 Roman:—Publius.

g4197.d:
πορεία poreía, por-i'-ah; from G4198; travel (by land); figuratively (plural) proceedings, i.e.
 career:—journey(-ing), ways.
g4197.r: From πορεύω (G4198)|English: go, depart, walk, go (one's) way, misc

g4198.d:
πορεύομαι poreúomai, por-yoo'-om-ahee; middle voice from a derivative of the same as G3984; to traverse, i.e.
 travel (literally or figuratively; especially to remove (figuratively,
 die), live, etc.); --depart, go (away, forth, one's way, up), (make a,
 take a) journey, walk.
g4198.r: Only middle and passive voices used in the NT; from a derivative of the same as πεῖρα (G3984)|English: assay, trial

g4199.d:
πορθέω porthéō, por-theh'-o; prolongation from πέρθω pérthō (to sack); to ravage
 (figuratively):—destroy, waste.

g42.d: ἁγιωσύνη hagiōsýnē, hag-ee-o-soo'-nay; from G40; sacredness (i.e. properly, the quality):—holiness.
g42.r: From ἅγιος (G40)|English: holy, saints, Holy One, misc

g420.d: ἀνεξίκακος anexíkakos, an-ex-ik'-ak-os; from G430 and G2556; enduring of ill, i.e. forbearing:—patient.
g420.r: From ἀνέχω (G430) and κακός (G2556)|English: suffer, bear with, forbear, endure

g4200.d:
πορισμός porismós, por-is-mos'; from a derivative of πόρος póros (a way, i.e. means); furnishing
 (procuring), i.e. (by implication) money-getting (acquisition):—gain.
g4200.r: From a derivative of poros (a way, i.e. means)|

g4201.d: Πόρκιος Pórkios, por'-kee-os; of Latin origin; apparently swinish; Porcius, a Roman:—Porcius.

g4202.d:
πορνεία porneía, por-ni'-ah; from G4203; harlotry (including adultery and incest); figuratively,
 idolatry:—fornication.

g4203.d:
πορνεύω porneúō, porn-yoo'-o; from G4204; to act the harlot, i.e. (literally) indulge unlawful lust
 (of either sex), or (figuratively) practise idolatry:—commit
 (fornication).

g4204.d:
πόρνη pórnē, por'-nay; feminine of G4205; a strumpet; figuratively, an idolater:—harlot,
 whore.

g4205.d:
πόρνος pórnos, por'-nos; from πέρνημι pérnēmi (to sell; akin to the base of G4097); a (male) prostitute
 (as venal), i.e. (by analogy) a debauchee (libertine):—fornicator,
 whoremonger.
g4205.r: From pernemi (to sell, akin to the base of πιπράσκω (G4097))|English: sell

g4206.d:
πόῤῥω pórrhō, por'-rho; adverb from G4253; forwards, i.e. at a distance:—far, a great way off. 
 See also G4207.
g4206.r: From πρό (G4253)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4207.d:
πόῤῥωθεν pórrhōthen, por'-rho-then; from G4206 with adverbial enclitic of source; from far, or (by
 implication) at a distance, i.e. distantly:—afar off.
g4207.r: From πόρρω (G4206) with adverbial enclitic of source|English: far, a great way off

g4208.d:
†ποῤῥωτέρω porrhōtérō, por-rho-ter'-o; adverb comparative of G4206; further, i.e. a greater
 distance:—farther.
g4208.r: Comparative of πόρρω (G4206)|English: far, a great way off

g4209.d:
πορφύρα porphýra, por-foo'-rah; of Latin origin; the "purple" mussel, i.e. (by implication) the
 red-blue color itself, and finally a garment dyed with it:—purple.

g421.d:
ἀνεξιχνίαστος anexichníastos, an-ex-ikh-nee'-as-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a
 compound of G1537 and a derivative of G2487; not tracked out, i.e. (by
 implication) untraceable:—past finding out; unsearchable.
g421.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a compound of ἐκ (G1537) and a derivative of ἴχνος (G2487)|English: Alpha

g4210.d: †πορφυροῦς porphyroûs, por-foo-rooce'; from G4209; purpureal, i.e. bluish red:—purple.

g4211.d:
πορφυρόπωλις porphyrópōlis, por-foo-rop'-o-lis; feminine of a compound of G4209 and G4453; a female trader in purple
 cloth:—seller of purple.
g4211.r: From a compound of πορφύρα (G4209) and πωλέω (G4453)|English: purple

g4212.d: ποσάκις posákis, pos-ak'-is; multiplicative from G4214; how many times:—how oft(-en).
g4212.r: Multiplicative from πόσος (G4214)|English: how much, how many, how many things, what, how long, how great

g4213.d:
πόσις pósis, pos'-is; from the alternate of G4095; a drinking (the act), i.e. (concretely) a
 draught:—drink.
g4213.r: From the alternate of πίνω (G4095)|English: drink, drink of

g4214.d:
πόσος pósos, pos'-os; from an absolute πός pós (who, what) and G3739; interrogative pronoun (of
 amount) how much (large, long or (plural) many):—how great (long,
 many), what.
g4214.r: From an absolute pos (who, what) and ὅς (G3739)|English: which, whom, that, who, whose, what, that which, whereof, misc

g4215.d:
ποταμός potamós, pot-am-os'; probably from a derivative of the alternate of G4095 (compare G4224); a
 current, brook or freshet (as drinkable), i.e. running water:—flood,
 river, stream, water.
g4215.r: Probably from a derivative of the alternate of πίνω (G4095) (cf πότος (G4224))|English: drink, drink of

g4216.d:
ποταμοφόρητος potamophórētos, pot-am-of-or'-ay-tos; from G4215 and a derivative of G5409; river-borne, i.e. overwhelmed by a
 stream:—carried away of the flood.
g4216.r: From ποταμός (G4215) and a derivative of φορέω (G5409)|English: river, flood, stream, water

g4217.d:
ποταπός potapós, pot-ap-os'; apparently from G4219 and the base of G4226; interrogatively, whatever,
 i.e. of what possible sort:—what (manner of).
g4217.r: Apparently from πότε (G4219) and the base of ποῦ (G4226)|English: when, how long

g4218.d:
ποτέ poté, pot-eh'; from the base of G4225 and G5037; indefinite adverb, at some time,
 ever:—afore-(any, some-)time(-s), at length (the last), (+ n- )ever,
 in the old time, in time past, once, when.
g4218.r: From the base of πού (G4225) and τέ (G5037)|English: a certain place, about

g4219.d:
πότε póte, pot'-eh; from the base of G4226 and G5037; interrogative adverb, at what time:—+
 how long, when.
g4219.r: From the base of ποῦ (G4226) and τέ (G5037)|English: where, whither

g422.d:
ἀνεπαίσχυντος anepaíschyntos, an-ep-ah'-ee-skhoon-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a
 compound of G1909 and G153; not ashamed, i.e. irreprehensible: --that
 needeth not to be ashamed.
g422.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a compound of ἐπί (G1909) and αἰσχύνω (G153)|English: Alpha

g4220.d:
†πότερον póteron, pot'-er-on; neuter of a comparative of the base of G4226; interrogative as adverb,
 which (of two), i.e. is it this or that:—whether.
g4220.r: Neuter of a comparative of the base of ποῦ (G4226)|English: where, whither

g4221.r: Of a derivative of the alternate of πίνω (G4095)|English: drink, drink of

g4222.d:
ποτίζω potízō, pot-id'-zo; from a derivative of the alternate of G4095; to furnish drink,
 irrigate:—give (make) to drink, feed, water.
g4222.r: From a derivative of the alternate of πίνω (G4095)|English: drink, drink of

g4223.d:
Ποτίολοι Potíoloi, pot-ee'-ol-oy; of Latin origin; little wells, i.e. mineral springs; Potioli (i.e.
 Puteoli), a place in Italy:—Puteoli.

g4224.d: πότος pótos, pot'-os; from the alternate of G4095; a drinking-bout or carousal:—banqueting.
g4224.r: From the alternate of πίνω (G4095)|English: drink, drink of

g4225.d:
†πού poú, poo; genitive case of an indefinite pronoun πός pós (some) otherwise obsolete
 (compare G4214); as adverb of place, somewhere, i.e. nearly:—about, a
 certain place.
g4225.r: Genitive case of an indefinite pronoun pos (some) otherwise obsolete (cf πόσος (G4214))|English: how much, how many, how many things, what, how long, how great

g4226.d:
ποῦ poû, poo; genitive case of an interrogative pronoun πός pós (what) otherwise
 obsolete (perhaps the same as G4225 used with the rising slide of
 inquiry); as adverb of place; at (by implication, to) what
 locality:—where, whither.
g4226.r: Genitive case of an interrogative pronoun pos (what) otherwise obsolete (perhaps the same as πού (G4225) used with the rising slide of enquiry)|English: a certain place, about

g4227.d: Πούδης Poúdēs, poo'-dace; of Latin origin; modest; Pudes (i.e. Pudens), a Christian:—Pudens.

g4228.d: πούς poús, pooce; a primary word; a "foot" (figuratively or literally):—foot(-stool).

g4229.d:
πρᾶγμα prâgma, prag'-mah; from G4238; a deed; by implication, an affair; by extension, an object
 (material):—business, matter, thing, work.
g4229.r: From πράσσω (G4238)|English: do, commit, exact, require, deed, keep, use arts

g423.d:
†ἀνεπίληπτος anepílēptos, an-ep-eel'-ape-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G1949; not
 arrested, i.e. (by implication) inculpable:—blameless, unrebukeable.
g423.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of ἐπιλαμβάνομαι (G1949)|English: Alpha

g4230.d: πραγματεία pragmateía, prag-mat-i'-ah; from G4231; a transaction, i.e. negotiation:—affair.

g4231.d: πραγματεύομαι pragmateúomai, prag-mat-yoo'-om-ahee; from G4229; to busy oneself with, i.e. to trade:—occupy.
g4231.r: From πρᾶγμα (G4229)|English: thing, matter, business, work

g4232.d:
πραιτώριον praitṓrion, prahee-to'-ree-on; of Latin origin; the prætorium or governor's courtroom (sometimes
 including the whole edifice and camp):—(common, judgment) hall (of
 judgment), palace, prætorium.

g4233.d:
πράκτωρ práktōr, prak'-tor; from a derivative of G4238; a practiser, i.e. (specially), an official
 collector:—officer.
g4233.r: From a derivative of πράσσω (G4238)|English: do, commit, exact, require, deed, keep, use arts

g4234.d:
πρᾶξις prâxis, prax'-is; from G4238; practice, i.e. (concretely) an act; by extension, a
 function:—deed, office, work.
g4234.r: From πράσσω (G4238)|English: do, commit, exact, require, deed, keep, use arts

g4237.d:
πρασιά prasiá, pras-ee-ah'; perhaps from πράσον práson (a leek, and so an onion-patch); a garden plot,
 i.e. (by implication, of regular beds) a row (repeated in plural by
 Hebraism, to indicate an arrangement):—in ranks.
g4237.r: Perhaps from prason (a leek, and so an onion-patch)|

g4238.d:
πράσσω prássō, pras'-so; a primary verb; to "practise", i.e. perform repeatedly or habitually
 (thus differing from G4160, which properly refers to a single act); by
 implication, to execute, accomplish, etc.; specially, to collect
 (dues), fare (personally):—commit, deeds, do, exact, keep, require,
 use arts.

g4239.d:
πραΰς praÿs, prah-ooce'; apparently a primary word; mild, i.e. (by implication) humble:—meek. 
 See also G4235.

g424.d: ἀνέρχομαι anérchomai, an-erkh'-om-ahee; from G303 and G2064; to ascend:—go up.
g424.r: From ἀνά (G303) and ἔρχομαι (G2064)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g4240.d: πραΰτης praÿtēs, prah-oo'-tace; from G4239; mildness, i.e. (by implication) humility:—meekness.

g4241.d:
†πρέπω prépō, prep'-o; apparently a primary verb; to tower up (be conspicuous), i.e. (by
 implication) to be suitable or proper (third person singular present
 indicative, often used impersonally, it is fit or right):—become,
 comely.

g4242.d:
πρεσβεία presbeía, pres-bi'-ah; from G4243; seniority (eldership), i.e. (by implication) an embassy
 (concretely, ambassadors):—ambassage, message.

g4243.d:
πρεσβεύω presbeúō, pres-byoo'-o; from the base of G4245; to be a senior, i.e. (by implication) act as a
 representative (figuratively, preacher):—be an ambassador.
g4243.r: From the base of πρεσβύτερος (G4245)|English: elder, old man, eldest, elder woman

g4244.d:
πρεσβυτέριον presbytérion, pres-boo-ter'-ee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G4245; the order of elders, i.e.
 (specially), Israelite Sanhedrin or Christian "presbytery":—(estate
 of) elder(-s), presbytery.
g4244.r: From a presumed derivative of πρεσβύτερος (G4245)|English: elder, old man, eldest, elder woman

g4245.d:
πρεσβύτερος presbýteros, pres-boo'-ter-os; comparative of πρέσβυς présbys (elderly); older; as noun, a senior; specially,
 an Israelite Sanhedrist (also figuratively, member of the celestial
 council) or Christian "presbyter":—elder(-est), old.

g4246.d: πρεσβύτης presbýtēs, pres-boo'-tace; from the same as G4245; an old man:—aged (man), old man.
g4246.r: From the same as πρεσβύτερος (G4245)|English: elder, old man, eldest, elder woman

g4247.d: πρεσβῦτις presbŷtis, pres-boo'-tis; feminine of G4246; an old woman:—aged woman.
g4247.r: From πρεσβύτης (G4246)|English: old man, aged man, aged

g4248.d:
πρηνής prēnḗs, pray-nace'; from G4253; leaning (falling) forward ("prone"), i.e. head
 foremost:—headlong.
g4248.r: From πρό (G4253)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4249.d:
πρίζω prízō, prid'-zo; a strengthened form of a primary prio (to saw); to saw in two:—saw
 asunder.
g4249.r: A strengthened form of a primary prio (to saw)|

g425.d: ἄνεσις ánesis, an'-es-is; from G447; relaxation or (figuratively) relief:—eased, liberty, rest.

g4250.d: πρίν prín, prin; adverb from G4253; prior, sooner:—before (that), ere.
g4250.r: From πρό (G4253)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4251.d:
Πρίσκα Príska, pris'-kah; of Latin origin; feminine of Priscus, ancient; Priska, a Christian
 woman:—Prisca. See also G4252.

g4253.d:
πρό pró, pro; a primary preposition; "fore", i.e. in front of, prior (figuratively,
 superior) to:—above, ago, before, or ever.

g4254.d:
προάγω proágō, pro-ag'-o; from G4253 and G71; to lead forward (magisterially); intransitively, to
 precede (in place or time (participle, previous)):—bring (forth,
 out), go before.
g4254.r: From πρό (G4253) and ἄγω (G71)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4255.d:
προαιρέομαι proairéomai, pro-ahee-reh'-om-ahee; from G4253 and G138; to choose for oneself before another thing
 (prefer), i.e. (by implication) to propose (intend):—purpose.
g4255.r: From πρό (G4253) and αἱρέω (G138)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4256.d:
προαιτιάομαι proaitiáomai, pro-ahee-tee-ah'-om-ahee; from G4253 and a derivative of G156; to accuse already, i.e. previously
 charge:—prove before.
g4256.r: From πρό (G4253) and a derivative of αἰτία (G156)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4257.d: προακούω proakoúō, pro-ak-oo'-o; from G4253 and G191; to hear already,i.e. anticipate:—hear before.
g4257.r: From πρό (G4253) and ἀκούω (G191)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4258.d:
προαμαρτάνω proamartánō, pro-am-ar-tan'-o; from G4253 and G264; to sin previously (to conversion):—sin already,
 heretofore sin.
g4258.r: From πρό (G4253) and ἁμαρτάνω (G264)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4259.d:
προαύλιον proaúlion, pro-ow'-lee-on; neuter of a presumed compound of G4253 and G833; a forecourt, i.e.
 vestibule (alley-way):—porch.
g4259.r: From a presumed compound of πρό (G4253) and αὐλή (G833)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g426.d:
ἀνετάζω anetázō, an-et-ad'-zo; from G303 and ἐτάζω etázō (to test); to investigate (judicially):—(should
 have) examined(-d).

g4260.d:
προβαίνω probaínō, prob-ah'-ee-no; from G4253 and the base of G939; to walk forward, i.e. advance

 well stricken.
g4260.r: From πρό (G4253) and the base of βάσις (G939)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4261.d:
προβάλλω probállō, prob-al'-lo; from G4253 and G906; to throw forward, i.e. push to the front,
 germinate:—put forward, shoot forth.

g4262.d:
προβατικός probatikós, prob-at-ik-os'; from G4263; relating to sheep, i.e. (a gate) through which they were
 led into Jerusalem:—sheep (market).

g4263.d:
†πρόβατον próbaton, prob'-at-on; probably neuter of a presumed derivative of G4260; something that walks
 forward (a quadruped), i.e. (specially), a sheep (literally or
 figuratively):—sheep(-fold).

g4264.d:
προβιβάζω probibázō, prob-ib-ad'-zo; from G4253 and a reduplicated form of G971; to force forward, i.e. bring
 to the front, instigate:—draw, before instruct.
g4264.r: From πρό (G4253) and a reduplicated form of βιάζω (G971)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4265.d:
προβλέπω problépō, prob-lep'-o; from G4253 and G991; to look out beforehand, i.e. furnish in
 advance:—provide.
g4265.r: From πρό (G4253) and βλέπω (G991)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4266.d:
προγίνομαι progínomai, prog-in'-om-ahee; from G4253 and G1096; to be already, i.e. have previousy transpired:—be
 past.
g4266.r: From πρό (G4253) and γίνομαι (G1096)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4267.d:
προγινώσκω proginṓskō, prog-in-oce'-ko; from G4253 and G1097; to know beforehand, i.e. foresee:—foreknow
 (ordain), know (before).
g4267.r: From πρό (G4253) and γινώσκω (G1097)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4268.d: πρόγνωσις prógnōsis, prog'-no-sis; from G4267; forethought:—foreknowledge.
g4268.r: From προγινώσκω (G4267)|English: foreknow, foreordain, know, know before

g4269.d: πρόγονος prógonos, prog'-on-os; from G4266; an ancestor, (grand-)parent:—forefather, parent.

g427.d: ἄνευ áneu, an'-yoo; a primary particle; without:—without. Compare G1.

g4270.d:
προγράφω prográphō, prog-raf'-o; from G4253 and G1125; to write previously; figuratively, to announce,
 prescribe:—before ordain, evidently set forth, write (afore,
 aforetime).
g4270.r: From πρό (G4253) and γράφω (G1125)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4271.d:
πρόδηλος pródēlos, prod'-ay-los; from G4253 and G1212; plain before all men, i.e. obvious:—evident,
 manifest (open) beforehand.
g4271.r: From πρό (G4253) and δῆλος (G1212)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4272.d:
προδίδωμι prodídōmi, prod-id'-o-mee; from G4253 and G1325; to give before the other party has given:—first
 give.
g4272.r: From πρό (G4253) and δίδωμι (G1325)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4273.d:
προδότης prodótēs, prod-ot'-ace; from G4272 (in the sense of giving forward into another's (the enemy's)
 hands); a surrender:—betrayer, traitor.

g4274.d:
πρόδρομος pródromos, prod'-rom-os; from the alternate of G4390; a runner ahead, i.e. scout (figuratively,

g4276.d:
προελπίζω proelpízō, pro-el-pid'-zo; from G4253 and G1679; to hope in advance of other confirmation:—first
 trust.
g4276.r: From πρό (G4253) and ἐλπίζω (G1679)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4278.d: προενάρχομαι proenárchomai, pro-en-ar'-khom-ahee; from G4253 and G1728; to commence already:—begin (before).
g4278.r: From πρό (G4253) and ἐνάρχομαι (G1728)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4279.d: προεπαγγέλλομαι proepangéllomai, pro-ep-ang-ghel'-lom-ahee; middle voice from G4253 and G1861; to promise of old:—promise before.
g4279.r: Middle voice from πρό (G4253) and ἐπαγγέλλομαι (G1861)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g428.d:
ἀνεύθετος aneúthetos, an-yoo'-the-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G2111; not well set, i.e.
 inconvenient:—not commodious.
g428.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and εὔθετος (G2111)|English: Alpha

g4281.d:
προέρχομαι proérchomai, pro-er'-khom-ahee; from G4253 and G2064 (including its alternate); to go onward, precede
 (in place or time):—go before (farther, forward), outgo, pass on.
g4281.r: From πρό (G4253) and ἔρχομαι (G2064) (including its alternate)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4282.d:
προετοιμάζω proetoimázō, pro-et-oy-mad'-zo; from G4253 and G2090; to fit up in advance (literally or
 figuratively):—ordain before, prepare afore.
g4282.r: From πρό (G4253) and ἑτοιμάζω (G2090)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4283.d:
προευαγγελίζομαι proeuangelízomai, pro-yoo-ang-ghel-id'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G4253 and G2097; to announce glad news in
 advance:—preach before the gospel.
g4283.r: Middle voice from πρό (G4253) and εὐαγγελίζω (G2097)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4284.d:
†προέχομαι proéchomai, pro-ekh-om-ahee; middle voice from G4253 and G2192; to hold oneself before others, i.e.
 (figuratively) to excel:—be better.
g4284.r: Middle voice from πρό (G4253) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4285.d:
προηγέομαι proēgéomai, pro-ay-geh'-om-ahee; from G4253 and G2233; to lead the way for others, i.e. show
 deference:—prefer.
g4285.r: From πρό (G4253) and ἡγέομαι (G2233)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4287.d:
προθέσμιος prothésmios, proth-es'-mee-os; from G4253 and a derivative of G5087; fixed beforehand, i.e. (feminine
 with G2250 implied) a designated day:—time appointed.
g4287.r: From πρό (G4253) and a derivative of τίθημι (G5087)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

πρόθυμος próthymos, proth'-oo-mos; from G4253 and G2372; forward in spirit, i.e. predisposed; neuter (as

g429.d: ἀνευρίσκω aneurískō, an-yoo-ris'-ko; from G303 and G2147; to find out:—find.
