g4290.d: προθύμως prothýmōs, proth-oo'-moce; adverb from G4289; with alacrity:—willingly.

g4291.d:
προΐστημι proḯstēmi, pro-is'-tay-mee; from G4253 and G2476; to stand before, i.e. (in rank) to preside, or (by
 implication) to practise:—maintain, be over, rule.
g4291.r: From πρό (G4253) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4292.d:
†προκαλέομαι prokaléomai, prok-al-eh'-om-ahee; middle voice from G4253 and G2564; to call forth to oneself (challenge),
 i.e. (by implication) to irritate:—provoke.
g4292.r: Middle voice from πρό (G4253) and καλέω (G2564)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4293.d:
προκαταγγέλλω prokatangéllō, prok-at-ang-ghel'-lo; from G4253 and G2605; to anounce beforehand, i.e. predict,
 promise:—foretell, have notice, (shew) before.
g4293.r: From πρό (G4253) and καταγγέλλω (G2605)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4294.d: προκαταρτίζω prokatartízō, prok-at-ar-tid'-zo; from G4253 and G2675; to prepare in advance:—make up beforehand.
g4294.r: From πρό (G4253) and καταρτίζω (G2675)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4295.d:
πρόκειμαι prókeimai, prok'-i-mahee; from G4253 and G2749; to lie before the view, i.e. (figuratively) to be
 present (to the mind), to stand forth (as an example or reward):—be
 first, set before (forth).
g4295.r: From πρό (G4253) and κεῖμαι (G2749)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4296.d:
προκηρύσσω prokērýssō, prok-ay-rooce'-so; from G4253 and G2784; to herald (i.e. proclaim) in advance:—before
 (first) preach.
g4296.r: From πρό (G4253) and κηρύσσω (G2784)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4297.d:
προκοπή prokopḗ, prok-op-ay'; from G4298; progress, i.e. advancement (subjectively or
 objectively):—furtherance, profit.
g4297.r: From προκόπτω (G4298)|English: increase, be far spent, profit, proceed, wax

g4298.d:
προκόπτω prokóptō, prok-op'-to; from G4253 and G2875; to drive forward (as if by beating), i.e.
 (figuratively and intransitively) to advance (in amount, to grow; in
 time, to be well along):—increase, proceed, profit, be far spent,
 wax.
g4298.r: From πρό (G4253) and κόπτω (G2875)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4299.d:
πρόκριμα prókrima, prok'-ree-mah; from a compound of G4253 and G2919; a prejudgment (prejudice), i.e.
 prepossession:—prefer one before another.
g4299.r: From a compound of πρό (G4253) and κρίνω (G2919)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g43.d: ἀγκάλη ankálē, ang-kal'-ay; from ἄγκος ánkos (a bend, "ache"); an arm (as curved):—arm.

g430.d:
ἀνέχομαι anéchomai, an-ekh'-om-ahee; middle voice from G303 and G2192; to hold oneself up against, i.e.
 (figuratively) put up with:—bear with, endure, forbear, suffer.
g430.r: Middle voice from ἀνά (G303) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g4300.d: προκυρόω prokyróō, prok-oo-ro'-o; from G4253 and G2964; to ratify previously:—confirm before.
g4300.r: From πρό (G4253) and κυρόω (G2964)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4301.d:
προλαμβάνω prolambánō, prol-am-ban'-o; from G4253 and G2983; to take in advance, i.e. (literally) eat before
 others have an opportunity; (figuratively) to anticipate,
 surprise:—come aforehand, overtake, take before.
g4301.r: From πρό (G4253) and λαμβάνω (G2983)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4302.d:
προλέγω prolégō, prol-eg'-o; from G4253 and G3004; to say beforehand, i.e. predict,
 forewarn:—foretell, tell before.
g4302.r: From πρό (G4253) and λέγω (G3004)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4303.d:
προμαρτύρομαι promartýromai, prom-ar-too'-rom-ahee; from G4253 and G3143; to be a witness in advance i.e. predict:—testify
 beforehand.
g4303.r: From πρό (G4253) and μαρτύρομαι (G3143)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4304.d: προμελετάω promeletáō, prom-el-et-ah'-o; from G4253 and G3191; to premeditate:—meditate before.
g4304.r: From πρό (G4253) and μελετάω (G3191)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4305.d:
προμεριμνάω promerimnáō, prom-er-im-nah'-o; from G4253 and G3309; to care (anxiously) in advance:—take thought
 beforehand.
g4305.r: From πρό (G4253) and μεριμνάω (G3309)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4306.d:
προνοέω pronoéō, pron-o-eh'-o; from G4253 and G3539; to consider in advance, i.e. look out for
 beforehand (actively, by way of maintenance for others; middle voice
 by way of circumspection for oneself):—provide (for).
g4306.r: From πρό (G4253) and νοέω (G3539)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4307.d:
πρόνοια prónoia, pron'-oy-ah; from G4306; forethought, i.e. provident care or supply:—providence,
 provision.

g4308.d:
προοράω prooráō, pro-or-ah'-o; from G4253 and G3708; to behold in advance, i.e. (actively) to notice
 (another) previously, or (middle voice) to keep in (one's own)
 view:—foresee, see before.
g4308.r: From πρό (G4253) and ὁράω (G3708)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4309.d:
προορίζω proorízō, pro-or-id'-zo; from G4253 and G3724; to limit in advance, i.e. (figuratively)
 predetermine:—determine before, ordain, predestinate.
g4309.r: From πρό (G4253) and ὁρίζω (G3724)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g431.d:
†ἀνεψιός anepsiós, an-eps'-ee-os; from G1 (as a particle of union) and an obsolete νέπος népos (a brood); 
 properly, akin, i.e. (specially) a cousin:—sister's son.
g431.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a particle of union) and an obsolete nepos (a brood)|English: Alpha

g4310.d: προπάσχω propáschō, prop-as'-kho; from G4253 and G3958; to undergo hardship previously:—suffer before.
g4310.r: From πρό (G4253) and πάσχω (G3958)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4311.d:
προπέμπω propémpō, prop-em'-po; from G4253 and G3992; to send forward, i.e. escort or aid in
 travel:—accompany, bring (forward) on journey (way), conduct forth.
g4311.r: From πρό (G4253) and πέμπω (G3992)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4312.d:
προπετής propetḗs, prop-et-ace'; from a compound of G4253 and G4098; falling forward, i.e. headlong
 (figuratively, precipitate):—heady, rash(-ly).
g4312.r: From a compound of πρό (G4253) and πίπτω (G4098)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4313.d: προπορεύομαι proporeúomai, prop-or-yoo'-om-ahee; from G4253 and G4198; to precede (as guide or herald):—go before.
g4313.r: From πρό (G4253) and πορεύω (G4198)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4314.d:
πρός prós, pros; a strengthened form of G4253; a preposition of direction; forward to,
 i.e. toward (with the genitive case, the side of, i.e. pertaining to;
 with the dative case, by the side of, i.e. near to; usually with the
 accusative case, the place, time, occasion, or respect, which is the
 destination of the relation, i.e. whither or for which it is
 predicated):—about, according to , against, among, at, because of,
 before, between, (where-)by, for, × at thy house, in, for intent, nigh
 unto, of, which pertain to, that, to (the end that), × together, to
 (you) -ward, unto, with(-in). In the comparative case, it denotes
 essentially the same applications, namely, motion towards, accession
 to, or nearness at.
g4314.r: A strengthened form of πρό (G4253)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4315.d:
προσάββατον prosábbaton, pros-ab'-bat-on; from G4253 and G4521; a fore-sabbath, i.e. the Sabbath-eve:—day before
 the sabbath. Compare G3904.
g4315.r: From πρό (G4253) and σάββατον (G4521)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4316.d:
προσαγορεύω prosagoreúō, pros-ag-or-yoo'-o; from G4314 and a derivative of G58 (mean to harangue); to address, i.e.
 salute by name:—call.
g4316.r: From πρός (G4314) and a derivative of ἀγορά (G58) (mean to harangue)|English: unto, to, with, for, against, among, at, not tr, misc

g4317.d:
προσάγω proságō, pros-ag'-o; from G4314 and G71; to lead towards, i.e. (transitively) to conduct near
 (summon, present), or (intransitively) to approach:—bring, draw near.
g4317.r: From πρός (G4314) and ἄγω (G71)|English: unto, to, with, for, against, among, at, not tr, misc

g4318.d: προσαγωγή prosagōgḗ, pros-ag-ogue-ay'; from G4317 (compare G72); admission:—access.
g4318.r: From προσάγω (G4317) (cf ἀγωγή (G72))|English: bring, draw near

g4319.d: προσαιτέω prosaitéō, pros-ahee-teh'-o; from G4314 and G154; to ask repeatedly (importune), i.e. solicit:—beg.
g4319.r: From πρός (G4314) and αἰτέω (G154)|English: unto, to, with, for, against, among, at, not tr, misc

g432.d: ἄνηθον ánēthon, an'-ay-thon; probably of foreign origin; dill:—anise.

g4320.d:
προσαναβαίνω prosanabaínō, pros-an-ab-ah'-ee-no; from G4314 and G305; to ascend farther, i.e. be promoted (take an upper
 (more honorable) seat):—go up.

g4321.d: προσαναλίσκω prosanalískō, pros-an-al-is'-ko; from G4314 and G355; to expend further:—spend.

g4322.d: προσαναπληρόω prosanaplēróō, pros-an-ap-lay-ro'-o; from G4314 and G378; to fill up further, i.e. furnish fully:—supply.
g4322.r: From πρός (G4314) and ἀναπληρόω (G378)|English: unto, to, with, for, against, among, at, not tr, misc

προφήτης prophḗtēs, prof-ay'-tace; from a compound of G4253 and G5346; a foreteller ("prophet"); by
 analogy, an inspired speaker; by extension, a poet:—prophet.
g4396.r: From a compound of πρό (G4253) and φημί (G5346)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4397.d:
προφητικός prophētikós, prof-ay-tik-os'; from G4396; pertaining to a foreteller ("prophetic"):—of prophecy, of
 the prophets.

g4398.d:
προφῆτις prophētis, prof-ay'-tis; feminine of G4396; a female foreteller or an inspired
 woman:—prophetess.

g4399.d:
προφθάνω prophthánō, prof-than'-o; from G4253 and G5348; to get an earlier start of, i.e.
 anticipate:—prevent.
g4399.r: From πρό (G4253) and φθάνω (G5348)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g44.d: ἄγκιστρον ánkistron, ang'-kis-tron; from the same as G43; a hook (as bent):—hook.
g44.r: From the same as ἀγκάλη (G43)|English: arm

g440.d: ἄνθραξ ánthrax, anth'-rax; of uncertain derivation; a live coal:—coal of fire.

g4400.d:
προχειρίζομαι procheirízomai, prokh-i-rid'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G4253 and a derivative of G5495; to handle for oneself
 in advance, i.e. (figuratively) to purpose:—choose, make.
g4400.r: Middle voice from πρό (G4253) and a derivative of χείρ (G5495)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4401.d: προχειροτονέω procheirotonéō, prokh-i-rot-on-eh'-o; from G4253 and G5500; to elect in advance:—choose before.
g4401.r: From πρό (G4253) and χειροτονέω (G5500)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4402.d:
Πρόχορος Próchoros, prokh'-or-os; from G4253 and G5525; before the dance; Prochorus, a
 Christian:—Prochorus.
g4402.r: From πρό (G4253) and χορός (G5525)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4403.d:
πρύμνα prýmna, proom'-nah; feminine of πρυμνύς prymnýs (hindmost); the stern of a ship:—hinder part,
 stern.

g4404.d:
πρωΐ prōḯ, pro-ee'; adverb from G4253; at dawn; by implication, the day-break watch:—early
 (in the morning), (in the) morning.
g4404.r: From πρό (G4253)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4405.d: πρωΐα prōḯa, pro-ee'-ah; feminine of a derivative of G4404 as noun; day-dawn:—early, morning.
g4405.r: Feminine of a derivative of πρωΐ (G4404) as noun|English: in the morning, early in the morning, early, morning

g4407.d: πρωϊνός prōïnós, pro-ee-nos'; from G4404; pertaining to the dawn, i.e. matutinal:—morning.
g4407.r: From πρωΐ (G4404)|English: in the morning, early in the morning, early, morning

g4408.d:
†πρῶρα prōra, pro'-ra; feminine of a presumed derivative of G4253 as noun; the prow, i.e.
 forward part of a vessel:—forepart(-ship).
g4408.r: Feminine of a presumed derivative of πρό (G4253) as noun|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4409.d: πρωτεύω prōteúō, prote-yoo'-o; from G4413; to be first (in rank or influence):—have the preeminence.
g4409.r: From πρῶτος (G4413)|English: first, chief, first day, former, misc

g441.d: ἀνθρωπάρεσκος anthrōpáreskos, anth-ro-par'-es-kos; from G444 and G700; man-courting, i.e. fawning:—men-pleaser.
g441.r: From ἄνθρωπος (G444) and ἀρέσκω (G700)|English: man, not tr, misc

g4410.d:
πρωτοκαθεδρία prōtokathedría, pro-tok-ath-ed-ree'-ah; from G4413 and G2515; a sitting first (in the front row), i.e.
 preeminence in council:—chief (highest, uppermost) seat.
g4410.r: From πρῶτος (G4413) and καθέδρα (G2515)|English: first, chief, first day, former, misc

g4411.d:
πρωτοκλισία prōtoklisía, pro-tok-lis-ee'-ah; from G4413 and G2828; a reclining first (in the place of honor) at the
 dinner-bed, i.e. preeminence at meals:—chief (highest, uppermost)
 room.
g4411.r: From πρῶτος (G4413) and κλισία (G2828)|English: first, chief, first day, former, misc

g4413.d:
†πρῶτος prōtos, pro'-tos; contracted superlative of G4253; foremost (in time, place, order or
 importance):—before, beginning, best, chief(-est), first (of all),
 former.
g4413.r: Contracted superlative of πρό (G4253)|English: before, above, above ... ago, or ever

g4414.d:
πρωτοστάτης prōtostátēs, pro-tos-tat'-ace; from G4413 and G2476; one standing first in the ranks, i.e. a captain
 (champion):—ringleader.
g4414.r: From πρῶτος (G4413) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: first, chief, first day, former, misc

g4415.d: πρωτοτόκια prōtotókia, pro-tot-ok'-ee-ah; from G4416; primogeniture (as a privilege):—birthright.

g4416.d:
πρωτότοκος prōtótokos, pro-tot-ok'-os; from G4413 and the alternate of G5088; first-born (usually as noun,
 literally or figuratively):—firstbegotten(-born).
g4416.r: From πρῶτος (G4413) and the alternate of τίκτω (G5088)|English: first, chief, first day, former, misc

g4417.d:
πταίω ptaíō, ptah'-yo; a form of G4098; to trip, i.e. (figuratively) to err, sin, fail (of
 salvation):—fall, offend, stumble.
g4417.r: A form of πίπτω (G4098)|English: fall, fall down, light, fail

g4418.d: πτέρνα ptérna, pter'-nah; of uncertain derivation; the heel (figuratively):—heel.

g4419.d:
πτερύγιον pterýgion, pter-oog'-ee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G4420; a winglet, i.e.
 (figuratively) extremity (top corner):—pinnacle.
g4419.r: From a presumed derivative of πτέρυξ (G4420)|English: wing

g442.d:
ἀνθρώπινος anthrṓpinos, anth-ro'-pee-nos; from G444; human:—human, common to man, man(-kind), (man-)kind, men's,
 after the manner of men.
g442.r: From ἄνθρωπος (G444)|English: man, not tr, misc

g4420.d: πτέρυξ ptéryx, pter'-oox; from a derivative of G4072 (meaning a feather); a wing:—wing.
g4420.r: From a derivative of πέτομαι (G4072) (meaning a feather)|English: fly, flying

g4421.d: πτηνόν ptēnón, ptay-non'; contraction for G4071; a bird:—bird.

g4422.d:
πτοέω ptoéō, pto-eh'-o; probably akin to the alternate of G4098 (through the idea of causing to
 fall) or to G4072 (through that of causing to fly away); to
 scare:—frighten.
g4422.r: Probably akin to the alternate of πίπτω (G4098) (through the idea of causing to fall) or to πέτομαι (G4072) (through that of causing to fly away)|English: fall, fall down, light, fail

g4423.d: πτόησις ptóēsis, pto'-ay-sis; from G4422; alarm:—amazement.

g4424.d:
Πτολεμαΐς Ptolemaḯs, ptol-em-ah-is'; from Πτολεμαῖος Ptolemaîos (Ptolemy, after whom it was named); Ptolemais, a place
 in Palestine:—Ptolemais.
g4424.r: From Ptolemaios (Ptolemy, after whom it was named)|

g4425.d: πτύον ptýon, ptoo'-on; from G4429; a winnowing-fork (as scattering like spittle):—fan.

g4426.d:
πτύρω ptýrō, ptoo'-ro; from a presumed derivative of G4429 (and thus akin to G4422); to
 frighten:—terrify.
g4426.r: From a presumed derivative of πτύω (G4429) (and thus akin to πτοέω (G4422))|English: spit

g4427.d: πτύσμα ptýsma, ptoos'-mah; from G4429; saliva:—spittle.

g4428.d:
πτύσσω ptýssō, ptoos'-so; probably akin to πετάννυμι petánnymi (to spread; and thus apparently allied to
 G4072 through the idea of expansion, and to 4429 through that of
 flattening; compare G3961); to fold, i.e. furl a scroll:—close.
g4428.r: Probably akin to petannumi (to spread, and thus apparently allied to πέτομαι (G4072) through the idea of expansion, and to πτύω (G4429) through that of flattening, cf πατέω (G3961))|English: fly, flying

g4429.d: πτύω ptýō, ptoo'-o; a primary verb (compare G4428); to spit:—spit.

g443.d: ἀνθρωποκτόνος anthrōpoktónos, anth-ro-pok-ton'-os; from G444 and κτείνω kteínō(to kill); a manslayer:—murderer. Compare G5406.
g443.r: From ἄνθρωπος (G444) and kteine (to kill)|English: man, not tr, misc

g4430.d:
πτῶμα ptōma, pto'-mah; from the alternate of G4098; a ruin, i.e. (specially), lifeless body
 (corpse, carrion):—dead body, carcase, corpse.
g4430.r: From the alternate of πίπτω (G4098)|English: fall, fall down, light, fail

g4431.d:
πτῶσις ptōsis, pto'-sis; from the alternate of G4098; a crash, i.e. downfall (literally or
 figuratively):—fall.
g4431.r: From the alternate of πίπτω (G4098)|English: fall, fall down, light, fail

g4432.d:
πτωχεία ptōcheía, pto-khi'-ah; from G4433; beggary, i.e. indigence (literally or
 figuratively):—poverty.

g4433.d:
πτωχεύω ptōcheúō, pto-khyoo'-o; from G4434; to be a beggar, i.e. (by implication) to become indigent
 (figuratively):—become poor.
g4433.r: From πτωχός (G4434)|English: poor, beggar, poor man, beggarly

g4434.d:
πτωχός ptōchós, pto-khos'; from πτώσσω ptṓssō (to crouch); akin to G4422 and the alternate of G4098); a
 beggar (as cringing), i.e. pauper (strictly denoting absolute or
 public mendicancy, although also used in a qualified or relative
 sense; whereas G3993 properly means only straitened circumstances in
 private), literally (often as noun) or figuratively
 (distressed):—beggar(-ly), poor.
g4434.r: From ptosso {to crouch, akin to πτοέω (G4422) and the alternate of πίπτω (G4098)}|English: terrify

g4435.d:
πυγμή pygmḗ, poog-may'; from a primary πύξ pýx (the fist as a weapon); the clenched hand, i.e.
 (only in dative case as adverb) with the fist (hard scrubbing):—oft.
g4435.r: From a primary pux (the fist as a weapon)|

g4436.d:
Πύθων Pýthōn, poo'-thone; from Πυθώ Pythṓ (the name of the region where Delphi, the seat of the
 famous oracle, was located); a Python, i.e. (by analogy, with the
 supposed diviner there) inspiration (soothsaying):—divination.
g4436.r: From Putho (the name of the region where Delphi, the seat of the famous oracle, was located)|

g4437.d:
πυκνός pyknós, pook-nos'; from the same as G4635; clasped (thick), i.e. (figuratively) frequent;
 neuter plural (as adverb) frequently:—often(-er).
g4437.r: From the same as σκηνοποιός (G4635)|English: tentmaker

g4438.d:
†πυκτέω pyktéō, pook-teh'-o; from a derivative of the same as G4435; to box (with the fist), i.e.
 contend (as a boxer) at the games (figuratively):—fight.
g4438.r: From a derivative of the same as πυγμή (G4435)|English: oft

g4439.d:
πύλη pýlē, poo'-lay; apparently a primary word; a gate, i.e. the leaf or wing of a folding
 entrance (literally or figuratively):—gate.

g444.d:
ἄνθρωπος ánthrōpos, anth'-ro-pos; from G435 and ὤψ ṓps (the countenance; from G3700); man-faced, i.e. a human
 being:—certain, man.
g444.r: From ἀνήρ (G435) and ops (the countenance, from ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)); man-faced, i.e. a human being|English: man, husband, sir, fellow, not tr

g4440.d:
πυλών pylṓn, poo-lone'; from G4439; a gate-way, door-way of a building or city; by implication,
 a portal or vestibule:—gate, porch.

g4441.d:
πυνθάνομαι pynthánomai, poon-than'-om-ahee; middle voice prolonged from a primary πύθω pýthō (which occurs only as an
 alternate in certain tenses); to question, i.e. ascertain by inquiry
 (as a matter of information merely; and thus differing from G2065,
 which properly means a request as a favor; and from G154, which is
 strictly a demand for something due; as well as from G2212, which
 implies a search for something hidden; and from G1189, which involves
 the idea of urgent need); by implication, to learn (by casual
 intelligence):—ask, demand, enquire, understand.
g4441.r: Middle voice prolonged from a primary putho (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses)|

g4442.d:
πῦρ pŷr, poor; a primary word; "fire" (literally or figuratively, specially,
 lightning):—fiery, fire.

g4443.d: πυρά pyrá, poo-rah'; from G4442; a fire (concretely):—fire.

g4444.d: πύργος pýrgos, poor'-gos; apparently a primary word ("burgh"); a tower or castle:—tower.

g4445.d:
πυρέσσω pyréssō, poo-res'-so; from G4443; to be on fire, i.e. (specially), to have a fever:—be sick
 of a fever.

g4446.d:
πυρετός pyretós, poo-ret-os'; from G4445; inflamed, i.e. (by implication) feverish (as noun,
 fever):—fever.
g4446.r: From πυρέσσω (G4445)|English: be sick of a fever

g4447.d: πύρινος pýrinos, poo'-ree-nos; from G4443; fiery, i.e. (by implication) flaming:—of fire.

g4448.d:
πυρόω pyróō, poo-ro'-o; from G4442; to kindle, i.e. (passively) to be ignited, glow
 (literally), be refined (by implication), or (figuratively) to be
 inflamed (with anger, grief, lust):—burn, fiery, be on fire, try.

g4449.d: πυῤῥάζω pyrrházō, poor-hrad'-zo; from G4450; to redden (intransitively):—be red.

g4450.d: †πυῤῥός pyrrhós, poor-hros'; from G4442; fire-like, i.e. (specially), flame- colored:—red.

g4451.d:
πύρωσις pýrōsis, poo'-ro-sis; from G4448; ignition, i.e. (specially), smelting (figuratively,
 conflagration, calamity as a test):—burning, trial.
g4451.r: From πυρόω (G4448)|English: burn, fiery, be on fire, try

g4453.d:
πωλέω pōléō, po-leh'-o; probably ultimately from πέλομαι pélomai (to be busy, to trade); to barter (as
 a pedlar), i.e. to sell:—sell, whatever is sold.
g4453.r: Probably ultimately from pelomai (to be busy, to trade)|

g4454.d:
πῶλος pōlos, po'-los; apparently a primary word; a "foal" or "filly", i.e. (specially), a
 young ass:—colt.

g4455.d:
πώποτε pṓpote, po'-pot-e; from G4452 and G4218; at any time, i.e. (with negative particle) at no
 time:—at any time, + never (…to any man),
 + yet, never man.

g4456.d:
πωρόω pōróō, po-ro'-o; apparently from πῶρος pōros (a kind of stone); to petrify, i.e.
 (figuratively) to indurate (render stupid or callous):—blind,
 harden.
g4456.r: Apparently from poros (a kind of stone)|

g4457.d: πώρωσις pṓrōsis, po'-ro-sis; from G4456; stupidity or callousness:—blindness, hardness.

g4458.d:
-πώς -pṓs, poce; adverb from the base of G4225; an enclitic particle of indefiniteness
 of manner; somehow or anyhow; used only in composition:—haply, by any
 (some) means, perhaps. See G1513, G3381. Compare G4459.
g4458.r: Adverb from the base of πού (G4225), an enclitic particle of indefiniteness of manner|English: a certain place, about

g4459.d:
πῶς pōs, poce; adverb from the base of G4226; an interrogative particle of manner; in
 what way? (sometimes the question is indirect, how?); also as
 exclamation, how much!:—how, after (by) what manner (means), that. 
 (Occasionally unexpressed in English).
g4459.r: Adverb from the base of ποῦ (G4226), an interrogative particle of manner|English: where, whither

g446.d:
ἀνθύπατος anthýpatos, anth-oo'-pat-os; from G473 and a superlative of G5228; instead of the highest officer,
 i.e. (specially) a Roman proconsul:—deputy.
g446.r: From ἀντί (G473) and upatos (highest)|English: for, because, for ... cause, therefore, in the room of

g4460.d: Ῥαάβ Rhaáb, hrah-ab'; of Hebrew origin (H7343); Raab (i.e. Rachab), a Canaanitess:—Rahab. See also H4477.

g4461.d:
ῥαββί rhabbí, hrab-bee'; of Hebrew origin (H7227 with pronominal suffix); my master, i.e Rabbi,
 as an official title of honor:—Master, Rabbi.
g4461.r: Of Hebrew origin רַב (H7227) with pronominal suffix|English: many, great, much, captain, more, long, enough, multitude, mighty, greater, greatly, misc

g4462.d: ῥαββονί rhabboní, hrab-bon-ee'; of Chaldee origin; corresponding to G4461:—Lord, Rabboni.

g4463.d: ῥαβδίζω rhabdízō, hrab-did'-zo; from G4464; to strike with a stick, i.e. bastinado:—beat (with rods).

g4464.d:
ῥάβδος rhábdos, hrab'-dos; from the base of G4474; a stick or wand (as a cudgel, a cane or a baton
 of royalty):—rod, sceptre, staff.
g4464.r: From the base of ῥαπίζω (G4474)|English: smite, smite with the palm of (one's) hand

g4465.d:
ῥαβδοῦχος rhabdoûchos, hrab-doo'-khos; from G4464 and G2192; a rod- (the Latin fasces) holder, i.e. a Roman
 lictor (constable or executioner):—serjeant.
g4465.r: From ῥάβδος (G4464) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: rod, staff, sceptre

g4466.d: †Ῥαγαῦ Rhagaû, hrag-ow'; of Hebrew origin (H7466); Ragau (i.e. Reu), a patriarch:—Ragau.

g4467.d:
ῥᾳδιούργημα rhaidioúrgēma, hrad-ee-oorg'-ay-mah; from a comparative of ῥᾴδιος rháidios (easy, i.e. reckless) and G2041; 
 easy-going behavior, i.e. (by extension) a crime:—lewdness.
g4467.r: From a comparative of rhaidios (easy, i.e. reckless) and ἔργον (G2041)|English: work, deed, doing, labour

g4468.d:
ῥᾳδιουργία rhaidiourgía, hrad-ee-oorg-ee'-a; from the same as G4467; recklessness, i.e. (by extension)
 malignity:—mischief.
g4468.r: From the same as ῥᾳδιούργημα (G4467)|English: lewdness

g4469.d:
ῥακά rhaká, rhak-ah'; of Chaldee origin (compare H7386); O empty one, i.e. thou worthless (as
 a term of utter vilification):—Raca.
g4469.r: Of Aramaic origin cf רֵיק (H7386)|English: empty, vain, emptied, vain men, vain fellows

g447.d:
ἀνίημι aníēmi, an-ee'-ay-mee; from G303 and ἵημι híēmi (to send); to let up, i.e. (literally) slacken or
 (figuratively) desert, desist from:—forbear, leave, loose.
g447.r: From ἀνά (G303) and hiemi (to send)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g4470.d: ῥάκος rhákos, hrak'-os; from G4486; a "rag," i.e. piece of cloth:—cloth.
g4470.r: From ῥήγνυμι (G4486)|English: burst, tear, rend, break, break forth, throw down

g4471.d:
Ῥαμᾶ Rhamâ, hram-ah'; of Hebrew origin (H7414); Rama (i.e. Ramah), a place in
 Palestine:—Rama.

g4472.d:
ῥαντίζω rhantízō, hran-tid'-zo; from a derivative of ῥαίνω rhaínō (to sprinkle); to render besprinkled, i.e.
 asperse (ceremonially or figuratively):—sprinkle.
g4472.r: From a derivative of rhaino (to sprinkle)|

g4473.d: ῥαντισμός rhantismós, hran-tis-mos'; from G4472; aspersion (ceremonially or figuratively):—sprinkling.

g4474.d:
ῥαπίζω rhapízō, hrap-id'-zo; from a derivative of a primary ῥέπω rhépō (to let fall, "rap"); to
 slap:—smite (with the palm of the hand). Compare G5180.
g4474.r: From a derivative of a primary rhepo (to let fall, "rap")|

g4475.d:
ῥάπισμα rhápisma, hrap'-is-mah; from G4474; a slap:—(+ strike with the) palm of the hand, smite with
 the hand.
g4475.r: From ῥαπίζω (G4474)|English: smite, smite with the palm of (one's) hand

g4476.d:
†ῥαφίς rhaphís, hraf-ece'; from a primary ῥάπτω rháptō (to sew; perhaps rather akin to the base of G4474
 through the idea of puncturing); a needle:—needle.
g4476.r: From a primary rhapto (to sew; perhaps rather akin to the base of ῥαπίζω (G4474) through the idea of puncturing)|English: smite, smite with the palm of (one's) hand

g4477.d: Ῥαχάβ Rhacháb, hrakh-ab'; from the same as G4460; Rachab, a Canaanitess:—Rachab.
g4477.r: From the same as Ῥαάβ (G4460)|English: Rahab

g4478.d: Ῥαχήλ Rhachḗl, hrakh-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H7354); Rachel, the wife of Jacob:—Rachel.
g4478.r: Of Hebrew origin רָחֵל (H7354)|English: Rachel, Rahel

g4479.d:
Ῥεβέκκα Rhebékka, hreb-bek'-kah; of Hebrew origin (H7259); Rebecca (i.e. Ribkah), the wife of
 Isaac:—Rebecca.

g4480.d:
†ῥέδα rhéda, hred'-ah; of Latin origin; a rheda, i.e. four-wheeled carriage (wagon for
 riding):—chariot.

g4482.d:
ῥέω rhéō, hreh'-o; a primary verb; for some tenses of which a prolonged form
    ῥεύω rheúō  hryoo'-o is used

 to flow ("run"; as water):—flow.

g4484.d: Ῥήγιον Rhḗgion, hrayg'-ee-on; of Latin origin; Rhegium, a place in Italy:—Rhegium.

g4485.d:
ῥῆγμα rhēgma, hrayg'-mah; from G4486; something torn, i.e. a fragment (by implication and
 abstractly, a fall):—ruin.
g4485.r: From ῥήγνυμι (G4486)|English: burst, tear, rend, break, break forth, throw down

g4486.d:
ῥήγνυμι rhḗgnymi, hrayg'-noo-mee; both prolonged forms of ῥήκω rhḗkō (which appears only in certain forms,
 and is itself probably a strengthened form of ἄγνυμι ágnymi (see in G2608)) to
 "break," "wreck" or "crack", i.e. (especially) to sunder (by
 separation of the parts; G2608 being its intensive (with the
 preposition in composition), and G2352 a shattering to minute
 fragments; but not a reduction to the constituent particles, like
 G3089) or disrupt, lacerate; by implication, to convulse (with spasms);
 figuratively, to give vent to joyful emotions:—break (forth), burst,
 rend, tear.
g4486.r: Both prolonged forms of rheko (which appears only in certain forms, and is itself probably a strengthened form of agnumi [see in κατάγνυμι (G2608)])|English: break

g4487.d:
ῥῆμα rhēma, hray'-mah; from G4483; an utterance (individually, collectively or specially),; by
 implication, a matter or topic (especially of narration, command or
 dispute); with a negative naught whatever:—+ evil, + nothing, saying,
 word.
g4487.r: From ῥέω (G4483)|English: speak, say, speak of, command, make

g4488.d:
Ῥησά Rhēsá, hray-sah'; probably of Hebrew origin (apparently for H7509); Resa (i.e. Rephajah),
 an Israelite:—Rhesa.
g4488.r: Probably of Hebrew origin [apparently for רְפָיָה (H7509)]|English: Rephaiah

g4489.d:
ῥήτωρ rhḗtōr, hray'-tore; from G4483; a speaker, i.e. (by implication) a forensic
 advocate:—orator.
g4489.r: From ῥέω (G4483)|English: speak, say, speak of, command, make

g449.d:
ἄνιπτος ániptos, an'-ip-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G3538; 
 without ablution:—unwashen.
g449.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of νίπτω (G3538)|English: Alpha

g4490.d:
ῥητῶς rhētōs, hray-toce'; adverb from a derivative of G4483; out-spokenly, i.e.
 distinctly:—expressly.
g4490.r: From a derivative of ῥέω (G4483)|English: speak, say, speak of, command, make

g4491.d:
ῥίζα rhíza, hrid'-zah; apparently a primary word; a "root" (literally or
 figuratively):—root.

g4492.d: ῥιζόω rhizóō, hrid-zo'-o; from G4491; to root (figuratively, become stable):—root.

g4493.d:
ῥιπή rhipḗ, hree-pay'; from G4496; a jerk (of the eye, i.e. (by analogy) an
 instant):—twinkling.
g4493.r: From ῥίπτω (G4496)|English: cast down, cast, scatter abroad, cast out, throw

g4494.d:
ῥιπίζω rhipízō, hrip-id'-zo; from a derivative of G4496 (meaning a fan or bellows); to breeze up,
 i.e. (by analogy) to agitate (into waves):—toss.
g4494.r: From a derivative of ῥίπτω (G4496) (meaning a fan or bellows)|English: cast down, cast, scatter abroad, cast out, throw

g4496.d:
ῥίπτω rhíptō, hrip'-to; a primary verb (perhaps rather akin to the base of G4474, through the
 idea of sudden motion); to fling (properly, with a quick toss, thus
 differing from G906, which denotes a deliberate hurl; and from τείνω teínō
 (see in G1614), which indicates an extended projection); by
 qualification, to deposit (as if a load); by extension, to
 disperse:—cast (down, out), scatter abroad, throw.
g4496.r: A primary verb (perhaps rather akin to the base of ῥαπίζω (G4474), through the idea of sudden motion)|English: smite, smite with the palm of (one's) hand

g4497.d:
Ῥοβοάμ Rhoboám, hrob-o-am'; of Hebrew origin (H7346); Roboam (i.e. Rechobam), an
 Israelite:—Roboam.

g4498.d: Ῥόδη Rhódē, hrod'-ay; probably for rhode (a rose); Rode, a servant girl:—Rhoda.

g4499.d:
Ῥόδος Rhódos, hrod'-os; probably from ῥόδον rhódon (a rose); Rhodus, an island of the
 Mediterranean:—Rhodes.

g45.d: ἄγκυρα ánkyra, ang'-koo-rah; from the same as G43; an "anchor" (as crooked):—anchor.
g45.r: From the same as ἀγκάλη (G43)|English: arm

g450.d:
†ἀνίστημι anístēmi, an-is'-tay-mee; from G303 and G2476; to stand up (literal or figurative, transitive or
 intransitive):—arise, lift up, raise up (again), rise (again), stand
 up(-right).
g450.r: From ἀνά (G303) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g4500.d:
ῥοιζηδόν rhoizēdón, hroyd-zay-don'; adverb from a derivative of ῥοῖζος rhoîzos (a whir); whizzingly, i.e. with a
 crash:—with a great noise.
g4500.r: From a derivative of rhoizos (a whir)|

g4501.d:
ῥομφαία rhomphaía, hrom-fah'-yah; probably of foreign origin; a sabre, i.e. a long and broad cutlass
 (any weapon of the kind, literally or figuratively):—sword.

g4502.d: Ῥουβήν Rhoubḗn, hroo-bane'; of Hebrew origin (H7205); Ruben (i.e. Reuben), an Israelite:—Reuben.

g4503.d: Ῥούθ Rhoúth, hrooth; of Hebrew origin (H7327); Ruth, a Moabitess:—Ruth.

g4504.d: Ῥοῦφος Rhoûphos, hroo'-fos; of Latin origin; red; Rufus, a Christian:—Rufus.

g4505.d:
ῥύμη rhýmē, hroo'-may; prolongation from G4506 in its original sense; an alley or avenue (as
 crowded):—lane, street.
g4505.r: Prolongation from ῥύομαι (G4506) in its original sense|English: deliver, Deliverer

g4506.d:
ῥύομαι rhýomai, rhoo'-om-ahee; middle voice of an obsolete verb, akin to G4482 (through the idea of a
 current; compare G4511); to rush or draw (for oneself), i.e.
 rescue:—deliver(-er).
g4506.r: Middle voice of an obsolete verb, akin to ῥέω (G4482) (through the idea of a current, cf ῥύσις (G4511))|English: flow

g4507.d: ῥυπαρία rhyparía, hroo-par-ee'-ah; from G4508; dirtiness (morally):—turpitude.

g4508.d:
ῥυπαρός rhyparós, rhoo-par-os'; from G4509; dirty, i.e. (relatively) cheap or shabby; morally,
 wicked:—vile.

g4509.d: ῥύπος rhýpos, hroo'-pos; of uncertain affinity; dirt, i.e. (morally) depravity:—filth.

g451.d: Ἄννα Ánna, an'-nah; of Hebrew origin (H2584); Anna, an Israelitess:—Anna.

g4511.d:
ῥύσις rhýsis, hroo'-sis; from G4506 in the sense of its congener G4482; a flux (of
 blood):—issue.
g4511.r: From ῥύομαι (G4506) in the sense of its congener ῥέω (G4482)|English: deliver, Deliverer

g4512.d:
ῥυτίς rhytís, hroo-tece'; from G4506; a fold (as drawing together), i.e. a wrinkle (especially on
 the face):—wrinkle.

g4514.d: Ῥωμαῖος Rhōmaîos, hro-mah'-yos; from G4516; Romæan, i.e. Roman (as noun):—Roman, of Rome.

g4515.d:
Ῥωμαϊστί Rhōmaïstí, hro-mah-is-tee'; adverb from a presumed derivative of G4516; Romaistically, i.e. in the
 Latin language:—Latin.
g4515.r: From a presumed derivative of Ῥώμη (G4516)|English: Rome

g4516.d: Ῥώμη Rhṓmē, hro'-may; from the base of G4517; strength; Roma, the capital of Italy:—Rome.
g4516.r: From the base of ῥώννυμι (G4517)|English: farewell

g4517.d:
ῥώννυμι rhṓnnymi, hrone'-noo-mee; prolongation from ῥώομαι rhṓomai (to dart; probably akin to G4506); to
 strengthen, i.e. (impersonal passive) have health (as a parting
 exclamation, good-bye):—farewell.
g4517.r: Prolongation from rhoomai (to dart, probably akin to ῥύομαι (G4506))|English: deliver, Deliverer

g4518.d:
σαβαχθάνι sabachtháni, sab-akh-than-ee'; of Chaldee or (H7662 with pronominal suffix); thou hast left me;
 sabachthani (i.e. shebakthani), a cry of distress:—sabachthani.
g4518.r: Of Aramaic or שְׁבַק (H7662) with pronominal suffix|English: leave, let alone

g4519.d:
σαβαώθ sabaṓth, sab-ah-owth'; of Hebrew origin (H6635 in feminine plural); armies; sabaoth (i.e.
 tsebaoth), a military epithet of God:—sabaoth.
g4519.r: Of Hebrew origin צָבָא (H6635) in feminine plural|English: host, war, army, battle, service, appointed time, warfare, soldiers, company, misc

g452.d: Ἄννας Ánnas, an'-nas; of Hebrew origin (H2608); Annas (i.e. G367), an Israelite:—Annas.

g4520.d:
σαββατισμός sabbatismós, sab-bat-is-mos'; from a derivative of G4521; a "sabbatism", i.e. (figuratively) the
 repose of Christianity (as a type of heaven):—rest.
g4520.r: From a derivative of σάββατον (G4521)|English: sabbath day, sabbath, week

g4521.d:
σάββατον sábbaton, sab'-bat-on; of Hebrew origin (H7676); the Sabbath (i.e. Shabbath), or day of weekly
 repose from secular avocations (also the observance or institution
 itself); by extension, a se'nnight, i.e. the interval between two
 Sabbaths; likewise the plural in all the above applications:—sabbath
 (day), week.
g4521.r: Of Hebrew origin שַׁבָּת (H7676)|English: sabbath, another

g4522.d:
σαγήνη sagḗnē, sag-ay'-nay; from a derivative of σάττω sáttō (to equip) meaning furniture, especially a
 pack-saddle (which in the East is merely a bag of netted rope); a
 "seine" for fishing:—net.
g4522.r: From a derivative of satto (to equip) meaning furniture, especially a pack-saddle (which in the East is merely a bag of netted rope)|

g4523.d:
Σαδδουκαῖος Saddoukaîos, sad-doo-kah'-yos; probably from G4524; a Sadducæan (i.e. Tsadokian), or follower of a
 certain heretical Israelite:—Sadducee.

g4524.d: Σαδώκ Sadṓk, sad-oke'; of Hebrew origin (H6659); Sadoc (i.e. Tsadok), an Israelite:—Sadoc.

g4525.d:
σαίνω saínō, sah'-ee-no; akin to G4579; to wag (as a dog its tail fawningly), i.e. (generally)
 to shake (figuratively, disturb):—move.
g4525.r: Akin to σείω (G4579)|English: shake, move, quake

g4526.d:
σάκκος sákkos, sak'-kos; of Hebrew origin (H8242); "sack"-cloth, i.e. mohair (the material or
 garments made of it, worn as a sign of grief):—sackcloth.
g4526.r: Of Hebrew origin שַׂק (H8242)|English: sackcloth, sack, sackclothes

g4527.d: Σαλά Salá, sal-ah'; of Hebrew origin (H7974); Sala (i.e. Shelach), a patriarch:—Sala.
g4527.r: Of Hebrew origin שֶׁלַח (H7974)|English: Salah, Shelah

g4528.d:
Σαλαθιήλ Salathiḗl, sal-ath-ee-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H7597); Salathiel (i.e. Shealtiel), an
 Israelite:—Salathiel.
g4528.r: Of Hebrew origin שְׁאַלְתִּיאֵל (H7597)|English: Shealtiel, Salathiel

g4529.d:
Σαλαμίς Salamís, sal-am-ece'; probably from G4535 (from the surge on the shore); Salamis, a place in
 Cyprus:—Salamis.
g4529.r: Probably from σάλος (G4535) (from the surge on the shore)|English: wave

g453.d:
ἀνόητος anóētos, an-o'-ay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G3539; 
 unintelligent; by implication, sensual:—fool(-ish), unwise.
g453.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of νοέω (G3539)|English: Alpha

g4530.d: Σαλείμ Saleím, sal-ime'; probably from the same as G4531; Salim, a place in Palestine:—Salim.
g4530.r: Probably from the same as σαλεύω (G4531)|English: shake, move, shake together, that are shaken, which cannot be shaken, stir up

g4531.d:
σαλεύω saleúō, sal-yoo'-o; from G4535; to waver, i.e. agitate, rock, topple or (by implication)
 destroy; figuratively, to disturb, incite:—move, shake (together),
 which can(-not) be shaken, stir up.

g4532.d:
Σαλήμ Salḗm, sal-ame'; of Hebrew origin (H8004); Salem (i.e. Shalem), a place in
 Palestine:—Salem.
g4532.r: Of Hebrew origin שָׁלֵם (H8004)|English: Salem, Shalem

g4533.d: Σαλμών Salmṓn, sal-mone'; of Hebrew origin (H8012); Salmon, an Israelite:—Salmon.

g4534.d:
Σαλμώνη Salmṓnē, sal-mo'-nay; perhaps of similar origin to G4529; Salmone, a place in
 Crete:—Salmone.
g4534.r: Perhaps of similar origin to Σαλαμίς (G4529)|English: Salamis

g4535.d:
σάλος sálos, sal'-os; probably from the base of G4525; a vibration, i.e. (specially),
 billow:—wave.
g4535.r: Probably from the base of σαίνω (G4525)|English: move

g4536.d:
σάλπιγξ sálpinx, sal'-pinx; perhaps from G4535 (through the idea of quavering or reverberation); a
 trumpet:—trump(-et).
g4536.r: Perhaps from σάλος (G4535) (through the idea of quavering or reverberation)|English: wave

g4537.d:
σαλπίζω salpízō, sal-pid'-zo; from G4536; to trumpet, i.e. sound a blast (literally or
 figuratively):—(which are yet to) sound (a trumpet).

g4538.d: σαλπιστής salpistḗs, sal-pis-tace'; from G4537; a trumpeter:—trumpeter.
g4538.r: From σαλπίζω (G4537)|English: sound, sound of a trumpet, trumpet sounds

g4539.d:
Σαλώμη Salṓmē, sal-o'-may; probably of Hebrew origin (feminine from H7965); Salome (i.e.
 Shelomah), an Israelitess:—Salome.
g4539.r: Probably of Hebrew origin [feminine from שָׁלוֹם (H7965)]|English: peace, well, peaceably, welfare, salute, prosperity, did, safe, health, peaceable, misc

g454.d:
ἄνοια ánoia, an'-oy-ah; from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and G3563; stupidity; by
 implication, rage:—folly, madness.
g454.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and νοῦς (G3563)|English: Alpha

g4540.d:
Σαμάρεια Samáreia, sam-ar'-i-ah; of Hebrew origin (H8111); Samaria (i.e. Shomeron), a city and region of
 Palestine:—Samaria.

g4541.d: †Σαμαρείτης Samareítēs, sam-ar-i'-tace; from G4540; a Samarite, i.e. inhabitant of Samaria:—Samaritan.

g4542.d: †Σαμαρεῖτις Samareîtis, sam-ar-i'-tis; feminine of G4541; a Samaritess, i.e. woman of Samaria:—of Samaria.

g4543.d:
Σαμοθρᾴκη Samothráikē, sam-oth-rak'-ay; from G4544 and Θτρᾴκη Thtráikē (Thrace); Samo-thrace (Samos of Thrace), an
 island in the Mediterranean:—Samothracia.

g4544.d: Σάμος Sámos, sam'-os; of uncertain affinity; Samus, an island of the Mediterranean:—Samos.

g4545.d: Σαμουήλ Samouḗl, sam-oo-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H8050); Samuel (i.e. Shemuel), an Israelite:—Samuel.
g4545.r: Of Hebrew origin שְׁמוּאֵל (H8050)|English: Samuel, Shemuel

g4546.d:
Σαμψών Sampsṓn, samp-sone'; of Hebrew origin (H8123); Sampson (i.e. Shimshon), an
 Israelite:—Samson.

g4547.d:
σανδάλιον sandálion, san-dal'-ee-on; neuter of a derivative of σάνδαλον sándalon (a "sandal"; of uncertain origin);
 a slipper or sole-pad:—sandal.
g4547.r: From a derivative of sandalon (a "sandal"; of uncertain origin)|

g4548.d: σανίς sanís, san-ece'; of uncertain affinity; a plank:—board.

g4549.d:
Σαούλ Saoúl, sah-ool'; of Hebrew origin (H7586); Saul (i.e. Shaul), the Jewish name of
 Paul:—Saul. Compare G4569.
g4549.r: Of Hebrew origin שָׁאוּל (H7586)|English: Saul, Shaul

g455.d:
ἀνοίγω anoígō, an-oy'-go; from G303 and οἴγω oígō (to open); to open up (literally or figuratively, in
 various applications):—open.
g455.r: From ἀνά (G303) and oigo (to open)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g4550.d:
σαπρός saprós, sap-ros'; from G4595; rotten, i.e. worthless (literally or morally):—bad,
 corrupt. Compare G4190.

g4551.d: †Σαπφείρη Sappheírē, sap-fi'-ray; feminine of G4552; Sapphire, an Israelitess:—Sapphira.

g4552.d: †σάπφειρος sáppheiros, sap'-fi-ros; of Hebrew origin (H5601); a "sapphire" or lapis-lazuli gem:—sapphire.
g4552.r: Of Hebrew origin סַפִּיר (H5601)|English: sapphire, sapphire stone

g4553.d:
σαργάνη sargánē, sar-gan'-ay; apparently of Hebrew origin (H8276); a basket (as interwoven or
 wicker-work:—basket.
g4553.r: Apparently of Hebrew origin שָׂרַג (H8276)|English: wreathed, wrapped together

g4554.d:
Σάρδεις Sárdeis, sar'-dice; plural of uncertain derivation; Sardis, a place in Asia
 Minor:—Sardis.

g4556.d:
†σάρδιος sárdios, sar'-dee-os; properly, an adjective from an uncertain base; sardian (3037 being
 implied), i.e. (as noun) the gem so called:—sardius.
g4556.r: Properly, an adjective from an uncertain base|

g4557.d:
σαρδόνυξ sardónyx, sar-don'-oox; from the base of G4556 and ὄνυξ ónyx (the nail of a finger; hence the "onyx"
 stone); a "sardonyx", i.e. the gem so called:—sardonyx.
g4557.r: From the base of σάρδιον (G4556) and onux (the nail of a finger, hence the "onyx" stone)|English: sardius

g4558.d:
Σάρεπτα Sárepta, sar'-ep-tah; of Hebrew origin (H6886); Sarepta (i.e. Tsarephath), a place in
 Palestine:—Sarepta.

g4559.d:
σαρκικός sarkikós, sar-kee-kos'; from G4561; pertaining to flesh, i.e. (by extension) bodily, temporal,
 or (by implication) animal, unregenerate:—carnal, fleshly.
g4559.r: From σάρξ (G4561)|English: flesh, carnal, carnally minded, fleshly

g456.d: ἀνοικοδομέω anoikodoméō, an-oy-kod-om-eh'-o; from G303 and G3618; to rebuild:—build again.
g456.r: From ἀνά (G303) and οἰκοδομέω (G3618)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g4560.d: σάρκινος sárkinos, sar'-kee-nos; from G4561; similar to flesh, i.e. (by analogy) soft:—fleshly.
g4560.r: From σάρξ (G4561)|English: flesh, carnal, carnally minded, fleshly

g4561.d:
σάρξ sárx, sarx; probably from the base of G4563; flesh (as stripped of the skin), i.e.
 (strictly) the meat of an animal (as food), or (by extension) the body
 (as opposed to the soul (or spirit), or as the symbol of what is
 external, or as the means of kindred), or (by implication) human
 nature (with its frailties (physically or morally) and passions), or
 (specially), a human being (as such):—carnal(-ly, + -ly minded),
 flesh(-ly).
g4561.r: Probably from the base of σαρόω (G4563)|English: sweep

g4562.d: †Σαρούχ Saroúch, sar-ooch'; of Hebrew origin (H8286); Saruch (i.e. Serug), a patriarch:—Saruch.

g4563.d:
σαρόω saróō, sar-o'-o; from a derivative of σαίρω saírō (to brush off; akin to G4951); meaning a
 broom; to sweep:—sweep.
g4563.r: From a derivative of sairo (to brush off, akin to σύρω (G4951))|English: draw, drag, hale

g4564.d:
Σάῤῥα Sárrha, sar'-hrah; of Hebrew origin (H8283); Sarra (i.e. Sarah), the wife of
 Abraham:—Sara, Sarah.

g4565.d:
†Σάρων Sárōn, sar'-one; of Hebrew origin (H8289); Saron (i.e. Sharon), a district of
 Palestine:—Saron.
g4565.r: Of Hebrew origin שָׁרוֹן (H8289)|English: Sharon, Lasharon

g4567.d:
Σατανᾶς Satanâs, sat-an-as'; of Chaldee origin corresponding to H4566 (with the definite affix); the
 accuser, i.e. the devil:—Satan.
g4567.r: Of Aramaic origin corresponding to Σατάν (G4566) (with the definite affix)|English: Satan

g4568.d: σάτον sáton, sat'-on; of Hebrew origin (H5429); a certain measure for things dry:—measure.

g4569.d:
Σαῦλος Saûlos, sow'-los; of Hebrew origin, the same as G4549; Saulus (i.e. Shaul), the Jewish
 name of Paul:—Saul.
g4569.r: Of Hebrew origin, the same as Σαούλ (G4549)|English: Saul (Paul), Saul (son of Cis)

g457.d: ἄνοιξις ánoixis, an'-oix-is; from G455; opening (throat):—X open.

g4570.d:
σβέννυμι sbénnymi, sben'-noo-mee; a prolonged form of an apparently primary verb; to extinguish
 (literally or figuratively):—go out, quench.
g4570.r: A prolonged form of an apparently primary verb|

g4572.d:
σεαυτοῦ seautoû, seh-ow-too'; genitive case from G4571 and G846,
               also dative case of the same,
    σεαυτῷ seautōi  seh-ow-to', and accusative case
    σεαυτόν seautón  seh-ow-ton', likewise contracted
    σαυτοῦ sautoû  sow-too',
    σαυτῷ sautōi  sow-to',   and
    σαυτόν sautón  sow-ton',  respectively; 

 of (with, to) thyself:—thee, thine own self, (thou) thy(-self).
g4572.r: Genitive case from σέ (G4571) and αὐτός (G846)|English: thee, thou, thy house, not tr

g4573.d:
σεβάζομαι sebázomai, seb-ad'-zom-ahee; middle voice from a derivative of G4576; to venerate, i.e.
 adore:—worship.
g4573.r: Middle voice from a derivative of σέβω (G4576)|English: worship, devout, religious

g4574.d:
σέβασμα sébasma, seb'-as-mah; from G4573; something adored, i.e. an object of worship (god, altar,
 etc):—devotion, that is worshipped.

g4575.d:
σεβαστός sebastós, seb-as-tos'; from G4573; venerable (august), i.e. (as noun) a title of the Roman
 Emperor, or (as adjective) imperial:—Augustus(-').

g4576.d:
σέβομαι sébomai, seb'-om-ahee; middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to revere, i.e.
 adore:—devout, religious, worship.
g4576.r: Middle voice of an apparently primary verb|

g4577.d:
†σειρά seirá, si-rah'; probably from G4951 through its congener εἴρω eírō (to fasten; akin to G138);
 a chain (as binding or drawing):—chain.
g4577.r: Probably from σύρω (G4951) through its congener eiro (to fasten, akin to αἱρέω (G138))|English: draw, drag, hale

g4578.d:
σεισμός seismós, sice-mos'; from G4579; a commotion, i.e. (of the air) a gale, (of the ground) an
 earthquake:—earthquake, tempest.

g4579.d:
σείω seíō, si'-o; apparently a primary verb; to rock (vibrate, properly, sideways or to
 and fro), i.e. (generally) to agitate (in any direction; cause to
 tremble); figuratively, to throw into a tremor (of fear or
 concern):—move, quake, shake.

g458.d:
ἀνομία anomía, an-om-ee'-ah; from G459; illegality, i.e. violation of law or (genitive case)
 wickedness:—iniquity, × transgress(-ion of) the law, unrighteousness.
g458.r: From ἄνομος (G459)|English: without law, transgressor, wicked, lawless, unlawful

g4580.d: Σεκοῦνδος Sekoûndos, sek-oon'-dos; of Latin origin; "second"; Secundus, a Christian:—Secundus.

g4581.d:
Σελεύκεια Seleúkeia, sel-yook'-i-ah; from Σέλευκος Séleukos (Seleucus, a Syrian king); Seleuceia, a place in
 Syria:—Seleucia.

g4582.d:
σελήνη selḗnē, sel-ay'-nay; from σέλας sélas (brilliancy; probably akin to the alternate of G138, through
 the idea of attractiveness); the moon:—moon.
g4582.r: From selas (brilliancy, probably akin to the alternate of αἱρέω (G138), through the idea of attractiveness)|English: choose

g4583.d:
σεληνιάζομαι selēniázomai, sel-ay-nee-ad'-zom-ahee; middle voice or passive from a presumed derivative of G4582; to be
 moon-struck, i.e. crazy:—be a lunatic.
g4583.r: Middle voice or passive from a presumed derivative of σελήνη (G4582)|English: moon

g4584.d: †Σεμεΐ Semeḯ, sem-eh-ee'; of Hebrew origin (H8096); Semei (i.e. Shimi), an Israelite:—Semei.
g4584.r: Of Hebrew origin שִׁמְעִי (H8096)|English: Shimei, Shimhi, Shimi

g4585.d: σεμίδαλις semídalis, sem-id'-al-is; probably of foreign origin; fine wheaten flour:—fine flour.

g4586.d: σεμνός semnós, sem-nos'; from G4576; venerable, i.e. honorable:—grave, honest.

g4587.d: σεμνότης semnótēs, sem-not'-ace; from G4586; venerableness, i.e. probity:—gravity, honesty.

g4588.d: Σέργιος Sérgios, serg'-ee-os; of Latin origin; Sergius, a Roman:—Sergius.

g4589.d: Σήθ Sḗth, sayth; of Hebrew origin (H8352); Seth (i.e. Sheth), a patriarch:—Seth.
g4589.r: Of Hebrew origin שֵׁת (H8352)|English: Seth, Sheth

g459.d:
ἄνομος ánomos, an'-om-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G3551; lawless, i.e. (negatively)
 not subject to (the Jewish) law; (by implication, a Gentile), or
 (positively) wicked:—without law, lawless, transgressor, unlawful,
 wicked.
g459.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and νόμος (G3551)|English: Alpha

g4590.d: Σήμ Sḗm, same; of Hebrew origin (H8035); Sem (i.e. Shem), a patriarch:—Sem.

g4591.d: σημαίνω sēmaínō, say-mah'-ee-no; from σῆμα sēma (a mark; of uncertain derivation); to indicate:—signify.
g4591.r: From sema (a mark, of uncertain derivation)|

g4592.d:
σημεῖον sēmeîon, say-mi'-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of G4591; an indication,
 especially ceremonially or supernaturally:—miracle, sign, token,
 wonder.
g4592.r: From a presumed derivative of the base of σημαίνω (G4591)|English: signify

g4593.d: σημειόω sēmeióō, say-mi-o'-o; from G4592; to distinguish, i.e. mark (for avoidance):—note.
g4593.r: From σημεῖον (G4592)|English: sign, miracle, wonder, token

g4594.d:
σήμερον sḗmeron, say'-mer-on; neuter (as adverb) of a presumed compound of the article G3588 (t
 changed to s) and G2250; on the (i.e. this) day (or night current or
 just passed); generally, now (i.e. at present, hitherto):—this
 (to-)day.
g4594.r: Neuter (as adverb) of a presumed compound of the art. ὁ (G3588) and ἡμέρα (G2250), on the (i.e. this) day (or night current or just passed)|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g4595.d:
σήπω sḗpō, say'-po; apparently a primary verb; to putrefy, i.e. (figuratively) perish:—be
 corrupted.

g4597.d: σής sḗs, sace; apparently of Hebrew origin (H5580); a moth:—moth.
g4597.r: Apparently of Hebrew origin סָס (H5580)|English: worm

g4598.d: σητόβρωτος sētóbrōtos, say-tob'-ro-tos; from G4597 and a derivative of G977; moth-eaten:—motheaten.
g4598.r: From σής (G4597) and a derivative of βιβρώσκω (G977)|English: moth

g4599.d:
σθενόω sthenóō, sthen-o'-o; from σθένος sthénos (bodily vigor; probably akin to the base of G2476); to
 strengthen, i.e. (figuratively) confirm (in spiritual knowledge and
 power):—strengthen.
g4599.r: From sthenos (bodily vigour, probably akin to the base of ἵστημι (G2476))|English: stand, set, establish, stand still, stand by, misc

g46.d:
ἄγναφος ágnaphos, ag'-naf-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and the same as G1102; properly,
 unfulled, i.e. (by implication) new (cloth):—new.
g46.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and the same as γναφεύς (G1102)|English: Alpha

g460.d:
ἀνόμως anómōs, an-om'-oce; adverb from G459; lawlessly, i.e. (specially) not amenable to (the
 Jewish) law:—without law.
g460.r: From ἄνομος (G459)|English: without law, transgressor, wicked, lawless, unlawful

g4600.d:
σιαγών siagṓn, see-ag-one'; of uncertain derivation; the jaw-bone, i.e. (by implication) the cheek
 or side of the face:—cheek.

g4601.d:
σιγάω sigáō, see-gah'-o; from G4602; to keep silent (transitively or intransitively):—keep
 close (secret, silence), hold peace.

g4602.d:
σιγή sigḗ, see-gay'; apparently from σίζω sízō (to hiss, i.e. hist or hush); silence:—silence. 
 Compare G4623.
g4602.r: Appr. from sizo (to hiss, i.e. hist or hush)|

g4604.d: σίδηρος sídēros, sid'-ay-ros; of uncertain derivation; iron:—iron.

g4605.d:
Σιδών Sidṓn, sid-one'; of Hebrew origin (H6721); Sidon (i.e. Tsidon), a place in
 Palestine:—Sidon.
g4605.r: Of Hebrew origin צִידוֹן (H6721)|English: Zidon, Sidon

g4606.d: †Σιδώνιος Sidṓnios, sid-o'-nee-os; from G4605; a Sidonian, i.e. inhabitant of Sidon:—of Sidon.

g4607.d:
σικάριος sikários, sik-ar'-ee-os; of Latin origin; a dagger-man or assassin; a freebooter (Jewish
 fanatic outlawed by the Romans):—murderer. Compare G5406.

g4608.d:
σίκερα síkera, sik'-er-ah; of Hebrew origin (H7941); an intoxicant, i.e. intensely fermented
 liquor:—strong drink.
g4608.r: Of Hebrew origin שֵׁכָר (H7941)|English: strong drink, strong wine, drunkard

g4609.d: †Σίλας Sílas, see'-las; contraction for G4610; Silas, a Christian:—Silas.

g461.d:
ἀνορθόω anorthóō, an-orth-o'-o; from G303 and a derivative of the base of G3717; to straighten up:—lift
 (set) up, make straight.
g461.r: From ἀνά (G303) and a derivative of the base of ὀρθός (G3717)|English: by, apiece, every man, each, several, two and two, among, through, between, by, in

g4610.d:
Σιλουανός Silouanós, sil-oo-an-os'; of Latin origin; "silvan"; Silvanus, a Christian:—Silvanus. Compare
 G4609.

g4611.d:
Σιλωάμ Silōám, sil-o-am'; of Hebrew origin (H7975); Siloam (i.e. Shiloach), a pool of
 Jerusalem:—Siloam.

g4612.d:
σιμικίνθιον simikínthion, sim-ee-kin'-thee-on; of Latin origin; a semicinctium or half-girding, i.e. narrow covering
 (apron):—apron.

g4613.d:
Σίμων Símōn, see'-mone; of Hebrew origin (H8095); Simon (i.e. Shimon), the name of nine
 Israelites:—Simon. Compare G4826.
g4613.r: Of Hebrew origin שִׁמְעוֹן (H8095)|English: Simeon, Shimeon

g4614.d:
Σινᾶ Sinâ, see-nah'; of Hebrew origin (H5514); Sina (i.e. Sinai), a mountain in
 Arabia:—Sina.

g4615.d:
σίναπι sínapi, sin'-ap-ee; perhaps from σίνομαι sínomai (to hurt, i.e. sting); mustard (the
 plant):—mustard.
g4615.r: Perhaps from sinomai (to hurt, i.e. sting)|

g4616.d:
σινδών sindṓn, sin-done'; of uncertain (perhaps foreign) origin; byssos, i.e. bleached linen
 (the cloth or a garment of it):—(fine) linen (cloth).

g4617.d: σινιάζω siniázō, sin-ee-ad'-zo; from σινίον siníon (a sieve); to riddle (figuratively):—sift.

g4618.d: σιτευτός siteutós, sit-yoo-ros'; from a derivative of G4621; grain-fed, i.e. fattened:—fatted.
g4618.r: From a derivative of σῖτος (G4621)|English: wheat, corn

g4619.d: σιτιστός sitistós, sit-is-tos'; from a derivative of G4621; grained, i.e. fatted:—fatling.
g4619.r: From a derivative of σῖτος (G4621)|English: wheat, corn

g462.d: ἀνόσιος anósios, an-os'-ee-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G3741; wicked:—unholy.
g462.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and ὅσιος (G3741)|English: Alpha

g4620.d:
†σιτόμετρον sitómetron, sit-om'-et-ron; from G4621 and G3358; a grain-measure, i.e. (by implication) ration
 (allowance of food):—portion of meat.
g4620.r: From σῖτος (G4621) and μέτρον (G3358)|English: wheat, corn

g4621.d: †σῖτος sîtos, see'-tos; of uncertain derivation; grain, especially wheat:—corn, wheat.
g4621.r: Plural irregular neuter sita {see'-tah}, of uncertain derivation|

g4622.d:
Σιών Siṓn, see-own'; of Hebrew origin (H6726); Sion (i.e. Tsijon), a hill of Jerusalem;
 figuratively, the Church (militant or triumphant):—Sion.
g4622.r: Of Hebrew origin צִיּוֹן (H6726)|English: Zion, Sion

g4623.d: σιωπάω siōpáō, see-o-pah'-o; from σιωπή siōpḗ (silence, i.e. a hush; properly, muteness, i.e. involuntary stillness, or inability to speak; and thus differing from G4602, which is rather a voluntary refusal or indisposition to speak, although the terms are often used synonymously); to be dumb (but not deaf also, like G2974 properly); figuratively, to be calm (as quiet water):—dumb, (hold) peace.
g4623.r: From siope (silence, i.e. a hush, properly, muteness, i.e. involuntary stillness, or inability to speak, and thus differing from σιγή (G4602), which is rather a voluntary refusal or indisposition to speak, although the terms are often used synonymously)|English: silence

g4624.d:
σκανδαλίζω skandalízō, skan-dal-id'-zo; from G4625; to entrap, i.e. trip up (figuratively, stumble
 (transitively) or entice to sin, apostasy or displeasure):—(make to)
 offend.
g4624.r: From σκάνδαλον (G4625)|English: offence, stumbling block, occasion of stumbling, occasion to fall, thing that offends

g4625.d:
σκάνδαλον skándalon, skan'-dal-on; ("scandal"); probably from a derivative of G2578; a trap-stick (bent
 sapling), i.e. snare (figuratively, cause of displeasure or
 sin):—occasion to fall (of stumbling), offence, thing that offends,
 stumblingblock.
g4625.r: Probably from a derivative of κάμπτω (G2578)|English: bow

g4626.d: σκάπτω skáptō, skap'-to; apparently a primary verb; to dig:—dig.

g4627.d:
σκάφη skáphē, skaf'-ay; a "skiff" (as if dug out), or yawl (carried aboard a large vessel for
 landing):—boat.

g4628.d:
σκέλος skélos, skel'-os; apparently from σκέλλω skéllō (to parch; through the idea of leanness); the
 leg (as lank):—leg.
g4628.r: Apparently from skello (to parch, through the idea of leanness)|

g4629.d:
σκέπασμα sképasma, skep'-as-mah; from a derivative of σκέπας sképas (a covering; perhaps akin to the base of
 G4649 through the idea of noticeableness); clothing:—raiment.
g4629.r: From a derivative of skepas (a covering; perhaps akin to the base of σκοπός (G4649) through the idea of noticeableness)|English: mark

g463.d: ἀνοχή anochḗ, an-okh-ay'; from G430; self-restraint, i.e. tolerance:—forbearance.
g463.r: From ἀνέχω (G430)|English: suffer, bear with, forbear, endure

g4630.d:
Σκευᾶς Skeuâs, skyoo-as'; apparently of Latin origin; left-handed; Scevas (i.e. Scævus), an
 Israelite:—Sceva.

g4631.d: σκευή skeuḗ, skyoo-ay'; from G4632; furniture, i.e. spare tackle:—tackling.
g4631.r: From σκεῦος (G4632)|English: vessel, goods, stuff, sail

g4632.d:
σκεῦος skeûos, skyoo'-os; of uncertain affinity; a vessel, implement, equipment or apparatus
 (literally or figuratively [specially, a wife as contributing to the
 usefulness of the husband]):—goods, sail, stuff, vessel.

g4633.d:
σκηνή skēnḗ, skay-nay'; apparently akin to G4632 and G4639; a tent or cloth hut (literally or
 figuratively):—habitation, tabernacle.
g4633.r: Apparently akin to σκεῦος (G4632) and σκιά (G4639)|English: vessel, goods, stuff, sail

g4634.d:
σκηνοπηγία skēnopēgía, skay-nop-ayg-ee'-ah; from G4636 and G4078; the Festival of Tabernacles (so called from the
 custom of erecting booths for temporary homes):—tabernacles.

g4635.d: σκηνοποιός skēnopoiós, skay-nop-oy-os'; from G4633 and G4160; a manufacturer of tents:—tent-maker.
g4635.r: From σκηνή (G4633) and ποιέω (G4160)|English: tabernacle, habitation

g4636.d:
σκῆνος skēnos, skay'-nos; from G4633; a hut or temporary residence, i.e. (figuratively) the human
 body (as the abode of the spirit):—tabernacle.

g4637.d:
σκηνόω skēnóō, skay-no'-o; from G4636; to tent or encamp, i.e. (figuratively) to occupy (as a
 mansion) or (specially), to reside (as God did in the Tabernacle of
 old, a symbol of protection and communion):—dwell.

g4638.d:
σκήνωμα skḗnōma, skay'-no-mah; from G4637; an encampment, i.e. (figuratively) the Temple (as God's
 residence), the body (as a tenement for the soul):—tabernacle.

g4639.d:
σκιά skiá, skee'-ah; apparently a primary word; "shade" or a shadow (literally or
 figuratively (darkness of error or an adumbration)):—shadow.

g464.d:
ἀνταγωνίζομαι antagōnízomai, an-tag-o-nid'-zom-ahee; from G473 and G75; to struggle against (figuratively)
 ("antagonize"):—strive against.
g464.r: From ἀντί (G473) and ἀγωνίζομαι (G75)|English: for, because, for ... cause, therefore, in the room of

g4640.d:
σκιρτάω skirtáō, skeer-tah'-o; akin to σκαίρω skaírō (to skip); to jump, i.e. sympathetically move (as the
 quickening of a fetus):—leap (for joy).

g4641.d:
σκληροκαρδία sklērokardía, sklay-rok-ar-dee'-ah; feminine of a compound of G4642 and G2588; hard-heartedness, i.e.
 (specially), destitution of (spiritual) perception:—hardness of
 heart.
g4641.r: From a compound of σκληρός (G4642) and καρδία (G2588)|English: hard, fierce

g4642.d:
σκληρός sklērós, sklay-ros'; from the base of G4628; dry, i.e. hard or tough (figuratively, harsh,
 severe):—fierce, hard.
g4642.r: From the base of σκέλος (G4628)|English: leg

g4643.d: σκληρότης sklērótēs, sklay-rot'-ace; from G4642; callousness, i.e. (figuratively) stubbornness:—hardness.

g4644.d:
σκληροτράχηλος sklērotráchēlos, sklay-rot-rakh'-ay-los; from G4642 and G5137; hardnaped, i.e. (figuratively)
 obstinate:—stiffnecked.
g4644.r: From σκληρός (G4642) and τράχηλος (G5137)|English: hard, fierce

g4645.d: σκληρύνω sklērýnō, sklay-roo'-no; from G4642; to indurate, i.e. (figuratively) render stubborn:—harden.

g4646.d:
σκολιός skoliós, skol-ee-os'; from the base of G4628; warped, i.e. winding; figuratively,
 perverse:—crooked, froward, untoward.
g4646.r: From the base of σκέλος (G4628)|English: leg

g4647.d:
σκόλοψ skólops, skol'-ops; perhaps from the base of G4628 and G3700; withered at the front, i.e. a
 point or prickle (figuratively, a bodily annoyance or
 disability):—thorn.
g4647.r: Perhaps from the base of σκέλος (G4628) and ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)|English: leg

g4648.d:
σκοπέω skopéō, skop-eh'-o; from G4649; to take aim at (spy), i.e. (figuratively)
 regard:—consider, take heed, look at (on), mark. Compare G3700.

g4649.d:
σκοπός skopós, skop-os'; from σκέπτομαι sképtomai (to peer about ("skeptic"); perhaps akin to G4626
 through the idea of concealment; compare G4629); a watch (sentry or
 scout), i.e. (by implication) a goal:—mark.
g4649.r: From skeptomai (to peer about ["skeptic"], perhaps akin to σκάπτω (G4626) through the idea of concealment, cf σκέπασμα (G4629))|English: dig

g465.d: ἀντάλλαγμα antállagma, an-tal'-ag-mah; from a compound of G473 and G236; an equivalent or ransom:—in exchange.
g465.r: From a compound of ἀντί (G473) and ἀλλάσσω (G236)|English: for, because, for ... cause, therefore, in the room of

g4650.d:
σκορπίζω skorpízō, skor-pid'-zo; apparently from the same as G4651 (through the idea of penetrating); to
 dissipate, i.e. (figuratively) put to flight, waste, be
 liberal:—disperse abroad, scatter (abroad).
g4650.r: Apparently from the same as σκορπίος (G4651) (through the idea of penetrating)|English: scorpion

g4651.d:
σκορπίος skorpíos, skor-pee'-os; probably from an obsolete σκέρπω skérpō (perhaps strengthened from the base
 of G4649 and meaning to pierce); a "scorpion" (from its
 sting):—scorpion.
g4651.r: Probably from an obsolete skerpo (perhaps strengthened from the base of σκοπός (G4649) and meaning to pierce)|English: mark

g4652.d:
σκοτεινός skoteinós, skot-i-nos'; from G4655; opaque, i.e. (figuratively) benighted:—dark, full of
 darkness.

g4653.d:
σκοτία skotía, skot-ee'-ah; from G4655; dimness, obscurity (literally or
 figuratively):—dark(-ness).

g4654.d: σκοτίζω skotízō, skot-id-zo; from G4655; to obscure (literally or figuratively):—darken.

g4655.d:
σκότος skótos, skot'-os; from the base of G4639; shadiness, i.e. obscurity (literally or
 figuratively):—darkness.
g4655.r: From the base of σκιά (G4639)|English: shadow

g4656.d:
σκοτόω skotóō, skot-o'-o; from G4655; to obscure or blind (literally or figuratively):—be full
 of darkness.

g4657.d:
σκύβαλον skýbalon, skoo'-bal-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G1519 and G2965 and G906; what is
 thrown to the dogs, i.e. refuse (ordure):—dung.
g4657.r: Neuter of a presumed derivative of εἰς (G1519) and κύων (G2965) and βάλλω (G906)|English: into, to, unto, for, in, on, toward, against, misc

g4658.d:
Σκύθης Skýthēs, skoo'-thace; probably of foreign origin; a Scythene or Scythian, i.e. (by
 implication) a savage:—Scythian.

g4659.d:
σκυθρωπός skythrōpós, skoo-thro-pos'; from σκυθρός skythrós (sullen) and a derivative of G3700; angry-visaged, i.e.
 gloomy or affecting a mournful appearance:—of a sad countenance.
g4659.r: From skuthros (sullen) and a derivative of ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)|English: see, appear, look, show (one's) self, being seen

g466.d: ἀνταναπληρόω antanaplēróō, an-tan-ap-lay-ro'-o; from G473 and G378; to supplement:—fill up.
g466.r: From ἀντί (G473) and ἀναπληρόω (G378)|English: for, because, for ... cause, therefore, in the room of

g4660.d:
σκύλλω skýllō, skool'-lo; apparently a primary verb; to flay, i.e. (figuratively) to
 harass:—trouble(self).

g4661.d: σκῦλον skŷlon, skoo'-lon; neuter from G4660; something stripped (as a hide), i.e. booty:—spoil.

g4662.d:
σκωληκόβρωτος skōlēkóbrōtos, sko-lay-kob'-ro-tos; from G4663 and a derivative of G977; worm-eaten, i.e. diseased with
 maggots:—eaten of worms.
g4662.r: From σκώληξ (G4663) and a derivative of βιβρώσκω (G977)|English: worm

g4663.d: σκώληξ skṓlēx, sko'-lakes; of uncertain derivation; a grub, maggot or earth-worm:—worm.

g4664.d: σμαράγδινος smarágdinos, smar-ag'-dee-nos; from G4665; consisting of emerald:—emerald.

g4665.d: σμάραγδος smáragdos, smar'-ag-dos; of uncertain derivation; the emerald or green gem so called:—emerald.

g4666.d: σμύρνα smýrna, smoor'-nah; apparently strengthened for G3464; myrrh:—myrrh.

g4667.d: Σμύρνα Smýrna, smoor'-nah; the same as G4666; Smyrna, a place in Asia Minor:—Smyrna.

g4669.d:
σμυρνίζω smyrnízō, smoor-nid'-zo; from G4667; to tincture with myrrh, i.e. embitter (as a
 narcotic):—mingle with myrrh.

g467.d:
ἀνταποδίδωμι antapodídōmi, an-tap-od-ee'-do-mee; from G473 and G591; to requite (good or evil):—recompense, render,
 repay.
g467.r: From ἀντί (G473) and ἀποδίδωμι (G591)|English: for, because, for ... cause, therefore, in the room of

g4670.d:
Σόδομα Sódoma, sod'-om-ah; plural of Hebrew origin (H5467); Sodoma (i.e. Sedom), a place in
 Palestine:—Sodom.
g4670.r: Plural of Hebrew origin סְדֹם (H5467)|English: Sodom

g4672.d:
Σολομών Solomṓn, sol-om-one'; of Hebrew origin (H8010); Solomon (i.e. Shelomoh), the son of
 David:—Solomon.

g4673.d:
σορός sorós, sor-os'; probably akin to the base of G4987; a funereal receptacle (urn,
 coffin), i.e. (by analogy) a bier:—bier.
g4673.r: Probably akin to the base of σωρεύω (G4987)|English: heap, lade

g4674.d: σός sós, sos; from G4771; thine:—thine (own), thy (friend).

g4676.d:
σουδάριον soudárion, soo-dar'-ee-on; of Latin origin; a sudarium (sweat-cloth), i.e. towel (for wiping the
 perspiration from the face, or binding the face of a
 corpse):—handkerchief, napkin.

g4677.d:
†Σουσάννα Sousánna, soo-san'-nah; of Hebrew origin (H7799 feminine); lily; Susannah (i.e. Shoshannah), an
 Israelitess:—Susanna.
g4677.r: Of Hebrew origin שׁוּשַׁן (H7799) feminine|English: lily, Shoshannim

g4678.d: σοφία sophía, sof-ee'-ah; from G4680; wisdom (higher or lower, worldly or spiritual):—wisdom.

g4679.d:
σοφίζω sophízō, sof-id'-zo; from G4680; to render wise; in a sinister acceptation, to form
 "sophisms", i.e. continue plausible error:—cunningly devised, make
 wise.

g468.d: ἀνταπόδομα antapódoma, an-tap-od'-om-ah; from G467; a requital (properly, the thing):—recompense.
g468.r: From ἀνταποδίδωμι (G467)|English: recompense, recompense again, repay, render

g4680.d:
σοφός sophós, sof-os'; akin to σαφής saphḗs (clear); wise (in a most general application):—wise. 
 Compare G5429.

g4681.d: Σπανία Spanía, span-ee'-ah; probably of foreign origin; Spania, a region of Europe:—Spain.

g4682.d:
σπαράσσω sparássō, spar-as'-so; prolongation from σπαίρω spaírō (to grasp; apparently strengthened from G4685
 through the idea of spasmodic contraction); to mangle, i.e. convluse
 with epilepsy:—rend, tear.
g4682.r: Prolongation from spairo (to grasp, apparently strengthened from σπάω (G4685) through the idea of spasmodic contraction)|English: draw, draw out

g4683.d:
σπαργανόω sparganóō, spar-gan-o'-o; from σπάργανον spárganon (a strip; from a derivative of the base of G4682 meaning
 to strap or wrap with strips); to swathe (an infant after the Oriental
 custom):—wrap in swaddling clothes.
g4683.r: From sparganon (a strip, from a derivative of the base of σπαράσσω (G4682) meaning to strap or wrap with strips)|English: tear, rend

g4684.d: σπαταλάω spataláō, spat-al-ah'-o; from σπατάλη spatálē (luxury); to be voluptuous:—live in pleasure, be wanton.

g4685.d: σπάω spáō, spah'-o; a primary verb; to draw:—draw (out).

g4686.d:
σπεῖρα speîra, spi'-rah; of immediate Latin origin, but ultimately a derivative of G138 in the
 sense of its cognate G1507; a coil (spira, "spire"), i.e.
 (figuratively) a mass of men (a Roman military cohort; also (by
 analogy) a squad of Levitical janitors):—band.
g4686.r: Of immed. Latin origin, but ultimately a derivative of αἱρέω (G138) in the sense of its cognate εἱλίσσω (G1507)|English: choose

g4687.d:
†σπείρω speírō, spi'-ro; probably strengthened from G4685 (through the idea of extending); to
 scatter, i.e. sow (literally or figuratively):—sow(- er), receive
 seed.
g4687.r: Probably strengthened from σπάω (G4685) (through the idea of extending)|English: draw, draw out

g4688.d:
σπεκουλάτωρ spekoulátōr, spek-oo-lat'-ore; of Latin origin; a speculator, i.e. military scout (spy or (by
 extension) life-guardsman):—executioner.

g4689.d:
σπένδω spéndō, spen'-do; apparently a primary verb; to pour out as a libation, i.e.
 (figuratively) to devote (one's life or blood, as a sacrifice)
 ("spend"):—(be ready to) be offered.

g469.d: ἀνταπόδοσις antapódosis, an-tap-od'-os-is; from G467; requital (properly, the act):—reward.
g469.r: From ἀνταποδίδωμι (G467)|English: recompense, recompense again, repay, render

g4690.d:
σπέρμα spérma, sper'-mah; from G4687; something sown, i.e. seed (including the male "sperm"); by
 implication, offspring; specially, a remnant (figuratively, as if kept
 over for planting):—issue, seed.
g4690.r: From σπείρω (G4687)|English: sow, sower, receive seed

g4691.d:
σπερμολόγος spermológos, sper-mol-og'-os; from G4690 and G3004; a seed-picker (as the crow), i.e. (figuratively) a
 sponger, loafer (specially, a gossip or trifler in talk):—babbler.
g4691.r: From σπέρμα (G4690) and λέγω (G3004)|English: seed, issue

g4692.d:
σπεύδω speúdō, spyoo'-do; probably strengthened from G4228; to "speed" ("study"), i.e. urge on
 (diligently or earnestly); by implication, to await eagerly:—(make,
 with) haste unto.
g4692.r: Probably strengthened from πούς (G4228)|English: foot, footstool

g4693.d:
σπήλαιον spḗlaion, spay'-lah-yon; neuter of a presumed derivative of σπέος spéos (a grotto); a cavern; by
 implication, a hiding-place or resort:—cave, den.
g4693.r: From a presumed derivative of speos (a grotto)|

g4694.d:
σπιλάς spilás, spee-las'; of uncertain derivation; a ledge or reef of rock in the sea:—spot (by
 confusion with G4696).

g4695.d:
σπιλόω spilóō, spee-lo'-o; from G4696; to stain or soil (literally or figuratively):—defile,
 spot.

g4697.d:
σπλαγχνίζομαι splanchnízomai, splangkh-nid'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G4698; to have the bowels yearn, i.e. (figuratively)
 feel sympathy, to pity:—have (be moved with) compassion.
g4697.r: Middle voice from σπλάγχνον (G4698)|English: bowels, inward affection, tender mercy

g4698.d:
σπλάγχνον splánchnon, splangkh'-non; probably strengthened from σπλήν splḗn (the "spleen"); an intestine
 (plural); figuratively, pity or sympathy:—bowels, inward affection, +
 tender mercy.

g4699.d: σπόγγος spóngos, spong'-gos; perhaps of foreign origin; a "sponge":—spunge.

g47.d:
ἁγνεία hagneía, hag-ni'-ah; from G53; cleanliness (the quality), i.e. (specially)
 chastity:—purity.

g470.d:
ἀνταποκρίνομαι antapokrínomai, an-tap-ok-ree'-nom-ahee; from G473 and G611; to contradict or dispute:—answer again, reply
 against.
g470.r: From ἀντί (G473) and ἀποκρίνομαι (G611)|English: for, because, for ... cause, therefore, in the room of

g4700.d: σποδός spodós, spod-os'; of uncertain derivation; ashes:—ashes.

g4701.d: σπορά sporá, spor-ah'; from G4687; a sowing, i.e. (by implication) parentage:—seed.
g4701.r: From σπείρω (G4687)|English: sow, sower, receive seed

g4702.d: σπόριμος spórimos, spor'-ee-mos; from G4703; sown, i.e. (neuter plural) a planted field:—corn(-field).

g4703.d:
σπόρος spóros, spro'-os; from G4687; a scattering (of seed), i.e. (concretely) seed (as
 sown):—seed (X sown).
g4703.r: From σπείρω (G4687)|English: sow, sower, receive seed

g4704.d:
σπουδάζω spoudázō, spoo-dad'-zo; from G4710; to use speed, i.e. to make effort, be prompt or
 earnest:—do (give) diligence, be diligent (forward), endeavour,
 labour, study.
g4704.r: From σπουδή (G4710)|English: diligence, haste, business, care, forwardness, earnest care, carefulness

g4705.d: σπουδαῖος spoudaîos, spoo-dah'-yos; from G4710; prompt, energetic, earnest:—diligent.
g4705.r: From σπουδή (G4710)|English: diligence, haste, business, care, forwardness, earnest care, carefulness

g4709.d: σπουδαίως spoudaíōs, spoo-dah'-yoce; adverb from G4705; earnestly, promptly:—diligently, instantly.

g4710.d:
σπουδή spoudḗ, spoo-day'; from G4692; "speed", i.e. (by implication) despatch, eagerness,
 earnestness:—business, (earnest) care(-fulness), diligence,
 forwardness, haste.
g4710.r: From σπεύδω (G4692)|English: make haste, haste, haste unto, with haste

g4711.d: †σπυρίς spyrís, spoo-rece'; from G4687 (as woven); a hamper or lunch-receptacle:—basket.
g4711.r: From σπείρω (G4687) (as woven)|English: sow, sower, receive seed

g4712.d:
στάδιον stádion, stad'-ee-on; from the base of G2476 (as fixed); a stade or certain measure of
 distance; by implication, a stadium or race-course:—furlong, race.
g4712.r: Or masculine (in plural) stadios {stad'-ee-os}, from the base of ἵστημι (G2476) (as fixed)|English: stand, set, establish, stand still, stand by, misc

g4713.d: στάμνος stámnos, stam'-nos; from the base of G2476 (as stationary); a jar or earthen tank:—pot.
g4713.r: From the base of ἵστημι (G2476) (as stationary)|English: stand, set, establish, stand still, stand by, misc

g4714.d:
στάσις stásis, stas'-is; from the base of G2476; a standing (properly, the act), i.e. (by
 analogy) position (existence); by implication, a popular uprising;
 figuratively, controversy:—dissension, insurrection, × standing,
 uproar.
g4714.r: From the base of ἵστημι (G2476)|English: stand, set, establish, stand still, stand by, misc

g4715.d:
στατήρ statḗr, stat-air'; from the base of G2746; a stander (standard of value), i.e.
 (specially), a stater or certain coin:—piece of money.
g4715.r: From the base of καύχησις (G2746)|English: boasting, rejoicing, glorying, whereof I may glory

g4716.d:
σταυρός staurós, stow-ros'; from the base of G2476; a stake or post (as set upright), i.e.
 (specially), a pole or cross (as an instrument of capital punishment);
 figuratively, exposure to death, i.e. self-denial; by implication, the
 atonement of Christ:—cross.
g4716.r: From the base of ἵστημι (G2476)|English: stand, set, establish, stand still, stand by, misc

g4717.d:
σταυρόω stauróō, stow-ro'-o; from G4716; to impale on the cross; figuratively, to extinguish
 (subdue) passion or selfishness:—crucify.

g4718.d:
σταφυλή staphylḗ, staf-oo-lay'; probably from the base of G4735; a cluster of grapes (as if
 intertwined):—grapes.
g4718.r: Probably from the base of στέφανος (G4735)|English: crown

g4719.d:
στάχυς stáchys, stakh'-oos; from the base of G2476; a head of grain (as standing out from the
 stalk):—ear (of corn).
g4719.r: From the base of ἵστημι (G2476)|English: stand, set, establish, stand still, stand by, misc

g472.d:
ἀντέχομαι antéchomai, an-tekh'-om-ahee; from G473 and the middle voice of G2192; to hold oneself opposite to,
 i.e. (by implication) adhere to; by extension to care for:—hold fast,
 hold to, support.
g472.r: From ἀντί (G473) and the middle voice of ἔχω (G2192)|English: for, because, for ... cause, therefore, in the room of

g4720.d: Στάχυς Stáchys, stakh'-oos; the same as G4719; Stachys, a Christian:—Stachys.
g4720.r: The same as στάχυς (G4719)|English: ear of corn, ear

g4721.d:
στέγη stégē, steg'-ay; strengthened from a primary τέγος tégos (a "thatch" or "deck" of a
 building); a roof:—roof.
g4721.r: Strengthened from a primary tegos (a "thatch" or "deck" of a building)|

g4722.d:
στέγω stégō, steg'-o; from G4721; to roof over, i.e. (figuratively) to cover with silence
 (endure patiently):—(for-)bear, suffer.

g4723.d: †στείρος steíros, sti'-ros; a contraction from G4731 (as stiff and unnatural); "sterile":—barren.
g4723.r: A contraction from στερεός (G4731) (as stiff and unnatural)|English: strong, sure, stedfast

g4724.d:
στέλλω stéllō, stel'-lo; probably strengthened from the base of G2476; properly, to set fast
 ("stall"), i.e. (figuratively) to repress (reflexively, abstain from
 associating with):—avoid, withdraw self.
g4724.r: Probably strengthened from the base of ἵστημι (G2476)|English: stand, set, establish, stand still, stand by, misc

g4725.d: στέμμα stémma, stem'-mah; from the base of G4735; a wreath for show:—garland.
g4725.r: From the base of στέφανος (G4735)|English: crown

g4726.d: στεναγμός stenagmós, sten-ag-mos'; from G4727; a sigh:—groaning.
g4726.r: From στενάζω (G4727)|English: groan, sigh, with grief, grudge

g4727.d:
στενάζω stenázō, sten-ad'-zo; from G4728; to make (intransitively, be) in straits, i.e. (by
 implication) to sigh, murmur, pray inaudibly:—with grief, groan,
 grudge, sigh.

g4728.d:
στενός stenós, sten-os'; probably from the base of G2476; narrow (from obstacles standing close
 about):—strait.
g4728.r: Probably from the base of ἵστημι (G2476)|English: stand, set, establish, stand still, stand by, misc

g4729.d:
στενοχωρέω stenochōréō, sten-okh-o-reh'-o; from the same as G4730; to hem in closely, i.e. (figuratively)
 cramp:—distress, straiten.
g4729.r: From the same as στενοχωρία (G4730)|English: distress, anguish

g473.d:
†ἀντί antí, an-tee'; a primary particle; opposite, i.e. instead or because of (rarely in
 addition to):—for, in the room of.

g4730.d:
στενοχωρία stenochōría, sten-okh-o-ree'-ah; from a compound of G4728 and G5561; narrowness of room, i.e.
 (figuratively) calamity:—anguish, distress.
g4730.r: From a compound of στενός (G4728) and χώρα (G5561)|English: strait

g4731.d:
στερεός stereós, ster-eh-os'; from G2476; stiff, i.e. solid, stable (literally or
 figuratively):—stedfast, strong, sure.
g4731.r: From ἵστημι (G2476)|English: stand, set, establish, stand still, stand by, misc

g4732.d:
στερεόω stereóō, ster-eh-o'-o; from G4731; to solidify, i.e. confirm (literally or
 figuratively):—establish, receive strength, make strong.

g4733.d:
στερέωμα steréōma, ster-eh'-o-mah; from G4732; something established, i.e. (abstractly) confirmation
 (stability):—stedfastness.
g4733.r: From στερεόω (G4732)|English: receive strength, make strong, establish

g4734.d:
Στεφανᾶς Stephanâs, stef-an-as'; probably contraction for στεφανωτός stephanōtós (crowned; from G4737); Stephanas,
 a Christian:—Stephanas.
g4734.r: Probably contraction for stephanotos (crowned, from στεφανόω (G4737))|English: crown

g4735.d:
στέφανος stéphanos, stef'-an-os; from an apparently primary στέφω stéphō (to twine or wreathe); a chaplet (as
 a badge of royalty, a prize in the public games or a symbol of honor
 generally; but more conspicuous and elaborate than the simple fillet,
 G1238), literally or figuratively:—crown.
g4735.r: From an apparently primary stepho (to twine or wreathe)|

g4736.d: Στέφανος Stéphanos, stef'-an-os; the same as G4735; Stephanus, a Christian:—Stephen.

g4737.d:
στεφανόω stephanóō, stef-an-o'-o; from G4735; to adorn with an honorary wreath (literally or
 figuratively):—crown.

g4738.d:
