g5065.r: From τέσσαρες (G5064) and καί (G2532) and δέκατος (G1182)|English: four

g5066.d: τεταρταῖος tetartaîos, tet-ar-tah'-yos; from G5064; pertaining to the fourth day:—four days.

g5067.d: τέταρτος tétartos, tet'-ar-tos; ordinal from G5064; fourth:—four(-th).

g5068.d: τετράγωνος tetrágōnos, tet-rag'-o-nos; from G5064 and G1137; four-cornered, i.e. square:—foursquare.

g5069.d:
τετράδιον tetrádion, tet-rad'-ee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of τέτρας tétras (a tetrad; from G5064); a
 quaternion or squad (picket) of four Roman soldiers:—quaternion.
g5069.r: From a presumed derivative of tetras (a tetrad, from τέσσαρες (G5064))|English: four

g507.d: ἄνω ánō, an'-o; adverb from G473; upward or on the top:—above, brim, high, up.
g507.r: From ἀντί (G473)|English: for, because, for ... cause, therefore, in the room of

g5070.d:
τετρακισχίλιοι tetrakischílioi, tet-rak-is-khil'-ee-oy; from the multiplicative adverb of G5064 and G5507; four times a
 thousand:—four thousand.
g5070.r: From the multiplicative adverb of τέσσαρες (G5064) and χίλιοι (G5507)|English: four

g5071.d: τετρακόσιοι tetrakósioi, tet-rak-os'-ee-oy; plural from G5064 and G1540; four hundred:—four hundred.
g5071.r: Plural from τέσσαρες (G5064) and ἑκατόν (G1540)|English: four

g5072.d:
†τετράμηνον tetrámēnon, tet-ram'-ay-non; neuter of a compound of G5064 and G3376; a four months' space:—four
 months.
g5072.r: Neuter of a compound of τέσσαρες (G5064) and μήν (G3376)|English: four

g5073.d: τετραπλόος tetraplóos, tet-rap-lo'-os; from G5064 and a derivative of the base of G4118; quadruple:—fourfold.
g5073.r: From τέσσαρες (G5064) and a derivative of the base of πλεῖστος (G4118)|English: four

g5074.d: τετράπους tetrápous, tet-rap'-ooce; from G5064 and G4228; a quadruped:—fourfooted beast.

g5075.d: †τετραρχέω tetrarchéō, tet-rar-kheh'-o; from G5076; to be a tetrarch:—(be) tetrarch.

g5076.d:
†τετράρχης tetrárchēs, tet-rar'-khace; from G5064 and G757; the ruler of a fourth part of a country
 ("tetrarch"):—tetrarch.

g5077.d: τεφρόω tephróō, tef-ro'-o; from τέφρα téphra (ashes); to incinerate, i.e. consume:—turn to ashes.

g5078.d:
τέχνη téchnē, tekh'-nay; from the base of G5088; art (as productive), i.e. (specially), a trade,
 or (generally) skill:—art, craft, occupation.
g5078.r: From the base of τίκτω (G5088)|English: bring forth, be delivered, be born, be in travail, bear

g5079.d:
τεχνίτης technítēs, tekh-nee'-tace; from G5078; an artisan; figuratively, a founder (Creator):—builder,
 craftsman.

g5080.d: τήκω tḗkō, tay'-ko; apparently a primary verb; to liquefy:—melt.

g5081.d:
τηλαυγῶς tēlaugōs, tay-low-goce'; adverb from a compound of a derivative of G5056 and G827; in a
 far-shining manner, i.e. plainly:—clearly.
g5081.r: From a compound of a derivative of τέλος (G5056) and αὐγή (G827)|English: end, custom, uttermost, finally, ending, by (one's) continual

g5082.d:
τηλικοῦτος tēlikoûtos, tay-lik-oo'-tos; from a compound of G3588 with G2245 and G3778; such as this, i.e. (in
 (figurative) magnitude) so vast:—so great, so mighty.
g5082.r: From a compound of ὁ (G3588) with ἡλίκος (G2245) and οὗτος (G3778)|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g5083.d:
τηρέω tēréō, tay-reh'-o; from τερός terós (a watch; perhaps akin to G2334); to guard (from loss or
 injury, properly, by keeping the eye upon; and thus differing from
 G5442, which is properly to prevent escaping; and from G2892, which
 implies a fortress or full military lines of apparatus), i.e. to note
 (a prophecy; figuratively, to fulfil a command); by implication, to
 detain (in custody; figuratively, to maintain); by extension, to
 withhold (for personal ends; figuratively, to keep unmarried); by
 extension, to withhold (for personal ends; figuratively, to keep
 unmarried):—hold fast, keep(- er), (pre-, re-)serve, watch.
g5083.r: From teros (a watch, perhaps akin to θεωρέω (G2334))|English: see, behold, perceive, consider, look on

g5084.d:
τήρησις tḗrēsis, tay'-ray-sis; from G5083; a watching, i.e. (figuratively) observance, or (concretely)
 a prison:—hold.
g5084.r: From τηρέω (G5083)|English: keep, reserve, observe, watch, preserve, keeper, hold fast

g5085.d:
Τιβεριάς Tiberiás, tib-er-ee-as'; from G5086; Tiberias, the name of a town and a lake in
 Palestine:—Tiberias.

g5086.d:
Τιβέριος Tibérios, tib-er'-ee-os; of Latin origin; probably pertaining to the river Tiberis or Tiber;
 Tiberius, a Roman emperor:—Tiberius.

g5087.d:
τίθημι títhēmi, tith'-ay-mee; a prolonged form of a primary
    θέω théō  theh'-o    (which is used only as alternate in
                certain tenses); 

 to place (in the widest application, literally and figuratively;
 properly, in a passive or horizontal posture, and thus different from
 G2476, which properly denotes an upright and active position, while
 G2749 is properly reflexive and utterly prostrate):—+ advise,
 appoint, bow, commit, conceive, give,
 × kneel down, lay (aside, down, up), make, ordain, purpose,
 put, set (forth), settle, sink down.
g5087.r: A prolonged form of a primary theo {theh'-o} (which is used only as alternate in certain tenses)|

g5088.d:
τίκτω tíktō, tik'-to; a strengthened form of a primary τέκω tékō tek'-o (which is used only as
 alternate in certain tenses); to produce (from seed, as a mother, a
 plant, the earth, etc.), literally or figuratively:—bear, be born,
 bring forth, be delivered, be in travail.
g5088.r: A strengthened form of a primary teko {tek'-o} (which is used only as alternate in certain tenses)|

g5089.d:
τίλλω tíllō, til'-lo; perhaps akin to the alternate of G138, and thus to G4951; to pull
 off:—pluck.
g5089.r: Perhaps akin to the alternate of αἱρέω (G138), and thus to σύρω (G4951)|English: choose

g509.d:
ἄνωθεν ánōthen, an'-o-then; from G507; from above; by analogy, from the first; by implication,
 anew:—from above, again, from the beginning (very first), the top.
g509.r: From ἄνω (G507)|English: above, up, high, brim

g5090.d:
Τιμαῖος Timaîos, tim'-ah-yos; probably of Chaldee origin (compare H2931); Timæus (i.e. Timay), an
 Israelite:—Timæus.
g5090.r: Probably of Aramaic origin cf טָמֵא (H2931)|English: unclean, defiled, infamous, polluted, pollution

g5091.d:
τιμάω timáō, tim-ah'-o; from G5093; to prize, i.e. fix a valuation upon; by implication, to
 revere:—honour, value.
g5091.r: From τίμιος (G5093)|English: precious, most precious, more precious, dear, honourable, had in reputation

g5092.d:
τιμή timḗ, tee-may'; from G5099; a value, i.e. money paid, or (concretely and collectively)
 valuables; by analogy, esteem (especially of the highest degree), or
 the dignity itself:—honour, precious, price, some.

g5093.d:
τίμιος tímios, tim'-ee-os; from G5092; valuable, i.e. (objectively) costly, or (subjectively)
 honored, esteemed, or (figuratively) beloved:—dear, honourable,
 (more, most) precious, had in reputation.
g5093.r: From τιμή (G5092)|English: honour, price, sum, precious

g5094.d:
τιμιότης timiótēs, tim-ee-ot'-ace; from G5093; expensiveness, i.e. (by implication)
 magnificence:—costliness.
g5094.r: From τίμιος (G5093)|English: precious, most precious, more precious, dear, honourable, had in reputation

g5095.d:
Τιμόθεος Timótheos, tee-moth'-eh-os; from G5092 and G2316; dear to God; Timotheus, a Christian:—Timotheus,
 Timothy.
g5095.r: From τιμή (G5092) and θεός (G2316)|English: honour, price, sum, precious

g5096.d: Τίμων Tímōn, tee'-mone; from G5092; valuable; Timon, a Christian:—Timon.
g5096.r: From τιμή (G5092)|English: honour, price, sum, precious

g5097.d:
τιμωρέω timōréō, tim-o-reh'-o; from a comparative of G5092 and οὖρος oûros ouros (a guard); properly, to protect
 one's honor, i.e. to avenge (inflict a penalty):—punish.
g5097.r: From a comparative of τιμή (G5092) and ouros (a guard)|English: honour, price, sum, precious

g5098.d: τιμωρία timōría, tee-mo-ree'-ah; from G5097; vindication, i.e. (by implication) a penalty:—punishment.

g5099.d:
τίνω tínō, tee'-no; strengthened for a primary
    τίω tíō  tee'-o  (which is only used as an alternate in
            certain tenses); 

 to pay a price, i.e. as a penalty:—be punished with.
g5099.r: Strengthened for a primary tio {tee'-o} (which is only used as an alternate in certain tenses)|

g51.d: ἀγνόημα agnóēma, ag-no'-ay-mah; from G50; a thing ignored, i.e. shortcoming:—error.
g51.r: From ἀγνοέω (G50)|English: be ignorant, ignorant, know not, understand not, ignorantly, unknown

g510.d: ἀνωτερικός anōterikós, an-o-ter-ee-kos'; from G511; superior, i.e. (locally) more remote:—upper.

g5100.d:
τὶς tìs, tis; an enclitic indefinite pronoun; some or any person or object:—a (kind
 of), any (man, thing, thing at all), certain (thing), divers, he
 (every) man, one (X thing), ought, + partly, some (man, -body, -
 thing, -what), (+ that no-)thing, what(-soever), × wherewith,
 whom(-soever), whose(-soever).

g5101.d:
τίς tís, tis; probably emphatic of G5100; an interrogative pronoun, who, which or
 what (in direct or indirect questions):—every man, how (much), +
 no(-ne, thing), what (manner, thing), where (-by, -fore, -of, -unto, -
 with, -withal), whether, which, who(-m, -se), why.
g5101.r: Probably emphat. of τις (G5100)|English: certain, some, any man, any, one, man, anything, a, certain man, something, somewhat, ought, some man, certain thing, nothing,  divers, he, thing, another, not tr

g5102.d: τίτλος títlos, tit'-los; of Latin origin; a titulus or "title" (placard):—title.

g5103.d:
†Τίτος Títos, tee'-tos; of Latin origin but uncertain significance; Titus, a
 Christian:—Titus.
g5103.r: Of Latin origin but uncertain signification|

g5105.d:
τοιγαροῦν toigaroûn, toy-gar-oon'; from G5104 and G1063 and G3767; truly for then, i.e.
 consequently:—there-(where-)fore.
g5105.r: From τοι (G5104) and γάρ (G1063) and οὖν (G3767)|English: n/a

g5106.d: τοίνυν toínyn, toy'-noon; from G5104 and G3568; truly now, i.e. accordingly:—then, therefore.

g5107.d: τοιόσδε toiósde, toy-os'-deh; (including the other inflections); from a derivative of G5104 and G1161; such-like then, i.e. so great:—such.
g5107.r: From a derivative of τοι (G5104) and δέ (G1161)|English: n/a

g5108.d:
τοιοῦτος toioûtos, toy-oo'-tos; (including the other inflections); from G5104 and G3778; truly this,
 i.e. of this sort (to denote character or individuality):—like, such
 (an one).

g5109.d: τοῖχος toîchos, toy'-khos; another form of G5038; a wall:—wall.

g511.d:
ἀνώτερος anṓteros, an-o'-ter-os; comparative degree of G507; upper, i.e. (neuter as adverb) to a more
 conspicuous place, in a former part of the book:—above, higher.
g511.r: Comparative degree of ἄνω (G507)|English: above, up, high, brim

g5110.d:
τόκος tókos, tok'-os; from the base of G5088; interest on money loaned (as a
 produce):—usury.
g5110.r: From the base of τίκτω (G5088)|English: bring forth, be delivered, be born, be in travail, bear

g5111.d:
τολμάω tolmáō, tol-mah'-o; from τόλμα tólma (boldness; probably itself from the base of G5056 through
 the idea of extreme conduct); to venture (objectively or in act; while
 G2292 is rather subjective or in feeling); by implication, to be
 courageous:—be bold, boldly, dare, durst.
g5111.r: From tolma (boldness, probably itself from the base of τέλος (G5056) through the idea of extreme conduct)|English: end, custom, uttermost, finally, ending, by (one's) continual

g5112.d: †τολμηρότερον tolmēróteron, tol-may-rot'-er-on; neuter of the compound of a derivative of the base of G5111 (as adverb); more daringly, i.e. with greater confidence than otherwise:—the more boldly.
g5112.r: Neuter of the compound of a derivative of the base of τολμάω (G5111) (as adverb)|English: durst, dare, be bold, boldly

g5113.d: τολμητής tolmētḗs, tol-may-tace'; from G5111; a daring (audacious) man:—presumptuous.
g5113.r: From τολμάω (G5111)|English: durst, dare, be bold, boldly

g5114.d:
τομώτερος tomṓteros, tom-o'-ter-os; comparative of a derivative of the primary τέμνω témnō (to cut; more
 comprehensive or decisive than G2875, as if by a single stroke; whereas
 that implies repeated blows, like hacking); more keen:—sharper.
g5114.r: Comparative of a derivative of the primary temno (to cut, more comprehensive or decisive than κόπτω (G2875), as if by a single stroke, whereas that implies repeated blows, like hacking)|English: bewail, lament, cut down, wail, mourn

g5115.d:
τόξον tóxon, tox'-on; from the base of G5088; a bow (apparently as the simplest
 fabric):—bow.
g5115.r: From the base of τίκτω (G5088)|English: bring forth, be delivered, be born, be in travail, bear

g5116.d:
τοπάζιον topázion, top-ad'-zee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative (alternately) of τόπαζος tópazos (a "topaz"; 
 of uncertain origin); a gem, probably the chrysolite:—topaz.
g5116.r: From a presumed derivative (alternately) of topazos (a "topaz", of uncertain origin)|

g5117.d:
τόπος tópos, top'-os; apparently a primary word; a spot (general in space, but limited by
 occupancy; whereas G5561 is a large but participle locality), i.e.
 location (as a position, home, tract, etc.); figuratively, condition,
 opportunity; specially, a scabbard:—coast, licence, place, × plain,
 quarter, + rock, room, where.

g5118.d:
τοσοῦτος tosoûtos, tos-oo'-tos; from τόσος tósos (so much; apparently from G3588 and G3739) and G3778
 (including its variations); so vast as this, i.e. such (in quantity,
 amount, number of space):—as large, so great (long, many, much),
 these many.
g5118.r: From tosos (so much, apparently from ὁ (G3588) and ὅς (G3739)) and οὗτος (G3778) (including its variations)|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g5119.d:
τότε tóte, tot'-eh; from (the neuter of) G3588 and G3753; the when, i.e. at the time that
 (of the past or future, also in consecution):—that time, then.
g5119.r: From (the neuter of) ὁ (G3588) and ὅτε (G3753)|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g512.d:
†ἀνωφελής anōphelḗs, an-o-fel'-ace; from G1 (as a negative particle) and the base of G5624; useless or
 (neuter) inutility:—unprofitable(-ness).
g512.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and the base of ὠφέλιμος (G5624)|English: Alpha

g5121.d:
τοὐναντίον tounantíon, too-nan-tee'-on; contraction for the neuter of G3588 and G1726; on the
 contrary:—contrariwise.
g5121.r: Contraction for the neuter of ὁ (G3588) and ἐναντίον (G1726)|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g5122.d: τοὔνομα toúnoma, too'-no-mah; contraction for the neuter of G3588 and G3686; the name (is):—named.
g5122.r: Contraction for the neuter of ὁ (G3588) and ὄνομα (G3686)|English: which, who, the things, the son, misc

g5123.d: τουτέστι toutésti, toot-es'-tee; contraction for G5124 and G2076; that is:—that is (to say).
g5123.r: Contraction for τοῦτο (G5124) and ἐστί (G2076)|English: this, therefore, that, for this cause, wherefore, it, not tr, misc

g5124.d:
τοῦτο toûto, too'-to; neuter singular nominative or accusative case of G3778; that
 thing:—here (-unto), it, partly, self(-same), so, that (intent), the
 same, there(-fore, -unto), this, thus, where(-fore).
g5124.r: Neuter singular nominative or accusative case of οὗτος (G3778)|English: this, these, he, the same, this man, she, they, misc

g5126.d:
τοῦτον toûton, too'-ton; accusative case singular masculine of G3778; this (person, as objective
 of verb or preposition):—him, the same, that, this.
g5126.r: Accusative case singular masculine of οὗτος (G3778)|English: this, these, he, the same, this man, she, they, misc

g5128.d:
τούτους toútous, too'-tooce; accusative case plural masculine of G3778; these (persons, as objective
 of verb or preposition):—such, them, these, this.
g5128.r: Accusative case plural masculine of οὗτος (G3778)|English: this, these, he, the same, this man, she, they, misc

g513.d: ἀξίνη axínē, ax-ee'-nay; probably from ἄγνυμι ágnymi (to break; compare G4486); an axe:—axe.
g513.r: Probably from agnumi (to break, cf ῥήγνυμι (G4486))|English: burst, tear, rend, break, break forth, throw down

g5131.d: τράγος trágos, trag'-os; from the base of G5176; a he-goat (as a gnawer):—goat.
g5131.r: From the base of τρώγω (G5176)|English: eat

g5132.d:
τράπεζα trápeza, trap'-ed-zah; probably contracted from G5064 and G3979; a table or stool (as being
 four-legged), usually for food (figuratively, a meal); also a counter
 for money (figuratively, a broker's office for loans at
 interest):—bank, meat, table.
g5132.r: Probably contracted from τέσσαρες (G5064) and πεζῇ (G3979)|English: four

g5133.d: τραπεζίτης trapezítēs, trap-ed-zee'-tace; from G5132; a money-broker or banker:—exchanger.

g5134.d:
τραῦμα traûma, trow'-mah; from the base of τιτρώσκω titrṓskō (to wound; akin to the base of G2352, G5147,
 G5149, etc.); a wound:—wound.
g5134.r: From the base of titrosko (to wound; akin to the base of θραύω (G2352), τρίβος (G5147), τρίζω (G5149), etc.)|English: bruise

g5135.d: τραυματίζω traumatízō, trow-mat-id'-zo; from G5134; to inflict a wound:—wound.

g5136.d:
τραχηλίζω trachēlízō, trakh-ay-lid'-zo; from G5137; to seize by the throat or neck, i.e. to expose the gullet
 of a victim for killing (generally, to lay bare):—opened.

g5137.d:
τράχηλος tráchēlos, trakh'-ay-los; probably from G5143 (through the idea of mobility); the throat (neck),
 i.e. (figuratively) life:—neck.
g5137.r: Probably from τρέχω (G5143) (through the idea of mobility)|English: run, have course

g5138.d:
τραχύς trachýs, trakh-oos'; perhaps strengthened from the base of G4486 (as if jagged by rents); 
 uneven, rocky (reefy):—rock, rough.
g5138.r: Perhaps strengthened from the base of ῥήγνυμι (G4486) (as if jagged by rents)|English: burst, tear, rend, break, break forth, throw down

g5139.d:
Τραχωνῖτις Trachōnîtis, trakh-o-nee'-tis; from a derivative of G5138; rough district; Trachonitis, a region of
 Syria:—Trachonitis.
g5139.r: From a derivative of τραχύς (G5138)|English: rough, rock

g514.d:
ἄξιος áxios, ax'-ee-os; probably from G71; deserving, comparable or suitable (as if drawing
 praise):—due reward, meet, (un-)worthy.
g514.r: Probably from ἄγω (G71)|English: bring, lead, go, bring forth, misc, vr bring

g5140.d: τρεῖς treîs, trice; a primary (plural) number; "three":—three.

g5141.d:
τρέμω trémō, trem'-o; strengthened from a primary τρέω tréō (to "dread", "terrify"); to "tremble"
 or fear:—be afraid, trembling.

g5142.d:
τρέφω tréphō, tref'-o; a primary verb (properly, τρέφω tréphō; but perhaps strengthened from the
 base of G5157 through the idea of convolution); properly, to stiffen,
 i.e. fatten (by implication, to cherish (with food, etc.), pamper,
 rear):—bring up, feed, nourish.
g5142.r: A primary verb (properly, threpho; but perhaps strength. from the base of τροπή (G5157) through the idea of convolution)|English: turning

g5143.r: Apparently a primary verb (properly, threcho, cf θρίξ (G2359)), which uses dremo {drem'-o} (the base of δρόμος (G1408)) as alternate in certain tenses|English: hair

g5144.d: τριάκοντα triákonta, tree-ak'-on-tah; the decade of G5140; thirty:—thirty.

g5145.d: τριακόσιοι triakósioi, tree-ak-os'-ee-oy; plural from G5140 and G1540; three hundred:—three hundred.
g5145.r: Plural from τρεῖς (G5140) and ἑκατόν (G1540)|English: three

g5146.d:
τρίβολος tríbolos, trib'-ol-os; from G5140 and G956; properly, a crow-foot (three-pronged obstruction in
 war), i.e. (by analogy) a thorny plant (caltrop):—brier, thistle.

g5147.d:
τρίβος tríbos, tree'-bos; from τρίβω tríbō (to "rub"; akin to τείρω teírō, τρύω trýō, and the base of G5131,
 G5134); a rut or worn track:—path.
g5147.r: From tribo (to "rub", akin to teiro, truo, and the base of τράγος (G5131), τραῦμα (G5134))|English: goat

g5148.d:
τριετία trietía, tree-et-ee'-ah; from a compound of G5140 and G2094; a three years' period
 (triennium):—space of three years.
g5148.r: From a compound of τρεῖς (G5140) and ἔτος (G2094)|English: three

g5149.d:
τρίζω trízō, trid'-zo; apparently a primary verb; to creak (squeak), i.e. (by analogy) to
 grate the teeth (in frenzy):—gnash.

g515.d:
ἀξιόω axióō, ax-ee-o'-o; from G514; to deem entitled or fit:—desire, think good, count (think)
 worthy.
g515.r: From ἄξιος (G514)|English: worthy, meet, due reward, unworthy

g5150.d:
†τρίμηνον trímēnon, trim'-ay-non; neuter of a compound of G5140 and G3376 as noun; a three months'
 space:—three months.
g5150.r: Neuter of a compound of τρεῖς (G5140) and μήν (G3376) as noun|English: three

g5151.d: τρίς trís, trece; adverb from G5140; three times:—three times, thrice.

g5152.d:
τρίστεγον trístegon, tris'-teg-on; neuter of a compound of G5140 and G4721 as noun; a third roof
 (story):—third loft.
g5152.r: Neuter of a compound of τρεῖς (G5140) and στέγη (G4721) as noun|English: three

g5153.d: τρισχίλιοι trischílioi, tris-khil'-ee-oy; from G5151 and G5507; three times a thousand:—three thousand.
g5153.r: From τρίς (G5151) and χίλιοι (G5507)|English: thrice, three times

g5154.d:
τρίτος trítos, tree'-tos; ordinal from G5140; third; neuter (as noun) a third part, or (as
 adverb) a (or the) third time, thirdly:—third(-ly).

g5155.d: τρίχινος tríchinos, trikh'-ee-nos; from G2359; hairy, i.e. made of hair (mohair):—of hair.

g5156.d: τρόμος trómos, trom'-os; from G5141; a "trembling", i.e. quaking with fear:—+ tremble(-ing).

g5157.d:
τροπή tropḗ, trop-ay'; from an apparently primary τρέπω trépō to turn; a turn ("trope"), i.e.
 revolution (figuratively, variation):—turning.
g5157.r: From an apparently primary trepo {to turn}|

g5158.d:
τρόπος trópos, trop'-os; from the same as G5157; a turn, i.e. (by implication) mode or style
 (especially with preposition or relative prefix as adverb, like);
 figuratively, deportment or character:—(even) as, conversation, (+
 like) manner, (+ by any) means, way.
g5158.r: From the same as τροπή (G5157)|English: turning

g5159.d: τροποφορέω tropophoréō, trop-of-or-eh'-o; from G5158 and G5409; to endure one's habits:—suffer the manners.
g5159.r: From τρόπος (G5158) and φορέω (G5409)|English: as, even as, way, means, even as, in like manner as, manner, conversation

g516.d:
ἀξίως axíōs, ax-ee'-oce; adverb from G514; appropriately:—as becometh, after a godly sort,
 worthily(-thy).
g516.r: From ἄξιος (G514)|English: worthy, meet, due reward, unworthy

g5160.d:
τροφή trophḗ, trof-ay'; from G5142; nourishment (literally or figuratively); by implication,
 rations (wages):—food, meat.
g5160.r: From τρέφω (G5142)|English: feed, nourish, bring up

g5161.d: Τρόφιμος Tróphimos, trof'-ee-mos; from G5160; nutritive; Trophimus, a Christian:—Trophimus.
g5161.r: From τροφή (G5160)|English: meat, food, some meat, not tr

g5162.d: τροφός trophós, trof-os'; from G5142; a nourisher, i.e. nurse:—nurse.
g5162.r: From τρέφω (G5142)|English: feed, nourish, bring up

g5163.d:
τροχιά trochiá, trokh-ee-ah'; from G5164; a track (as a wheel-rut), i.e. (figuratively) a course of
 conduct:—path.

g5164.d:
τροχός trochós, trokh-os'; from G5143; a wheel (as a runner), i.e. (figuratively) a circuit of
 physical effects:—course.

g5165.d: †τρύβλιον trýblion, troob'-lee-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of uncertain affinity; a bowl:—dish.
g5165.r: From a presumed derivative of uncertain affinity|

g5166.d:
τρυγάω trygáō, troo-gah'-o; from a derivative of τρύγω trýgō (to dry) meaning ripe fruit (as if dry); to
 collect the vintage:—gather.
g5166.r: From a derivative of trugo (to dry) meaning ripe fruit (as if dry)|

g5167.d:
τρυγών trygṓn, troo-gone'; from τρύζω trýzō (to murmur; akin to G5149, but denoting a duller sound); a
 turtle-dove (as cooing):—turtle-dove.
g5167.r: From truzo (to murmur; akin to τρίζω (G5149), but denoting a duller sound)|English: gnash

g5168.d:
†τρυμαλιά trymaliá, troo-mal-ee-ah'; from a derivative of τρύω trýō (to wear away; akin to the base of G5134,
 G5147 and G5176); an orifice, i.e. needle's eye:—eye. Compare G5169.
g5168.r: From a derivative of truo (to wear away, akin to the base of τραῦμα (G5134), τρίβος (G5147) and τρώγω (G5176))|English: wound

g5169.d:
τρύπημα trýpēma, troo'-pay-mah; from a derivative of the base of G5168; an aperture, i.e. a needle's
 eye:—eye.
g5169.r: From a derivative of the base of τρυμαλιά (G5168)|English: eye

g517.d:
ἀόρατος aóratos, ah-or'-at-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G3707; invisible:—invisible
 (thing).
g517.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and ὁρατός (G3707)|English: Alpha

g5170.d: Τρύφαινα Trýphaina, troo'-fahee-nah; from G5172; luxurious; Tryphæna, a Christian woman:—Tryphena.

g5171.d: τρυφάω trypháō, troo-fah'-o; from G5172; to indulge in luxury:—live in pleasure.

g5172.d:
τρυφή tryphḗ, troo-fay'; from θρύπτω thrýptō (to break up or (figuratively) enfeeble, especially the
 mind and body by indulgence); effeminacy, i.e. luxury or
 debauchery:—delicately, riot.
g5172.r: From thrupto (to break up or [figuratively] enfeeble, especially the mind and body by indulgence)|

g5173.d: Τρυφῶσα Tryphōsa, troo-fo'-sah; from G5172; luxuriating; Tryphosa, a Christian female:—Tryphosa.

g5174.d:
†Τρωάς Trōás, tro-as'; from Τρός Trós (a Trojan); the Troad (or plain of Troy), i.e. Troas, a
 place in Asia Minor:—Troas.

g5176.d:
τρώγω trṓgō, tro'-go; probably strengthened from a collateral form of the base of G5134 and
 G5147 through the idea of corrosion or wear; or perhaps rather of a
 base of G5167 and G5149 through the idea of a craunching sound; to gnaw
 or chew, i.e. (generally) to eat:—eat.
g5176.r: Probably strengthened from a collateral form of the base of τραῦμα (G5134) and τρίβος (G5147) through the idea of corrosion or wear, or perhaps rather of a base of τρυγών (G5167) and τρίζω (G5149) through the idea of a crunching sound|English: wound

g5177.d:
τυγχάνω tynchánō, toong-khan'-o; probably for an obsolete τύχω týchō (for which the middle voice of another
 alternate τεύχω teúchō (to make ready or bring to pass) is used in certain
 tenses; akin to the base of G5088 through the idea of effecting;
 properly, to affect; or (specially), to hit or light upon (as a mark
 to be reached), i.e. (transitively) to attain or secure an object or
 end, or (intransitively) to happen (as if meeting with); but in the
 latter application only impersonal (with G1487), i.e. perchance; or
 (present participle) as adjective, usual (as if commonly met with,
 with G3756, extraordinary), neuter (as adverb) perhaps; or (with
 another verb) as adverb, by accident (as it were):—be, chance, enjoy,
 little, obtain, × refresh…self, + special. Compare G5180.
g5177.r: Probably for an obsolete tucho (for which the middle voice of another alternate teucho [to make ready or bring to pass] is used in certain tenses, akin to the base of τίκτω (G5088) through the idea of effecting|English: bring forth, be delivered, be born, be in travail, bear

g5178.d:
τυμπανίζω tympanízō, toom-pan-id'-zo; from a derivative of G5180 (meaning a drum, "tympanum"); to stretch on
 an instrument of torture resembling a drum, and thus beat to
 death:—torture.
g5178.r: From a derivative of τύπτω (G5180) (meaning a drum, "tympanum")|English: smite, beat, strike, wound

g5179.d:
†τύπος týpos, too'-pos; from G5180; a die (as struck), i.e. (by implication) a stamp or scar;
 by analogy, a shape, i.e. a statue, (figuratively) style or
 resemblance; specially, a sampler ("type"), i.e. a model (for
 imitation) or instance (for warning):—en-(ex-)ample, fashion, figure,
 form, manner, pattern, print.
g5179.r: From τύπτω (G5180)|English: smite, beat, strike, wound

g518.d:
ἀπαγγέλλω apangéllō, ap-ang-el'-lo; from G575 and the base of G32; to announce:—bring word (again),
 declare, report, shew (again), tell.
g518.r: From ἀπό (G575) and the base of ἄγγελος (G32)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5180.d:
τύπτω týptō, toop'-to; a primary verb (in a strengthened form); to "thump", i.e. cudgel or
 pummel (properly, with a stick or bastinado), but in any case by
 repeated blows; thus differing from G3817 and G3960, which denote a
 (usually single) blow with the hand or any instrument, or G4141 with
 the fist (or a hammer), or G4474 with the palm; as well as from G5177,
 an accidental collision); by implication, to punish; figuratively, to
 offend (the conscience):—beat, smite, strike, wound.
g5180.r: A primary verb (in a strengthened form)|

g5181.d:
Τύραννος Týrannos, too'-ran-nos; a provincial form of the derivative of the base of G2962; a "tyrant";
 Tyrannus, an Ephesian:—Tyrannus.
g5181.r: A provincial form of the derivative of the base of κύριος (G2962)|English: Lord, lord, master, sir, Sir, misc

g5183.d: Τύριος Týrios, too'-ree-os; from G5184; a Tyrian, i.e. inhabitant of Tyrus:—of Tyre.

g5184.d:
Τύρος Týros, too'-ros; of Hebrew origin (H6865): Tyrus (i.e. Tsor), a place in
 Palestine:—Tyre.
g5184.r: Of Hebrew origin צֹר (H6865)|English: Tyrus, Tyre

g5185.d:
†τυφλός typhlós, toof-los'; from, G5187; opaque (as if smoky), i.e. (by analogy) blind (physically
 or mentally):—blind.
g5185.r: From τυφόω (G5187)|English: be proud, be lifted up with pride, highminded

g5186.d: τυφλόω typhlóō, toof-lo'-o; from G5185; to make blind, i.e. (figuratively) to obscure:—blind.

g5187.d:
τυφόω typhóō, toof-o'-o; from a derivative of G5188; to envelop with smoke, i.e. (figuratively)
 to inflate with self-conceit:—high-minded, be lifted up with pride,
 be proud.
g5187.r: From a derivative of τύφω (G5188)|English: smoke

g5188.d:
†τύφω týphō, too'-fo; apparently a primary verb; to make a smoke, i.e. slowly consume
 without flame:—smoke.

g5189.d: τυφωνικός typhōnikós, too-fo-nee-kos'; from a derivative of G5188; stormy (as if smoky):—tempestuous.
g5189.r: From a derivative of τύφω (G5188)|English: smoke

g519.d:
†ἀπάγχομαι apánchomai, ap-ang'-khom-ahee; from G575 and ἄγχω ánchō (to choke; akin to the base of G43); to strangle
 oneself off (i.e. to death):—hang himself.
g519.r: From ἀπό (G575) and agcho (to choke akin to the base of ἀγκάλη (G43))|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5190.d:
Τυχικός Tychikós, too-khee-kos'; from a derivative of G5177; fortuitous, i.e. fortunate; Tychicus, a
 Christian:—Tychicus.
g5190.r: From a derivative of τυγχάνω (G5177)|English: obtain, be, chance, little, enjoy, may be, not tr, misc

g5191.d: ὑακίνθινος hyakínthinos, hoo-ak-in'-thee-nos; from G5192; "hyacinthine" or "jacinthine", i.e. deep blue:—jacinth.

g5192.d:
ὑάκινθος hyákinthos, hoo-ak'-in-thos; of uncertain derivation; the "hyacinth" or "jacinth", i.e. some gem of
 a deep blue color, probably the zirkon:—jacinth.

g5193.d: ὑάλινος hyálinos, hoo-al'-ee-nos; from G5194; glassy, i.e. transparent:—of glass.

g5194.d:
ὕαλος hýalos, hoo'-al-os; perhaps from the same as G5205 (as being transparent like rain); 
 glass:—glass.
g5194.r: Perhaps from the same as ὑετός (G5205) (as being transparent like rain)|English: rain

g5195.d:
ὑβρίζω hybrízō, hoo-brid'-zo; from G5196; to exercise violence, i.e. abuse:—use despitefully,
 reproach, entreat shamefully (spitefully).

g5196.d:
ὕβρις hýbris, hoo'-bris; from G5228; insolence (as over-bearing), i.e. insult, injury:—harm,
 hurt, reproach.
g5196.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5197.d: ὑβριστής hybristḗs, hoo-bris-tace'; from G5195; an insulter, i.e. maltreater:—despiteful, injurious.
g5197.r: From ὑβρίζω (G5195)|English: entreat spitefully, reproach, use despitefully, shamefully entreat

g5198.d:
ὑγιαίνω hygiaínō, hoog-ee-ah'-ee-no; from G5199; to have sound health, i.e. be well (in body); figuratively,
 to be uncorrupt (true in doctrine):—be in health, (be safe and)
 sound, (be) whole(-some).

g5199.d:
ὑγιής hygiḗs, hoog-ee-ace'; from the base of G837; healthy, i.e. well (in body); figuratively, true
 (in doctrine):—sound, whole.
g5199.r: From the base of αὐξάνω (G837)|English: grow, increase, give the increase, grow up

g52.d: ἄγνοια ágnoia, ag'-noy-ah; from G50; ignorance (properly, the quality):—ignorance.
g52.r: From ἀγνοέω (G50)|English: be ignorant, ignorant, know not, understand not, ignorantly, unknown

g520.d:
ἀπάγω apágō, ap-ag'-o; from G575 and G71; to take off (in various senses):—bring, carry away,
 lead (away), put to death, take away.
g520.r: From ἀπό (G575) and ἄγω (G71)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5200.d:
ὑγρός hygrós, hoo-gros'; from the base of G5205; wet (as if with rain), i.e. (by implication)
 sappy (fresh):—green.
g5200.r: From the base of ὑετός (G5205)|English: rain

g5201.d: ὑδρία hydría, hoo-dree-ah'; from G5204; a water-jar, i.e. receptacle for family supply:—water-pot.

g5202.d:
ὑδροποτέω hydropotéō, hoo-drop-ot-eh'-o; from a compound of G5204 and a derivative of G4095; to be a
 water-drinker, i.e. to abstain from vinous beverages:—drink water.
g5202.r: From a compound of ὕδωρ (G5204) and a derivative of πίνω (G4095)|English: water

g5203.d:
ὑδρωπικός hydrōpikós, hoo-dro-pik-os'; from a compound of G5204 and a derivative of G3700 (as if looking
 watery); to be "dropsical":—have the dropsy.
g5203.r: From a compound of ὕδωρ (G5204) and a derivative of ὀπτάνομαι (G3700) (as if looking watery)|English: water

g5204.d:
ὕδωρ hýdōr, hoo'-dore; from the base of G5205; water (as if rainy) literally or
 figuratively:—water.
g5204.r: Genitive case, hudatos {hoo'-dat-os}, etc., from the base of ὑετός (G5205)|English: rain

g5205.d: ὑετός hyetós, hoo-et-os'; from a primary ὕω hýō (to rain); rain, especially a shower:—rain.

g5206.d:
υἱοθεσία huiothesía, hwee-oth-es-ee'-ah; from a presumed compound of G5207 and a derivative of G5087; the placing
 as a son, i.e. adoption (figuratively, Christian sonship in respect to
 God):—adoption (of children, of sons).
g5206.r: From a presumed compound of υἱός (G5207) and a derivative of τίθημι (G5087)|English: son(s), Son of Man, Son of God, child(ren), Son, his Son, Son of David, my beloved Son, thy Son, only begotten Son, his (David's) son, firstborn son

g5207.d:
υἱός huiós, hwee-os'; apparently a primary word; a "son" (sometimes of animals), used very
 widely of immediate, remote or figuratively, kinship:—child, foal,
 son.

g5208.d: ὕλη hýlē, hoo-lay'; perhaps akin to G3586; a forest, i.e. (by implication) fuel:—matter.
g5208.r: Perhaps akin to ξύλον (G3586)|English: tree, staff, wood, stocks

g5209.d:
ὑμᾶς hymâs, hoo-mas'; accusative case of G5210; you (as the objective of a verb or
 preposition):—ye, you (+ -ward), your (+ own).
g5209.r: Accusative case of ὑμεῖς (G5210)|English: ye, ye yourselves, you, not tr

g521.d:
ἀπαίδευτος apaídeutos, ap-ah'-ee-dyoo-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G3811; 
 uninstructed, i.e. (figuratively) stupid:—unlearned.
g521.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of παιδεύω (G3811)|English: Alpha

g5210.d:
ὑμεῖς hymeîs, hoo-mice'; irregular plural of G4771; you (as subjective of verb):—ye
 (yourselves), you.

g5211.d:
†Ὑμεναῖος Hymenaîos, hoo-men-ah'-yos; from Ὑμήν Hymḗn (the god of weddings); "hymenæal"; Hymenæus, an opponent of
 Christianity:—Hymenæus.

g5212.d: ὑμέτερος hyméteros, hoo-met'-er-os; from G5210; yours, i.e. pertaining to you:—your (own).
g5212.r: From ὑμεῖς (G5210)|English: ye, ye yourselves, you, not tr

g5213.d:
ὑμῖν hymîn, hoo-min'; irregular dative case of G5210; to (with or by) you:—ye, you,
 your(-selves).
g5213.r: Irregular dative case of ὑμεῖς (G5210)|English: ye, ye yourselves, you, not tr

g5214.d:
ὑμνέω hymnéō, hoom-neh'-o; from G5215; to hymn, i.e. sing a religious ode; by implication, to
 celebrate (God) in song:—sing a hymn (praise unto).

g5215.r: Apparently from a simpler (obsolete) form of hudeo (to celebrate, probably akin to ᾄδω (G103), cf  (G5667))|English: sing

g5216.d:
ὑμῶν hymōn, hoo-mone'; genitive case of G5210; of (from or concerning) you:—ye, you, your
 (own, -selves).
g5216.r: Genitive case of ὑμεῖς (G5210)|English: ye, ye yourselves, you, not tr

g5217.d:
ὑπάγω hypágō, hoop-ag'-o; from G5259 and G71; to lead (oneself) under, i.e. withdraw or retire (as
 if sinking out of sight), literally or figuratively:—depart, get
 hence, go (a-)way.
g5217.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and ἄγω (G71)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5218.d:
ὑπακοή hypakoḗ, hoop-ak-o-ay'; from G5219; attentive hearkening, i.e. (by implication) compliance or
 submission:—obedience, (make) obedient, obey(-ing).
g5218.r: From ὑπακούω (G5219)|English: obey, be obedient to, hearken

g5219.d:
ὑπακούω hypakoúō, hoop-ak-oo'-o; from G5259 and G191; to hear under (as a subordinate), i.e. to listen
 attentively; by implication, to heed or conform to a command or
 authority:—hearken, be obedient to, obey.
g5219.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and ἀκούω (G191)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g522.d: ἀπαίρω apaírō, ap-ah'-ee-ro; from G575 and G142; to lift off, i.e. remove:—take (away).
g522.r: From ἀπό (G575) and αἴρω (G142)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5220.d:
ὕπανδρος hýpandros, hoop'-an-dros; from G5259 and G435; in subjection under a man, i.e. a married
 woman:—which hath an husband.
g5220.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and ἀνήρ (G435)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5221.d:
ὑπαντάω hypantáō, hoop-an-tah'-o; from G5259 and a derivative of G473; to go opposite (meet) under
 (quietly), i.e. to encounter, fall in with:—(go to) meet.
g5221.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and a derivative of ἀντί (G473)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5222.d:
ὑπάντησις hypántēsis, hoop-an'-tay-sis; from G5221; an encounter or concurrence (with G1519 for infinitive, in
 order to fall in with):—meeting.
g5222.r: From ὑπαντάω (G5221)|English: meet, go and meet

g5223.d:
ὕπαρξις hýparxis, hoop'-arx-is; from G5225; existency or proprietorship, i.e. (concretely) property,
 wealth:—goods, substance.
g5223.r: From ὑπάρχω (G5225)|English: be, have, live, after, not tr

g5225.d:
ὑπάρχω hypárchō, hoop-ar'-kho; from G5259 and G756; to begin under (quietly), i.e. come into existence
 (be present or at hand); expletively, to exist (as copula or
 subordinate to an adjective, participle, adverb or preposition, or as
 an auxiliary to a principal (verb):—after, behave, live.
g5225.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and ἄρχομαι (G756)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5226.d: ὑπείκω hypeíkō, hoop-i'-ko; from G5259 and εἴκω eíkō (to yield, be "weak"); to surrender:—submit self.
g5226.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and eiko (to yield, be "weak")|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5227.d:
ὑπεναντίος hypenantíos, hoop-en-an-tee'-os; from G5259 and G1727; under (covertly) contrary to, i.e. opposed or (as
 noun) an opponent:—adversary, against.
g5227.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and ἐναντίος (G1727)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5228.d:
†ὑπέρ hypér, hoop-er'; a primary preposition; "over", i.e. (with the genitive case) of place,
 above, beyond, across, or causal, for the sake of, instead, regarding;
 with the accusative case superior to, more than:—(+ exceeding,
 abundantly) above, in (on) behalf of, beyond, by, + very chiefest,
 concerning, exceeding (above, -ly), for, + very highly, more (than),
 of, over, on the part of, for sake of, in stead, than, to(-ward),
 very.

g5229.d:
†ὑπεραίρομαι hyperaíromai, hoop-er-ah'-ee-rom-ahee; middle voice from G5228 and G142; to raise oneself over, i.e.
 (figuratively) to become haughty:—exalt self, be exalted above
 measure.
g5229.r: Middle voice from ὑπέρ (G5228) and αἴρω (G142)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g523.d: ἀπαιτέω apaitéō, ap-ah'-ee-teh-o; from G575 and G154; to demand back:—ask again, require.
g523.r: From ἀπό (G575) and αἰτέω (G154)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5230.d:
ὑπέρακμος hypérakmos, hoop-er'-ak-mos; from G5228 and the base of G188; beyond the "acme", i.e. figuratively
 (of a daughter) past the bloom (prime) of youth:—+ pass the flower of
 (her) age.
g5230.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and the base of ἀκμήν (G188)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5231.d:
ὑπεράνω hyperánō, hoop-er-an'-o; from G5228 and G507; above upward, i.e. greatly higher (in place or
 rank):—far above, over.
g5231.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and ἄνω (G507)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5232.d:
ὑπεραυξάνω hyperauxánō, hoop-er-owx-an'-o; from G5228 and G837; to increase above ordinary degree:—grow
 exceedingly.
g5232.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and αὐξάνω (G837)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5233.d:
ὑπερβαίνω hyperbaínō, hoop-er-bah'-ee-no; from G5228 and the base of G939; to transcend, i.e. (figuratively) to
 overreach:—go beyond.
g5233.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and the base of βάσις (G939)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5234.d:
ὑπερβαλλόντως hyperballóntōs, hoop-er-bal-lon'-toce; adverb from present participle active of G5235; excessively:—beyond
 measure.
g5234.r: From present participle active of ὑπερβάλλω (G5235)|English: exceed, excel, pass

g5235.d:
ὑπερβάλλω hyperbállō, hoop-er-bal'-lo; from G5228 and G906; to throw beyond the usual mark, i.e. (figuratively)
 to surpass (only active participle supereminent):—exceeding, excel,
 pass.
g5235.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and βάλλω (G906)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5236.d:
ὑπερβολή hyperbolḗ, hoop-er-bol-ay'; from G5235; a throwing beyond others, i.e. (figuratively)
 supereminence; adverbially (with G1519 or G2596) pre-
 eminently:—abundance, (far more) exceeding, excellency, more
 excellent, beyond (out of) measure.

g5238.d:
ὑπερέκεινα hyperékeina, hoop-er-ek'-i-nah; from G5228 and the neuter plural of G1565; above those parts, i.e. still
 farther:—beyond.
g5238.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and the neuter plural of ἐκεῖνος (G1565)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5239.d: ὑπερεκτείνω hyperekteínō, hoop-er-ek-ti'-no; from G5228 and G1614; to extend inordinately:—stretch beyond.
g5239.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and ἐκτείνω (G1614)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g524.d:
ἀπαλγέω apalgéō, ap-alg-eh'-o; from G575 and ἀλγέω algéō (to smart); to grieve out, i.e. become
 apathetic:—be past feeling.
g524.r: From ἀπό (G575) and algeo (to smart)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5240.d:
ὑπερεκχύνω hyperekchýnō, hoop-er-ek-khoo'-no; from G5228 and the alternate form of G1632; to pour out over, i.e.
 (passively) to overflow:—run over.
g5240.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and the alternate form of ἐκχέω (G1632)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5241.d: ὑπερεντυγχάνω hyperentynchánō, hoop-er-en-toong-khan'-o; from G5228 and G1793; to intercede in behalf of:—make intercession for.
g5241.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and ἐντυγχάνω (G1793)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5242.d:
ὑπερέχω hyperéchō, hoop-er-ekh'-o; from G5228 and G2192; to hold oneself above, i.e. (figuratively) to
 excel; participle (as adjective, or neuter as noun) superior,
 superiority:—better, excellency, higher, pass, supreme.
g5242.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5243.d: ὑπερηφανία hyperēphanía, hoop-er-ay-fan-ee'-ah; from G5244; haughtiness:—pride.

g5244.d:
ὑπερήφανος hyperḗphanos, hoop-er-ay'-fan-os; from G5228 and G5316; appearing above others (conspicuous), i.e.
 (figuratively) haughty:—proud.
g5244.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and φαίνω (G5316)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5245.d:
ὑπερνικάω hypernikáō, hoop-er-nik-ah'-o; from G5228 and G3528; to vanquish beyond, i.e. gain a decisive
 victory:—more than conquer.
g5245.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and νικάω (G3528)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5246.d:
ὑπέρογκος hypéronkos, hoop-er'-ong-kos; from G5228 and G3591; bulging over, i.e. (figuratively) insolent:—great
 swelling.
g5246.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and ὄγκος (G3591)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5247.d:
ὑπεροχή hyperochḗ, hoop-er-okh-ay'; from G5242; prominence, i.e. (figuratively) superiority (in rank or
 character):—authority, excellency.
g5247.r: From ὑπερέχω (G5242)|English: higher, better, excellency, pass, supreme

g5248.d: ὑπερπερισσεύω hyperperisseúō, hoop-er-per-is-syoo'-o; from G5228 and G4052; to super-abound:—abound much more, exceeding.
g5248.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and περισσεύω (G4052)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5249.d:
ὑπερπερισσῶς hyperperissōs, hoop-er-per-is-soce'; from G5228 and G4057; superabundantly, i.e. exceedingly:—beyond
 measure.
g5249.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and περισσῶς (G4057)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g525.d:
ἀπαλλάσσω apallássō, ap-al-las'-so; from G575 and G236; to change away, i.e. release, (reflexively)
 remove:—deliver, depart.
g525.r: From ἀπό (G575) and ἀλλάσσω (G236)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5250.d: ὑπερπλεονάζω hyperpleonázō, hoop-er-pleh-on-ad'-zo; from G5228 and G4121; to superabound:—be exceeding abundant.
g5250.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and πλεονάζω (G4121)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5251.d:
ὑπερυψόω hyperypsóō, hoop-er-oop-so'-o; from G5228 and G5312; to elevate above others, i.e. raise to the highest
 position:—highly exalt.
g5251.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and ὑψόω (G5312)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5252.d:
ὑπερφρονέω hyperphronéō, hoop-er-fron-eh'-o; from G5228 and G5426; to esteem oneself overmuch, i.e. be vain or
 arrogant:—think more highly.
g5252.r: From ὑπέρ (G5228) and φρονέω (G5426)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5253.d:
ὑπερῷον hyperōion, hoop-er-o'-on; neuter of a derivative of G5228; a higher part of the house, i.e.
 apartment in the third story:—upper chamber (room).
g5253.r: From a derivative of ὑπέρ (G5228)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5254.d:
ὑπέχω hypéchō, hoop-ekh'-o; from G5259 and G2192; to hold oneself under, i.e. endure with
 patience:—suffer.
g5254.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and ἔχω (G2192)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5255.d:
ὑπήκοος hypḗkoos, hoop-ay'-ko-os; from G5219; attentively listening, i.e. (by implication)
 submissive:—obedient.
g5255.r: From ὑπακούω (G5219)|English: obey, be obedient to, hearken

g5256.d:
ὑπηρετέω hypēretéō, hoop-ay-ret-eh'-o; from G5257; to be a subordinate, i.e. (by implication)
 subserve:—minister (unto), serve.

g5257.d:
ὑπηρέτης hypērétēs, hoop-ay-ret'-ace; from G5259 and a derivative of ἐρέσσω eréssō (to row); an under-oarsman, i.e.
 (generally) subordinate (assistant, sexton, constable):—minister,
 officer, servant.
g5257.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and a derivative of eresso (to row)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5258.d:
ὕπνος hýpnos, hoop'-nos; from an obsolete primary (perhaps akin to G5259 through the idea of
 subsilience); sleep, i.e. (figuratively) spiritual torpor:—sleep.
g5258.r: From an obsolete primary (perhaps akin to ὑπό (G5259) through the idea of subsilience)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5259.d:
ὑπό hypó, hoop-o'; a primary preposition; under, i.e. (with the genitive case) of place
 (beneath), or with verbs (the agency or means, through); (with the
 accusative case) of place (whither (underneath) or where (below) or
 time (when (at)):—among, by, from, in, of, under, with.

g526.d:
ἀπαλλοτριόω apallotrióō, ap-al-lot-ree-o'-o; from G575 and a derivative of G245; to estrange away, i.e. (passively
 and figuratively) to be non-participant:—alienate, be alien.
g526.r: From ἀπό (G575) and a derivative of ἀλλότριος (G245)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5260.d:
ὑποβάλλω hypobállō, hoop-ob-al'-lo; from G5259 and G906; to throw in stealthily, i.e. introduce by
 collusion:—suborn.
g5260.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and βάλλω (G906)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5261.d:
ὑπογραμμός hypogrammós, hoop-og-ram-mos'; from a compound of G5259 and G1125; an underwriting, i.e. copy for
 imitation (figuratively):—example.
g5261.r: From a compound of ὑπό (G5259) and γράφω (G1125)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5262.d:
ὑπόδειγμα hypódeigma, hoop-od'-igue-mah; from G5263; an exhibit for imitation or warning (figuratively,
 specimen, adumbration):—en-(ex-)ample, pattern.

g5263.d:
ὑποδείκνυμι hypodeíknymi, hoop-od-ike'-noo-mee; from G5259 and G1166; to exhibit under the eyes, i.e. (figuratively) to
 exemplify (instruct, admonish):—show, (fore-)warn.
g5263.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and δεικνύω (G1166)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5264.d:
ὑποδέχομαι hypodéchomai, hoop-od-ekh'-om-ahee; from G5259 and G1209; to admit under one's roof, i.e. entertain
 hospitably:—receive.
g5264.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and δέχομαι (G1209)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5265.d:
ὑποδέω hypodéō, hoop-od-eh'-o; from G5259 and G1210; to bind under one's feet, i.e. put on shoes or
 sandals:—bind on, (be) shod.
g5265.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and δέω (G1210)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5266.d:
ὑπόδημα hypódēma, hoop-od'-ay-mah; from G5265; something bound under the feet, i.e. a shoe or
 sandal:—shoe.
g5266.r: From ὑποδέω (G5265)|English: bind on, shod, be shod with

g5267.d:
ὑπόδικος hypódikos, hoop-od'-ee-kos; from G5259 and G1349; under sentence, i.e. (by implication)
 condemned:—guilty.
g5267.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and δίκη (G1349)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5268.d:
ὑποζύγιον hypozýgion, hoop-od-zoog'-ee-on; neuter of a compound of G5259 and G2218; an animal under the yoke
 (draught-beast), i.e. (specially), a donkey:—ass.
g5268.r: Neuter of a compound of ὑπό (G5259) and ζυγός (G2218)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5269.d:
ὑποζώννυμι hypozṓnnymi, hoop-od-zone'-noo-mee; from G5259 and G2224; to gird under, i.e. frap (a vessel with cables
 across the keel, sides and deck):—undergirt.
g5269.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and ζώννυμι (G2224)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g527.d: ἀπαλός apalós, ap-al-os'; of uncertain derivation; soft:—tender.

g5270.d: ὑποκάτω hypokátō, hoop-ok-at'-o; from G5259 and G2736; down under, i.e. beneath:—under.
g5270.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and κάτω (G2736)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5271.d:
ὑποκρίνομαι hypokrínomai, hoop-ok-rin'-om-ahee; middle voice from G5259 and G2919; to decide (speak or act) under a
 false part, i.e. (figuratively) dissemble (pretend):—feign.
g5271.r: Middle voice from ὑπό (G5259) and κρίνω (G2919)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5272.d:
ὑπόκρισις hypókrisis, hoop-ok'-ree-sis; from G5271; acting under a feigned part, i.e. (figuratively) deceit
 ("hypocrisy"):—condemnation, dissimulation, hypocrisy.

g5273.d:
ὑποκριτής hypokritḗs, hoop-ok-ree-tace'; from G5271; an actor under an assumed character (stage-player), i.e.
 (figuratively) a dissembler ("hypocrite":—hypocrite.

g5274.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and λαμβάνω (G2983)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5275.d:
ὑπολείπω hypoleípō, hoop-ol-i'-po; from G5295 and G3007; to leave under (behind), i.e. (passively) to
 remain (survive):—be left.
g5275.r: From ὑποτρέχω (G5295) and λείπω (G3007)|English: run under

g5276.d:
ὑπολήνιον hypolḗnion, hoop-ol-ay'-nee-on; neuter of a presumed compound of G5259 and G3025; vessel or receptacle
 under the press, i.e. lower wine-vat:—winefat.
g5276.r: From a presumed compound of ὑπό (G5259) and ληνός (G3025)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5277.d: ὑπολιμπάνω hypolimpánō, hoop-ol-im-pan'-o; a prolonged form for G5275; to leave behind, i.e. bequeath:—leave.
g5277.r: A prolonged form for ὑπολείπω (G5275)|English: leave

g5278.d:
ὑπομένω hypoménō, hoop-om-en'-o; from G5259 and G3306; to stay under (behind), i.e. remain; figuratively,
 to undergo, i.e. bear (trials), have fortitude, persevere:—abide,
 endure, (take) patient(-ly), suffer, tarry behind.
g5278.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and μένω (G3306)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5279.d:
†ὑπομιμνήσκω hypomimnḗskō, hoop-om-im-nace'-ko; from G5259 and G3403; to remind quietly, i.e. suggest to the (middle
 voice, one's own) memory:—put in mind, remember, bring to (put in)
 remembrance.
g5279.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and μιμνῄσκομαι (G3403)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g528.d: ἀπαντάω apantáō, ap-an-tah'-o; from G575 and a derivative of G473; to meet away, i.e. encounter:—meet.
g528.r: From ἀπό (G575) and a derivative of ἀντί (G473)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5280.d: ὑπόμνησις hypómnēsis, hoop-om'-nay-sis; from G5279; a reminding or (reflexively) recollection:—remembrance.
g5280.r: From ὑπομιμνῄσκω (G5279)|English: put in remembrance, remember, bring to remembrance, put in mind

g5281.d:
ὑπομονή hypomonḗ, hoop-om-on-ay'; from G5278; cheerful (or hopeful) endurance, constancy:—enduring,
 patience, patient continuance (waiting).
g5281.r: From ὑπομένω (G5278)|English: endure, take patiently, tarry behind, abide, patient, suffer

g5282.d:
ὑπονοέω hyponoéō, hoop-on-o-eh'-o; from G5259 and G3539; to think under (privately), i.e. to surmise or
 conjecture:—think, suppose, deem.
g5282.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and νοέω (G3539)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5283.d: ὑπόνοια hypónoia, hoop-on'-oy-ah; from G5282; suspicion:—surmising.

g5284.d: ὑποπλέω hypopléō, hoop-op-leh'-o; from G5259 and G4126; to sail under the lee of:—sail under.
g5284.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and πλέω (G4126)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5285.d: ὑποπνέω hypopnéō, hoop-op-neh'-o; from G5259 and G4154; to breathe gently, i.e. breeze:—blow softly.
g5285.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and πνέω (G4154)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5286.d:
ὑποπόδιον hypopódion, hoop-op-od'-ee-on; neuter of a compound of G5259 and G4228; something under the feet, i.e.
 a foot-rest (figuratively):—footstool.
g5286.r: From a compound of ὑπό (G5259) and πούς (G4228)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5287.d:
ὑπόστασις hypóstasis, hoop-os'-tas-is; from a compound of G5259 and G2476; a setting under (support), i.e.
 (figuratively) concretely, essence, or abstractly, assurance
 (objectively or subjectively):—confidence, confident, person,
 substance.
g5287.r: From a compound of ὑπό (G5259) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5288.d:
ὑποστέλλω hypostéllō, hoop-os-tel'-lo; from G5259 and G4724; to withhold under (out of sight), i.e.
 (reflexively) to cower or shrink, (figuratively) to conceal
 (reserve):—draw (keep) back, shun, withdraw.
g5288.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and στέλλω (G4724)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5289.d:
ὑποστολή hypostolḗ, hoop-os-tol-ay'; from G5288; shrinkage (timidity), i.e. (by implication) apostasy:—draw
 back.
g5289.r: From ὑποστέλλω (G5288)|English: keep back, shun, withdraw, draw back

g529.d: ἀπάντησις apántēsis, ap-an'-tay-sis; from G528; a (friendly) encounter:—meet.

g5290.d:
ὑποστρέφω hypostréphō, hoop-os-tref'-o; from G5259 and G4762; to turn under (behind), i.e. to return (literally
 or figuratively):—come again, return (again, back again), turn back
 (again).
g5290.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and στρέφω (G4762)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5291.d:
ὑποστρώννυμι hypostrṓnnymi, hoop-os-trone'-noo-mee; from G5259 and G4766; to strew underneath (the feet as a
 carpet):—spread.
g5291.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and στρωννύω (G4766)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5292.d: ὑποταγή hypotagḗ, hoop-ot-ag-ay'; from G5293; subordination:—subjection.
g5292.r: From ὑποτάσσω (G5293)|English: put under, be subject unto, be subject to, submit (one's) self unto, submit (one's) self to, be in subjection unto, put in subjection under, misc

g5293.d:
ὑποτάσσω hypotássō, hoop-ot-as'-so; from G5259 and G5021; to subordinate; reflexively, to obey:—be under
 obedience (obedient), put under, subdue unto, (be, make) subject (to,
 unto), be (put) in subjection (to, under), submit self unto.
g5293.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and τάσσω (G5021)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5294.d:
ὑποτίθημι hypotíthēmi, hoop-ot-ith'-ay-mee; from G5259 and G5087; to place underneath, i.e. (figuratively) to
 hazard, (reflexively) to suggest:—lay down, put in remembrance.
g5294.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and τίθημι (G5087)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5295.d:
ὑποτρέχω hypotréchō, hoop-ot-rekh'-o; from G5259 and G5143 (including its alternate); to run under, i.e.
 (specially), to sail past:—run under.
g5295.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and τρέχω (G5143) (including its alternate)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5296.d:
ὑποτύπωσις hypotýpōsis, hoop-ot-oop'-o-sis; from a compound of G5259 and a derivative of G5179; typification under
 (after), i.e. (concretely) a sketch (figuratively) for
 imitation:—form, pattern.
g5296.r: From a compound of ὑπό (G5259) and a derivative of τύπος (G5179)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5297.d:
ὑποφέρω hypophérō, hoop-of-er'-o; from G5259 and G5342; to bear from underneath, i.e. (figuratively) to
 undergo hardship:—bear, endure.
g5297.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and φέρω (G5342)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5298.d:
ὑποχωρέω hypochōréō, hoop-okh-o-reh'-o; from G5259 and G5562; to vacate down, i.e. retire quietly:—go aside,
 withdraw self.
g5298.r: From ὑπό (G5259) and χωρέω (G5562)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5299.d:
ὑπωπιάζω hypōpiázō, hoop-o-pee-ad'-zo; from a compound of G5259 and a derivative of G3700; to hit under the eye
 (buffet or disable an antagonist as a pugilist), i.e. (figuratively)
 to tease or annoy (into compliance), subdue (one's passions):—keep
 under, weary.
g5299.r: From a compound of ὑπό (G5259) and a derivative of ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g53.d:
ἁγνός hagnós, hag-nos'; from the same as G40; properly, clean, i.e. (figuratively) innocent,
 modest, perfect:—chaste, clean, pure.
g53.r: From the same as ἅγιος (G40)|English: holy, saints, Holy One, misc

g530.d:
ἅπαξ hápax, hap'-ax; probably from G537; one (or a single) time (numerically or
 conclusively):—once.
g530.r: Probably from ἅπας (G537)|English: all, all things, whole, every one, every

g5300.d: ὗς hŷs, hoos; apparently a primary word; a hog ("swine"):—sow.

g5301.d: ὕσσωπος hýssōpos, hoos'-so-pos; of foreign origin (H231); "hyssop":—hyssop.

g5303.d:
ὑστέρημα hystérēma, hoos-ter'-ay-mah; from G5302; a deficit; specially, poverty:—that which is behind, (that
 which was) lack(-ing), penury, want.
g5303.r: From ὑστερέω (G5302)|English: lack, be behind, want, come short, be in want, fail, come behind, be destitute, misc

g5304.d:
ὑστέρησις hystérēsis, hoos-ter'-ay-sis; from G5302; 

 a falling short, i.e. (specially), penury:—want.
g5304.r: From ὑστερέω (G5302)|English: lack, be behind, want, come short, be in want, fail, come behind, be destitute, misc

g5306.d: ὕστερος hýsteros, hoos'-ter-os; comparative from G5259 (in the sense of behind); later:—latter.
g5306.r: Comparative from ὑπό (G5259) (in the sense of behind)|English: of, by, under, with, in, not tr, misc

g5307.d: ὑφαντός hyphantós, hoo-fan-tos'; from ὑφαίνω hyphaínō to weave; woven, i.e. (perhaps) knitted:—woven.

g5308.d: ὑψηλός hypsēlós, hoop-say-los'; from G5311; lofty (in place or character):—high(-er, -ly) (esteemed).
g5308.r: From ὕψος (G5311)|English: on high, height, high, be exalted

g5309.d:
ὑψηλοφρονέω hypsēlophronéō, hoop-say-lo-fron-eh'-o; from a compound of G5308 and G5424; to be lofty in mind, i.e.
 arrogant:—be highminded.
g5309.r: From a compound of ὑψηλός (G5308) and φρήν (G5424)|English: high, higher, highly esteemed, high things

g531.d:
ἀπαράβατος aparábatos, ap-ar-ab'-at-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G3845; not passing
 away, i.e. untransferable (perpetual):—unchangeable.
g531.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of παραβαίνω (G3845)|English: Alpha

g5310.d:
ὕψιστος hýpsistos, hoop'-sis-tos; superlative from the base of G5311; highest, i.e. (masculine singular)
 the Supreme (God), or (neuter plural) the heavens:—most high,
 highest.
g5310.r: Superlative from the base of ὕψος (G5311)|English: on high, height, high, be exalted

g5311.d:
ὕψος hýpsos, hoop'-sos; from a derivative of G5228; elevation, i.e. (abstractly) altitude,
 (specially), the sky, or (figuratively) dignity:—be exalted, height,
 (on) high.
g5311.r: From a derivative of ὑπέρ (G5228)|English: for, of, above, for (one's) sake, on (one's) behalf, more than, in (one's) stead, than, very chiefest, beyond, to, over, more, exceedingly abundantly, exceedingly, very highly

g5312.d: ὑψόω hypsóō, hoop-so'-o; from G5311; to elevate (literally or figuratively):—exalt, lift up.
g5312.r: From ὕψος (G5311)|English: on high, height, high, be exalted

g5313.d:
ὕψωμα hýpsōma, hoop'-so-mah; from G5312; an elevated place or thing, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, or
 (by implication) a barrier (figuratively):—height, high thing.

g5314.d: φάγος phágos, fag'-os; from G5315; a glutton:—gluttonous.

g5316.d:
φαίνω phaínō, fah'-ee-no; prolongation for the base of G5457; to lighten (shine), i.e. show
 (transitive or intransitive, literal or figurative):—appear, seem,
 be seen, shine, × think.
g5316.r: Prolongation for the base of φῶς (G5457)|English: light, fire

g5317.d: †Φάλεκ Phálek, fal'-ek; of Hebrew origin (H6389); Phalek (i.e. Peleg), a patriarch:—Phalec.

g5318.d:
φανερός phanerós, fan-er-os'; from G5316; shining, i.e. apparent (literally or figuratively); neuter
 (as adverb) publicly, externally:—abroad, + appear, known, manifest,
 open (+ -ly), outward (+ -ly).
g5318.r: From φαίνω (G5316)|English: appear, shine, be seen, seem, think

g5319.d:
φανερόω phaneróō, fan-er-o'-o; from G5318; to render apparent (literally or figuratively):—appear,
 manifestly declare, (make) manifest (forth), shew (self).
g5319.r: From φανερός (G5318)|English: manifest, openly, known, abroad, spread abroad, outwardly, outward, appear

g532.d:
ἀπαρασκεύαστος aparaskeúastos, ap-ar-ask-yoo'-as-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G3903; 
 unready:—unprepared.
g532.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of παρασκευάζω (G3903)|English: Alpha

g5320.d:
φανερῶς phanerōs, fan-er-oce'; adverb from G5318; plainly, i.e. clearly or publicly:—evidently,
 openly.
g5320.r: From φανερός (G5318)|English: manifest, openly, known, abroad, spread abroad, outwardly, outward, appear

g5321.d:
φανέρωσις phanérōsis, fan-er'-o-sis; from G5319; exhibition, i.e. (figuratively) expression, (by extension)
 a bestowment:—manifestation.
g5321.r: From φανερόω (G5319)|English: make manifest, appear, manifest, show, be manifest, show (one's) self, manifestly declare, manifest forth

g5322.d: φανός phanós, fan-os'; from G5316; a lightener, i.e. light; lantern:—lantern.
g5322.r: From φαίνω (G5316)|English: appear, shine, be seen, seem, think

g5323.d:
Φανουήλ Phanouḗl, fan-oo-ale'; of Hebrew origin (H6439); Phanuel (i.e. Penuel), an
 Israelite:—Phanuel.
g5323.r: Of Hebrew origin פְּנוּאֵל (H6439)|English: Penuel, Peniel

g5324.d:
φαντάζω phantázō, fan-tad'-zo; from a derivative of G5316; to make apparent, i.e. (passively) to
 appear (neuter participle as noun, a spectacle):—sight.
g5324.r: From a derivative of φαίνω (G5316)|English: appear, shine, be seen, seem, think

g5325.d:
φαντασία phantasía, fan-tas-ee'-ah; from a derivative of G5324; (properly abstract) a (vain) show
 ("fantasy"):—pomp.
g5325.r: From a derivative of φαντάζω (G5324)|English: sight

g5326.d:
φάντασμα phántasma, fan'-tas-mah; from G5324; (properly concrete) a (mere) show ("phantasm"), i.e.
 spectre:—spirit.

g5327.d:
φάραγξ pháranx, far'-anx; properly, strengthened from the base of G4008 or rather of G4486; a gap
 or chasm, i.e. ravine (winter-torrent):—valley.
g5327.r: Properly, strengthened from the base of πέραν (G4008) or rather of ῥήγνυμι (G4486)|English: other side, beyond, over, on the other side, farther side

g5328.d:
Φαραώ Pharaṓ, far-ah-o'; of foreign origin (H6547); Pharao (i.e. Pharoh), an Egyptian
 king:—Pharaoh.

g5329.d: Φάρες Pháres, far-es'; of Hebrew origin (H6557); Phares (i.e. Perets), an Israelite:—Phares.
g5329.r: Of Hebrew origin פֶּרֶץ (H6557)|English: Pharez, Perez

g533.d: ἀπαρνέομαι aparnéomai, ap-ar-neh'-om-ahee; from G575 and G720; to deny utterly, i.e. disown, abstain:—deny.
g533.r: From ἀπό (G575) and ἀρνέομαι (G720)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5330.d:
†Φαρισαῖος Pharisaîos, far-is-ah'-yos; of Hebrew origin (compare H6567); a separatist, i.e. exclusively
 religious; a Pharisean, i.e. Jewish sectary:—Pharisee.
g5330.r: Of Hebrew origin cf פָּרַשׁ (H6567)|English: shew, scatter, declare, distinctly, sting

g5331.d:
†φαρμακεία pharmakeía, far-mak-i'-ah; from G5332; medication ("pharmacy"), i.e. (by extension) magic
 (literally or figuratively):—sorcery, witchcraft.

g5332.d:
φαρμακεύς pharmakeús, far-mak-yoos'; from φάρμακον phármakon (a drug, i.e. spell-giving potion); a druggist
 ("pharmacist") or poisoner, i.e. (by extension) a magician:—sorcerer.
g5332.r: From pharmakon (a drug, i.e. spell-giving potion)|

g5333.d: φάρμακος phármakos, far-mak-os'; the same as G5332:—sorcerer.

g5334.d:
φάσις phásis, fas'-is; from G5346 (not the same as "phase", which is from G5316); a saying,
 i.e. report:—tidings.
g5334.r: From φημί (G5346) (not the same as "phase", which is from φαίνω (G5316))|English: say, affirm

g5335.d: φάσκω pháskō, fas'-ko; prolongation from the same as G5346; to assert:—affirm, profess, say.
g5335.r: Prolongation from the same as φημί (G5346)|English: say, affirm

g5336.d: φάτνη phátnē, fat'-nay; from πατέομαι patéomai (to eat); a crib (for fodder):—manager, stall.

g5337.d:
φαῦλος phaûlos, fow'-los; apparently a primary word; "foul" or "flawy", i.e. (figuratively)
 wicked:—evil.

g5338.d: φέγγος phéngos, feng'-gos; probably akin to the base of G5457 (compare G5350); brilliancy:—light.
g5338.r: Probably akin to the base of φῶς (G5457) [cf φθέγγομαι (G5350)]|English: light, fire

g5339.d:
φείδομαι pheídomai, fi'-dom-ahee; of uncertain affinity; to be chary of, i.e. (subjectively) to abstain
 or (objectively) to treat leniently:—forbear, spare.

g534.d:
ἀπάρτι apárti, ap-ar'-tee; from G575 and G737; from now, i.e. henceforth (already):—from
 henceforth.
g534.r: From ἀπό (G575) and ἄρτι (G737)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5340.d:
φειδομένως pheidoménōs, fi-dom-en'-oce; adverb from participle of G5339; abstemiously, i.e.
 stingily:—sparingly.
g5340.r: From participle of φείδομαι (G5339)|English: spare, forbear

g5341.d:
†φελόνης phelónēs, fel-on'-ace; by transposition for a derivative probably of G5316 (as showing outside
 the other garments); a mantle (surtout):—cloke.
g5341.r: By transposition for a derivative probably of φαίνω (G5316) (as showing outside the other garments)|English: appear, shine, be seen, seem, think

g5342.r: A primary verb (for which other and apparently not cognate ones are used in certain tenses only, namely, oio {oy'-o}; and enegko {en-eng'-ko)|

g5343.d:
φεύγω pheúgō, fyoo'-go; apparently a primary verb; to run away (literally or figuratively); by
 implication, to shun; by analogy, to vanish:—escape, flee (away).

g5344.d: Φῆλιξ Phēlix, fay'-lix; of Latin origin; happy; Phelix (i.e. Felix), a Roman:—Felix.

g5345.d: φήμη phḗmē, fay'-may; from G5346; a saying, i.e. rumor ("fame"):—fame.

g5346.d:
φημί phēmí, fay-mee'; properly, the same as the base of G5457 and G5316; to show or make known
 one's thoughts, i.e. speak or say:—affirm, say. Compare G3004.
g5346.r: Properly, the same as the base of φῶς (G5457) and φαίνω (G5316)|English: light, fire

g5347.d: Φῆστος Phēstos, face'-tos; of Latin derivation; festal; Phestus (i.e. Festus), a Roman:—Festus.

g5348.d:
φθάνω phthánō, fthan'-o; apparently a primary verb; to be beforehand, i.e. anticipate or
 precede; by extension, to have arrived at:—(already) attain, come,
 prevent.

g5349.d: φθαρτός phthartós, fthar-tos'; from G5351; decayed, i.e. (by implication) perishable:—corruptible.
g5349.r: From φθείρω (G5351)|English: corrupt, corrupt (one's) self, be corrupt, defile, destroy

g535.d: ἀπαρτισμός apartismós, ap-ar-tis-mos'; from a derivative of G534; completion:—finishing.
g535.r: From a derivative of ἀπάρτι (G534)|English: from henceforth

g5350.d:
φθέγγομαι phthéngomai, ftheng'-gom-ahee; probably akin to G5338 and thus to G5346; to utter a clear sound, i.e.
 (generally) to proclaim:—speak.
g5350.r: Probably akin to φέγγος (G5338) and thus to φημί (G5346)|English: light

g5351.d:
φθείρω phtheírō, fthi'-ro; probably strengthened from φθίω phthíō (to pine or waste); properly, to
 shrivel or wither, i.e. to spoil (by any process) or (generally) to
 ruin (especially figuratively, by moral influences, to
 deprave):—corrupt (self), defile, destroy.
g5351.r: Probably strengthened from phthio (to pine or waste)|

g5352.d:
φθινοπωρινός phthinopōrinós, fthin-op-o-ree-nos'; from derivative of φθίνω phthínō (to wane; akin to the base of G5351) and
 G3703 (meaning late autumn); autumnal (as stripped of leaves):—whose
 fruit withereth.
g5352.r: From derivative of phthino (to wane; akin to the base of φθείρω (G5351)) and ὀπώρα (G3703) (meaning late autumn)|English: corrupt, corrupt (one's) self, be corrupt, defile, destroy

g5353.d:
φθόγγος phthóngos, ftong'-gos; from G5350; utterance, i.e. a musical note (vocal or
 instrumental):—sound.

g5354.d: φθονέω phthonéō, fthon-eh'-o; from G5355; to be jealous of:—envy.

g5355.d:
φθόνος phthónos, fthon'-os; probably akin to the base of G5351; ill-will (as detraction), i.e.
 jealousy (spite):—envy.
g5355.r: Probably akin to the base of φθείρω (G5351)|English: corrupt, corrupt (one's) self, be corrupt, defile, destroy

g5356.d:
φθορά phthorá, fthor-ah'; from G5351; decay, i.e. ruin (spontaneous or inflicted, literally or
 figuratively):—corruption, destroy, perish.
g5356.r: From φθείρω (G5351)|English: corrupt, corrupt (one's) self, be corrupt, defile, destroy

g5357.d: φιάλη phiálē, fee-al'-ay; of uncertain affinity; a broad shallow cup ("phial"):—vial.

g5358.d:
φιλάγαθος philágathos, fil-ag'-ath-os; from G5384 and G18; fond to good, i.e. a promoter of virtue:—love of
 good men.

g5359.d:
Φιλαδέλφεια Philadélpheia, fil-ad-el'-fee-ah; from Φιλάδελφος Philádelphos (the same as G5361), a king of Pergamos; 
 Philadelphia, a place in Asia Minor:—Philadelphia.
g5359.r: From Philadelphos (the same as φιλάδελφος (G5361))|English: love as brethren

g536.d:
ἀπαρχή aparchḗ, ap-ar-khay'; from a compound of G575 and G756; a beginning of sacrifice, i.e. the
 (Jewish) first-fruit (figuratively):—first-fruits.
g536.r: From a compound of ἀπό (G575) and ἄρχομαι (G756)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g5360.d:
φιλαδελφία philadelphía, fil-ad-el-fee'-ah; from G5361; fraternal affection:—brotherly love (kindness), love of
 the brethren.

g5361.d: φιλάδελφος philádelphos, fil-ad'-el-fos; from G5384 and G80; fond of brethren, i.e. fraternal:—love as brethren.

g5362.d:
φίλανδρος phílandros, fil'-an-dros; from G5384 and G435; fond of man, i.e. affectionate as a wife:—love
 their husbands.

g5363.d:
φιλανθρωπία philanthrōpía, fil-an-thro-pee'-ah; from the same as G5364; fondness of mankind, i.e. benevolence
 ("philanthropy"):—kindness, love towards man.
g5363.r: From the same as φιλανθρώπως (G5364)|English: courteously

g5364.d:
φιλανθρώπως philanthrṓpōs, fil-an-thro'-poce; adverb from a compound of G5384 and G444; fondly to man
 ("philanthropically"), i.e. humanely:—courteously.
g5364.r: From a compound of φίλος (G5384) and ἄνθρωπος (G444)|English: friend

g5365.d: φιλαργυρία philargyría, fil-ar-goo-ree'-ah; from G5366; avarice:—love of money.

g5366.d: φιλάργυρος philárgyros, fil-ar'-goo-ros; from G5384 and G696; fond of silver (money), i.e. avaricious:—covetous.

g5367.d: φίλαυτος phílautos, fil'-ow-tos; from G5384 and G846; fond of self, i.e. selfish:—lover of own self.

g5368.d:
φιλέω philéō, fil-eh'-o; from G5384; to be a friend to (fond of (an individual or an object)),
 i.e. have affection for (denoting personal attachment, as a matter of
 sentiment or feeling; while G25 is wider, embracing especially the
 judgment and the deliberate assent of the will as a matter of
 principle, duty and propriety: the two thus stand related very much as
 G2309 and G1014, or as G2372 and G3563 respectively; the former being
 chiefly of the heart and the latter of the head); specially, to kiss
 (as a mark of tenderness):—kiss, love.

g5369.d:
φιλήδονος philḗdonos, fil-ay'-don-os; from G5384 and G2237; fond of pleasure, i.e. voluptuous:—lover of
 pleasure.

g537.d:
ἅπας hápas, hap'-as; from G1 (as a particle of union) and G3956; absolutely all or (singular)
 every one:—all (things), every (one), whole.
g537.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a particle of union) and πᾶς (G3956)|English: Alpha

g5370.d: φίλημα phílēma, fil'-ay-mah; from G5368; a kiss:—kiss.

g5371.d: Φιλήμων Philḗmōn, fil-ay'-mone; from G5368; friendly; Philemon, a Christian:—Philemon.

g5372.d: Φίλητος Phílētos, fil-ay-tos'; from G5368; amiable; Philetus, an opposer of Christianity:—Philetus.

g5373.d: φιλία philía, fil-ee'-ah; from G5384; fondness:—friendship.

g5374.d:
Φιλιππήσιος Philippḗsios, fil-ip-pay'-see-os; from G5375; a Philippesian (Philippian), i.e. native of
 Philippi:—Philippian.

g5375.d: Φίλιπποι Phílippoi, fil'-ip-poy; plural of G5376; Philippi, a place in Macedonia:—Philippi.
g5375.r: Plural of Φίλιππος (G5376)|English: Philip (the apostle), Philip (the evangelist), Philip (Herod), Philippi (an adjunct of Caesarea), Philip (the tetrarch)

g5376.d:
Φίλιππος Phílippos, fil'-ip-pos; from G5384 and G2462; fond of horses; Philippus, the name of four
 Israelites:—Philip.

g5377.d: φιλόθεος philótheos, fil-oth'-eh-os; from G5384 and G2316; fond of God, i.e. pious:—lover of God.

g5378.d:
Φιλόλογος Philólogos, fil-ol'-og-os; from G5384 and G3056; fond of words, i.e. talkative (argumentative,
 learned, "philological"); Philologus, a Christian:—Philologus.

g5379.d: φιλονεικία philoneikía, fil-on-i-kee'-ah; from G5380; quarrelsomeness, i.e. a dispute:—strife.

g538.d: ἀπατάω apatáō, ap-at-ah'-o; of uncertain derivation; to cheat, i.e. delude:—deceive.

g5380.d:
φιλόνεικος philóneikos, fil-on'-i-kos; from G5384 and νεῖκος neîkos (a quarrel; probably akin to G3534); fond of
 strife, i.e. disputatious:—contentious.
g5380.r: From φίλος (G5384) and neikos (a quarrel, probably akin to νῖκος (G3534))|English: friend

g5381.d: †φιλονεξία philonexía, fil-on-ex-ee'-ah; from G5382; hospitableness:—entertain stranger, hospitality.
g5381.r: From φιλόξενος (G5382)|English: given to hospitality, lover of hospitality, use hospitality

g5382.d:
φιλόξενος philóxenos, fil-ox'-en-os; from G5384 and G3581; fond of guests, i.e. hospitable:—given to (lover
 of, use) hospitality.

g5383.d:
φιλοπρωτεύω philoprōteúō, fil-op-rote-yoo'-o; from a compound of G5384 and G4413; to be fond of being first, i.e.
 ambitious of distinction:—love to have the preeminence.
g5383.r: From a compound of φίλος (G5384) and πρῶτος (G4413)|English: friend

g5384.d:
†φίλος phílos, fee'-los; properly, dear, i.e. a friend; actively, fond, i.e. friendly (still as
 a noun, an associate, neighbor, etc.):—friend.

g5385.d:
φιλοσοφία philosophía, fil-os-of-ee'-ah; from G5386; "philosophy", i.e. (specially), Jewish
 sophistry:—philosophy.

g5386.d:
φιλόσοφος philósophos, fil-os'-of-os; from G5384 and G4680; fond of wise things, i.e. a
 "philosopher":—philosopher.

g5387.d:
φιλόστοργος philóstorgos, fil-os'-tor-gos; from G5384 and στοργή storgḗ (cherishing one's kindred, especially parents or
 children); fond of natural relatives, i.e. fraternal towards fellow
 Christian:—kindly affectioned.
g5387.r: From φίλος (G5384) and storge (cherishing one's kindred, especially parents or children)|English: friend

g5388.d:
φιλότεκνος philóteknos, fil-ot'-ek-nos; from G5384 and G5043; fond of one's children, i.e. maternal:—love their
 children.

g5389.d:
φιλοτιμέομαι philotiméomai, fil-ot-im-eh'-om-ahee; middle voice from a compound of G5384 and G5092; to be fond of honor,
 i.e. emulous (eager or earnest to do something):—labour, strive,
 study.
g5389.r: Middle voice from a compound of φίλος (G5384) and τιμή (G5092)|English: friend

g539.d: ἀπάτη apátē, ap-at'-ay; from G538; delusion:—deceit(-ful, -fulness), deceivableness(-ving).

g5390.d:
φιλοφρόνως philophrónōs, fil-of-ron'-oce; adverb from G5391; with friendliness of mind, i.e.
 kindly:—courteously.

g5392.d: †φιμόω phimóō, fee-mo'-o; from φιμός phimós (a muzzle); to muzzle:—muzzle.

g5393.d:
Φλέγων Phlégōn, fleg'-one; active participle of the base of G5395; blazing; Phlegon, a
 Christian:—Phlegon.
g5393.r: Active participle of the base of φλόξ (G5395)|English: flame, flaming

g5394.d:
φλογίζω phlogízō, flog-id'-zo; from G5395; to cause a blaze, i.e. ignite (figuratively, to inflame
 with passion):—set on fire.

g5395.d: φλόξ phlóx, flox; from a primary φλέγω phlégō (to "flash" or "flame"); a blaze:—flame(-ing).

g5396.d:
φλυαρέω phlyaréō, floo-ar-eh'-o; from G5397; to be a babbler or trifler, i.e. (by implication) to berate
 idly or mischievously:—prate against.

g5397.d: φλύαρος phlýaros, floo'-ar-os; from φλύω phlýō (to bubble); a garrulous person, i.e. prater:—tattler.

g5398.d:
