ἀπροσωπολήπτως aprosōpolḗptōs, ap-ros-o-pol-ape'-tos; adverb from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed
 derivative of a presumed compound of G4383 and G2983 (compare G4381); in
 a way not accepting the person, i.e. impartially:—without respect of
 persons.
g678.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a presumed compound of πρόσωπον (G4383) and λαμβάνω (G2983) [cf προσωπολήμπτης (G4381)]|English: Alpha

g679.d:
ἄπταιστος áptaistos, ap-tah'-ee-stos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G4417; not
 stumbling, i.e. (figuratively) without sin:—from falling.
g679.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of πταίω (G4417)|English: Alpha

g68.d:
ἀγρός agrós, ag-ros'; from G71; a field (as a drive for cattle); genitive case, the country;
 specially, a farm, i.e. hamlet:—country, farm, piece of ground, land.
g68.r: From ἄγω (G71)|English: bring, lead, go, bring forth, misc, vr bring

g681.d:
†ἅπτω háptō, hap'-to; a primary verb; properly, to fasten to, i.e. (specially) to set on
 fire:—kindle, light.

g682.d: Ἀπφία Apphía, ap-fee'-a; probably of foreign origin; Apphia, a woman of Collosæ:—Apphia.

g683.d:
†ἀπωθέομαι apōthéomai, ap-o-theh'-om-ahee; from G575 and the middle voice of ὠθέω ōthéō or ὤθω ṓthō (to shove); to push
 off, figuratively, to reject:—cast away, put away (from), thrust away
 (from).
g683.r: From ἀπό (G575) and the middle voice of otheo or otho (to shove)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g684.d:
ἀπώλεια apṓleia, ap-o'-li-a; from a presumed derivative of G622; ruin or loss (physical, spiritual
 or eternal):—damnable(-nation), destruction, die, perdition, X
 perish, pernicious ways, waste.
g684.r: From a presumed derivative of ἀπόλλυμι (G622)|English: perish, destroy, lose, be lost, lost, misc

g685.d:
ἀρά ará, ar-ah'; probably from G142; properly, prayer (as lifted to Heaven), i.e. (by
 implication) imprecation:—curse.
g685.r: Probably from αἴρω (G142)|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g686.d:
ἄρα ára, ar'-ah; probably from G142 (through the idea of drawing a conclusion); a
 particle denoting an inference more or less decisive (as
 follows):—haply, (what) manner (of man), no doubt, perhaps, so be,
 then, therefore, truly, wherefore. Often used in connection with other
 particles, especially G1065 or G3767 (after) or G1487 (before). Compare
 also G687.
g686.r: Probably from αἴρω (G142) (through the idea of drawing a conclusion)|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g687.d:
ἆρα âra, ar'-ah; a form of G686, denoting an interrogation to which a negative answer is
 presumed:—therefore.
g687.r: A form of ἄρα (G686), denoting an interrogation to which a negative answer is presumed|English: therefore, so then, now therefore, then, wherefore, haply, not tr, misc

g688.d: Ἀραβία Arabía, ar-ab-ee'-ah; of Hebrew origin (H6152); Arabia, a region of Asia:—Arabia.

g689.d: †Ἀράμ Arám, ar-am'; of Hebrew origin (H7410); Aram (i.e. Ram), an Israelite:—Aram.

g69.d:
ἀγρυπνέω agrypnéō, ag-roop-neh'-o; ultimately from G1 (as negative particle) and G5258; to be sleepless,
 i.e. keep awake:—watch.
g69.r: Ultimately from ἄλφα (G1) (as negative particle) and ὕπνος (G5258)|English: Alpha

g690.d: Ἄραψ Áraps, ar'-aps; from G688; an Arab or native of Arabia:—Arabian.

g691.d: ἀργέω argéō, arg-eh'-o; from G692; to be idle, i.e. (figuratively) to delay:—linger.

g692.d:
ἀργός argós, ar-gos'; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G2041; inactive, i.e. unemployed;
 (by implication) lazy, useless:—barren, idle, slow.
g692.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and ἔργον (G2041)|English: Alpha

g693.d: †ἀργύρεος argýreos, ar-goo'-reh-os; from G696; made of silver:—(of) silver.

g694.d:
ἀργύριον argýrion, ar-goo'-ree-on; neuter of a presumed derivative of G696; silvery, i.e. (by implication)
 cash; specially, a silverling (i.e. drachma or shekel):—money, (piece
 of) silver (piece).
g694.r: Neuter of a presumed derivative of ἄργυρος (G696)|English: silver

g695.d: ἀργυροκόπος argyrokópos, ar-goo-rok-op'-os; from G696 and G2875; a beater (i.e. worker) of silver:—silversmith.

g696.d:
ἄργυρος árgyros, ar'-goo-ros; from ἀργός argós (shining); silver (the metal, in the articles or
 coin):—silver.

g697.d:
†Ἄρειος Πάγος Áreios Págos, ar'-i-os pag'-os; from Ἄρης Árēs (the name of the Greek deity of war) and a derivative of
 G4078; rock of Ares, a place in Athens:—Areopagus, Mars' Hill.
g697.r: From Ares (the name of the Greek deity of war) and a derivative of πήγνυμι (G4078)|English: pitch

g698.d:
Ἀρεοπαγίτης Areopagítēs, ar-eh-op-ag-ee'-tace; from G697; an Areopagite or member of the court held on Mars'
 Hill:—Areopagite.
g698.r: From Ἄρειος πάγος (G697)|English: Areopagus, Mars Hill

g699.d: †ἀρεσκεία areskeía, ar-es'-ki-ah; from a derivative of G700; complaisance:—pleasing.
g699.r: From a derivative of ἀρέσκω (G700)|English: please

g7.d: Ἀβιά Abiá, ab-ee-ah'; of Hebrew origin (H29); Abijah, the name of two Israelites:—Abia.
g7.r: Of Hebrew origin אֲבִיָה (H29)|English: Abijah, Abiah, Abia

g70.d: ἀγρυπνία agrypnía, ag-roop-nee'-ah; from G69; sleeplessness, i.e. a keeping awake:—watch.

g700.d:
ἀρέσκω aréskō, ar-es'-ko; probably from G142 (through the idea of exciting emotion); to be
 agreeable (or by implication, to seek to be so):—please.
g700.r: Probably from αἴρω (G142) (through the idea of exciting emotion)|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g701.d:
ἀρεστός arestós, ar-es-tos'; from G700; agreeable; by implication, fit:—(things that) please(-ing),
 reason.

g702.d: Ἀρέτας Arétas, ar-et'-as; of foreign origin; Aretas, an Arabian:—Aretas.

g703.d:
ἀρέτη arétē, ar-et'-ay; from the same as G730; properly, manliness (valor), i.e. excellence
 (intrinsic or attributed):—praise, virtue.
g703.r: From the same as ἄρρην (G730)|English: male, man, man child, man child

g704.d: ἀρήν arḗn, ar-ane'; perhaps the same as G730; a lamb (as a male):—lamb.
g704.r: Perhaps the same as ἄρρην (G730)|English: male, man, man child, man child

g705.d: ἀριθμέω arithméō, ar-ith-meh'-o; from G706; to enumerate or count:—number.

g706.d: ἀριθμός arithmós, ar-ith-mos'; from G142; a number (as reckoned up):—number.
g706.r: From αἴρω (G142)|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g707.d:
Ἀριμαθαία Arimathaía, ar-ee-math-ah'-ee-ah; of Hebrew origin (H7414); Arimathæa (or Ramah), a place in
 Palestine:—Arimathæa.

g708.d:
Ἀρίσταρχος Arístarchos, ar-is'-tar-khos; from the same as G712 and G757; best ruling; Aristarchus, a
 Macedonian:—Aristarchus.
g708.r: From the same as ἄριστον (G712) and ἄρχω (G757)|English: dinner

g709.d: ἀριστάω aristáō, ar-is-tah'-o; from G712; to take the principle meal:—dine.

g71.d:
ἄγω ágō, ag'-o; a primary verb; properly, to lead; by implication, to bring, drive,
 (reflexively) go, (specially) pass (time), or (figuratively)
 induce:—be, bring (forth), carry, (let) go, keep, lead away, be open.

g710.d:
ἀριστερός aristerós, ar-is-ter-os'; apparently a comparative of the same as G712; the left hand (as
 second-best):—left (hand).
g710.r: Apparently a comparative of the same as ἄριστον (G712)|English: dinner

g711.d:
Ἀριστόβουλος Aristóboulos, ar-is-tob'-oo-los; from the same as G712 and G1012; best counselling; Aristoboulus, a
 Christian:—Aristobulus.
g711.r: From the same as ἄριστον (G712) and βουλή (G1012)|English: dinner

g712.d:
ἄριστον áriston, ar'-is-ton; apparently neuter of a superlative from the same as G730; the best meal
 (or breakfast; perhaps from ἦρι ēri ("early")), i.e. luncheon:—dinner.
g712.r: Apparently neuter of a superlative from the same as ἄρρην (G730)|English: male, man, man child, man child

g713.d: ἀρκετός arketós, ar-ket-os'; from G714; satisfactory:—enough, suffice (-ient).
g713.r: From ἀρκέω (G714)|English: be content, be sufficient, be enough, suffice, content

g714.d:
ἀρκέω arkéō, ar-keh'-o; apparently a primary verb (but probably akin to G142 through the idea
 of raising a barrier); properly, to ward off, i.e. (by implication) to
 avail (figuratively, be satisfactory):—be content, be enough,
 suffice, be sufficient.
g714.r: Apparently a primary word [but probably akin to αἴρω (G142) through the idea of raising a barrier]|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g715.d: †ἄρκτος árktos, ark'-tos; probably from G714; a bear (as obstructing by ferocity):—bear.
g715.r: Probably from ἀρκέω (G714)|English: be content, be sufficient, be enough, suffice, content

g716.d:
ἅρμα hárma, har'-mah; probably from G142 (perhaps with G1 (as a particle of union) prefixed); 
 a chariot (as raised or fitted together (compare G719)):—chariot.
g716.r: Probably from αἴρω (G142) [perhaps with ἄλφα (G1) (as a particle of union) prefixed]|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g717.d:
†Ἀρμαγεδδών Armageddṓn, ar-mag-ed-dohn'; of Hebrew origin (H2022 and H4023); Armageddon (or Har-Meggiddon), a
 symbolic name:—Armageddon.
g717.r: Of Hebrew origin הַר (H2022) and מְגִדּוֹן (H4023)|English: mountain, mount, hill, hill country, promotion

g718.d:
ἁρμόζω harmózō, har-mod'-zo; from G719; to joint, i.e. (figuratively) to woo (reflexively, to
 betroth):—espouse.

g719.d: ἁρμός harmós, har-mos'; from the same as G716; an articulation (of the body):—joint.
g719.r: From the same as ἅρμα (G716)|English: chariot

g72.d:
ἀγωγή agōgḗ, ag-o-gay'; reduplicated from G71; a bringing up, i.e. mode of living:—manner of
 life.
g72.r: Reduplicated from ἄγω (G71)|English: bring, lead, go, bring forth, misc, vr bring

g720.d:
ἀρνέομαι arnéomai, ar-neh'-om-ahee; perhaps from G1 (as a negative particle) and the middle voice of G4483; 
 to contradict, i.e. disavow, reject, abnegate:—deny, refuse.
g720.r: Perhaps from ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and the middle voice of ῥέω (G4483)|English: Alpha

g721.d: ἀρνίον arníon, ar-nee'-on; diminutive from G704; a lambkin:—lamb.

g722.d: †ἀροτριόω arotrióō, ar-ot-ree-o'-o; from G723; to plow:—plough.

g723.d: ἄροτρον árotron, ar'-ot-ron; from ἀρόω aróō (to till); a plow:—plough.

g724.d: ἁρπαγή harpagḗ, har-pag-ay'; from G726; pillage (properly abstract):—extortion, ravening, spoiling.
g724.r: From ἁρπάζω (G726)|English: catch up, take by force, catch away, pluck, catch, pull

g725.d: ἁρπαγμός harpagmós, har-pag-mos'; from G726; plunder (properly concrete):—robbery.
g725.r: From ἁρπάζω (G726)|English: catch up, take by force, catch away, pluck, catch, pull

g726.d:
ἁρπάζω harpázō, har-pad'-zo; from a derivative of G138; to seize (in various applications):—catch
 (away, up), pluck, pull, take (by force).
g726.r: From a derivative of αἱρέω (G138)|English: choose

g727.d: ἅρπαξ hárpax, har'-pax; from G726; rapacious:—extortion, ravening.
g727.r: From ἁρπάζω (G726)|English: catch up, take by force, catch away, pluck, catch, pull

g728.d:
ἀῤῥαβών arrhabṓn, ar-hrab-ohn'; of Hebrew origin (H6162); a pledge, i.e. part of the purchase-money or
 property given in advance as security for the rest:—earnest.

g73.d:
ἀγών agṓn, ag-one'; from G71; properly, a place of assembly (as if led), i.e. (by
 implication) a contest (held there); figuratively, an effort or
 anxiety:—conflict, contention, fight, race.
g73.r: From ἄγω (G71)|English: bring, lead, go, bring forth, misc, vr bring

g731.d:
ἄῤῥητος árrhētos, ar'-hray-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and the same as G4490; unsaid, i.e. (by
 implication) inexpressible:—unspeakable.
g731.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and the same as ῥητῶς (G4490)|English: Alpha

g732.d:
ἄῤῥωστος árrhōstos, ar'-hroce-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G4517; 
 infirm:—sick (folk, -ly).
g732.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ῥώννυμι (G4517)|English: Alpha

g733.d:
ἀρσενοκοίτης arsenokoítēs, ar-sen-ok-oy'-tace; from G730 and G2845; a sodomite:—abuser of (that defile) self with
 mankind.
g733.r: From ἄρρην (G730) and κοίτη (G2845)|English: male, man, man child, man child

g734.d:
Ἀρτεμάς Artemás, ar-tem-as'; contracted from a compound of G735 and G1435; gift of Artemis; Artemas
 (or Artemidorus), a Christian:—Artemas.
g734.r: Contracted from a compound of Ἄρτεμις (G735) and δῶρον (G1435)|English: Diana

g735.d:
Ἄρτεμις Ártemis, ar'-tem-is; probably from the same as G736; prompt; Artemis, the name of a Grecian
 goddess borrowed by the Asiatics for one of their deities:—Diana.
g735.r: Probably from the same as ἀρτέμων (G736)|English: mainsail

g736.d:
ἀρτέμων artémōn, ar-tem'-ohn; from a derivative of G737; properly, something ready (or else more
 remotely from G142 (compare G740); something hung up), i.e. (specially)
 the topsail (rather foresail or jib) of a vessel:—mainsail.
g736.r: From a derivative of ἄρτι (G737)|English: now, henceforth, hereafter, this present, hitherto, misc

g737.d:
ἄρτι árti, ar'-tee; adverb from a derivative of G142 (compare G740) through the idea of
 suspension; just now:—this day (hour), hence(-forth), here(-after),
 hither(-to), (even) now, (this) present.
g737.r: From a derivative of αἴρω (G142) (cf ἄρτος (G740)) through the idea of suspension|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g738.d:
ἀρτιγέννητος artigénnētos, ar-teeg-en'-nay-tos; from G737 and G1084; just born, i.e. (figuratively) a young
 convert:—new born.
g738.r: From ἄρτι (G737) and γεννητός (G1084)|English: now, henceforth, hereafter, this present, hitherto, misc

g739.d: ἄρτιος ártios, ar'-tee-os; from G737; fresh, i.e. (by implication) complete:—perfect.
g739.r: From ἄρτι (G737)|English: now, henceforth, hereafter, this present, hitherto, misc

g74.d:
ἀγωνία agōnía, ag-o-nee'-ah; from G73; a struggle (properly, the state), i.e. (figuratively)
 anguish:—agony.
g74.r: From ἀγών (G73)|English: conflict, fight, contention, race

g740.d: ἄρτος ártos, ar'-tos; from G142; bread (as raised) or a loaf:—(shew-)bread, loaf.
g740.r: From αἴρω (G142)|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g741.d:
ἀρτύω artýō, ar-too'-o; from a presumed derivative of G142; to prepare, i.e. spice (with
 stimulating condiments):—season.
g741.r: From a presumed derivative of αἴρω (G142)|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g742.d:
Ἀρφαξάδ Arphaxád, ar-fax-ad'; of Hebrew origin (H775); Arphaxad, a post-diluvian
 patriarch:—Arphaxad.

g743.d: ἀρχάγγελος archángelos, ar-khang'-el-os; from G757 and G32; a chief angel:—archangel.
g743.r: From ἄρχω (G757) and ἄγγελος (G32)|English: rule over, reign over

g744.d: ἀρχαῖος archaîos, ar-khah'-yos; from G746; original or primeval:—(them of) old (time).
g744.r: From ἀρχή (G746)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g745.d:
Ἀρχέλαος Archélaos, ar-khel'-ah-os; from G757 and G2994; people-ruling; Archelaus, a Jewish
 king:—Archelaus.
g745.r: From ἄρχω (G757) and Λαοδικεύς (G2994)|English: rule over, reign over

g746.d:
ἀρχή archḗ, ar-khay'; from G756; (properly abstract) a commencement, or (concretely) chief
 (in various applications of order, time, place, or rank):—beginning,
 corner, (at the, the) first (estate), magistrate, power, principality,
 principle, rule.
g746.r: From ἄρχομαι (G756)|English: begin, rehearse from the beginning

g747.d: ἀρχηγός archēgós, ar-khay-gos'; from G746 and G71; a chief leader:—author, captain, prince.
g747.r: From ἀρχή (G746) and ἄγω (G71)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g748.d: ἀρχιερατικός archieratikós, ar-khee-er-at-ee-kos'; from G746 and a derivative of G2413; high-priestly:—of the high-priest.
g748.r: From ἀρχή (G746) and a derivative of ἱερός (G2413)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g749.d:
ἀρχιερεύς archiereús, ar-khee-er-yuce'; from G746 and G2409; the high-priest (literally, of the Jews, typically,
 Christ); by extension a chief priest:—chief (high) priest, chief of
 the priests.
g749.r: From ἀρχή (G746) and ἱερεύς (G2409)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g75.d:
ἀγωνίζομαι agōnízomai, ag-o-nid'-zom-ahee; from G73; to struggle, literally (to compete for a prize), figuratively
 (to contend with an adversary), or genitive case (to endeavor to
 accomplish something):—fight, labor fervently, strive.
g75.r: From ἀγών (G73)|English: conflict, fight, contention, race

g750.d: ἀρχιποίμην archipoímēn, ar-khee-poy'-mane; from G746 and G4166; a head shepherd:—chief shepherd.
g750.r: From ἀρχή (G746) and ποιμήν (G4166)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g751.d: Ἄρχιππος Árchippos, ar'-khip-pos; from G746 and G2462; horse-ruler; Archippus, a Christian:—Archippus.
g751.r: From ἀρχή (G746) and ἵππος (G2462)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g752.d:
ἀρχισυνάγωγος archisynágōgos, ar-khee-soon-ag'-o-gos; from G746 and G4864; director of the synagogue services:—(chief) ruler
 of the synagogue.
g752.r: From ἀρχή (G746) and συναγωγή (G4864)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g753.d:
ἀρχιτέκτων architéktōn, ar-khee-tek'-tone; from G746 and G5045; a chief constructor, i.e.
 "architect":—masterbuilder.
g753.r: From ἀρχή (G746) and τέκτων (G5045)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g754.d:
ἀρχιτελώνης architelṓnēs, ar-khee-tel-o'-nace; from G746 and G5057; a principle tax-gatherer:—chief among the
 publicans.
g754.r: From ἀρχή (G746) and τελώνης (G5057)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g755.d:
ἀρχιτρίκλινος architríklinos, ar-khee-tree'-klee-nos; from G746 and a compound of G5140 and G2827 (a dinner-bed, because
 composed of three couches); director of the entertainment:—governor
 (ruler) of the feast.
g755.r: From ἀρχή (G746) and a compound of τρεῖς (G5140) and κλίνω (G2827) (a dinner-bed, because composed of three couches)|English: beginning, principality, corner, first, misc

g757.d:
ἄρχω árchō, ar'-kho; a primary verb; to be first (in political rank or power):—reign
 (rule) over.

g758.d:
ἄρχων árchōn, ar'-khone; present participle of G757; a first (in rank or power):—chief (ruler),
 magistrate, prince, ruler.
g758.r: Present participle of ἄρχω (G757)|English: rule over, reign over

g759.d:
ἄρωμα árōma, ar'-o-mah; from G142 (in the sense of sending off scent); an aromatic:—(sweet)
 spice.
g759.r: From αἴρω (G142) (in the sense of sending off scent)|English: take up, take away, take, away with, lift up, bear, misc

g76.d:
Ἀδάμ Adám, ad-am'; of Hebrew origin (H121); Adam, the first man; typically (of Jesus) man
 (as his representative):—Adam.

g760.d: †Ἀσά Asá, as-ah'; of Hebrew origin (H609); Asa, an Israelite:—Asa.

g761.d:
ἀσάλευτος asáleutos, as-al'-yoo-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G4531; unshaken,
 i.e. (by implication) immovable (figuratively):—which cannot be
 moved, unmovable.
g761.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of σαλεύω (G4531)|English: Alpha

g762.d:
ἄσβεστος ásbestos, as'-bes-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G4570; not
 extinguished, i.e. (by implication) perpetual:—not to be quenched,
 unquenchable.
g762.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of σβέννυμι (G4570)|English: Alpha

g763.d:
ἀσέβεια asébeia, as-eb'-i-ah; from G765; impiety, i.e. (by implication)
 wickedness:—ungodly(-liness).

g764.d:
ἀσεβέω asebéō, as-eb-eh'-o; from G765; to be (by implied act) impious or wicked:—commit (live,
 that after should live) ungodly.

g765.d:
ἀσεβής asebḗs, as-eb-ace'; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G4576; 
 irreverent, i.e. (by extension) impious or wicked:—ungodly (man).
g765.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of σέβω (G4576)|English: Alpha

g766.d:
ἀσέλγεια asélgeia, as-elg'-i-a; from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed
 σελγής selgḗs (of uncertain derivation, but apparently meaning
 continent); licentiousness (sometimes including other
 vices):—filthy, lasciviousness, wantonness.
g766.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed selges (of uncertain derivation, but apparently meaning continent)|English: Alpha

g767.d:
ἄσημος ásēmos, as'-ay-mos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and the base of G4591; unmarked, i.e.
 (figuratively) ignoble:—mean.
g767.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and the base of σημαίνω (G4591)|English: Alpha

g768.d: Ἀσήρ Asḗr, as-ayr'; of Hebrew origin (H836); Aser (i.e. Asher), an Israelite tribe:—Aser.

g769.d:
ἀσθένεια asthéneia, as-then'-i-ah; from G772; feebleness (of mind or body); by implication, malady;
 morally, frailty:—disease, infirmity, sickness, weakness.
g769.r: From ἀσθενής (G772)|English: weak, sick, weakness, weaker, weak things, impotent, more feeble, without strength

g77.d:
ἀδάπανος adápanos, ad-ap'-an-os; from G1 (as negative particle); and G1160; costless, i.e.
 gratuitous:—without expense.
g77.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as negative particle) and δαπάνη (G1160)|English: Alpha

g770.d:
ἀσθενέω asthenéō, as-then-eh'-o; from G772; to be feeble (in any sense):—be diseased, impotent folk
 (man), (be) sick, (be, be made) weak.
g770.r: From ἀσθενής (G772)|English: weak, sick, weakness, weaker, weak things, impotent, more feeble, without strength

g771.d: ἀσθένημα asthénēma, as-then'-ay-mah; from G770; a scruple of conscience:—infirmity.
g771.r: From ἀσθενέω (G770)|English: be weak, be sick, sick, weak, impotent man, be diseased, be made weak

g772.d:
ἀσθενής asthenḗs, as-then-ace'; from G1 (as a negative particle) and the base of G4599; strengthless (in
 various applications, literal, figurative and moral):—more feeble,
 impotent, sick, without strength, weak(-er, -ness, thing).
g772.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and the base of σθενόω (G4599)|English: Alpha

g773.d:
Ἀσία Asía, as-ee'-ah; of uncertain derivation; Asia, i.e. Asia Minor, or (usually) only its
 western shore:—Asia.

g774.d: Ἀσιανός Asianós, as-ee-an-os'; from G773; an Asian (i.e. Asiatic) or an inhabitant of Asia:—of Asia.

g775.d:
Ἀσιάρχης Asiárchēs, as-ee-ar'-khace; from G773 and G746; an Asiarch or president of the public festivities in
 a city of Asia Minor:—chief of Asia.

g776.d: ἀσιτία asitía, as-ee-tee'-ah; from G777; fasting (the state):—abstinence.

g777.d:
ἄσιτος ásitos, as'-ee-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G4621; without (taking)
 food:—fasting.
g777.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and σῖτος (G4621)|English: Alpha

g778.d:
ἀσκέω askéō, as-keh'-o; probably from the same as G4632; to elaborate, i.e. (figuratively)
 train (by implication, strive):—exercise.
g778.r: Probably from the same as σκεῦος (G4632)|English: vessel, goods, stuff, sail

g779.d:
ἀσκός askós, as-kos'; from the same as G778; a leathern (or skin) bag used as a
 bottle:—bottle.
g779.r: From the same as ἀσκέω (G778)|English: exercise

g78.d: Ἀδδί Addí, ad-dee'; probably of Hebrew origin (compare H5716); Addi, an Israelite:—Addi.
g78.r: Probably of Hebrew origin, cf עֲדִי (H5716)|English: ornament, mouth, excellent

g780.d: ἀσμένως asménōs, as-men'-oce; adverb from a derivative of the base of G2237; with pleasure:—gladly.
g780.r: From a derivative of the base of ἡδονή (G2237)|English: pleasure, lust

g781.d: ἄσοφος ásophos, as'-of-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G4680; unwise:—fool.
g781.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and σοφός (G4680)|English: Alpha

g782.d:
†ἀσπάζομαι aspázomai, as-pad'-zom-ahee; from G1 (as a particle of union) and a presumed form of G4685; to enfold
 in the arms, i.e. (by implication) to salute, (figuratively) to
 welcome:—embrace, greet, salute, take leave.
g782.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a particle of union) and a presumed form of σπάω (G4685)|English: Alpha

g783.d: ἀσπασμός aspasmós, as-pas-mos'; from G782; a greeting (in person or by letter):—greeting, salutation.
g783.r: From ἀσπάζομαι (G782)|English: salute, greet, embrace, take leave

g784.d:
ἄσπιλος áspilos, as'-pee-los; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G4695; unblemished (physically or
 morally):—without spot, unspotted.
g784.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and σπιλόω (G4695)|English: Alpha

g785.d:
ἀσπίς aspís, as-pece'; of uncertain derivation; a buckler (or round shield); used of a
 serpent (as coiling itself), probably the "asp":—asp.

g786.d:
ἄσπονδος áspondos, as'-pon-dos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G4689; literally,
 without libation (which usually accompanied a treaty), i.e. (by
 implication) truceless:—implacable, truce-breaker.
g786.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of σπένδω (G4689)|English: Alpha

g787.d: ἀσσάριον assárion, as-sar'-ee-on; of Latin origin; an assarius or as, a Roman coin:—farthing.

g788.d:
ἆσσον âsson, as'-son; neuter comparative of the base of G1451; more nearly, i.e. very
 near:—close.
g788.r: Neuter comparative of the base of ἐγγύς (G1451)|English: nigh, at hand, nigh at hand, near, from, nigh unto, ready

g789.d: Ἄσσος Ássos, as'-sos; probably of foreign origin; Assus, a city of Asia MInor:—Assos.

g79.d: ἀδελφή adelphḗ, ad-el-fay'; feminine of G80; a sister (naturally or ecclesiastically):—sister.
g79.r: From ἀδελφός (G80)|English: brethren, brother, brother's, brother's way

g790.d:
ἀστατέω astatéō, as-tat-eh'-o; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G2476; to be
 non-stationary, i.e. (figuratively) homeless:—have no certain
 dwelling-place.
g790.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of ἵστημι (G2476)|English: Alpha

g791.d: ἀστεῖος asteîos, as-ti'-os; from ἄστυ ásty (a city); urbane, i.e. (by implication) handsome:—fair.

g792.d:
ἀστήρ astḗr, as-tare'; probably from the base of G4766; a star (as strown over the sky),
 literally or figuratively:—star.
g792.r: Probably from the base of στρωννύω (G4766)|English: spread, straw, furnish, make (one's) bed

g793.d:
ἀστήρικτος astḗriktos, as-tay'-rik-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G4741; 
 unfixed, i.e. (figuratively) vacillating:—unstable.
g793.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of στηρίζω (G4741)|English: Alpha

g794.d:
ἄστοργος ástorgos, as'-tor-gos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of
 στέργω stérgō (to cherish affectionately); hard-hearted towards
 kindred:—without natural affection.
g794.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of stergo (to cherish affectionately)|English: Alpha

g795.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and stoichos (an aim)|English: Alpha

g796.d: ἀστραπή astrapḗ, as-trap-ay'; from G797; lightning; by analogy, glare:—lightning, bright shining.

g797.d: ἀστράπτω astráptō, as-trap'-to; probably from G792; to flash as lightning:—lighten, shine.

g798.d:
ἄστρον ástron, as'-tron; neuter from G792; properly, a constellation; put for a single star
 (natural or artificial):—star.

g799.d:
Ἀσύγκριτος Asýnkritos, as-oong'-kree-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G4793; 
 incomparable; Asyncritus, a Christian:—Asyncritos.
g799.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of συγκρίνω (G4793)|English: Alpha

g8.d: †Ἀβιαθάρ Abiathár, ab-ee-ath'-ar; of Hebrew origin (H54); Abiathar, an Israelite:—Abiathar.

g80.d:
ἀδελφός adelphós, ad-el-fos'; from G1 (as a connective particle) and δελφύς delphýs (the womb); a brother
 (literally or figuratively) near or remote (much like G1):—brother.
g80.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a connective particle) and delphus (the womb)|English: Alpha

g800.d:
ἀσύμφωνος asýmphōnos, as-oom'-fo-nos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G4859; inharmonious
 (figuratively):—agree not.
g800.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and σύμφωνος (G4859)|English: Alpha

g801.d:
ἀσύνετος asýnetos, as-oon'-ay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G4908; unintelligent; by
 implication, wicked:—foolish, without understanding.
g801.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and συνετός (G4908)|English: Alpha

g802.d:
ἀσύνθετος asýnthetos, as-oon'-thet-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G4934; properly,
 not agreed, i.e. treacherous to compacts:—covenant-breaker.
g802.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of συντίθημι (G4934)|English: Alpha

g803.d: ἀσφάλεια aspháleia, as-fal'-i-ah; from G804; security (literally or figuratively):—certainty, safety.
g803.r: From ἀσφαλής (G804)|English: certainty, certain, safe, sure

g804.d:
ἀσφαλής asphalḗs, as-fal-ace'; from G1 (as a negative particle) and sphallo (to "fail"); secure
 (literally or figuratively):—certain(-ty), safe, sure.
g804.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and sphallo (to "fail")|English: Alpha

g805.d: ἀσφαλίζω asphalízō, as-fal-id'-zo; from G804; to render secure:—make fast (sure).
g805.r: From ἀσφαλής (G804)|English: certainty, certain, safe, sure

g806.d:
ἀσφαλῶς asphalōs, as-fal-oce'; adverb from G804; securely (literally or figuratively):—assuredly,
 safely.
g806.r: From ἀσφαλής (G804)|English: certainty, certain, safe, sure

g807.d:
ἀσχημονέω aschēmonéō, as-kay-mon-eh'-o; from G809; to be (i.e. act) unbecoming:—behave self uncomely
 (unseemly).

g808.d:
ἀσχημοσύνη aschēmosýnē, as-kay-mos-oo'-nay; from G809; an indecency; by implication, the pudenda:—shame, that
 which is unseemly.

g809.d:
ἀσχήμων aschḗmōn, as-kay'-mone; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G2192 (in
 the sense of its congener G4976); properly, shapeless, i.e.
 (figuratively) inelegant:—uncomely.
g809.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ἔχω (G2192) (in the sense of its congener σχῆμα (G4976))|English: Alpha

g81.d:
ἀδελφότης adelphótēs, ad-el-fot'-ace; from G80; brotherhood (properly, the feeling of brotherliness), i.e.
 the (Christian) fraternity:—brethren, brotherhood.
g81.r: From ἀδελφός (G80)|English: brethren, brother, brother's, brother's way

g810.d:
ἀσωτία asōtía, as-o-tee'-ah; from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed
 derivative of G4982; properly, unsavedness, i.e. (by implication)
 profligacy:—excess, riot.
g810.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of σῴζω (G4982)|English: Alpha

g811.d: ἀσώτως asṓtōs, as-o'-toce; adverb from the same as G810; dissolutely:—riotous.
g811.r: From the same as ἀσωτία (G810)|English: riot, excess

g812.d: ἀτακτέω ataktéō, at-ak-teh'-o; from G813; to be (i.e. act) irregular:—behave self disorderly.

g813.d:
ἄτακτος átaktos, at'-ak-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G5021; unarranged,
 i.e. (by implication) insubordinate (religiously):—unruly.
g813.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of τάσσω (G5021)|English: Alpha

g814.d: ἀτάκτως atáktōs, at-ak'-toce; adverb from G813, irregularly (morally):—disorderly.

g815.d:
ἄτεκνος áteknos, at'-ek-nos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5043; childless:—childless,
 without children.
g815.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and τέκνον (G5043)|English: Alpha

g816.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a particle of union) and teino (to stretch)|English: Alpha

g817.d:
ἄτερ áter, at'-er; a particle probably akin to G427; aloof, i.e. apart from (literally or
 figuratively):—in the absence of, without.
g817.r: A particle probably akin to ἄνευ (G427)|English: without

g818.d:
ἀτιμάζω atimázō, at-im-ad'-zo; from G820; to render infamous, i.e. (by implication) contemn or
 maltreat:—despise, dishonour, suffer shame, entreat shamefully.
g818.r: From ἄτιμος (G820)|English: without honour, despised, less honourable

g819.d:
ἀτιμία atimía, at-ee-mee'-ah; from G820; infamy, i.e. (subjectively) comparative indignity,
 (objectively) disgrace:—dishonour, reproach, shame, vile.
g819.r: From ἄτιμος (G820)|English: without honour, despised, less honourable

g82.d:
ἄδηλος ádēlos, ad'-ay-los; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G1212; hidden, figuratively,
 indistinct:—appear not, uncertain.
g82.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and δῆλος (G1212)|English: Alpha

g820.d:
ἄτιμος átimos, at'-ee-mos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5092; (negatively) unhonoured or
 (positively) dishonoured:—despised, without honour, less honourable
 (comparative degree).
g820.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and τιμή (G5092)|English: Alpha

g821.d: †ἀτιμόω atimóō, at-ee-mo'-o; from G820; used like G818, to maltreat:—handle shamefully.
g821.r: From ἄτιμος (G820)|English: without honour, despised, less honourable

g822.d: ἀτμίς atmís, at-mece'; from the same as G109; mist:—vapour.
g822.r: From the same as ἀήρ (G109)|English: air

g823.d:
ἄτομος átomos, at'-om-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and the base of G5114; uncut, i.e. (by
 implication) indivisible (an "atom" of time):—moment.
g823.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and the base of τομός (G5114)|English: Alpha

g824.d:
ἄτοπος átopos, at'-op-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5117; out of place, i.e.
 (figuratively) improper, injurious, wicked:—amiss, harm,
 unreasonable.
g824.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and τόπος (G5117)|English: Alpha

g825.d:
Ἀττάλεια Attáleia, at-tal'-i-ah; from Ἄτταλος Áttalos (a king of Pergamus); Attaleia, a place in
 Pamphylia:—Attalia.

g826.d: αὐγάζω augázō, ow-gad'-zo; from G827; to beam forth (figuratively):—shine.

g827.d:
αὐγή augḗ, owg'-ay; of uncertain derivation; a ray of light, i.e. (by implication)
 radiance, dawn:—break of day.

g828.d:
Αὔγουστος Augoûstos, ow'-goos-tos; from Latin ("august"); Augustus, a title of the Roman
 emperor:—Augustus.

g829.d:
αὐθάδης authádēs, ow-thad'-ace; from G846 and the base of G2237; self-pleasing, i.e.
 arrogant:—self-willed.
g829.r: From αὐτός (G846) and the base of ἡδονή (G2237)|English: him, his, their, he, her, they, same, himself, misc

g83.d: ἀδηλότης adēlótēs, ad-ay-lot'-ace; from G82; uncertainty:—X uncertain.

g830.d:
αὐθαίρετος authaíretos, ow-thah'-ee-ret-os; from G846 and the same as G140; self-chosen, i.e. (by implication)
 voluntary:—of own accord, willing of self.
g830.r: From αὐτός (G846) and the same as αἱρετίζω (G140)|English: him, his, their, he, her, they, same, himself, misc

g831.d:
αὐθεντέω authentéō, ow-then-teh'-o; from a compound of G846 and an obsolete ἕντης héntēs (a worker); to act of
 oneself, i.e. (figuratively) dominate:—usurp authority over.
g831.r: From a compound of αὐτός (G846) and an obsolete hentes (a worker)|English: him, his, their, he, her, they, same, himself, misc

g832.d: αὐλέω auléō, ow-leh'-o; from G836; to play the flute:—pipe.

g833.d:
αὐλή aulḗ, ow-lay'; from the same as G109; a yard (as open to the wind); by implication, a
 mansion:—court, (sheep-)fold, hall, palace.
g833.r: From the same as ἀήρ (G109)|English: air

g834.d: αὐλητής aulētḗs, ow-lay-tace'; from G832; a flute-player:—minstrel, piper.

g835.d:
αὐλίζομαι aulízomai, ow-lid'-zom-ahee; middle voice from G833; to pass the night (properly, in the open
 air):—abide, lodge.
g835.r: Middle voice from αὐλή (G833)|English: palace, hall, sheepfold, fold, court

g836.d: αὐλός aulós, ow-los'; from the same as G109; a flute (as blown):—pipe.
g836.r: From the same as ἀήρ (G109)|English: air

g837.d:
αὐξάνω auxánō, owx-an'-o; a prolonged form of a primary verb; to grow ("wax"), i.e. enlarge
 (literal or figurative, active or passive):—grow (up), (give the)
 increase.
g837.r: A prolonged form of a primary verb|

g838.d: αὔξησις aúxēsis, owx'-ay-sis; from G837; growth:—increase.
g838.r: From αὐξάνω (G837)|English: grow, increase, give the increase, grow up

g839.d:
αὔριον aúrion, ow'-ree-on; from a derivative of the same as G109 (meaning a breeze, i.e. the
 morning air); properly, fresh, i.e. (adverb with ellipsis of G2250)
 to-morrow:—(to-)morrow, next day.
g839.r: From a derivative of the same as ἀήρ (G109) (meaning a breeze, i.e. the morning air)|English: air

g84.d: ἀδήλως adḗlōs, ad-ay'-loce; adverb from G82; uncertainly:—uncertainly.

g840.d:
αὐστηρός austērós, ow-stay-ros'; from a (presumed) derivative of the same as G109 (meaning blown); rough
 (properly as a gale), i.e. (figuratively) severe:—austere.
g840.r: From a (presumed) derivative of the same as ἀήρ (G109) (meaning blown)|English: air

g841.d:
αὐτάρκεια autárkeia, ow-tar'-ki-ah; from G842; self-satisfaction, i.e. (abstractly) contentedness, or
 (concretely) a competence:—contentment, sufficiency.

g842.d: αὐτάρκης autárkēs, ow-tar'-kace; from G846 and G714; self-complacent, i.e. contented:—content.
g842.r: From αὐτός (G846) and ἀρκέω (G714)|English: him, his, their, he, her, they, same, himself, misc

g843.d: αὐτοκατάκριτος autokatákritos, ow-tok-at-ak'-ree-tos; from G846 and a derivative or G2632; self-condemned:—condemned of self.
g843.r: From αὐτός (G846) and a derivative or κατακρίνω (G2632)|English: him, his, their, he, her, they, same, himself, misc

g844.d:
αὐτόματος autómatos, ow-tom'-at-os; from G846 and the same as G3155; self-moved ("automatic"), i.e.
 spontaneous:—of own accord, of self.
g844.r: From αὐτός (G846) and the same as μάτην (G3155)|English: him, his, their, he, her, they, same, himself, misc

g845.d: αὐτόπτης autóptēs, ow-top'-tace; from G846 and G3700; self-seeing, i.e. an eye-witness:—eye-witness.
g845.r: From αὐτός (G846) and ὀπτάνομαι (G3700)|English: him, his, their, he, her, they, same, himself, misc

g846.d:
αὐτός autós, ow-tos'; from the particle αὖ aû (perhaps akin to the base of G109 through the idea
 of a baffling wind) (backward); the reflexive pronoun self, used
 (alone or in the comparative G1438) of the third person , and (with the
 proper personal pronoun) of the other persons:—her, it(-self), one,
 the other, (mine) own, said, (self-), the) same, ((him-, my-, thy-
 )self, (your-)selves, she, that, their(-s), them(-selves), there(-at,
 - by, -in, -into, -of, -on, -with), they, (these) things, this (man),
 those, together, very, which. Compare G848.
g846.r: From the particle au [perhaps akin to the base of ἀήρ (G109) through the idea of a baffling wind] (backward)|English: air

g847.r: Genitive (i.e. possessive) of αὐτός (G846), used as an adverb of location|English: him, his, their, he, her, they, same, himself, misc

g848.d:
αὑτοῦ hautoû, how-too'; contracted for G1438; self (in some oblique case or reflexively,
 relation):—her (own), (of) him(-self), his (own), of it, thee, their
 (own), them(-selves), they.
g848.r: Contracted for ἑαυτοῦ (G1438)|English: himself, themselves, yourselves, ourselves, his, their, itself, misc

g849.d:
αὐτόχειρ autócheir, ow-tokh'-ire; from G846 and G5495; self-handed, i.e. doing personally:—with … own
 hands.
g849.r: From αὐτός (G846) and χείρ (G5495)|English: him, his, their, he, her, they, same, himself, misc

g85.d:
ἀδημονέω adēmonéō, ad-ay-mon-eh'-o; from a derivative of ἀδέω adéō (to be sated to loathing); to be in distress
 (of mind):—be full of heaviness, be very heavy.
g85.r: From a derivative of adeo (to be sated to loathing)|

g850.d:
αὐχμηρός auchmērós, owkh-may-ros'; from αὐχμός auchmós (probably from a base akin to that of G109) (dust, as
 dried by wind); properly, dirty, i.e. (by implication) obscure:—dark.
g850.r: From auchmos [probably from a base akin to that of ἀήρ (G109)] (dust, as dried by wind)|English: air

g851.d:
ἀφαιρέω aphairéō, af-ahee-reh'-o; from G575 and G138; to remove (literally or figuratively):—cut (smite)
 off, take away.
g851.r: From ἀπό (G575) and αἱρέω (G138)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g852.d:
ἀφανής aphanḗs, af-an-ace'; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5316; non-apparent):—that is not
 manifest.
g852.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and φαίνω (G5316)|English: Alpha

g853.d:
ἀφανίζω aphanízō, af-an-id'-zo; from G852; to render unapparent, i.e. (actively) consume (becloud), or
 (passively) disappear (be destroyed):—corrupt, disfigure, perish,
 vanish away.
g853.r: From ἀφανής (G852)|English: that is not manifest

g854.d: ἀφανισμός aphanismós, af-an-is-mos'; from G853; disappearance, i.e. (figuratively) abrogation:—vanish away.
g854.r: From ἀφανίζω (G853)|English: corrupt, disfigure, perish, vanish away

g855.d:
ἄφαντος áphantos, af'-an-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G5316; 
 non-manifested, i.e. invisible:—vanished out of sight.
g855.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of φαίνω (G5316)|English: Alpha

g856.d:
ἀφεδρών aphedrṓn, af-ed-rone'; from a compound of G575 and the base of G1476; a place of sitting apart,
 i.e. a privy:—draught.
g856.r: From a compound of ἀπό (G575) and the base of ἑδραῖος (G1476)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g857.d:
ἀφειδία apheidía, af-i-dee'-ah; from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and G5339; unsparingness,
 i.e. austerity (asceticism):—neglecting.
g857.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and φείδομαι (G5339)|English: Alpha

g858.d:
ἀφελότης aphelótēs, af-el-ot'-ace; from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and φέλλος phéllos (in the
 sense of a stone as stubbing the foot); smoothness, i.e.
 (figuratively) simplicity:—singleness.
g858.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and phellos (in the sense of a stone as stubbing the foot)|English: Alpha

g859.d:
ἄφεσις áphesis, af'-es-is; from G863; freedom; (figuratively) pardon:—deliverance, forgiveness,
 liberty, remission.
g859.r: From ἀφίημι (G863)|English: leave, forgive, suffer, let, forsake, let alone, misc

g86.d:
†ᾅδης háidēs, hah'-dace; from G1 (as negative particle) and G1492; properly, unseen, i.e. "Hades"
 or the place (state) of departed souls:—grave, hell.
g86.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as negative particle) and εἴδω (G1492)|English: Alpha

g860.d: ἁφή haphḗ, haf-ay'; from G680; probably a ligament (as fastening):—joint.

g861.d:
ἀφθαρσία aphtharsía, af-thar-see'-ah; from G862; incorruptibility; genitive, unending existence;
 (figuratively) genuineness:—immortality, incorruption, sincerity.
g861.r: From ἄφθαρτος (G862)|English: incorruptible, uncorruptible, immortal, not corruptible

g862.d:
ἄφθαρτος áphthartos, af'-thar-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G5351; undecaying
 (in essence or continuance):—not (in-, un-)corruptible, immortal.
g862.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of φθείρω (G5351)|English: Alpha

g863.d:
ἀφίημι aphíēmi, af-ee'-ay-mee; from G575 and ἵημι híēmi (to send; an intensive form of εἶμι eîmi, to go); to
 send forth, in various applications (as follow):—cry, forgive,
 forsake, lay aside, leave, let (alone, be, go, have), omit, put (send)
 away, remit, suffer, yield up.
g863.r: From ἀπό (G575) and hiemi (to send, an intens. form of eimi, to go)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g864.d:
ἀφικνέομαι aphiknéomai, af-ik-neh'-om-ahee; from G575 and the base of G2425; to go (i.e. spread) forth (by
 rumor):—come abroad.
g864.r: From ἀπό (G575) and the base of ἱκανός (G2425)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g865.d:
ἀφιλάγαθος aphilágathos, af-il-ag'-ath-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5358; hostile to virtue:—despiser
 of those that are good.
g865.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and φιλάγαθος (G5358)|English: Alpha

g866.d:
ἀφιλάργυρος aphilárgyros, af-il-ar'-goo-ros; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5366; unavaricious:—without
 covetousness, not greedy of filthy lucre.
g866.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and φιλάργυρος (G5366)|English: Alpha

g867.d:
ἄφιξις áphixis, af'-ix-is; from G864; properly, arrival, i.e. (by implication)
 departure:—departing.

g868.r: From ἀπό (G575) and ἵστημι (G2476)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g869.d: ἄφνω áphnō, af'-no; adverb from G852 (contraction); unawares, i.e. unexpectedly:—suddenly.
g869.r: From ἀφανής (G852) (contraction)|English: that is not manifest

g87.d:
ἀδιάκριτος adiákritos, ad-ee-ak'-ree-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G1252; properly,
 undistinguished, i.e. (actively) impartial:—without partiality.
g87.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of διακρίνω (G1252)|English: Alpha

g870.d:
ἀφόβως aphóbōs, af-ob'-oce; adverb from a compound of G1 (as a negative particle) and G5401; 
 fearlessly:—without fear.
g870.r: From a compound of ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and φόβος (G5401)|English: Alpha

g871.d: ἀφομοιόω aphomoióō, af-om-oy-o'-o; from G575 and G3666; to assimilate closely:—make like.
g871.r: From ἀπό (G575) and ὁμοιόω (G3666)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g872.d: ἀφοράω aphoráō, af-or-ah'-o; from G575 and G3708; to consider attentively:—look.
g872.r: From ἀπό (G575) and ὁράω (G3708)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g873.d:
ἀφορίζω aphorízō, af-or-id'-zo; from G575 and G3724; to set off by boundary, i.e. (figuratively) limit,
 exclude, appoint, etc.:—divide, separate, sever.
g873.r: From ἀπό (G575) and ὁρίζω (G3724)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g874.d:
ἀφορμή aphormḗ, af-or-may'; from a compound of G575 and G3729; a starting-point, i.e. (figuratively)
 an opportunity:—occasion.
g874.r: From a compound of ἀπό (G575) and ὁρμάω (G3729)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g875.d: ἀφρίζω aphrízō, af-rid'-zo; from G876; to froth at the mouth (in epilepsy):—foam.

g876.d: ἀφρός aphrós, af-ros'; apparently a primary word; froth, i.e. slaver:—foaming.

g877.d:
ἀφροσύνη aphrosýnē, af-ros-oo'-nay; from G878; senselessness, i.e. (euphemistically) egotism; (morally)
 recklessness:—folly, foolishly(-ness).

g878.d:
ἄφρων áphrōn, af'-rone; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5424; properly, mindless, i.e.
 stupid, (by implication) ignorant, (specially) egotistic,
 (practically) rash, or (morally) unbelieving:—fool(-ish), unwise.
g878.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and φρήν (G5424)|English: Alpha

g879.d:
ἀφυπνόω aphypnóō, af-oop-no'-o; from a compound of G575 and G5258; properly, to become awake, i.e. (by
 implication) to drop (off) in slumber:—fall asleep.
g879.r: From a compound of ἀπό (G575) and ὕπνος (G5258)|English: from, of, out of, for, off, by, at, in, since, on, not tr., misc.

g88.d:
ἀδιάλειπτος adiáleiptos, ad-ee-al'-ipe-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of a compound of G1223
 and G3007; unintermitted, i.e. permanent:—without ceasing, continual.
g88.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of a compound of διά (G1223) and λείπω (G3007)|English: Alpha

g880.d:
ἄφωνος áphōnos, af'-o-nos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5456; voiceless, i.e. mute (by
 nature or choice); figuratively, unmeaning:—dumb, without
 signification.
g880.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and φωνή (G5456)|English: Alpha

g881.d: †Ἀχάζ Acház, akh-adz'; of Hebrew origin (H271); Achaz, an Israelite:—Achaz.

g882.d:
Ἀχαΐα Achaḯa, ach-ah-ee'-ah; of uncertain derivation; Achaia (i.e. Greece), a country of
 Europe:—Achaia.

g883.d: Ἀχαϊκός Achaïkós, ach-ah-ee-kos'; from G882; an Achaian; Achaicus, a Christian:—Achaicus.

g884.d:
ἀχάριστος acháristos, ach-ar'-is-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of G5483; 
 thankless, i.e. ungrateful:—unthankful.
g884.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of χαρίζομαι (G5483)|English: Alpha

g885.d: †Ἀχείμ Acheím, akh-ime'; probably of Hebrew origin (compare H3137); Achim, an Israelite:—Achim.
g885.r: Probably of Hebrew origin cf יוֹקִים (H3137)|English: Jokim

g886.d:
ἀχειροποίητος acheiropoíētos, akh-i-rop-oy'-ay-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5499; unmanufactured, i.e.
 inartificial:—made without (not made with) hands.
g886.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and χειροποίητος (G5499)|English: Alpha

g887.d:
ἀχλύς achlýs, akh-looce'; of uncertain derivation; dimness of sight, i.e. (probably) a
 cataract:—mist.

g888.d:
ἀχρεῖος achreîos, akh-ri'-os; from G1 (as a negative particle) and a derivative of G5534 (compare
 G5532); useless, i.e. (euphemistically) unmeritorious:—unprofitable.
g888.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of χρή (G5534) [cf χρεία (G5532)]|English: Alpha

g889.d: ἀχρειόω achreióō, akh-ri-o'-o; from G888; to render useless, i.e. spoil:—become unprofitable.

g89.d:
ἀδιαλείπτως adialeíptōs, ad-ee-al-ipe'-toce; adverb from G88; uninterruptedly, i.e. without omission (on an
 appropriate occasion):—without ceasing.

g890.d:
ἄχρηστος áchrēstos, akh'-race-tos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5543; inefficient, i.e. (by
 implication) detrimental:—unprofitable.
g890.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and χρηστός (G5543)|English: Alpha

g891.d:
ἄχρι áchri, akh'-ree; akin to G206 (through the idea of a terminus); (of
 time) until or (of place) up to:—as far as, for, in(-to), till,
 (even, un-)to, until, while. Compare G3360.
g891.r: Akin to ἄκρον (G206) (through the idea of a terminus)|English: uttermost part, one end, other, tip, top

g892.d:
ἄχυρον áchyron, akh'-oo-ron; perhaps remotely from χέω chéō (to shed forth); chaff (as
 diffusive):—chaff.
g892.r: Perhaps remotely from cheo (to shed forth)|

g893.d: ἀψευδής apseudḗs, aps-yoo-dace'; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5579; veracious:—that cannot lie.
g893.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and ψεῦδος (G5579)|English: Alpha

g894.d:
ἄψινθος ápsinthos, ap'-sin-thos; of uncertain derivation; wormwood (as a type of bitterness, i.e.
 (figuratively) calamity):—wormwood.
g894.r: Of uncertain derivation. Though the word is usually neuter, the NT uses a feminine for the proper name.|

g895.d:
ἄψυχος ápsychos, ap'-soo-khos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G5590; lifeless, i.e. inanimate
 (mechanical):—without life.
g895.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and ψυχή (G5590)|English: Alpha

g896.d:
Βάαλ Báal, bah'-al; of Hebrew origin (H1168); Baal, a Phœnician deity (used as a symbol of
 idolatry):—Baal.
g896.r: Of Hebrew origin בַּעַל (H1168)|English: Baal, Baalim

g897.d:
Βαβυλών Babylṓn, bab-oo-lone'; of Hebrew origin (H894); Babylon, the capitol of Chaldæa (literally or
 figuratively (as a type of tyranny)):—Babylon.
g897.r: Of Hebrew origin בָּבֶל (H894)|English: Babylon, Babylonian, Babel

g898.d:
βαθμός bathmós, bath-mos'; from the same as G899; a step, i.e. (figuratively) grade (of
 dignity):—degree.
g898.r: From the same as βάθος (G899)|English: depth, deep, deep, deepness, deep thing

g899.d:
βάθος báthos, bath'-os; from the same as G901; profundity, i.e. (by implication) extent;
 (figuratively) mystery:—deep(-ness, things), depth.
g899.r: From the same as βαθύς (G901)|English: deep, very early in the morning

g9.d: Ἀβιληνή Abilēnḗ, ab-ee-lay-nay'; of foreign origin (compare H58); Abilene, a region of Syria:—Abilene.
g9.r: Of foreign origin, cf ἀγορά (G58)|English: market, marketplace, street

g900.d: βαθύνω bathýnō, bath-oo'-no; from G901; to deepen:—deep.
g900.r: From βαθύς (G901)|English: deep, very early in the morning

g901.d:
βαθύς bathýs, bath-oos'; from the base of G939; profound (as going down), literally or
 figuratively:—deep, very early.
g901.r: From the base of βάσις (G939)|English: foot (sole of)

g902.d:
βαΐον baḯon, bah-ee'-on; a diminutive of a derivative probably of the base of G939; a palm twig
 (as going out far):—branch.
g902.r: A diminutive of a derivative probably of the base of βάσις (G939)|English: foot (sole of)

g903.d:
Βαλαάμ Balaám, bal-ah-am'; of Hebrew origin (H1109); Balaam, a Mesopotamian (symbolic of a false
 teacher):—Balaam.
g903.r: Of Hebrew origin בִּלְעָם (H1109)|English: Balaam, Bileam

g904.d: Βαλάκ Balák, bal-ak'; of Hebrew origin (H1111); Balak, a Moabite:—Balac.

g905.d:
†βαλάντιον balántion, bal-an'-tee-on; probably remotely from G906 (as a depository); a pouch (for
 money):—bag, purse.
g905.r: Probably remotely from βάλλω (G906) (as a depository)|English: cast, put, thrust, cast out, lay, lie, misc

g906.d:
†βάλλω bállō, bal'-lo; a primary verb; to throw (in various applications, more or less
 violent or intense):—arise, cast (out), × dung, lay, lie, pour, put
 (up), send, strike, throw (down), thrust. Compare G4496.

g907.d:
βαπτίζω baptízō, bap-tid'-zo; from a derivative of G911; to immerse, submerge; to make whelmed (i.e.
 fully wet); used only (in the New Testament) of ceremonial ablution,
 especially (technically) of the ordinance of Christian
 baptism:—Baptist, baptize, wash.
g907.r: From a derivative of βάπτω (G911)|English: dip

g908.d: βάπτισμα báptisma, bap'-tis-mah; from G907; baptism (technically or figuratively):—baptism.
g908.r: From βαπτίζω (G907)|English: baptize (), wash, baptist, baptized

g909.d: βαπτισμός baptismós, bap-tis-mos'; from G907; ablution (ceremonial or Christian):—baptism, washing.
g909.r: From βαπτίζω (G907)|English: baptize (), wash, baptist, baptized

g91.d:
ἀδικέω adikéō, ad-ee-keh'-o; from G94; to be unjust, i.e. (actively) do wrong (morally, socially or
 physically):—hurt, injure, be an offender, be unjust, (do, suffer,
 take) wrong.

g910.d: Βαπτιστής Baptistḗs, bap-tis-tace'; from G907; a baptizer, as an epithet of Christ's forerunner:—Baptist.
g910.r: From βαπτίζω (G907)|English: baptize (), wash, baptist, baptized

g911.d:
βάπτω báptō, bap'-to; a primary verb; to whelm, i.e. cover wholly with a fluid; in the New
 Testament only in a qualified or special sense, i.e. (literally) to
 moisten (a part of one's person), or (by implication) to stain (as
 with dye):—dip.

g912.d:
Βαραββᾶς Barabbâs, bar-ab-bas'; of Chaldee origin (H1347 and H5); son of Abba; Bar-abbas, an
 Israelite:—Barabbas.
g912.r: Of Aramaic origin בַּר (H1247) and אֲבַגְתָא (H5)|English: son, about

g913.d: Βαράκ Barák, bar-ak'; of Hebrew origin (H1301); Barak, an Israelite:—Barak.

g914.d:
Βαραχίας Barachías, bar-akh-ee'-as; of Hebrew origin (H1296); Barachias (i.e. Berechijah), an
 Israelite:—Barachias.
g914.r: Of Hebrew origin בֶּרֶכְיָה (H1296)|English: Berechiah, Berachiah

g915.d:
βάρβαρος bárbaros, bar'-bar-os; of uncertain derivation; a foreigner (i.e.
 non-Greek):—barbarian(-rous).

g916.d: †βαρέω baréō, bar-eh'-o; from G926; to weigh down (figuratively):—burden, charge, heavy, press.
g916.r: From βαρύς (G926)|English: grievous, heavy, weighty, weighter

g917.d: βαρέως baréōs, bar-eh'-oce; adverb from G926; heavily (figuratively):—dull.
g917.r: From βαρύς (G926)|English: grievous, heavy, weighty, weighter

g918.d:
Βαρθολομαῖος Bartholomaîos, bar-thol-om-ah'-yos; of Chaldee origin (H1247 and H8526); son of Tolmai; Bar-tholomæus, a
 Christian apostle:—Bartholomeus.
g918.r: Of Aramaic origin בַּר (H1247) and תַּלְמַי (H8526)|English: son, about

g919.d:
Βαριησοῦς Bariēsoûs, bar-ee-ay-sooce'; of Chaldee origin (H1247 and H3091); son of Jesus (or Joshua);
 Bar-jesus, an Israelite:—Barjesus.
g919.r: Of Aramaic origin בַּר (H1247) and יְהוֹשׁוּעַ (H3091)|English: son, about

g92.d: ἀδίκημα adíkēma, ad-eek'-ay-mah; from G91; a wrong done:—evil doing, iniquity, matter of wrong.
g92.r: From ἀδικέω (G91)|English: hurt, do wrong, wrong, suffer wrong, be unjust, take wrong, injure, be an offender, vr hope

g920.d:
†Βαριωνᾶς Bariōnâs, bar-ee-oo-nas'; of Chaldee origin (H1247 and H3124); son of Jonas (or Jonah); Bar-jonas,
 an Israelite:—Bar-jona.
g920.r: Of Aramaic origin בַּר (H1247) and יוֹנָה (H3124)|English: son, about

g921.d:
Βαρνάβας Barnábas, bar-nab'-as; of Chaldee origin (H1247 and H5029); son of Nabas (i.e. prophecy);
 Barnabas, an Israelite:—Barnabas.
g921.r: Of Aramaic origin בַּר (H1247) and נְבִיא (H5029)|English: son, about

g922.r: Probably from the same as βάσις (G939) (through the notion of going down; cf βάθος (G899))|English: foot (sole of)

g923.d:
Βαρσαβᾶς Barsabâs, bar-sab-as'; of Chaldee origin (H1247 and probably H6634); son of Sabas (or Tsaba);
 Bar-sabas, the name of two Israelites:—Barsabas.
g923.r: Of Aramaic origin בַּר (H1247) and probably צְבָה (H6634)|English: son, about

g924.d:
Βαρτιμαῖος Bartimaîos, bar-tim-ah'-yos; of Chaldee origin (H1247 and H2931); son of Timæus (or the unclean);
 Bar-timæus, an Israelite:—Bartimæus.
g924.r: Of Aramaic origin בַּר (H1247) and טָמֵא (H2931)|English: son, about

g926.d:
βαρύς barýs, bar-ooce'; from the same as G922; weighty, i.e. (fig) burdensome,
 grave:—grievous, heavy, weightier.
g926.r: From the same as βάρος (G922)|English: burden, burdensome, weight

g927.d: βαρύτιμος barýtimos, bar-oo'-tim-os; from G926 and G5092; highly valuable:—very precious.
g927.r: From βαρύς (G926) and τιμή (G5092)|English: grievous, heavy, weighty, weighter

g928.d: βασανίζω basanízō, bas-an-id'-zo; from G931; to torture:—pain, toil, torment, toss, vex.

g929.d: βασανισμός basanismós, bas-an-is-mos'; from G928; torture:—torment.
g929.r: From βασανίζω (G928)|English: torment, pain, toss, vex, toil

g93.d:
ἀδικία adikía, ad-ee-kee'-ah; from G94; (legal) injustice (properly, the quality, by implication, the
 act); morally, wrongfulness (of character, life or act):—iniquity,
 unjust, unrighteousness, wrong.

g930.d: βασανιστής basanistḗs, bas-an-is-tace'; from G928; a torturer:—tormentor.
g930.r: From βασανίζω (G928)|English: torment, pain, toss, vex, toil

g931.d:
βάσανος básanos, bas'-an-os; perhaps remotely from the same as G939 (through the notion of going to
 the bottom); a touch-stone, i.e. (by analogy) torture:—torment.
g931.r: Perhaps remotely from the same as βάσις (G939) (through the notion of going to the bottom)|English: foot (sole of)

g932.d:
βασιλεία basileía, bas-il-i'-ah; from G935; properly, royalty, i.e. (abstractly) rule, or (concretely) a
 realm (literally or figuratively):—kingdom,
 + reign.
g932.r: From βασιλεύς (G935)|English: king, King (of Jews), King (God or Christ), King (of Israel)

g934.d: βασίλειος basíleios, bas-il'-i-os; from G935; kingly (in nature):—royal.

g935.d:
βασιλεύς basileús, bas-il-yooce'; probably from G939 (through the notion of a foundation of power); a
 sovereign (abstractly, relatively, or figuratively):—king.
g935.r: Probably from βάσις (G939) (through the notion of a foundation of power)|English: foot (sole of)

g936.d: βασιλεύω basileúō, bas-il-yoo'-o; from G935; to rule (literally or figuratively):—king, reign.
g936.r: From βασιλεύς (G935)|English: king, King (of Jews), King (God or Christ), King (of Israel)

g937.d:
βασιλικός basilikós, bas-il-ee-kos'; from G935; regal (in relation), i.e. (literally) belonging to (or
 befitting) the sovereign (as land, dress, or a courtier), or
 (figuratively) preeminent:—king's, nobleman, royal.
g937.r: From βασιλεύς (G935)|English: king, King (of Jews), King (God or Christ), King (of Israel)

g938.d: βασίλισσα basílissa, bas-il'-is-sah; feminine from G936; a queen:—queen.

g939.d:
βάσις básis, bas'-ece; from βαίνω baínō (to walk); a pace ("base"), i.e. (by implication) the
 foot:—foot.

g94.d:
ἄδικος ádikos, ad'-ee-kos; from G1 (as a negative particle) and G1349; unjust; by extension wicked;
 by implication, treacherous; specially, heathen:—unjust, unrighteous.
g94.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and δίκη (G1349)|English: Alpha

g940.d:
βασκαίνω baskaínō, bas-kah'-ee-no; akin to G5335; to malign, i.e. (by extension) to fascinate (by false
 representations):—bewitch.
g940.r: Akin to φάσκω (G5335)|English: say, affirm, profess

g941.d:
βαστάζω bastázō, bas-tad'-zo; perhaps remotely derived from the base of G939 (through the idea of
 removal); to lift, literally or figuratively (endure, declare,
 sustain, receive, etc.):—bear, carry, take up.
g941.r: Perhaps remotely derived from the base of βάσις (G939) (through the idea of removal)|English: foot (sole of)

g942.d: βάτος bátos, bat'-os; of uncertain derivation; a brier shrub:—bramble, bush.

g944.d: βάτραχος bátrachos, bat'-rakh-os; of uncertain derivation; a frog:—frog.

g945.d:
βαττολογέω battologéō, bat-tol-og-eh'-o; from Βάττος Báttos (a proverbial stammerer) and G3056; to stutter, i.e. (by
 implication) to prate tediously:—use vain repetitions.
g945.r: From Battos (a proverbial stammerer) and λόγος (G3056)|English: word, saying, account, speech, Word (Christ), thing, not tr, misc

g946.d: βδέλυγμα bdélygma, bdel'-oog-mah; from G948; a detestation, i.e. (specially) idolatry:—abomination.

g947.d: βδελυκτός bdelyktós, bdel-ook-tos'; from G948; detestable, i.e. (specially) idolatrous:—abominable.

g948.d:
†βδελύσσω bdelýssō, bdel-oos'-so; from a (presumed) derivative of βδέω bdéō (to stink); to be disgusted, i.e.
 (by implication) detest (especially of idolatry):—abhor, abominable.
g948.r: From a (presumed) derivative of bdeo (to stink)|

g949.d:
βέβαιος bébaios, beb'-ah-yos; from the base of G939 (through the idea of basality); stable (literally
 or figuratively):—firm, of force, stedfast, sure.
g949.r: From the base of βάσις (G939) (through the idea of basality)|English: foot (sole of)

g95.d: ἀδίκως adíkōs, ad-ee'-koce; adverb from G94; unjustly:—wrongfully.

g950.d: βεβαιόω bebaióō, beb-ah-yo'-o; from G949; to stabilitate (figuratively):—confirm, (e-)stablish.
g950.r: From βέβαιος (G949)|English: stedfast, sure, firm, of force, more sure

g9501.d:
†Α A, al'-fah; of Hebrew origin; the first letter of the alphabet; figuratively, only
 (from its use as a numeral) the first:—Alpha. Often used (usually
 ἄν án, before a vowel) also in composition (as a contraction from G427) in
 the sense of privation; so, in many words, beginning with this letter;
 occasionally in the sense of union (as a contraction of G260).

g951.d: βεβαίωσις bebaíōsis, beb-ah'-yo-sis; from G950; stabiliment:—confirmation.

g952.d:
βέβηλος bébēlos, beb'-ay-los; from the base of G939 and βηλός bēlós (a threshold); accessible (as by
 crossing the door-way), i.e. (by implication, of Jewish notions)
 heathenish, wicked:—profane (person).
g952.r: From the base of βάσις (G939) and belos (a threshold)|English: foot (sole of)

g953.d: βεβηλόω bebēlóō, beb-ay-lo'-o; from G952; to desecrate:—profane.

g954.d:
†Βεελζεβούλ Beelzeboúl, beh-el-zeb-ool'; of Chaldee origin (by parody on H1176); dung-god; Beelzebul, a name of
 Satan:—Beelzebub.
g954.r: Of Aramaic origin [by parody on בַּעַל  זְבוּב (H1176)]|English: Baalzebub

g955.d:
Βελίαλ Belíal, bel-ee'-al; of Hebrew origin (H1100); worthlessness; Belial, as an epithet of
 Satan:—Belial.
g955.r: Of Hebrew origin בְּלִיַּעַל (H1100)|English: Belial, wicked, ungodly, evil, naughty ungodly men

g956.d: βέλος bélos, bel'-os; from G906; a missile, i.e. spear or arrow:—dart.
g956.r: From βάλλω (G906)|English: cast, put, thrust, cast out, lay, lie, misc

g957.d:
†βελτίον beltíon, bel-tee'-on; neuter of a compound of a derivative of G906 (used for the comparative
 of G18); better:—very well.
g957.r: A compound of a derivative of βάλλω (G906) (used for the comparative of ἀγαθός (G18))|English: cast, put, thrust, cast out, lay, lie, misc

g958.d: Βενιαμίν Beniamín, ben-ee-am-een'; of Hebrew origin (H1144); Benjamin, an Israelite:—Benjamin.

g959.d:
Βερνίκη Berníkē, ber-nee'-kay; from a provincial form of G5342 and G3529; victorious; Bernice, a member
 of the Herodian family:—Bernice.
g959.r: From a provincial form of φέρω (G5342) and νίκη (G3529)|English: bring, bear, bring forth, come, reach, endure, carry, misc

g96.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle) and δόκιμος (G1384)|English: Alpha

g960.d:
Βέροια Béroia, ber'-oy-ah; perhaps a provincial from a derivative of G4008 (Perœa, i.e. the
 region beyond the coast-line); Berœa, a place in Macedonia:—Berea.
g960.r: Perhaps a provincial from a derivative of πέραν (G4008) [Peroea, i.e. the region beyond the coast-line]|English: other side, beyond, over, on the other side, farther side

g961.d: Βεροιαῖος Beroiaîos, ber-oy-ah'-yos; from G960; a Berœoean or native of Berœa:—of Berea.

g963.d:
Βηθανία Bēthanía, bay-than-ee'-ah; of Chaldee origin; date-house; Beth-any, a place in
 Palestine:—Bethany.

g964.d:
†Βηθεσδά Bēthesdá, bay-thes-dah'; of Chaldee origin (compare H1004 and H2617); house of kindness;
 Beth-esda, a pool in Jerusalem:—Bethesda.
g964.r: Of Aramaic origin [cf בַּיִת (H1004) and חֶסֶד (H2617)]|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

g965.d:
†Βηθλεέμ Bēthleém, bayth-leh-em'; of Hebrew origin (H1036); Bethleem (i.e. Beth-lechem), a place in
 Palestine:—Bethlehem.
g965.r: Of Hebrew origin בֵּית  לֶחֶם (H1035)|English: Bethlehem, Bethlehemjudah

g966.d:
Βηθσαϊδά Bēthsaïdá, bayth-sahee-dah'; of Chaldee origin (compare H1004 and H6719); fishing-house; Bethsaida, a
 place in Palestine:—Bethsaida.
g966.r: Of Aramaic origin cf בַּיִת (H1004) and צַיָּד (H6719)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

g967.d:
†Βηθφαγή Bēthphagḗ, bayth-fag-ay'; of Chaldee origin (compare H1004 and H6291); fig-house; Beth-phage, a
 place in Palestine:—Bethphage.
g967.r: Of Aramaic origin cf בַּיִת (H1004) and פַּג (H6291)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

g968.d:
βῆμα bēma, bay'-ma; from the base of G939; a step, i.e. foot-breath; by implication, a
 rostrum, i.e. a tribunal:—judgment-seat, set (foot) on, throne.
g968.r: From the base of βάσις (G939)|English: foot (sole of)

g969.d: βήρυλλος bḗryllos, bay'-rool-los; of uncertain derivation; a "beryl":—beryl.

g97.d:
ἄδολος ádolos, ad'-ol-os; from G1 (as a negative particle); and G1388; undeceitful, i.e.
 (figuratively) unadulterated:—sincere.
g97.r: From ἄλφα (G1) (as a negative particle), and δόλος (G1388)|English: Alpha

g970.d:
βία bía, bee'-ah; probably akin to G979 (through the idea of vital activity); 
 force:—violence.
g970.r: Probably akin to βία (G970) (through the idea of vital activity)|English: violence

g971.d:
βιάζω biázō, bee-ad'-zo; from G979; to force, i.e. (reflexively) to crowd oneself (into), or
 (passively) to be seized:—press, suffer violence.

g972.d: βίαιος bíaios, bee'-ah-yos; from G970; violent:—mighty.

g973.d: βιαστής biastḗs, bee-as-tace'; from G971; a forcer, i.e. (figuratively) energetic:—violent.

g974.d: βιβλιαρίδιον bibliarídion, bib-lee-ar-id'-ee-on; a diminutive of G975; a booklet:—little book.
g974.r: A diminutive of βιβλίον (G975)|English: book, bill, scroll, writing

g975.d: βιβλίον biblíon, bib-lee'-on; a diminutive of G976; a roll:—bill, book, scroll, writing.

g976.d:
βίβλος bíblos, bib'-los; properly, the inner bark of the papyrus plant, i.e. (by implication) a
 sheet or scroll of writing:—book.

g977.d:
βιβρώσκω bibrṓskō, bib-ro'-sko; a reduplicated and prolonged form of an obsolete primary verb (perhaps
 causative of G1006); to eat:—eat.
g977.r: A reduplicated and prolonged form of an obsolete primary word [perhaps causative of βόσκω (G1006)]|English: feed, keep

g978.d: Βιθυνία Bithynía, bee-thoo-nee'-ah; of uncertain derivation; Bithynia, a region of Asia:—Bithynia.

g979.d:
βίος bíos, bee'-os; a primary word; life, i.e. (literally) the present state of existence;
 by implication, the means of livelihood:—good, life, living.

g98.d:
Ἀδραμυττηνός Adramyttēnós, ad-ram-oot-tay-nos'; from Ἀδραμύττειον Adramýtteion (a place in Asia Minor); Adramyttene or belonging to
 Adramyttium:—of Adramyttium.
g98.r: From Adramutteion (a place in Asia Minor)|

g980.d: βιόω bióō, bee-o'-o; from G979; to spend existence:—live.

g981.d:
βίωσις bíōsis, bee'-o-sis; from G980; living (properly, the act, by implication, the
 mode):—manner of life.

g982.d:
βιωτικός biōtikós, bee-o-tee-kos'; from a derivative of G980; relating to the present existence:—of
 (pertaining to, things that pertain to) this life.
g982.r: From a derivative of βιόω (G980)|English: live

g983.d: βλαβερός blaberós, blab-er-os'; from G984; injurious:—hurtful.

g984.d:
βλάπτω bláptō, blap'-to; a primary verb; properly, to hinder, i.e. (by implication) to
 injure:—hurt.

g985.d:
βλαστάνω blastánō, blas-tan'-o; from βλαστός blastós (a sprout); to germinate; by implication, to yield
 fruit:—bring forth, bud, spring (up).

g986.d:
Βλάστος Blástos, blas'-tos; perhaps the same as the base of G985; Blastus, an officer of Herod
 Agrippa:—Blastus.
g986.r: Perhaps the same as the base of βλαστάνω (G985)|English: spring up, bud, bring forth

g987.d:
†βλασφημέω blasphēméō, blas-fay-meh'-o; from G989; to vilify; specially, to speak impiously:—(speak)
 blaspheme(-er, -mously, -my), defame, rail on, revile, speak evil.

g988.d:
βλασφημία blasphēmía, blas-fay-me'-ah; from G989; vilification (especially against God):—blasphemy, evil
 speaking, railing.

g989.d:
βλάσφημος blásphēmos, blas'-fay-mos; from a derivative of G984 and G5345; scurrilious, i.e. calumnious
 (against men), or (specially) impious (against
 God):—blasphemer(-mous), railing.
g989.r: From a derivative of βλάπτω (G984) and φήμη (G5345)|English: hurt

g99.d:
Ἀδρίας Adrías, ad-ree'-as; from Ἀδρία Adría (a place near its shore); the Adriatic sea (including the
 Ionian):—Adria.
g99.r: From Adria (a place near its shore)|

g990.d:
βλέμμα blémma, blem'-mah; from G991; vision (properly concrete; by implication,
 abstract):—seeing.
g990.r: From βλέπω (G991)|English: see, take heed, behold, beware, look on, look, beware of, misc

g991.d:
βλέπω blépō, blep'-o; a primary verb; to look at (literally or figuratively):—behold,
 beware, lie, look (on, to), perceive, regard, see, sight, take heed. 
 Compare G3700.

g992.d: βλητέος blētéos, blay-teh'-os; from G906; fit to be cast (i.e. applied):—must be put.
g992.r: From βάλλω (G906)|English: cast, put, thrust, cast out, lay, lie, misc

g993.d:
Βοανεργές Boanergés, bo-an-erg-es'; of Chaldee origin (H1123 and H7266); sons of commotion; Boanerges, an
 epithet of two of the apostles:—Boanerges.
g993.r: Of Aramaic origin בֵּן (H1123) and רְגַז (H7266)|English: children, son, young, of the captives

g994.d:
βοάω boáō, bo-ah'-o; apparently a prolonged form of a primary verb; to halloo, i.e. shout
 (for help or in a tumultuous way):—cry.
g994.r: Apparently a prol. form of a primary word|

g995.d: βοή boḗ, bo-ay'; from G994; a halloo, i.e. call (for aid, etc.):—cry.

g996.d:
βοήθεια boḗtheia, bo-ay'-thi-ah; from G998; aid; specially, a rope or chain for frapping a
 vessel:—help.

g997.d: βοηθέω boēthéō, bo-ay-theh'-o; from G998; to aid or relieve:—help, succor.

g998.d: βοηθός boēthós, bo-ay-thos'; from G995 and theo (to run); a succorer:—helper.
g998.r: From βοή (G995) and theo (to run)|English: cry

g999.d:
βόθυνος bóthynos, both'-oo-nos; akin to G900; a hole (in the ground); specially, a cistern:—ditch,
 pit.

h1.d: אָב ʼâb, awb; a primitive word;  father, in a literal and immediate, or figurative and remote application:—chief, (fore-) father(-less), × patrimony, principal. Compare names in 'Abi-'.

h1000.d: בֵּיצָה bêytsâh, bay-tsaw'; from the same as H948;  an egg (from its whiteness):—egg.
h1000.r: From the same as בּוּץ (H948)|English: fine linen, white linen

h1003.d: בִּירָנִית bîyrânîyth, bee-raw-neeth'; from H1002;  a fortress:—castle.

h1004.d: בַּיִת bayith, bah'-yith; probably from H1129 abbreviated;  a house (in the greatest variation of applications, especially family, etc.):—court, daughter, door, + dungeon, family, + forth of, × great as would contain, hangings, home(born), (winter) house(-hold), inside(-ward), palace, place, + prison, + steward, + tablet, temple, web, + within(-out).
h1004.s: proper patrial adjective, adverb, masculine noun
h1004.r: Probably from בָּנָה (H1129) abbreviated|English: build, build up, builder, made, built again, repair, set up, have children, obtain children, surely (inf. for emphasis)

h1005.d: בַּיִת bayith, bah-yith; (Aramaic) corresponding to H1004:—house.
h1005.r: Corresponding to בַּיִת (H1004)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1007.d: בֵּית אָוֶן Bêyth ʼÂven, bayth aw'-ven; from H1004 and H205; house of vanity;  Beth-Aven, a place in Palestine:—Beth-aven.
h1007.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and אָוֶן (H205)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1008.d: בֵּית־אֵל Bêyth-ʼÊl, bayth-ale'; from H1004 and H410; house of God;  Beth-El, a place in Palestine:—Beth-el.
h1008.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and אֵל (H410)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1009.d: בֵּית אַרְבֵּאל Bêyth ʼArbêʼl, bayth ar-bale'; from H1004 and H695 and H410; house of God's ambush;  Beth-Arbel, a place in Palestine:—Beth-Arbel.
h1009.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and אֶרֶב (H695) and אֵל (H410)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1011.d: בֵּית בִּרְאִי Bêyth Birʼîy, bayth bir-ee'; from H1004 and H1254; house of a creative one;  Beth-Biri, a place in Palestine:—Bethbirei.
h1011.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and בָּרָא (H1254)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1014.d: בֵּית גָּמוּל Bêyth Gâmûwl, bayth gaw-mool'; from H1004 and the passive participle of H1576; house of (the) weaned;  Beth-Gamul, a place East of the Jordan:—Beth-gamul.
h1014.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and the pass. participle of גְּמוּל (H1576)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1016.d: בֵּית־דָּגוֹן Bêyth-Dâgôwn, bayth-daw-gohn'; from H1004 and H1712; house of Dagon;  Beth-Dagon, the name of two places in Palestine:—Beth-dagon.
h1016.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and דָּגוֹן (H1712)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1020.d: בֵּית הַיְשִׁימוֹת Bêyth ha-Yshîy-môwth, bayth hah-yesh-eemoth'; from H1004 and the plural of H3451 with the article interposed; house of the deserts;  Beth-ha-Jeshimoth, a town East of the Jordan:—Beth-jeshimoth.
h1020.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and the plural of יְשִׁימָה (H3451) with the article interposed|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1024.d: בֵּית הַמַּרְכָּבוֹת Bêyth ham-Markâbôwth, bayth ham-markaw-both'; or (shortened) בֵּית מַרְכָּבוֹת Bêyth Mar-kâbôwth; from H1004 and the plural of H4818 (with or without the article interposed); place of (the) chariots;  Beth-ham-Markaboth or Beth-Markaboth, a place in Palestine:—Bethmarcaboth.
h1024.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and the pl. of מֶרְכָּבָה (H4818) (with or without the article interposed)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1026.d: בֵּית הָעֲרָבָה Bêyth hâ-ʻĂrâbâh, bayth haw-ar-aw-baw; from H1004 and H6160 with the article interposed; house of the Desert;  Beth-ha-Arabah, a place in Palestine:—Beth-arabah.
h1026.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and עֲרָבָה (H6160) with the article interposed|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1027.d: בֵּית הָרָם Bêyth hâ-Râm, bayth haw-rawm'; from H1004 and H7311 with the article interposed; house of the height;  Beth-ha-Ram, a place East of the Jordan:—Beth-aram.
h1027.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and רוּם (H7311) with the article interposed|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h103.d: אָגַר ʼâgar, aw-gar'; a primitive root;  to harvest:—gather.

h1032.d: בֵּית חוֹרוֹן Bêyth Chôwrôwn, bayth kho-rone'; from H1004 and H2356; house of hollowness;  Beth-Choron, the name of two adjoining places in Palestine:—Beth-horon.
h1032.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and חוֹר (H2356)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1033.d: בֵּית כַּר Bêyth Kar, bayth kar; from H1004 and H3733; house of pasture;  Beth-Car, a place in Palestine:—Beth-car.
h1033.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and כַּר (H3733)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1035.d: בֵּית לֶחֶם Bêyth Lechem, bayth leh'-khem; from H1004 and H3899; house of bread;  Beth-Lechem, a place in Palestine:—Bethlehem.
h1035.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and לֶחֶם (H3899)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h1037.d: בֵּית מִלּוֹא Bêyth Millôwʼ, bayth mil-lo'; or בֵּית מִלֹּא Bêyth Millôʼ; from H1004 and H4407; house of (the) rampart;  Beth-Millo, the name of two citadels:—house of Millo.
h1037.r: From בַּיִת (H1004) and מִלּוֹא (H4407)|English: house, household, home, within, temple, prison, place, family, families, dungeon, misc

h104.d: אִגְּרָא ʼiggᵉrâʼ, ig-er-aw'; (Aramaic) of Persian origin;  an epistle (as carried by a state courier or postman):—letter.

h1047.d: בֵּית פְּעוֹר Bêyth Pᵉʻôwr, bayth pe-ore'; from H1004 and H6465; house of Peor;  Beth-Peor, a place East of the Jordan:—Bethpeor.
